"aa1":[null,"Proline has a cyclic structure and is an IMINO acid, not a standard alpha-amino acid structure.","Glycine has only H as its R-group and IS a standard amino acid, but the question asks about the general structure.","Cysteine's thiol group is important for disulfide bonds, but the basic amino acid structure applies to all 20."],
"aa2":[null,"This confuses the properties of a different amino acid or side chain category with the one being asked about.","This describes a different structural or chemical property than what the question specifically targets.","This option is incorrect because it misidentifies the amino acid property or confuses it with a different molecular feature."],
"aa3":[null,"This confuses the properties of a different amino acid or side chain category with the one being asked about.","This describes a different structural or chemical property than what the question specifically targets.","This option is incorrect because it misidentifies the amino acid property or confuses it with a different molecular feature."],
"aa4":[null,"This confuses the properties of a different amino acid or side chain category with the one being asked about.","This describes a different structural or chemical property than what the question specifically targets.","This option is incorrect because it misidentifies the amino acid property or confuses it with a different molecular feature."],
"aa5":[null,"This confuses the properties of a different amino acid or side chain category with the one being asked about.","This describes a different structural or chemical property than what the question specifically targets.","This option is incorrect because it misidentifies the amino acid property or confuses it with a different molecular feature."],
"aa6":[null,"Lysine's amino group participates in hydrogen bonding and post-translational modification, not disulfide bridges.","Proline's ring connects to the backbone nitrogen, restricting rotation. It cannot form disulfide bonds.","Glycine has only hydrogen as its side chain. It has no reactive group to form crosslinks like disulfides."],
"aa7":[null,"Lys, Arg, and His are positively charged. Their side chains don't have conjugated systems that absorb UV at 280nm.","Asp and Glu are negatively charged with simple carboxylate groups. They lack the aromatic rings needed for UV absorption.","Ser, Thr, and Cys have polar side chains but no aromatic ring systems. UV 280nm absorption requires conjugation."],
"aa8":[null,"This confuses the properties of a different amino acid or side chain category with the one being asked about.","This describes a different structural or chemical property than what the question specifically targets.","This option is incorrect because it misidentifies the amino acid property or confuses it with a different molecular feature."],
"aa9":[null,"Hydrophobic residues on the surface would be exposed to water, which is thermodynamically unfavorable.","Disulfide bonds involve cysteine specifically. Hydrophobic amino acids cluster through non-covalent hydrophobic interactions.","Active sites often contain polar and charged residues for catalysis. Hydrophobic residues provide the structural core."],
"aa10":[null,"Primary structure (peptide bonds) survives denaturation. Heat and urea break non-covalent bonds, not covalent peptide bonds.","Quaternary structure is lost, but so are secondary and tertiary. It's not limited to just quaternary.","The amino acid sequence IS primary structure, which is maintained. Denaturation doesn't break peptide bonds."],
"aa11":[null,"At pH 7.4, both groups are ionized: NH3+ and COO-. Having only positive charge would require very low pH.","Having only negative charge would require very high pH where both amino and carboxyl are deprotonated.","Both the amino and carboxyl groups are ionizable. At physiological pH, they ARE charged (as a zwitterion)."],
"aa12":[null,"Tryptophan is too bulky for collagen's tightly wound triple helix. Glycine's small size is essential.","Histidine plays roles in catalysis and buffering. It has no special structural role in collagen.","Methionine is the start codon amino acid. It has no specific role in collagen's repetitive Gly-X-Y structure."],
