"bs1":[null,"A short loop of Henle limits the kidney's ability to concentrate urine but doesn't affect GFR.","Sweat glands are excretory but primarily for thermoregulation, not waste nitrogen removal.","Blood vessel walls are involved in exchange but are not excretory organs in the traditional sense."],
"bs2":[null,"The PCT reabsorbs ~65% of water constitutively. ADH specifically acts on the collecting duct.","The ascending loop is impermeable to water — this is essential for the countercurrent mechanism.","The glomerulus filters blood. ADH acts downstream at the collecting duct to control water reabsorption."],
"bs3":[null,"Podocytes form the filtration barrier with fenestrated endothelium, not the reabsorption machinery.","Macula densa cells sense NaCl concentration and regulate GFR via tubuloglomerular feedback.","Intercalated cells in the collecting duct handle acid-base balance (H+ and HCO3-), not proximal reabsorption."],
"bs4":[null,"This option describes a different physiological mechanism than what is being tested. Review the specific organ system involved.","This is incorrect because it either reverses the direction of the process or confuses it with a different pathway.","This answer confuses the function described with a related but distinct biological process in a different organ system."],
"bs5":[null,"Decreased CO2, H+, temp, and BPG would shift the curve LEFT (increased O2 affinity), not right.","Increased pH means less H+ — this shifts LEFT, increasing hemoglobin's O2 affinity (Bohr effect).","CO binds hemoglobin at the same site as O2 but shifts the curve LEFT (increased affinity for remaining sites)."],
"bs6":[null,"ADH (vasopressin) directly increases water reabsorption. Aldosterone works on Na+/K+ exchange.","Aldosterone increases Na+ reabsorption, not decreases it. Decreased Na+ reabsorption occurs with its absence.","Aldosterone acts on the DCT/collecting duct, not the proximal tubule, and affects Na+/K+, not glucose."],
"bs7":[null,"This option describes a different physiological mechanism than what is being tested. Review the specific organ system involved.","This is incorrect because it either reverses the direction of the process or confuses it with a different pathway.","This answer confuses the function described with a related but distinct biological process in a different organ system."],
"bs8":[null,"Systemic BP influences GFR but is not the primary regulatory mechanism — arteriolar tone is.","ADH regulates water reabsorption in the collecting duct. It affects urine concentration, not GFR directly.","Urine volume is an output measure. GFR is regulated by the input side — arteriolar resistance."],
"bs9":[null,"K+ efflux occurs during repolarization (returning to resting potential), not during the depolarization upstroke.","Cl- influx causes hyperpolarization (IPSPs), not depolarization. It moves potential away from threshold.","Ca2+ efflux via ATPase pumps occurs at rest to maintain low intracellular Ca2+, not during depolarization."],
"bs10":[null,"AV node has a slower intrinsic rate (~40-60 bpm) than SA node (~60-100 bpm). It serves as backup only.","Purkinje fibers have the slowest intrinsic rate (~20-40 bpm). They conduct impulses, not initiate them.","Bundle of His conducts impulses from atria to ventricles. It doesn't generate the primary heartbeat rhythm."],
"bs11":[null,"T3/T4 increase heart rate (positive chronotropic effect), not decrease it.","T3/T4 promote lipolysis and thermogenesis. They increase fat breakdown, not storage.","Thyroid hormones promote growth (in conjunction with GH). They don't suppress it."],
"bs12":[null,"This option describes a different physiological mechanism than what is being tested. Review the specific organ system involved.","This is incorrect because it either reverses the direction of the process or confuses it with a different pathway.","This answer confuses the function described with a related but distinct biological process in a different organ system."],
"bs13":[null,"This option describes a different physiological mechanism than what is being tested. Review the specific organ system involved.","This is incorrect because it either reverses the direction of the process or confuses it with a different pathway.","This answer confuses the function described with a related but distinct biological process in a different organ system."],
"bs14":[null,"ADH and oxytocin are made in the hypothalamus and stored/released by the posterior pituitary.","Epinephrine comes from the adrenal medulla, not the anterior pituitary.","Insulin comes from pancreatic beta cells, not the anterior pituitary."],
"pbs1":[null,"This option describes a different physiological mechanism than what is being tested. Review the specific organ system involved.","This is incorrect because it either reverses the direction of the process or confuses it with a different pathway.","This answer confuses the function described with a related but distinct biological process in a different organ system."],
"pbs2":[null,"TEA blocks K+ channels needed for repolarization, causing prolonged depolarization, not blocking it.","TTX prevents depolarization by blocking Na+ channels. It doesn't cause continuous depolarization.","TTX has a dramatic effect — it completely prevents action potentials from occurring at the treated node."],
"pbs3":[null,"This option describes a different physiological mechanism than what is being tested. Review the specific organ system involved.","This is incorrect because it either reverses the direction of the process or confuses it with a different pathway.","This answer confuses the function described with a related but distinct biological process in a different organ system."],
"bs15":[null,"Blood doesn't go from aorta to right atrium. The aorta sends blood to the body, then returns via vena cava.","Blood flows from LA to LV (left side), not LA to RA. Right and left sides have separate circuits.","Blood returns from lungs via pulmonary veins to the LEFT atrium, not through RV to lungs again."],
