var CARDS={
"Acid-Base":[
"pH = -log[H+]. Low pH = acidic (more H+), high pH = basic (fewer H+). pOH = 14 - pH.",
"Strong acids (HCl, HNO3, H2SO4) fully dissociate. Weak acids partially dissociate and have a Ka value.",
"Henderson-Hasselbalch: pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]). At the half-equivalence point, pH = pKa exactly.",
"Buffers resist pH change. Most effective within +/-1 pH unit of the acid's pKa, when [HA] roughly equals [A-].",
"Titration of weak acid with strong base: equivalence point pH > 7 (conjugate base is basic). Strong acid + strong base: equivalence point at pH 7.",
"Polyprotic acids donate protons sequentially. Ka1 >> Ka2 >> Ka3. Each step is harder (removing H+ from a more negative species)."
],
"Amino Acid Properties":[
"20 standard amino acids share a backbone: alpha-carbon bonded to NH3+, COO-, H, and a unique R-group (side chain).",
"At physiological pH (7.4), amino acids exist as zwitterions: NH3+ (protonated amino) and COO- (deprotonated carboxyl).",
"Nonpolar/hydrophobic AAs (G,A,V,L,I,P,F,W,M) cluster in protein interiors. Polar/charged AAs face the aqueous surface.",
"Aromatic AAs (Trp, Tyr, Phe) absorb UV at 280nm. Trp absorbs most strongly. Used for protein quantification (Beer-Lambert law).",
"Side chain pKas of charged AAs: Asp ~3.65, Glu ~4.25, His ~6.0, Cys ~8.3, Lys ~10.5, Arg ~12.5.",
"Special AAs: Cys forms disulfide bonds. Pro is a helix breaker (rigid ring). Gly is the smallest (most flexible). His is the best physiological buffer (pKa ~6)."
],
"Enzyme Inhibition":[
"Competitive: binds active site (competes with substrate). Km increases (apparent lower affinity), Vmax unchanged. Overcome by excess [S].",
"Noncompetitive: binds allosteric site on E and ES equally. Km unchanged, Vmax decreases. Cannot be overcome by adding substrate.",
"Uncompetitive: binds only ES complex. Both Km AND Vmax decrease. Lineweaver-Burk shows parallel lines (unique pattern).",
"Mixed: binds allosteric site with different affinity for E vs ES. Both Km and Vmax change. Noncompetitive is the special case where affinity is equal.",
"Lineweaver-Burk (1/V vs 1/[S]): Competitive = same y-intercept. Noncompetitive = same x-intercept. Uncompetitive = parallel lines.",
"Irreversible inhibitors permanently modify the enzyme (often covalent). Example: aspirin acetylates COX. Not overcome by substrate."
],
"Social Psychology":[
"Fundamental attribution error: overestimate personality (dispositional) and underestimate situation when explaining OTHERS' behavior.",
"Bystander effect: more people present = less likely any individual helps. Diffusion of responsibility + pluralistic ignorance.",
"Asch conformity: ~75% conformed at least once to obviously wrong group answer. One ally dramatically reduces conformity.",
"Cognitive dissonance (Festinger): holding contradictory beliefs/actions causes discomfort. Resolved by changing belief, behavior, or adding justification.",
"Groupthink: cohesive groups prioritize harmony over critical analysis, leading to poor decisions. Prevention: devil's advocate, outside experts.",
"Self-serving bias: attribute own success to internal factors, failure to external. Actor-observer bias: others' failure = personality, own failure = situation."
],
"Nervous System":[
"Resting potential ~-70mV maintained by Na+/K+ ATPase (3 Na+ out, 2 K+ in) and K+ leak channels.",
"Action potential: threshold (-55mV) -> Na+ channels open (depolarization to +30mV) -> Na+ inactivate, K+ open (repolarization) -> refractory period.",
"Saltatory conduction: myelin insulates axon, AP jumps node to node. Much faster (~120 m/s) than unmyelinated (~1 m/s).",
"Sympathetic = fight or flight (NE). Parasympathetic = rest and digest (ACh). Both preganglionic neurons use ACh.",
"Neuromuscular junction: motor neuron releases ACh -> nicotinic receptors on muscle -> Na+ influx -> contraction. AChE degrades ACh.",
"Myelin: Schwann cells (PNS), oligodendrocytes (CNS). Demyelination: MS (CNS), Guillain-Barre (PNS)."
],
"Protein Structure":[
"Primary = amino acid sequence (peptide bonds). Secondary = local folds: alpha-helix and beta-sheet (backbone H-bonds).",
"Tertiary = overall 3D shape of one polypeptide. Stabilized by R-group interactions: hydrophobic, ionic (salt bridges), H-bonds, disulfide bonds (covalent).",
"Quaternary = multiple polypeptide subunits assembled together. Not all proteins have this level. Example: hemoglobin (alpha2-beta2).",
"Denaturation disrupts secondary/tertiary/quaternary structure but NOT primary (peptide bonds intact). Caused by heat, extreme pH, urea.",
"The hydrophobic effect is the primary driving force of folding -- nonpolar residues collapse to the interior to avoid water.",
"Chaperones (like Hsp70) assist protein folding. Misfolded proteins can cause disease (prions, Alzheimer's amyloid)."
],
"Hormones":[
"Peptide hormones (insulin, glucagon, ADH): hydrophilic, bind SURFACE receptors (GPCRs or RTKs), act via second messengers. Fast acting.",
"Steroid hormones (cortisol, aldosterone, estrogen, testosterone): lipophilic, cross membrane, bind INTRACELLULAR/nuclear receptors, alter gene transcription. Slower acting.",
"Thyroid hormones (T3/T4): amino acid-derived but act like steroids (cross membrane, bind nuclear receptors). Increase basal metabolic rate.",
"HPA axis: Hypothalamus (CRH) -> Anterior pituitary (ACTH) -> Adrenal cortex (cortisol). Negative feedback at each level.",
"HPT axis: Hypothalamus (TRH) -> Anterior pituitary (TSH) -> Thyroid (T3/T4). Negative feedback suppresses TRH and TSH.",
"Anterior pituitary makes: FLAT PiG (FSH, LH, ACTH, TSH, Prolactin, GH). Posterior pituitary stores/releases: ADH + Oxytocin (made in hypothalamus)."
],
"Brain Anatomy":[
"Frontal lobe: motor cortex, prefrontal cortex (executive function, planning, personality). Broca's area (speech production).",
"Temporal lobe: auditory cortex, Wernicke's area (language comprehension), hippocampus (new declarative memories).",
"Parietal lobe: somatosensory cortex (touch, pain, temperature), spatial awareness. Damage: neglect syndrome.",
"Occipital lobe: primary visual cortex. Damage: cortical blindness.",
"Limbic system: amygdala (fear/emotion), hippocampus (memory), hypothalamus (homeostasis, hunger, thirst, temp, endocrine link).",
"Cerebellum: motor coordination, balance, motor learning. Basal ganglia: movement initiation/planning. Parkinson's (too little movement) vs Huntington's (too much)."
],
"Electron Transport Chain":[
"ETC is in the inner mitochondrial membrane. Complexes I-IV transfer electrons and pump H+ into the intermembrane space.",
"NADH enters at Complex I (pumps H+). FADH2 enters at Complex II (does NOT pump H+). Both feed electrons to CoQ.",
"Flow: NADH->I->CoQ->III->CytC->IV->O2. Each of I, III, IV pumps protons. O2 is the final electron acceptor (reduced to H2O).",
"ATP synthase (Complex V): protons flow back through Fo channel, driving rotational catalysis in F1 to make ATP (chemiosmosis).",
"NADH yields ~2.5 ATP (uses 3 proton pumps). FADH2 yields ~1.5 ATP (uses 2 pumps, skips Complex I).",
"Inhibitors: rotenone (I), antimycin A (III), cyanide/CO (IV), oligomycin (ATP synthase). Uncouplers (DNP): dissipate gradient as heat, INCREASE O2 use."
],
"Cardiovascular System":[
"Blood flow: vena cava -> RA -> RV -> pulmonary arteries -> lungs -> pulmonary veins -> LA -> LV -> aorta -> body.",
"SA node (right atrium) = pacemaker (60-100 bpm). Pathway: SA -> AV (delay) -> Bundle of His -> bundle branches -> Purkinje fibers.",
"BP highest in aorta, drops across arterioles (most resistance, R proportional to 1/r^4 by Poiseuille's law), lowest in veins.",
"Baroreceptors (carotid sinus/aortic arch): high BP -> more firing -> parasympathetic up -> HR down. Low BP -> opposite. Negative feedback.",
"RAAS: low BP -> renin -> angiotensin I -> ACE (lungs) -> angiotensin II -> vasoconstriction + aldosterone + ADH + thirst."
],
"Thermodynamics":[
"delta-G = delta-H - T*delta-S. Negative delta-G = spontaneous. At equilibrium, delta-G = 0.",
"Exothermic (H<0) + entropy increase (S>0) = always spontaneous. Endothermic + entropy decrease = never spontaneous.",
"delta-G-standard = -RT*ln(Keq). Large Keq = very negative delta-G-standard = strongly favors products.",
"Enthalpy (H): heat content. Exothermic releases heat (products lower energy). Endothermic absorbs heat.",
"Entropy (S): disorder. Increases with: more gas molecules, higher temperature, more particles, dissolution."
],
"Stereochemistry":[
"Stereocenter (chiral center): sp3 carbon with 4 different substituents. Max stereoisomers = 2^n.",
"Enantiomers: non-superimposable mirror images (ALL stereocenters inverted). Same physical properties except optical rotation and chiral interactions.",
"Diastereomers: stereoisomers that are NOT mirror images (some but not all stereocenters differ). Different physical properties.",
"Meso compounds: have stereocenters but an internal plane of symmetry. Achiral despite having stereocenters. Optically inactive.",
"R/S assignment: Cahn-Ingold-Prelog priority rules (by atomic number). Lowest priority pointing away: clockwise = R, counterclockwise = S.",
"SN2 = Walden inversion (backside attack). SN1 = racemization (planar carbocation, attack from either side)."
],
"Equilibrium":[
"At equilibrium: forward rate = reverse rate. Concentrations are constant but NOT necessarily equal. delta-G = 0, Q = K.",
"Le Chatelier: system opposes stress. Add reactant -> shifts right. Add product -> shifts left. Only temperature changes Keq.",
"For exothermic reactions: increasing T decreases Keq (treat heat as product). For endothermic: increasing T increases Keq.",
"Q vs K: Q < K -> forward favored (not yet at equilibrium). Q > K -> reverse favored. Q = K -> at equilibrium.",
"Catalysts lower activation energy and speed up BOTH directions equally. They do NOT change Keq or delta-G."
],
"Metabolic Regulation":[
"PFK-1 (glycolysis gatekeeper): activated by AMP, ADP, fructose-2,6-bisphosphate. Inhibited by ATP, citrate.",
"Fructose-2,6-bisphosphate (most potent PFK-1 activator) is made by PFK-2. Insulin activates PFK-2; glucagon inhibits it.",
"Fed state (insulin high): glycolysis ON, glycogen synthesis ON, lipogenesis ON. Fasting (glucagon high): gluconeogenesis ON, glycogenolysis ON, beta-oxidation ON.",
"PDH is activated by insulin and inhibited by its products (acetyl-CoA, NADH) and by phosphorylation (PDH kinase).",
"Key irreversible glycolysis steps (bypassed in gluconeogenesis): hexokinase, PFK-1, pyruvate kinase."
],
"Cell Cycle":[
"Phases: G1 (grow) -> S (DNA synthesis) -> G2 (prepare) -> M (mitosis + cytokinesis). G0 = quiescent (non-dividing).",
"Cyclin-CDK complexes drive transitions: Cyclin D/CDK4 (G1), Cyclin E/CDK2 (G1/S), Cyclin A/CDK2 (S), Cyclin B/CDK1 (M).",
"G1/S checkpoint: p53 detects DNA damage -> activates p21 (CDK inhibitor) -> arrests cycle. If damage irreparable, p53 triggers apoptosis.",
"Rb protein blocks E2F transcription factor. Phosphorylation by cyclin-CDK releases E2F -> S phase genes activated.",
"Tumor suppressors (p53, Rb): loss-of-function = cancer (need both alleles lost, two-hit). Oncogenes (Ras): gain-of-function = cancer (one allele sufficient)."
],
"Mendelian Genetics":[
"Aa x Aa: 1/4 AA, 2/4 Aa, 1/4 aa. Phenotype ratio 3:1 (dominant:recessive).",
"Dihybrid (AaBb x AaBb): 9:3:3:1 ratio. Both dominant = 9/16 = 3/4 x 3/4. Requires independent assortment.",
"Testcross: cross unknown phenotype with homozygous recessive (aa) to determine if AA or Aa.",
"Codominance: both alleles fully expressed (AB blood type). Incomplete dominance: intermediate phenotype (pink flowers).",
"Epistasis: one gene masks expression of another gene at a different locus. Modifies classic Mendelian ratios."
],
"Endocrine System":[
"Hypothalamus links nervous and endocrine systems. Releases hormones that control the anterior pituitary.",
"Anterior pituitary: FLAT PiG (FSH, LH, ACTH, TSH, Prolactin, GH). Posterior pituitary: stores ADH + Oxytocin.",
"Adrenal cortex: cortisol (stress, glucocorticoid), aldosterone (Na+/K+, mineralocorticoid), androgens. Adrenal medulla: epinephrine/norepinephrine.",
"Pancreas: beta-cells make insulin (fed state, lowers glucose). Alpha-cells make glucagon (fasting, raises glucose).",
"Thyroid: T3/T4 (metabolism). Parathyroid: PTH (raises Ca2+). Calcitonin (thyroid C-cells): lowers Ca2+."
],
"Solutions":[
"Molarity (M) = mol solute / L solution. Molality (m) = mol solute / kg solvent (used for colligative properties).",
"Colligative properties depend on NUMBER of particles, not identity: BP elevation (delta-Tb = iKbm), FP depression, osmotic pressure, VP lowering.",
"Van't Hoff factor i: NaCl=2, CaCl2=3, glucose=1. More particles = greater colligative effect.",
"Raoult's law: P = x_solvent * P_pure. Nonvolatile solute lowers vapor pressure.",
"Like dissolves like: polar/ionic in polar solvents (water). Nonpolar in nonpolar solvents (hexane)."
],
"Substitution Reactions":[
"SN2: one step, backside attack, Walden inversion. Rate = k[sub][nuc]. Favored: methyl > 1 > 2. Never 3. Strong nuc, polar aprotic.",
"SN1: two steps (carbocation intermediate), racemization. Rate = k[sub]. Favored: 3 > 2. Weak nuc, polar protic.",
"Good leaving groups are weak bases (stable anions): I- > Br- > Cl- >> F-. OH- is terrible (must protonate to H2O first).",
"Polar aprotic solvents (DMSO, acetone): keep nucleophile reactive -> favor SN2. Polar protic (water, MeOH): stabilize carbocation -> favor SN1.",
"Competition: strong nuc + primary = SN2. Weak nuc + tertiary = SN1. Bulky base + any = E2. Weak base + tertiary + heat = E1."
],
"Functional Groups":[
"Carbonyl (C=O): aldehydes (R-CHO, end of chain), ketones (R-CO-R', middle). Aldehydes more reactive (less steric hindrance).",
"Carboxylic acids (R-COOH): pKa ~4-5. More acidic than alcohols because conjugate base has resonance stabilization (two equivalent oxygens).",
"Esters (R-COO-R'): formed from acid + alcohol - water (Fischer esterification). Saponification: ester + NaOH -> soap + alcohol.",
"Amines: primary (RNH2), secondary (R2NH), tertiary (R3N). Basic (lone pair on N accepts H+). Amides (R-CO-NH2) are NOT basic (resonance delocalizes lone pair).",
"Alcohols: 1 (R-CH2OH), 2 (R2-CHOH), 3 (R3-COH). Oxidation: 1 -> aldehyde -> carboxylic acid. 2 -> ketone. 3 -> no reaction."
],
"Work and Energy":[
"W = Fd*cos(theta). Perpendicular = 0 work. Parallel = max positive work. Antiparallel = negative work (friction).",
"KE = 1/2mv^2. PE (gravitational) = mgh. Conservation: KE + PE = constant (without non-conservative forces).",
"Work-energy theorem: net work = change in KE. Power = work/time = Fv.",
"First law of thermodynamics: delta-U = Q - W (internal energy = heat added minus work done by system).",
"Conservative forces (gravity, electrostatic): path-independent, energy conserved. Non-conservative (friction): path-dependent, energy lost as heat."
],
"Learning and Conditioning":[
"Classical conditioning (Pavlov): NS paired with UCS -> NS becomes CS -> produces CR. Bell + food -> bell alone -> salivation.",
"Operant conditioning (Skinner): behavior shaped by consequences. Positive/negative = add/remove. Reinforcement/punishment = increase/decrease behavior.",
"Schedules: fixed ratio (fastest response), variable ratio (most resistant to extinction, e.g., gambling), fixed interval, variable interval.",
"Extinction: removing reinforcement -> behavior decreases. Spontaneous recovery: extinguished response briefly reappears after rest period.",
"Observational learning (Bandura): learn by watching others. Bobo doll study. Requires: attention, retention, reproduction, motivation."
],
"Sensation and Perception":[
"Absolute threshold: minimum stimulus detected 50% of the time. Difference threshold (JND): minimum detectable change.",
"Weber's Law: JND is proportional to stimulus intensity (delta-I/I = constant). Percent change matters, not absolute.",
"Signal detection theory: detection depends on both sensitivity (d-prime) and response criterion (willingness to say yes). Accounts for hits, misses, false alarms, correct rejections.",
"Sensory adaptation: receptors decrease firing for constant stimuli. Exception: pain (nociceptors adapt minimally).",
"Bottom-up processing: data-driven (raw sensation -> perception). Top-down: expectation-driven (prior knowledge guides perception)."
],
"Kinetics Parameters":[
"Km = [S] at half-Vmax. Low Km = high affinity (reaches half-speed with little substrate). High Km = low affinity.",
"Vmax = maximum rate when all active sites saturated. Vmax = kcat * [E]total. More enzyme = higher Vmax.",
"kcat/Km = catalytic efficiency (specificity constant). Diffusion-limited enzymes: kcat/Km around 10^8-10^9 /M/s.",
"Lineweaver-Burk plot (1/V vs 1/[S]): y-intercept = 1/Vmax, x-intercept = -1/Km, slope = Km/Vmax.",
"At [S] << Km: V is approximately proportional to [S] (first-order region). At [S] >> Km: V approaches Vmax (zero-order)."
],
"Aerobic Respiration":[
"Overall: C6H12O6 + 6O2 -> 6CO2 + 6H2O + 30-32 ATP (modern estimate, NOT 36-38).",
"Glycolysis (cytoplasm): glucose -> 2 pyruvate. Yields 2 ATP + 2 NADH. No O2 required.",
"PDH (mitochondrial matrix): pyruvate -> acetyl-CoA + CO2 + NADH. Irreversible. 5 cofactors (B1,B2,B3,B5,lipoate).",
"Krebs cycle (matrix): per turn = 3 NADH + 1 FADH2 + 1 GTP + 2 CO2. Per glucose = double everything.",
"ETC + oxidative phosphorylation (inner membrane): NADH->2.5 ATP, FADH2->1.5 ATP. O2 = final electron acceptor."
],
"Oxidative Phosphorylation":[
"Chemiosmotic hypothesis (Mitchell): ETC pumps H+ into intermembrane space, creating a proton gradient. ATP synthase uses this gradient to make ATP.",
"ATP synthase is a rotary motor: H+ flows through Fo channel -> rotates c-ring -> drives conformational changes in F1 -> ADP + Pi -> ATP.",
"P/O ratio: NADH ~2.5 ATP (electrons enter at Complex I, use 3 proton pumps). FADH2 ~1.5 ATP (enters at Complex II, use 2 pumps).",
"Uncouplers (DNP, thermogenin in brown fat): make membrane leaky to H+. Gradient dissipates as heat. O2 consumption INCREASES but ATP decreases.",
"Oligomycin blocks the Fo proton channel of ATP synthase. Stops ATP production AND slows ETC (gradient builds up with nowhere to go)."
],
"Organelles":[
"Nucleus: contains DNA, site of transcription and DNA replication. Nuclear envelope has nuclear pores for mRNA export.",
"Rough ER: ribosomes on surface, synthesizes secretory/membrane proteins. Signal peptide + SRP directs to ER. N-linked glycosylation occurs here.",
"Smooth ER: lipid synthesis, steroid hormone production, detoxification (cytochrome P450), calcium storage.",
"Golgi apparatus: modifies (O-linked glycosylation), sorts (mannose-6-phosphate tag for lysosomes), and packages proteins.",
"Mitochondria: double membrane, own DNA (maternal inheritance), site of Krebs cycle (matrix) and ETC (inner membrane). Apoptosis trigger (cytochrome c release).",
"Lysosomes: pH ~5, acid hydrolases for recycling. Storage diseases = enzyme deficiency (Tay-Sachs, Gaucher's, Pompe's)."
],
"Membrane Transport":[
"Simple diffusion: small nonpolar molecules (O2, CO2, steroid hormones) cross directly. No protein, no energy.",
"Facilitated diffusion: polar/charged molecules use channel or carrier proteins. No energy, DOWN gradient. Example: GLUT transporters for glucose.",
"Primary active transport: directly uses ATP. Na+/K+ ATPase (3 Na+ out, 2 K+ in), Ca2+ ATPase (SERCA), H+/K+ ATPase (stomach acid).",
"Secondary active transport: uses gradient from primary active transport. Symport (SGLT1: Na+ and glucose same direction) or antiport (Na+/H+ exchanger).",
"Osmosis: water moves toward higher solute concentration across semipermeable membrane. Hypo = swell, Hyper = shrink, Iso = no change."
],
"Population Genetics":[
"Hardy-Weinberg: p^2 + 2pq + q^2 = 1. p + q = 1. q^2 = frequency of affected (homozygous recessive).",
"HW conditions: large population, random mating, no selection, no mutation, no migration. Violation -> allele frequencies change.",
"Carriers (2pq) vastly outnumber affected (q^2) for rare recessive diseases.",
"Genetic drift: random changes in allele frequency, especially in small populations. Bottleneck and founder effects.",
"Natural selection: differential survival/reproduction. Directional (favors one extreme), stabilizing (favors average), disruptive (favors both extremes)."
],
"Immune System":[
"Innate: immediate, nonspecific, no memory. Barriers (skin, mucus), cells (neutrophils, macrophages, NK cells, dendritic cells), complement, inflammation.",
"Adaptive: slower (days on first exposure), specific, has MEMORY. Humoral (B cells -> antibodies) and cell-mediated (T cells -> kill infected cells).",
"MHC I: on ALL nucleated cells, presents intracellular antigens to CD8+ cytotoxic T cells. MHC II: on APCs only, presents extracellular antigens to CD4+ helper T cells.",
"Antibody classes: IgM (first, pentamer), IgG (most abundant, crosses placenta), IgA (mucosa, breast milk), IgE (allergy/parasites), IgD (B cell surface).",
"T cell maturation in thymus: positive selection (must recognize self-MHC) then negative selection (must NOT react to self-antigens). ~2% survive."
]
};
