var PASSAGES={
p1:{text:"A researcher investigates enzyme X. She measures initial velocity at varying [S] with and without 10mM inhibitor I. With inhibitor: Vmax decreases from 100 to 50 umol/min, and Km decreases from 8mM to 4mM. A Lineweaver-Burk plot shows two parallel lines."},
p2:{text:"A patient presents with fatigue and jaundice. Labs show elevated unconjugated bilirubin, low haptoglobin, elevated LDH, and reticulocyte count of 8% (normal <2%). Peripheral blood smear reveals spherocytes. Direct antiglobulin test (Coombs) is positive."},
p3:{text:"Researchers isolate an enzyme from an extremophilic bacterium. It maintains >90% activity between pH 2-10. When they mutate histidine-57 to alanine, the enzyme loses all catalytic activity despite maintaining its tertiary structure."},
p4:{text:"An experiment measures O2 consumption in isolated mitochondria. With NADH as electron donor, O2 consumption is robust. Adding rotenone completely stops O2 consumption. When succinate is then added, O2 consumption resumes at a reduced rate."},
p5:{text:"A genetics study examines a rare autosomal recessive disorder in a population of 10,000. Twenty-five individuals are affected. Researchers want to determine carrier frequency."},
p6:{text:"A neuroscience lab measures action potentials in myelinated neurons. They apply tetrodotoxin (TTX, blocks voltage-gated Na+ channels) to one node of Ranvier and tetraethylammonium (TEA, blocks voltage-gated K+ channels) to a different node."},
p7:{text:"Participants are placed in a room with 7 confederates who unanimously give an obviously wrong answer to a simple line-length comparison. Researchers measure how often the real participant conforms across 18 trials."},
p8:{text:"Fibroblasts are exposed to increasing UV radiation. After 24h, flow cytometry shows: at low UV doses, cells arrest at G1/S boundary. At high UV doses, widespread apoptosis with caspase-3 activation occurs."},
p9:{text:"Drug A structurally resembles the substrate of enzyme Z. Drug B binds a regulatory site on enzyme Z that only appears when substrate is already bound. With Drug A, increasing [S] restores normal activity. With Drug B, increasing [S] does NOT restore activity."},
c1:{text:"Structural violence, first described by Galtung in 1969, refers to social structures that systematically disadvantage certain groups. Unlike direct violence, it is embedded in political and economic systems, producing inequality without any single actor intending harm. Paul Farmer showed that TB outcomes in Haiti were shaped by poverty rather than biology, demonstrating that 'personal health choices' are constrained by social position. Critics argue the concept dilutes 'violence' beyond usefulness by conflating poverty with assault."},
c2:{text:"Patient autonomy holds that competent individuals may make their own medical decisions, even against medical advice. This emerged as a reaction to historical paternalism. Yet autonomy is not absolute: emergency medicine overrides wishes when consent is impossible, and psychiatric commitment restricts autonomy to prevent harm. In collectivist cultures, medical decisions are made by families, and insisting on individual autonomy may itself be a form of cultural imposition."},
c3:{text:"Durkheim argued deviance serves essential social functions: clarifying moral boundaries, reinforcing norms, and driving social change. Merton extended this with strain theory, arguing deviance results from a disconnect between culturally valued goals and legitimate means to achieve them. When paths to success are blocked, people adapt -- some innovate through crime, others retreat into substance abuse, and still others rebel by rejecting both goals and means."},
p11:{text:"A patient with a thyroid nodule undergoes blood work. Results show: TSH is very low (0.1 mIU/L, normal 0.4-4.0), free T4 is elevated (4.2 ng/dL, normal 0.8-1.8), and free T3 is elevated. The patient reports weight loss, heat intolerance, tremors, and palpitations. Physical exam reveals exophthalmos (bulging eyes)."},
p12:{text:"Researchers study a membrane protein that transports glucose into intestinal epithelial cells. On the apical (lumen-facing) side, glucose enters via SGLT1, a sodium-glucose cotransporter that moves glucose against its concentration gradient by coupling it to Na+ influx. On the basolateral side, glucose exits via GLUT2, a facilitated diffusion transporter. The Na+/K+ ATPase on the basolateral membrane maintains the Na+ gradient that drives SGLT1."},
c4:{text:"The biomedical model of health defines disease as a deviation from measurable biological norms -- a broken machine to be fixed through medical intervention. This model has produced remarkable advances: antibiotics, surgical techniques, and diagnostic imaging have transformed medicine. Yet the biomedical model has been criticized for neglecting psychological and social dimensions of illness. A patient with chronic pain may have no identifiable tissue damage. A person with controlled HIV may face greater suffering from stigma than from the virus itself. The biopsychosocial model, proposed by George Engel in 1977, argues that health and illness emerge from the interaction of biological factors (genetics, physiology), psychological factors (mood, personality, coping), and social factors (family, SES, culture). This model does not reject biology but embeds it within a broader context."},
p20:{text:"Researchers investigate the effect of a novel drug, Compound X, on cholesterol biosynthesis in cultured human hepatocytes. Cholesterol synthesis proceeds through the mevalonate pathway: HMG-CoA is converted to mevalonate by HMG-CoA reductase, the rate-limiting enzyme, which is then converted through several steps to squalene and ultimately cholesterol. The researchers measure HMG-CoA reductase activity, mRNA levels, and protein concentration under several experimental conditions. In Experiment 1, hepatocytes are treated with increasing concentrations of Compound X (0, 10, 50, 100, and 500 nM) for 24 hours. Results are shown in Table 1: at 0 nM, enzyme activity is 100%, mRNA is 100%, and protein level is 100%. At 10 nM, activity drops to 75%, mRNA is 98%, protein is 99%. At 50 nM, activity is 40%, mRNA is 97%, protein is 98%. At 100 nM, activity is 15%, mRNA is 95%, protein is 97%. At 500 nM, activity is 3%, mRNA is 93%, protein is 96%. In Experiment 2, cells are treated with 100 nM Compound X, then increasing concentrations of HMG-CoA substrate are added. At 10x normal substrate concentration, enzyme activity recovers to 85% of untreated levels. In Experiment 3, mevalonate is added directly to Compound X-treated cells. Cholesterol synthesis proceeds normally, confirming that all downstream enzymes are functional. In Experiment 4, Compound X is removed by washing, and enzyme activity returns to 90% within 4 hours, indicating reversible binding. The researchers note that Compound X is structurally similar to HMG-CoA, sharing the same hydroxymethylglutaryl moiety but with a modified CoA tail."},
p21:{text:"A clinical study examines a patient with suspected McArdle disease (glycogen storage disease type V). During an exercise test, the patient experiences severe muscle cramps and fatigue within 2 minutes. Blood lactate levels fail to rise during exercise (normal response: 3-5 fold increase). However, blood ammonia levels increase normally. A muscle biopsy shows excess glycogen accumulation. The enzyme deficient in McArdle disease is myophosphorylase, the muscle-specific form of glycogen phosphorylase."},
p22:{text:"Scientists study a bacterial operon that controls tryptophan biosynthesis. When tryptophan is abundant in the growth medium, the operon is repressed and the biosynthetic enzymes are not produced. When tryptophan is scarce, the operon is active and all five biosynthetic enzymes are expressed. The researchers create a mutant strain in which the repressor protein cannot bind tryptophan. They also create a second mutant in which the operator sequence is altered so no protein can bind to it."},
p23:{text:"Researchers measure membrane potential changes in cardiac pacemaker cells of the SA node. Unlike typical neurons, these cells do not have a stable resting potential. Instead, they exhibit a slow, spontaneous depolarization during diastole (phase 4) due to funny current (If) -- a mixed Na+/K+ inward current through HCN channels. When the membrane reaches threshold (~-40mV), voltage-gated Ca2+ channels (L-type) open, producing the upstroke. Repolarization occurs through K+ efflux. The parasympathetic neurotransmitter acetylcholine slows phase 4 depolarization, while sympathetic norepinephrine accelerates it."},
p24:{text:"A biochemistry experiment compares two patients with jaundice. Patient A has elevated unconjugated (indirect) bilirubin, normal conjugated (direct) bilirubin, and normal liver enzymes (AST, ALT). Patient B has elevated conjugated (direct) bilirubin, dark urine, pale stools, and markedly elevated alkaline phosphatase. Both patients have yellowish sclera. Bilirubin is produced from heme degradation: heme -> biliverdin -> unconjugated bilirubin (carried by albumin) -> conjugated in liver by UDP-glucuronosyltransferase -> excreted in bile."},
p25:{text:"A chemistry lab performs a titration to characterize the acid-base properties of an unknown weak acid, HA. They dissolve 0.500 g of the purified acid (molecular weight = 100 g/mol) in 50.0 mL of distilled water and titrate with standardized 0.100 M NaOH, recording pH after each addition. The neutralization reaction is: HA + NaOH -> NaA + H2O. Selected data points from the titration curve are presented in Table 1. At 0 mL NaOH added, pH = 2.88. At 10 mL, pH = 4.26. At 25 mL, pH = 4.76. At 40 mL, pH = 5.26. At 50 mL, pH = 8.72. At 60 mL, pH = 12.05. At 75 mL, pH = 12.70. The students observe that the buffering region, where pH changes least per mL of NaOH added, extends from approximately 15 mL to 35 mL. Outside this region, pH changes rapidly with small additions of base. They calculate the initial concentration of HA: 0.500 g divided by 100 g/mol = 0.00500 mol in 50.0 mL, giving 0.100 M. At the equivalence point (50 mL NaOH), moles of NaOH added equals 0.100 M times 0.050 L = 0.00500 mol, confirming the 1:1 stoichiometry. The equivalence point pH of 8.72 is above 7.00, which the students note is characteristic of weak acid-strong base titrations. A second group repeats the experiment using a diprotic acid, H2A (two ionizable protons, pKa1 = 3.0, pKa2 = 7.0), and observes two distinct equivalence points and two half-equivalence plateaus in their titration curve."},
p26:{text:"A physics experiment measures the behavior of light passing through different media. A beam of light travels from air (n=1.00) into glass (n=1.50) at an angle of incidence of 45 degrees. Using Snell's law, the researchers calculate the angle of refraction. They then direct light from glass into air and gradually increase the angle of incidence until total internal reflection occurs. They also observe that the wavelength of light decreases inside the glass while the frequency remains unchanged."},
p27:{text:"An electrochemistry lab constructs and characterizes a galvanic cell. The cell consists of a zinc electrode immersed in 1.00 M ZnSO4 solution and a copper electrode immersed in 1.00 M CuSO4 solution, connected by a KNO3 salt bridge. Standard reduction potentials are: Zn2+/Zn, E-standard = -0.76 V; Cu2+/Cu, E-standard = +0.34 V. Under standard conditions, the measured cell voltage is 1.10 V. The students then systematically vary conditions and record the cell voltage in Table 1. Trial 1 (standard): [Zn2+] = 1.0 M, [Cu2+] = 1.0 M, E-cell = 1.10 V. Trial 2: [Zn2+] = 1.0 M, [Cu2+] = 0.01 M, E-cell = 1.04 V. Trial 3: [Zn2+] = 0.01 M, [Cu2+] = 1.0 M, E-cell = 1.16 V. Trial 4: [Zn2+] = 1.0 M, [Cu2+] = 1.0 M, temperature raised from 25 degrees C to 50 degrees C, E-cell = 1.08 V. The net cell reaction is: Zn(s) + Cu2+(aq) -> Zn2+(aq) + Cu(s). Over time, students observe that the zinc electrode loses mass while the copper electrode gains mass. The salt bridge is periodically tested; removing it causes the voltage to drop to zero immediately. In a separate experiment, the students construct an electrolytic cell using the same electrodes but with an external power supply of 2.0 V. They observe that the reactions reverse: copper dissolves and zinc plates out, and the minimum voltage required to drive this non-spontaneous process is greater than 1.10 V."},
p28:{text:"A calorimetry experiment measures the specific heat of an unknown metal. A 150g sample of the metal is heated to 100C in boiling water, then transferred to 200g of water at 25C in an insulated calorimeter. The final equilibrium temperature is 28.5C. The specific heat of water is 4.184 J/g-C. The students assume no heat is lost to the surroundings and apply the principle that heat lost by the metal equals heat gained by the water."},
p29:{text:"A developmental psychology study examines theory of mind in children ages 3-5 using the Sally-Anne false belief test. Sally places a marble in a basket and leaves the room. Anne moves the marble to a box while Sally is away. When Sally returns, children are asked where Sally will look for her marble. Results: 85% of 3-year-olds say Sally will look in the box (where the marble actually is), while 75% of 5-year-olds correctly say Sally will look in the basket (where she left it)."},
p30:{text:"Researchers conduct a study on stereotype threat and academic performance. Two hundred college students (100 female, 100 male), matched for prior math achievement (mean SAT math score: 680 for both groups), are randomly assigned to one of three experimental conditions before taking a challenging 30-question math test. In Condition A (threat activated), participants read: 'This test has consistently shown gender differences in performance.' In Condition B (threat nullified), participants read: 'This test has never shown any gender differences.' In Condition C (control), participants receive no statement about gender differences. Results are presented in Table 1, showing mean score (out of 30), standard deviation, and statistical comparisons. Condition A: Women scored 17.2 (SD=4.1), Men scored 22.8 (SD=3.9), difference p<0.001. Condition B: Women scored 22.5 (SD=4.3), Men scored 22.9 (SD=4.0), difference p=0.62 (not significant). Condition C: Women scored 19.8 (SD=4.5), Men scored 22.4 (SD=4.2), difference p=0.01. Additional measures are collected. Self-reported anxiety (1-10 scale): Condition A women report 7.3 versus 4.1 for men; Condition B shows no significant difference (4.5 vs 4.2). Working memory capacity, measured by an operation span task administered after the math test: Condition A women show a 22% decrease relative to their baseline, while men show no change. Condition B shows no decrease for either gender. The researchers also assess test completion rate: in Condition A, women attempt only 24.1 of 30 questions (versus 28.5 for men). In Condition B, both groups attempt approximately 28 questions. A follow-up study finds that a brief self-affirmation exercise (writing about a personal value) before Condition A reduces the gender gap by 60%."},
p31:{text:"A social psychology experiment examines the effects of cognitive load on decision-making. Participants are divided into two groups. The high-load group must memorize a 7-digit number while making food choices. The low-load group memorizes a 2-digit number. Both groups are then offered a choice between fruit salad and chocolate cake. Results: 63% of the high-load group chose cake versus 41% of the low-load group (p<0.05). Researchers also measured response time, finding the high-load group made faster decisions."},
c5:{text:"The concept of wilderness as pristine, untouched nature is itself a cultural construction. William Cronon argues that the wilderness ideal emerged from 19th-century Romanticism and the frontier myth, not from ecological reality. Indigenous peoples had shaped North American landscapes for thousands of years through controlled burning, selective cultivation, and wildlife management. What European colonists encountered was not virgin wilderness but a carefully managed environment whose stewards had been decimated by disease and displacement. The irony, Cronon suggests, is that preserving wilderness as untouched often requires removing the very human communities whose practices created and maintained it. Conservation that fetishizes pristine nature may paradoxically harm both ecosystems and indigenous rights."},
c6:{text:"Thomas Kuhn's The Structure of Scientific Revolutions, published in 1962, fundamentally altered how philosophers and historians understand scientific progress. Against the prevailing view that science advances through steady, cumulative accumulation of knowledge, Kuhn argued that scientific development alternates between two distinct phases. During periods of normal science, which constitute the vast majority of scientific activity, researchers work within an accepted paradigm -- a shared framework of theories, methods, instrumentation, and standards that defines both legitimate problems and acceptable solutions. Scientists engaged in normal science are not testing the paradigm itself; they are solving puzzles that the paradigm defines. Anomalies -- observations that resist explanation within the current paradigm -- are initially set aside, reinterpreted, or attributed to experimental error rather than taken as evidence against the paradigm. Only when anomalies accumulate to the point of creating a genuine crisis does the scientific community become open to revolutionary science: the proposal and eventual adoption of a new paradigm that reframes the field's fundamental assumptions. Kuhn's most controversial claim was that successive paradigms are incommensurable. By this he meant not merely that paradigms disagree about specific facts, but that they define different problems as important, employ different standards of evidence, and even use the same terms to mean different things. The shift from Newtonian to Einsteinian physics, for example, did not simply add new equations; it redefined the meaning of mass, space, and time. Critics have argued that incommensurability, taken literally, would make scientific progress impossible to evaluate. If paradigms cannot be compared, how can we claim that Einstein's physics is better than Newton's? Larry Laudan, for instance, argued that Kuhn confuses the difficulty of comparison with its impossibility, and that empirical adequacy provides a cross-paradigm standard. Kuhn himself softened his position in later writings, acknowledging that paradigms can be compared on criteria such as accuracy, scope, and fruitfulness, even if no single criterion is decisive."},
c7:{text:"The trolley problem has dominated moral philosophy for decades, yet its relevance to real ethical dilemmas has been questioned. Critics argue that trolley-style thought experiments strip away the contextual richness that characterizes actual moral decisions. In reality, we rarely face choices between clearly defined outcomes with known probabilities. Moreover, the utilitarian framing -- maximize lives saved -- assumes a consequentialist framework that many ethical traditions reject. Virtue ethicists ask not 'what should I do?' but 'what kind of person should I be?' Care ethicists emphasize relationships and responsibilities over abstract calculations. By narrowing moral reasoning to a single calculus, the trolley problem may distort rather than illuminate how people actually navigate ethical complexity."},
p40:{text:"A biochemistry research group investigates the thermodynamics and kinetics of lysozyme folding using multiple complementary techniques. Lysozyme (14.3 kDa, 129 amino acids, 4 disulfide bonds) is selected as a model protein. In Experiment 1, they monitor unfolding by circular dichroism (CD) spectroscopy at 222 nm, which measures alpha-helical content. Native lysozyme shows a strong negative signal at 222 nm. As urea concentration increases from 0 to 8 M, results are as follows: at 0 M urea, CD signal is -100% (fully folded) and enzyme activity is 100%. At 2 M, CD is -95% and activity is 92%. At 3 M, CD is -70% and activity is 55%. At 4 M, CD is -25% and activity is 12%. At 5 M, CD is -8% and activity is 3%. At 8 M, CD is -2% and activity is less than 1%. The transition is cooperative, occurring primarily between 3-5 M urea. In Experiment 2, denatured lysozyme (8 M urea) is diluted into buffer without urea. Refolding is monitored by recovery of both CD signal and enzyme activity. Results: 80% of native CD signal and 78% of enzyme activity recover within 2 hours. Adding molecular chaperone GroEL increases recovery to 95%. In Experiment 3, the researchers add 10 mM DTT (a reducing agent) before attempting refolding. In the presence of DTT, only 15% of CD signal and 5% of enzyme activity recover, even with extended incubation. When DTT is removed and the oxidizing agent GSSG is added, recovery improves to 70%. In Experiment 4, differential scanning calorimetry measures the melting temperature (Tm) of lysozyme at different pH values: pH 2.0, Tm = 45 degrees C; pH 5.0, Tm = 72 degrees C; pH 7.0, Tm = 76 degrees C; pH 9.0, Tm = 68 degrees C."},
p41:{text:"A 35-year-old woman presents to the neurology clinic with progressive fatigue, exercise intolerance, and bilateral ptosis over the past 2 years. She reports that mild exertion, such as climbing one flight of stairs, causes severe muscle pain and shortness of breath. Family history reveals her mother and maternal uncle had similar symptoms; her father is unaffected. Laboratory findings are presented in Table 1. Serum lactate at rest: 4.2 mmol/L (normal: 0.5-2.2). Serum lactate after 10 minutes of light cycling: 12.8 mmol/L (normal response: 2-4x baseline). Serum pyruvate: 0.18 mmol/L (normal). Lactate-to-pyruvate ratio: 23:1 (normal: less than 15:1). Creatine kinase: 280 U/L (mildly elevated). Blood glucose and ammonia are normal. Muscle biopsy reveals ragged-red fibers on Gomori trichrome stain, indicating subsarcolemmal mitochondrial proliferation. Electron microscopy shows abnormal mitochondrial morphology with paracrystalline inclusions. Enzyme activity assays from the biopsy are presented in Table 2. Complex I (NADH dehydrogenase): 12% of normal control. Complex II (succinate dehydrogenase): 98% of normal control. Complex III (cytochrome bc1): 45% of normal control. Complex IV (cytochrome c oxidase): 38% of normal control. ATP synthase (Complex V): 85% of normal control. Citrate synthase (matrix marker): 250% of normal (indicating mitochondrial proliferation as compensation). Genetic testing reveals a heteroplasmic point mutation in the mitochondrial tRNA-Leu gene at position 3243 (A3243G), present at 78% mutant load in muscle tissue and 45% in blood leukocytes."},
p42:{text:"Scientists study a novel signaling pathway by treating cultured cells with Growth Factor X (GFX). Within 30 seconds, they detect phosphorylation of a receptor tyrosine kinase (RTK). By 2 minutes, Ras-GTP levels increase 5-fold. By 5 minutes, the MAP kinase cascade is activated, and by 15 minutes, transcription factor phosphorylation is detected in the nucleus. Adding a competitive inhibitor of Ras-GTPase-activating protein (GAP) prolongs Ras activation and amplifies downstream signaling. Cells with a mutation that locks Ras in the GTP-bound state show constitutive MAP kinase activation even without GFX."},
p43:{text:"A genetics experiment crosses a heterozygous black guinea pig (Bb) with a white guinea pig (bb). They produce 40 offspring. Expected Mendelian ratio is 1:1 (black:white). Observed results: 24 black, 16 white. To determine if the deviation from expected is statistically significant, the researchers perform a chi-squared test. They calculate chi-squared = (24-20)^2/20 + (16-20)^2/20 = 0.8+0.8 = 1.6. With 1 degree of freedom, the critical value at p=0.05 is 3.84."},
p44:{text:"Researchers investigate nephron physiology by performing micropuncture studies on rat kidneys. They measure solute concentrations, osmolarity, and transporter expression at four key points along the nephron. The results are presented in Table 1, showing values in the proximal convoluted tubule (PCT), the descending limb of the loop of Henle, the ascending limb, and the collecting duct. In the PCT: glucose concentration drops from 100 mg/dL in filtrate to 0 mg/dL (100% reabsorbed); Na+ is reduced by 65%; osmolarity remains approximately 300 mOsm/L (isosmotic reabsorption); and both SGLT2 and Na+/K+ ATPase are highly expressed. In the descending limb: water exits freely through aquaporin-1 channels; Na+ concentration increases passively; and osmolarity rises to approximately 1200 mOsm/L at the bend. In the thick ascending limb: the NKCC2 cotransporter actively reabsorbs Na+, K+, and Cl-; no water channels are present (impermeable to water); and osmolarity drops to approximately 100 mOsm/L (diluting segment). In the collecting duct: water reabsorption varies with ADH levels via aquaporin-2 insertion; the principal cells respond to aldosterone by increasing ENaC sodium channels; and final osmolarity ranges from 50 mOsm/L (maximally dilute, no ADH) to 1200 mOsm/L (maximally concentrated, high ADH). In a second experiment, the researchers administer furosemide, a loop diuretic that blocks NKCC2 in the thick ascending limb. After furosemide administration, urine output increases 5-fold, urine osmolarity drops to 300 mOsm/L, and the medullary concentration gradient is abolished. They also note that serum K+ decreases from 4.2 to 3.1 mEq/L after furosemide treatment."},
p45:{text:"A pulmonary function lab measures gas exchange in a patient at rest and during exercise. At rest: PaO2 = 95 mmHg, PaCO2 = 40 mmHg, oxygen saturation = 97%. During moderate exercise: PaO2 = 95 mmHg, PaCO2 = 40 mmHg, O2 consumption increases 3-fold. During heavy exercise: PaO2 = 90 mmHg, PaCO2 = 35 mmHg, blood pH = 7.35, respiratory rate increases from 15 to 35 breaths/min. Adding supplemental oxygen during heavy exercise does not significantly improve performance."},
p46:{text:"Electron micrographs show a cell actively secreting digestive enzymes. The cell has extensive rough ER, prominent Golgi apparatus, and numerous secretory vesicles at the apical membrane. Researchers label newly synthesized proteins with radioactive leucine and track their location over time. At 5 minutes, radioactivity is concentrated in the rough ER. At 15 minutes, it appears in the Golgi. At 30 minutes, labeled protein is found in secretory vesicles. At 45 minutes, radioactivity is detected outside the cell."},
p47:{text:"A biochemistry lab measures the kinetics of an enzyme with and without an unknown inhibitor. They generate the following Lineweaver-Burk (double-reciprocal) data: Without inhibitor: y-intercept = 0.02, x-intercept = -0.5. With inhibitor: y-intercept = 0.02, x-intercept = -0.25. Both lines intersect at the y-axis. The enzyme follows Michaelis-Menten kinetics."},
p48:{text:"An organic chemistry experiment compares reaction rates of four alkyl halides with NaOH in an acetone-water mixture: methyl bromide reacts fastest with complete inversion of stereochemistry. Tert-butyl bromide reacts slowly with NaOH but quickly when water alone is used, producing a racemic mixture. Isopropyl bromide gives a mixture of substitution and elimination products. Neopentyl bromide (2,2-dimethyl-1-bromopropane) reacts extremely slowly under all conditions."},
p49:{text:"A nuclear medicine department uses technetium-99m (Tc-99m) for diagnostic imaging. Tc-99m has a half-life of 6 hours and decays by gamma emission. A patient receives an injection of 800 MBq of Tc-99m at 8:00 AM. The imaging procedure is performed at 2:00 PM. Tc-99m is produced from molybdenum-99 (half-life 66 hours) in a generator system on-site."},
p50:{text:"Researchers in a cardiovascular physiology lab study the relationship between vessel geometry and blood flow using an in vitro model. They pump fluid through rigid tubes of varying diameter at constant pressure and measure flow rate. The fluid used has a viscosity of 3.0 centipoise (similar to blood). Results are presented in Table 1 for tubes of length 10 cm at a pressure difference of 100 mmHg. Tube A: radius 2.0 mm, flow rate 320 mL/min. Tube B: radius 1.5 mm, flow rate 101 mL/min. Tube C: radius 1.0 mm, flow rate 20 mL/min. Tube D: radius 0.5 mm, flow rate 1.25 mL/min. The researchers verify that these results fit Poiseuille's equation: Q = (pi times r-to-the-fourth times delta-P) divided by (8 times viscosity times length). In a second experiment, they test the effect of viscosity changes by increasing the fluid viscosity from 3.0 to 6.0 centipoise (simulating polycythemia) while keeping Tube A dimensions constant. Flow rate decreases from 320 to 160 mL/min. In a third experiment, they model a stenosis by inserting a 1 cm constriction (radius reduced from 2.0 mm to 1.0 mm) into Tube A while keeping the rest at 2.0 mm radius. Total flow through the tube drops by 85%. The researchers note that the body compensates for such stenoses by increasing blood pressure and by collateral vessel development. They also measure the velocity profile across the tube diameter and confirm that flow is laminar (parabolic velocity profile) at the flow rates tested, with maximum velocity at the center of the tube equal to twice the average velocity."},
p51:{text:"Cognitive psychologists investigate the effects of encoding strategy on long-term memory retention. One hundred and fifty college students are randomly assigned to three groups (n=50 each) and presented with a list of 40 common English nouns, each displayed for 8 seconds. Group A (structural processing) judges whether each word is printed in uppercase or lowercase letters. Group B (acoustic processing) judges whether each word rhymes with a given target word. Group C (semantic processing) judges whether each word fits meaningfully into a sentence describing a personal experience. A surprise free-recall test is administered at three time points: immediately after encoding, after a 24-hour delay, and after a one-week delay. Results are presented in Table 1 as mean number of words recalled (out of 40). Immediate recall: Group A = 12.3 (SD=3.1), Group B = 19.5 (SD=3.8), Group C = 28.2 (SD=4.0). 24-hour recall: Group A = 7.8 (SD=2.9), Group B = 14.6 (SD=3.5), Group C = 25.8 (SD=3.7). One-week recall: Group A = 4.2 (SD=2.4), Group B = 9.1 (SD=3.2), Group C = 21.5 (SD=4.1). The researchers calculate the forgetting rate as percentage lost from immediate to one-week recall: Group A loses 66%, Group B loses 53%, Group C loses 24%. In a follow-up experiment, they add Group D, which uses semantic processing plus retrieval practice (recalling words from memory after initial encoding, rather than re-studying). Group D's one-week recall is 29.8 out of 40 -- significantly higher than Group C (p<0.01). Error analysis reveals that Group A's recalled words tend to share visual features (similar word length), Group B's share phonological features (similar sounds), and Group C's cluster by semantic category (related meanings)."},
p52:{text:"A sociological study examines health outcomes across socioeconomic strata in an urban area. Researchers find that residents of the lowest-income neighborhoods have: life expectancy 12 years shorter than the wealthiest neighborhoods, 3x higher rates of diabetes, 2x higher rates of depression, and significantly fewer grocery stores per capita (food deserts). After controlling for individual health behaviors (diet, exercise, smoking), the income-based health gap decreases by 40% but remains statistically significant."},
p53:{text:"A clinical trial tests a new antidepressant (Drug Y) that selectively inhibits serotonin reuptake. 200 patients with major depressive disorder are randomized to Drug Y or placebo for 8 weeks. Results: Drug Y group shows 45% improvement on the Hamilton Depression Scale vs 30% for placebo (p=0.03). Side effects include sexual dysfunction (25%), weight gain (15%), and insomnia (10%). Brain imaging shows Drug Y increases serotonin levels in the synaptic cleft within 2 hours, but clinical improvement takes 4-6 weeks."},
c8:{text:"The concept of meritocracy -- that success should be determined by talent and effort rather than birth -- has become the dominant legitimizing ideology of modern inequality. Michael Young, who coined the term in 1958 as a dystopian warning, watched in dismay as it was adopted as an aspirational ideal. The meritocratic promise contains a cruel paradox: if we accept that success reflects merit, then failure must reflect its absence. Those at the bottom deserve to be there. The meritocratic framework thus transforms structural disadvantage into personal inadequacy, making inequality appear natural and just. Studies consistently show that belief in meritocracy correlates with reduced support for redistributive policies and increased blame toward the poor, even when presented with evidence of systemic barriers."},
c9:{text:"The replication crisis in psychology has forced a reckoning with how science actually works. Between 2011 and 2015, large-scale replication projects found that only 36-39% of published psychology findings could be reliably reproduced. The causes are multiple: publication bias favoring positive results, small sample sizes inflating effect sizes, flexible data analysis (p-hacking), and perverse career incentives that reward novelty over rigor. Some have argued this crisis reveals fundamental flaws in the scientific method itself. But this conclusion mistakes the disease for the cure. The crisis was discovered through scientific methods -- replication, meta-analysis, statistical reform. Science corrected itself. The real lesson is not that science fails but that science without institutional safeguards against human bias produces unreliable knowledge."},
c10:{text:"The debate over genetic enhancement raises questions that existing ethical frameworks struggle to answer. If gene therapy can cure sickle cell disease by correcting a single mutation, few object. But what if the same technology could enhance memory, increase height, or select for specific personality traits? The line between treatment and enhancement blurs upon examination: treating growth hormone deficiency is accepted, but using the same hormone to make an average-height child taller is controversial. Some bioethicists argue for a principle of genetic conservatism -- that we should not alter the human germline because we cannot predict long-term consequences across generations. Others counter that refusing to enhance when we have the capability is itself a choice with moral consequences, condemning future generations to preventable suffering."},
};

// QUESTION TYPES: "mc" = multiple choice, "match" = matching
var QS=[
// ============ ENZYME KINETICS (16) ============
{id:"ek1",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Kinetics Parameters"],diff:2,q:"In uncompetitive inhibition, what happens to Km and Vmax?",o:["Both decrease","Km increases, Vmax decreases","Both increase","Km decreases, Vmax unchanged"],a:0,ex:"The inhibitor only binds the enzyme-substrate (ES) complex, creating a dead-end ESI complex. This traps ES, and by Le Chatelier's principle, the equilibrium E + S <-> ES shifts right to compensate -- the enzyme appears to have higher affinity (lower Km). Meanwhile, locked-up ESI reduces the effective enzyme pool, lowering Vmax. The signature: both Km and Vmax decrease together. No other inhibition type does this. Competitive raises Km only. Noncompetitive lowers Vmax only. Mixed changes both but not in parallel.",mn:"UN-competitive = everything goes UN-der (both down together)"},
{id:"ek2",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Kinetics Parameters"],diff:2,q:"Noncompetitive inhibition changes which parameter?",o:["Only Vmax decreases","Only Km increases","Both decrease","Only Km decreases"],a:0,ex:"Noncompetitive inhibitors bind an allosteric site on the enzyme regardless of whether substrate is bound. Since the inhibitor does not interfere with substrate binding, Km stays the same. But the enzyme-inhibitor complex has reduced or zero catalytic activity -- like permanently removing some machines from a factory. Fewer working enzymes means lower maximum rate (Vmax drops). This is the defining feature: unchanged Km, decreased Vmax.",mn:"NON-competitive = NO Km change. Only Vmax drops."},
{id:"ek3",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Lineweaver-Burk"],diff:2,q:"Lineweaver-Burk plot for uncompetitive inhibition shows:",o:["Parallel lines","Lines crossing on y-axis","Lines crossing on x-axis","Same line"],a:0,ex:"On the double-reciprocal (1/V vs 1/[S]) Lineweaver-Burk plot: the slope = Km/Vmax. In uncompetitive inhibition, both Km and Vmax decrease by the same factor, so the slope stays constant -- producing PARALLEL lines. This is the most distinctive pattern. Quick reference: Competitive = y-axis intersection (same Vmax). Noncompetitive = x-axis intersection (same Km). Uncompetitive = parallel (unique).",mn:"Parallel lines = uncompetitive. The ONLY type with this LB pattern."},
{id:"ek4",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Lineweaver-Burk"],diff:2,q:"Competitive inhibitor LB lines intersect on the:",o:["Y-axis","X-axis","Origin","They are parallel"],a:0,ex:"Competitive inhibitors compete for the active site. More substrate can always outcompete them, so Vmax is unchanged (same y-intercept = 1/Vmax). But apparent Km increases (different x-intercept = -1/Km). All lines share the y-intercept and fan outward.",mn:"Competitive = same y-intercept (Vmax unchanged)"},
{id:"ek5",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Equilibrium"],diff:3,q:"Why does Km decrease in uncompetitive inhibition?",o:["Inhibitor traps ES complex, shifting equilibrium toward ES formation","Inhibitor binds free enzyme and directly increases substrate affinity","Excess substrate accumulates and saturates the active site","Enzyme undergoes a permanent conformational change at allosteric site"],a:0,ex:"The uncompetitive inhibitor binds ES to form dead-end ESI, removing ES from the equilibrium E + S <-> ES. By Le Chatelier's principle, the system shifts right to replace the lost ES, making it appear that the enzyme has higher substrate affinity (lower apparent Km). The enzyme does not actually bind substrate better -- it is an equilibrium effect, not a real affinity change.",mn:"Le Chatelier: trapping ES forces equilibrium to make more ES = apparent higher affinity"},
{id:"ek6",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:1,q:"An uncompetitive inhibitor binds to:",o:["Only the ES complex","Only free enzyme","Both E and ES","Substrate directly"],a:0,ex:"Each inhibition type is defined by where it binds: Competitive = free enzyme only (active site). Noncompetitive = both E and ES equally (allosteric). Uncompetitive = ES complex only (site revealed by substrate binding). Mixed = both E and ES with different affinities.",mn:"UN-able to bind alone -- needs substrate there first"},
{id:"ek7",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Kinetics Parameters"],diff:1,q:"Km represents:",o:["[S] at half-Vmax","Maximum rate","Binding energy","Turnover number"],a:0,ex:"Km is the substrate concentration at which V = Vmax/2. Low Km = high apparent affinity (enzyme reaches half-speed at low [S]). High Km = low affinity (needs lots of substrate). Km = (k-1 + k2)/k1 from Michaelis-Menten. Not identical to Kd but related when catalysis is slow.",mn:"Low Km = hungry enzyme (high affinity)"},
{id:"ek8",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Kinetics Parameters"],diff:2,q:"Catalytic efficiency is measured by:",o:["kcat/Km","Vmax/Km","Km/Vmax","kcat x Km"],a:0,ex:"kcat/Km (the specificity constant) captures both speed (kcat = Vmax/[E]total) and affinity (Km). 'Perfect' diffusion-limited enzymes: kcat/Km around 10^8 to 10^9 /M/s. Examples: carbonic anhydrase, acetylcholinesterase, triose phosphate isomerase.",mn:"Efficiency = speed (kcat) / appetite (Km)"},
{id:"ek9",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Lineweaver-Burk"],diff:2,q:"Noncompetitive LB lines intersect on the:",o:["X-axis","Y-axis","Parallel","Origin"],a:0,ex:"Same Km = same x-intercept (-1/Km). Different Vmax = different y-intercept. Lines fan from x-axis. Summary: competitive = y-axis, noncompetitive = x-axis, uncompetitive = parallel.",mn:"NON-competitive = X-axis (Km unchanged)"},
{id:"ek10",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:3,q:"Mixed inhibition differs from noncompetitive because:",o:["It changes both Km AND Vmax","It only changes Km","It only changes Vmax","It binds the active site"],a:0,ex:"Mixed inhibition is the general case -- inhibitor binds allosterically with DIFFERENT affinities for E vs ES. If it prefers E, Km increases; if it prefers ES, Km decreases. Vmax always drops. Pure noncompetitive = special case where E and ES affinity are equal, so Km does not change.",mn:"Mixed = both change. Noncompetitive = special case (only Vmax)"},
{id:"ek11",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Allosteric Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Allosteric enzymes display:",o:["Sigmoidal kinetics","Hyperbolic kinetics","Linear kinetics","No saturation"],a:0,ex:"Multiple subunits with cooperative binding produce an S-shaped (sigmoidal) V vs [S] curve. Cannot use Michaelis-Menten equation -- use Hill equation instead. Hill coefficient n > 1 = positive cooperativity. Classic example: hemoglobin O2 binding. Allosteric enzymes can be shifted by activators (left shift) and inhibitors (right shift).",mn:"Allosteric = S-curve (sigmoidal), NOT hyperbolic"},
{id:"ek12",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:2,q:"Which inhibition preserves Vmax?",o:["Competitive","Noncompetitive","Uncompetitive","Mixed"],a:0,ex:"Only competitive. At high [S], substrate outcompetes the inhibitor for the active site, so Vmax is still reachable. All other types create dead-end complexes that cannot be overcome by adding more substrate.",mn:"Competitive = only type where more substrate fixes the problem"},
{id:"pek1",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p1",q:"Based on the passage, inhibitor I is:",o:["Uncompetitive","Competitive","Noncompetitive","Mixed"],a:0,ex:"Three converging clues: (1) Vmax decreased (100 to 50), (2) Km decreased (8 to 4), (3) parallel LB lines. All point to uncompetitive. Competitive would increase Km. Noncompetitive would leave Km unchanged.",mn:"Both down + parallel = uncompetitive (three confirming clues)"},
{id:"pek2",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:3,pass:"p9",q:"Drug A (resembles substrate, overcome by more [S]) is:",o:["Competitive","Uncompetitive","Noncompetitive","Irreversible"],a:0,ex:"Drug A looks like substrate (structural mimic) and can be overcome by adding more substrate. Both are hallmarks of competitive inhibition -- it sits in the active site but can be outcompeted.",mn:"Looks like substrate + overcome by more [S] = competitive"},
{id:"pek3",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:3,pass:"p9",q:"Drug B (binds site that appears only when substrate is bound, NOT overcome by [S]) is:",o:["Uncompetitive","Competitive","Noncompetitive","Allosteric activator"],a:0,ex:"Drug B's binding site only exists after substrate binds (= binds ES complex only) and cannot be overcome by substrate. This is uncompetitive inhibition. Adding more substrate actually makes it worse -- more ES = more targets for Drug B.",mn:"Binds only with substrate present + not overcome = uncompetitive"},
{id:"ek13",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Allosteric Regulation"],diff:3,q:"Positive cooperativity in an enzyme means:",o:["First substrate binding increases affinity of remaining subunits for substrate","Binding of product molecules activates the enzyme through positive feedback","The Michaelis constant increases proportionally with substrate concentration","The enzyme operates as a single independent subunit without cooperative effects"],a:0,ex:"In positive cooperativity, binding of the first substrate molecule causes a conformational change (T-state to R-state) that increases affinity of neighboring subunits -- each subsequent substrate binds more easily. Hill coefficient n > 1. This creates the sigmoidal curve. Hemoglobin: first O2 is hardest to bind; subsequent ones are easier.",mn:"More the merrier -- each binding makes the next easier"},
// ============ METABOLISM (18) ============
{id:"met1",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Aerobic Respiration","ATP Yield"],diff:1,q:"Net ATP from one glucose (aerobic):",o:["30-32 ATP per glucose molecule","36-38 ATP per glucose molecule","2 ATP per glucose molecule only","4 ATP per glucose molecule only"],a:0,ex:"Modern answer: 30-32 ATP. The old 36-38 used incorrect P/O ratios. Breakdown: Glycolysis = 2 ATP + 2 NADH. PDH = 2 NADH. Krebs = 2 GTP + 6 NADH + 2 FADH2. Each NADH yields ~2.5 ATP, each FADH2 ~1.5 ATP in oxidative phosphorylation. If you see 36-38, it is almost certainly a trap answer.",mn:"30-32 is correct. 36-38 is the MCAT trap."},
{id:"met2",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Enzyme Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Rate-limiting enzyme of glycolysis:",o:["PFK-1","Hexokinase","Pyruvate kinase","Aldolase"],a:0,ex:"PFK-1 catalyzes the committed step (F6P to F1,6BP). Activated by AMP, ADP, fructose-2,6-bisphosphate. Inhibited by ATP, citrate. Hexokinase is the first step but G6P has other possible fates (PPP, glycogen).",mn:"PFK-1 = gatekeeper of glycolysis. Low energy turns it ON."},
{id:"met3",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Fatty Acid Metabolism","Beta-Oxidation"],diff:2,q:"Beta-oxidation occurs in the:",o:["Mitochondrial matrix space","Cytoplasmic compartment","Smooth ER lumen","Peroxisomal matrix only"],a:0,ex:"Fatty acids enter the matrix via the carnitine shuttle (CPT-I on outer membrane, CPT-II on inner). Each beta-oxidation cycle removes one 2C acetyl-CoA and produces 1 FADH2 + 1 NADH. CPT-I is rate-limiting and inhibited by malonyl-CoA (first step of FA synthesis) to prevent simultaneous synthesis and breakdown.",mn:"Carnitine shuttle is the gatekeeper. Malonyl-CoA blocks entry."},
{id:"met4",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Anaerobic Metabolism","Glycolysis"],diff:2,q:"Pyruvate is converted to lactate primarily to:",o:["Regenerate NAD+ so glycolysis can continue producing ATP","Generate additional ATP through substrate-level phosphorylation","Provide acetyl-CoA as a direct substrate for the Krebs cycle","Store excess pyruvate as a long-term energy reserve molecule"],a:0,ex:"Without O2, the ETC stalls and NAD+ is depleted. Glycolysis requires NAD+ at the GAPDH step. LDH converts pyruvate to lactate while recycling NADH back to NAD+, allowing glycolysis to continue producing 2 ATP/glucose. The lactate is exported to blood and recycled in the liver (Cori cycle).",mn:"No O2 = no ETC = NAD+ runs out. LDH recycles it."},
{id:"met5",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Krebs Cycle","Electron Carriers"],diff:2,q:"Products per turn of the Krebs cycle:",o:["3 NADH, 1 FADH2, 1 GTP","2 NADH, 2 FADH2, 1 GTP","4 NADH, 1 FADH2","1 NADH, 1 FADH2, 2 GTP"],a:0,ex:"Per turn: 3 NADH (at isocitrate DH, alpha-KG DH, malate DH), 1 FADH2 (at succinate DH = Complex II of ETC), 1 GTP (at succinyl-CoA synthetase). Per glucose: multiply by 2 since each glucose yields 2 acetyl-CoA. The Krebs cycle occurs in the mitochondrial matrix.",mn:"Per turn: 3N, 1F, 1G. Per glucose: double everything."},
{id:"met6",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Hormonal Regulation","Insulin"],diff:2,q:"Insulin promotes:",o:["Glycolysis, glycogen synthesis, and lipogenesis in fed state","Gluconeogenesis, glycogenolysis, and ketone body production","Beta-oxidation, lipolysis, and glucagon receptor expression","Ketogenesis, proteolysis, and hepatic glucose output only"],a:0,ex:"Insulin = fed state hormone (beta-cells). Activates: glycolysis, glycogen synthase, lipogenesis, protein synthesis, GLUT4 translocation. Inhibits: gluconeogenesis, glycogenolysis, lipolysis, ketogenesis. Glucagon does the opposite (fasting state, alpha-cells).",mn:"Insulin = fed = STORE. Glucagon = fasting = MOBILIZE."},
{id:"met7",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Hormonal Regulation","Glucagon"],diff:2,q:"Glucagon primarily targets the:",o:["Liver","Skeletal muscle","Brain","Adipose tissue"],a:0,ex:"Glucagon targets the LIVER for glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis. Critical fact: muscle has NO glucagon receptors. Muscle uses epinephrine (not glucagon) to activate glycogenolysis during fight-or-flight. Muscle also lacks glucose-6-phosphatase, so it cannot export glucose to blood.",mn:"Glucagon = liver ONLY. No muscle receptors."},
{id:"met8",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation"],diff:3,q:"FADH2 enters the ETC at:",o:["Complex II","Complex I","Complex III","Complex IV"],a:0,ex:"FADH2 donates electrons to Complex II (succinate dehydrogenase), bypassing Complex I. Since Complexes I, III, and IV are the three proton pumps, FADH2 uses only two pumps (III and IV), producing ~1.5 ATP vs ~2.5 for NADH (which enters at Complex I and uses all three). Flow: NADH -> I -> CoQ -> III -> CytC -> IV -> O2. FADH2 -> II -> CoQ -> III -> CytC -> IV -> O2.",mn:"FADH2 enters at Complex II, skips I = fewer protons = 1.5 ATP"},
{id:"met9",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Ketogenesis","Fatty Acid Metabolism"],diff:3,q:"Ketone bodies are produced from:",o:["Excess acetyl-CoA in the liver","Pyruvate in muscle","Glucose in the brain","Fatty acids in adipose"],a:0,ex:"During fasting, the liver produces excess acetyl-CoA from beta-oxidation that overwhelms the Krebs cycle (OAA is diverted to gluconeogenesis). Excess acetyl-CoA becomes ketone bodies: acetoacetate, beta-hydroxybutyrate, acetone. The liver CANNOT use ketones (lacks thiophorase). Brain, heart, and muscle can. Brain adapts to ~75% ketone use during prolonged starvation.",mn:"Liver makes ketones but cannot use them. Brain adapts."},
{id:"met10",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Pyruvate Dehydrogenase","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:2,q:"PDH complex produces:",o:["Acetyl-CoA, CO2, and NADH in the mitochondrial matrix","Oxaloacetate, FADH2, and GTP in the cytoplasm","Lactate, NAD+, and ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation","Citrate, NADPH, and acetaldehyde in the intermembrane space"],a:0,ex:"PDH is the bridge between glycolysis and Krebs. Irreversible oxidative decarboxylation: pyruvate (3C) loses CO2, gets oxidized (NADH), and the 2C fragment joins CoA. Requires 5 cofactors: TPP (B1), FAD (B2), NAD+ (B3), CoA (B5), lipoic acid. Inhibited by its products (acetyl-CoA, NADH).",mn:"PDH = bridge reaction. 5 cofactors from B vitamins."},
{id:"met11",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Pentose Phosphate Pathway"],diff:3,q:"Pentose phosphate pathway primarily produces:",o:["NADPH for reductive biosynthesis and ribose-5-phosphate for nucleotides","ATP and NADH for energy production through oxidative phosphorylation","FADH2 and succinate for electron transport chain entry at Complex II","Lactate and oxaloacetate for gluconeogenesis substrate generation"],a:0,ex:"PPP branches from glycolysis at G6P. Two products: (1) NADPH for reductive biosynthesis (FA/cholesterol synthesis) and glutathione maintenance (antioxidant defense, critical in RBCs). (2) Ribose-5-phosphate for nucleotide synthesis. Rate-limiting: G6PD. G6PD deficiency = most common enzyme deficiency, causes hemolytic anemia on oxidative stress.",mn:"PPP = NADPH (antioxidant) + Ribose (nucleotides). G6PD deficiency = hemolysis."},
{id:"met12",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Gluconeogenesis"],diff:3,q:"Gluconeogenesis bypasses PFK-1 with:",o:["Fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase","Glucose-6-phosphatase","Pyruvate carboxylase","PEP carboxykinase"],a:0,ex:"Glycolysis has 3 irreversible steps that gluconeogenesis must bypass: (1) Pyruvate kinase -> pyruvate carboxylase + PEP carboxykinase. (2) PFK-1 -> fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase. (3) Hexokinase -> glucose-6-phosphatase (liver/kidney only). Gluconeogenesis costs 6 ATP per glucose vs 2 ATP earned from glycolysis.",mn:"3 irreversible steps -> 4 bypass enzymes"},
{id:"pmet1",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p4",q:"Why does rotenone stop O2 consumption with NADH?",o:["Blocks Complex I, halting the entire electron flow from NADH to oxygen","Blocks Complex IV, preventing final electron acceptance by oxygen","Uncouples the proton gradient from ATP synthesis at the inner membrane","Inhibits ATP synthase by plugging the Fo proton channel directly"],a:0,ex:"Rotenone specifically inhibits Complex I. With NADH as the only electron source, ALL electrons must pass through Complex I. Blocking it stops the entire chain downstream -- no electrons reach O2, so O2 consumption stops. This is different from uncoupling, which would actually INCREASE O2 consumption.",mn:"Rotenone = Complex I poison. Blocks NADH but not FADH2 pathway."},
{id:"pmet2",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p4",q:"Why does succinate restore O2 consumption after rotenone?",o:["Succinate feeds electrons at Complex II, bypassing blocked Complex I","Succinate chemically reverses rotenone binding at the active site","Succinate provides additional NADH through a cytoplasmic shuttle","Succinate directly reduces molecular oxygen without ETC involvement"],a:0,ex:"Succinate is oxidized by Complex II (succinate dehydrogenase), feeding electrons to CoQ -> III -> IV -> O2. This entirely bypasses the rotenone-blocked Complex I. The reduced rate reflects fewer protons pumped (skipping one of three pumps). This experiment demonstrates the ETC has parallel entry points.",mn:"Complex II is downstream of Complex I. Rotenone cannot block it."},
{id:"met13",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Cori Cycle","Anaerobic Metabolism"],diff:2,q:"The Cori cycle shuttles:",o:["Lactate from muscle to liver for conversion back to glucose","Glucose from liver to muscle via direct hepatic secretion","Amino acids from skeletal muscle to brain for neurotransmitter use","Ketone bodies from adipose tissue to liver for beta-oxidation"],a:0,ex:"Working muscle produces lactate (anaerobic glycolysis, 2 ATP). Lactate travels via blood to the liver, which converts it back to glucose (gluconeogenesis, costs 6 ATP). Glucose returns to muscle. Net cost: 4 ATP per cycle. The liver subsidizes muscle during intense exercise.",mn:"Muscle: glucose -> lactate (2 ATP). Liver: lactate -> glucose (-6 ATP)."},
{id:"met14",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation"],diff:3,q:"Cyanide poisoning stops cellular respiration by inhibiting:",o:["Complex IV, blocking final electron transfer to oxygen","Complex I, blocking NADH oxidation at the first ETC step","Complex II, blocking succinate dehydrogenase activity directly","ATP synthase, blocking proton flow through the Fo channel"],a:0,ex:"Cyanide binds to the iron in Complex IV, preventing the final transfer of electrons to O2. Since electron flow stops completely, the proton gradient dissipates, ATP synthase halts, and the cell cannot produce ATP aerobically. Other ETC poisons: rotenone (Complex I), antimycin A (Complex III), oligomycin (ATP synthase -- blocks proton channel, not an uncoupler).",mn:"Cyanide = Complex IV. Rotenone = I. Antimycin = III. Oligomycin = ATP synthase."},
{id:"met15",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Metabolic Regulation","Enzyme Regulation"],diff:3,q:"Fructose-2,6-bisphosphate is the most potent activator of:",o:["PFK-1, the rate-limiting committed step of glycolysis","PFK-2, the kinase that produces fructose-2,6-bisphosphate","Pyruvate kinase, the final irreversible step of glycolysis","Hexokinase, the first phosphorylation step of glucose entry"],a:0,ex:"F2,6BP is made by PFK-2 (a bifunctional enzyme that also has FBPase-2 activity). In the fed state, insulin activates PFK-2 (via dephosphorylation), which makes F2,6BP, which powerfully activates PFK-1, driving glycolysis forward. In fasting, glucagon activates FBPase-2 side (via phosphorylation), reducing F2,6BP levels, slowing glycolysis and favoring gluconeogenesis.",mn:"F2,6BP = most potent PFK-1 activator. Made by PFK-2. Insulin up, glucagon down."},
// ============ AMINO ACIDS & PROTEINS (22 including 4 matching) ============
// --- MATCHING QUESTIONS ---
{id:"aam1",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",type:"match",tags:["Amino Acid Classification"],diff:2,q:"Match each amino acid to its classification:",pairs:[["Lysine (K)","Positive charge at pH 7.4"],["Aspartate (D)","Negative charge at pH 7.4"],["Leucine (L)","Nonpolar, hydrophobic"],["Serine (S)","Polar, uncharged"],["Phenylalanine (F)","Aromatic, hydrophobic"]],ex:"At pH 7.4: Lys/Arg/His are positive (basic). Asp/Glu are negative (acidic). Leu/Ile/Val/Ala/Met/Pro/Gly/Trp/Phe are nonpolar. Ser/Thr/Asn/Gln/Tyr/Cys are polar uncharged. Phe/Trp/Tyr are aromatic (Tyr is polar aromatic due to -OH).",mn:"Charged: K,R,H (+) and D,E (-). Nonpolar: the greasy ones (L,I,V,A,M,P,G,W,F). Polar: S,T,N,Q,Y,C."},
{id:"aam2",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",type:"match",tags:["Amino Acid Properties"],diff:2,q:"Match each amino acid to its unique feature:",pairs:[["Cysteine (C)","Forms disulfide bonds (-S-S-)"],["Proline (P)","Helix breaker (rigid ring)"],["Glycine (G)","Smallest AA, most flexible"],["Histidine (H)","Best buffer near pH 7 (pKa ~6)"],["Tryptophan (W)","Strongest UV absorbance at 280nm"]],ex:"Each of these amino acids has a unique structural or chemical property that is commonly tested. Cys has a thiol (-SH) that can form covalent disulfide bonds. Pro has a cyclic side chain bonded to the backbone N, creating rigidity. Gly has only H as its side chain, giving maximum flexibility. His has an imidazole ring with pKa ~6. Trp has a large indole ring with the strongest UV absorption.",mn:"C=bonds, P=rigid, G=tiny, H=buffer, W=UV king"},
{id:"aam3",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",type:"match",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Protein Structure"],diff:3,q:"Match the amino acid to its side chain pKa:",pairs:[["Aspartate (D)","pKa ~3.65"],["Glutamate (E)","pKa ~4.25"],["Histidine (H)","pKa ~6.0"],["Lysine (K)","pKa ~10.5"],["Arginine (R)","pKa ~12.5"]],ex:"These five are the charged amino acids, and knowing their pKas is high-yield. Below their pKa, the side chain is protonated; above, it is deprotonated. At pH 7.4: D and E are deprotonated (negative). K and R are protonated (positive). H is mostly deprotonated (~90%) but can accept a proton -- making it an excellent buffer and acid-base catalyst.",mn:"pKa order: D(3.65) < E(4.25) < H(6.0) < K(10.5) < R(12.5)"},
{id:"aam4",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",type:"match",tags:["Essential Amino Acids"],diff:2,q:"Which are essential amino acids?",pairs:[["Phenylalanine","Essential (cannot synthesize)"],["Valine","Essential (cannot synthesize)"],["Tyrosine","NOT essential (made from Phe)"],["Cysteine","NOT essential (made from Met)"],["Tryptophan","Essential (cannot synthesize)"]],ex:"Essential AAs must come from diet: PVT TIM HALL (Phe, Val, Thr, Trp, Ile, Met, His, Arg-conditional, Leu, Lys). Tyr is made from Phe by phenylalanine hydroxylase (deficient in PKU). Cys is made from Met. These 'conditionally nonessential' AAs become essential if the precursor is missing.",mn:"PVT TIM HALL. Tyr from Phe. Cys from Met."},
// --- MULTIPLE CHOICE AA QUESTIONS ---
{id:"aa1",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Classification"],diff:1,q:"Positively charged amino acids at pH 7.4:",o:["Lys, Arg, His","Asp, Glu","Ser, Thr, Tyr","Phe, Trp, Tyr"],a:0,ex:"The basic (positively charged) AAs: Lysine (K, pKa ~10.5), Arginine (R, pKa ~12.5), Histidine (H, pKa ~6.0). At pH 7.4, Lys and Arg are fully protonated and positive. His is mostly deprotonated but still classified as basic since its imidazole ring can accept a proton. Arg has the highest pKa due to resonance stabilization of its guanidinium group across three nitrogen atoms.",mn:"K, R, H = positive. Remember: Kings Rule History."},
{id:"aa2",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Acid-Base"],diff:2,q:"Best biological buffer amino acid:",o:["Histidine","Tryptophan","Proline","Phenylalanine"],a:0,ex:"Buffers work best within +/-1 pH of their pKa. His pKa ~6.0 is closest to physiological pH (7.4) of any amino acid side chain. This allows His to both donate and accept protons near physiological pH. His is critical in enzyme active sites (acid-base catalysis, like chymotrypsin His-57) and in hemoglobin (Bohr effect -- His residues buffer H+ in active tissues, promoting O2 release).",mn:"His pKa ~6 = closest to 7.4 = best buffer. Used in enzymes and Hb."},
{id:"aa3",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Disulfide Bonds"],diff:1,q:"Disulfide bonds form between:",o:["Two cysteines","Two methionines","Serine and threonine","Any two amino acids"],a:0,ex:"Cysteine's thiol (-SH) groups undergo oxidation to form a covalent -S-S- disulfide bond. This is the ONLY covalent bond in tertiary/quaternary structure. All other stabilizing forces (H-bonds, ionic interactions, hydrophobic interactions, van der Waals) are non-covalent. Disulfide bonds form in the oxidizing environment of the ER lumen and extracellular space. The reducing cytoplasm prevents them.",mn:"Cys-Cys = only covalent bond in protein folding. Oxidizing environment only."},
{id:"aa4",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Classification"],diff:1,q:"Negatively charged amino acids at pH 7.4:",o:["Asp and Glu","Lys and Arg","Ser and Thr","Trp and Phe"],a:0,ex:"Aspartate (D, pKa ~3.65) and Glutamate (E, pKa ~4.25) have carboxyl (-COOH) side chains. At pH 7.4 (well above their pKas), they are fully deprotonated to -COO- and carry a -1 charge. Glu is Asp with one extra CH2. Both participate in enzyme active sites, salt bridges with basic AAs, and metal ion coordination.",mn:"D and E = acidic = negative. Dangerously nEgative."},
{id:"aa5",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure"],diff:2,q:"Which amino acid is a 'helix breaker'?",o:["Proline","Glycine","Alanine","Leucine"],a:0,ex:"Proline's cyclic side chain connects to the backbone nitrogen, creating a rigid pyrrolidine ring. This prevents: (1) donation of the backbone N-H hydrogen bond needed for alpha-helix stability, and (2) the backbone phi angle flexibility needed for helical geometry. Proline introduces kinks and is found in turns. Glycine is also a helix destabilizer but for the opposite reason -- too much flexibility (smallest side chain = H).",mn:"Pro = rigid ring = can't H-bond in helix. Gly = too flexible."},
{id:"aa6",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Isoelectric Point","Acid-Base"],diff:2,q:"At its isoelectric point (pI), an amino acid has:",o:["Cysteine residues forming covalent bonds between thiol side chains","Lysine residues forming hydrogen bonds between amino side chains","Proline residues forming peptide bonds within the rigid ring structure","Glycine residues forming hydrophobic contacts between methyl groups"],a:0,ex:"pI is the pH at which the molecule has zero NET charge -- it still has charges, but they balance out (zwitterion: NH3+ and COO-). At pI, the molecule will NOT migrate in an electric field (key for electrophoresis and isoelectric focusing). Calculation: for simple AAs, pI = average of the two pKas flanking the zwitterion. For acidic AAs: average of the two LOWEST pKas. For basic AAs: average of the two HIGHEST pKas.",mn:"pI = zero net charge = no migration in electric field"},
{id:"aa7",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties"],diff:2,q:"Which amino acids absorb UV light at 280nm?",o:["Trp, Tyr, and Phe due to their conjugated aromatic ring systems","Lys, Arg, and His due to their positively charged side chains","Asp and Glu due to their negatively charged carboxylate groups","Ser, Thr, and Cys due to their polar hydroxyl and thiol groups"],a:0,ex:"Only AROMATIC amino acids absorb UV at 280nm due to their conjugated ring systems. Tryptophan (W) has the strongest absorption (large indole ring), then Tyrosine (Y, phenol ring), then Phenylalanine (F, benzyl ring, very weak). This is used for protein quantification: measure A280 and apply Beer-Lambert law (A = epsilon * l * c). If a protein lacks Trp/Tyr, A280 is unreliable.",mn:"280nm = aromatic AAs only. Trp >> Tyr > Phe."},
{id:"aa8",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure"],diff:2,q:"The primary structure of a protein is its:",o:["Linear amino acid sequence","Alpha-helices and beta-sheets","3D folding","Multi-subunit assembly"],a:0,ex:"Four levels of protein structure: PRIMARY = linear sequence of amino acids connected by peptide bonds (determined by gene). SECONDARY = local folding into alpha-helices and beta-sheets (stabilized by backbone H-bonds). TERTIARY = overall 3D shape of a single polypeptide (stabilized by R-group interactions: hydrophobic, ionic, H-bonds, disulfide). QUATERNARY = assembly of multiple polypeptide subunits (e.g., hemoglobin has 4 subunits). Not all proteins have quaternary structure.",mn:"1=sequence, 2=local folds (helix/sheet), 3=3D shape, 4=multi-subunit"},
{id:"aa9",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Amino Acid Properties"],diff:2,q:"Hydrophobic amino acids are typically found:",o:["In the protein interior, shielded from the aqueous environment","On the protein surface, interacting with the surrounding solvent","Exclusively within disulfide bonds that stabilize tertiary structure","Only in enzyme active sites where they bind charged substrates"],a:0,ex:"The hydrophobic effect is the primary driving force of protein folding. Nonpolar amino acids (Leu, Ile, Val, Ala, Met, Phe, Trp, Pro) cluster in the protein interior to avoid water, while polar and charged residues face outward toward the aqueous environment. This arrangement minimizes the thermodynamically unfavorable ordering of water molecules around hydrophobic groups. Exceptions: membrane proteins have hydrophobic residues on the exterior (facing the lipid bilayer).",mn:"Nonpolar = interior (away from water). Polar/charged = surface."},
{id:"aa10",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure"],diff:3,q:"Denaturation of a protein destroys:",o:["Secondary, tertiary, and quaternary structure while preserving primary","All four structural levels including the covalent peptide backbone","Only quaternary structure while maintaining all other levels intact","Only the primary amino acid sequence through peptide bond hydrolysis"],a:0,ex:"Denaturation (by heat, extreme pH, urea, detergents) disrupts the non-covalent interactions that maintain higher-order structure: H-bonds (secondary), hydrophobic/ionic/van der Waals (tertiary), subunit interactions (quaternary). However, the PEPTIDE BONDS of the primary sequence are covalent and remain intact -- denaturation does not break them. Some proteins can refold (renature) when conditions normalize, demonstrating that the amino acid sequence contains all information needed for correct folding (Anfinsen's experiment with ribonuclease).",mn:"Denaturation = loss of shape, NOT loss of sequence. Peptide bonds survive."},
{id:"aa11",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties"],diff:1,q:"All amino acids at physiological pH exist as:",o:["Zwitterions carrying both positive and negative charges simultaneously","Cations with only a positively charged ammonium group present","Anions with only a negatively charged carboxylate group present","Neutral molecules with no ionizable groups at physiological pH"],a:0,ex:"At pH 7.4, the alpha-amino group (pKa ~9) is protonated (NH3+) and the alpha-carboxyl group (pKa ~2) is deprotonated (COO-). This creates a zwitterion -- a molecule with both positive and negative charges that has zero net charge (for neutral AAs). The side chain may add additional charges depending on its pKa relative to the pH.",mn:"Zwitterion = NH3+ and COO- at the same time. Always at physiological pH."},
{id:"aa12",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Protein Structure"],diff:3,q:"Collagen's structure depends heavily on which amino acid?",o:["Glycine, which occupies every third position in the triple helix","Tryptophan, which provides structural rigidity through its indole ring","Histidine, which buffers the local pH within the collagen matrix","Methionine, which initiates translation of all collagen polypeptides"],a:0,ex:"Collagen has a unique triple-helix structure requiring Gly-X-Y repeating triplets. Glycine (the smallest AA) must be at every third position because only H (Gly's side chain) fits in the crowded interior of the triple helix. X is often Proline, Y is often Hydroxyproline (Pro modified by vitamin C-dependent prolyl hydroxylase). Scurvy (vitamin C deficiency) impairs hydroxyproline formation, weakening collagen and causing bleeding gums, poor wound healing, and bruising.",mn:"Collagen = Gly-X-Y repeat. Gly must be every 3rd. Vitamin C needed for hydroxyproline."},
{id:"pmb1",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Acid-Base","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p3",q:"Why does the H57A mutation abolish activity despite maintaining structure?",o:["His-57 directly participates in the catalytic acid-base mechanism","Removal of histidine causes complete protein unfolding and aggregation","The alanine substitution blocks substrate access to the binding pocket","The mutation increases enzyme stability and prevents conformational change"],a:0,ex:"The passage states tertiary structure is maintained, so it is not unfolding. Structure does NOT equal function. His is commonly an acid-base catalyst in enzyme active sites because its imidazole ring (pKa ~6) can both donate and accept protons near physiological pH. The catalytic triad of serine proteases (chymotrypsin) uses His-57 to shuttle protons. Replacing it with Ala removes the chemical tool while leaving the structural scaffold intact.",mn:"Structure intact but catalytic tool removed. His = proton shuttle in active sites."},
// ============ CELL BIOLOGY (14) ============
{id:"cb1",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Cell Cycle","Mitosis"],diff:1,q:"Correct order of mitosis phases:",o:["Prophase, Metaphase, Anaphase, Telophase","Metaphase, Prophase, Anaphase, Telophase","Anaphase, Metaphase, Prophase, Telophase","Telophase, Prophase, Metaphase, Anaphase"],a:0,ex:"PMAT: Prophase (chromosomes condense, nuclear envelope breaks down). Metaphase (chromosomes align at metaphase plate). Anaphase (sister chromatids pulled apart by spindle fibers). Telophase (chromosomes decondense, nuclear envelopes reform). Cytokinesis follows: cleavage furrow (animals) or cell plate (plants).",mn:"PMAT: Prophase, Metaphase, Anaphase, Telophase"},
{id:"cb2",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Cell Cycle","Tumor Suppressors"],diff:2,q:"G1/S checkpoint is regulated by:",o:["p53 and Rb","Cyclins alone","ATP levels","Cell size"],a:0,ex:"p53 (guardian of genome) detects DNA damage, activates p21 (CDK inhibitor) to halt cell cycle for repair, or triggers apoptosis if damage is irreparable. Rb (retinoblastoma protein) blocks E2F transcription factor until phosphorylated by cyclin-CDK complexes, gating S-phase entry. Loss of either = uncontrolled division = cancer.",mn:"p53 = damage sensor. Rb = S-phase gate. Both are tumor suppressors."},
{id:"cb3",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Meiosis","Genetic Diversity"],diff:2,q:"Meiosis produces:",o:["G1 phase, before DNA replication begins at the restriction point","S phase, during active DNA synthesis and chromosome duplication","G2 phase, after DNA replication and before mitotic entry begins","M phase, during chromosome alignment and separation at metaphase"],a:0,ex:"Meiosis I: homologs separate (reductional). Meiosis II: sisters separate (equational). Result: 4 genetically unique haploid cells. Three sources of diversity: (1) crossing over in prophase I, (2) independent assortment (2^23 arrangements), (3) random fertilization. Compare mitosis: 2 identical diploid cells.",mn:"Meiosis: 1 diploid -> 4 unique haploid. Mitosis: 1 -> 2 identical diploid."},
{id:"cb4",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Organelles"],diff:2,q:"Lysosomes function at pH:",o:["~5 (acidic)","~7 (neutral)","~9 (basic)","~2 (very acidic)"],a:0,ex:"Lysosomes contain acid hydrolases optimized for pH ~5, maintained by H+ ATPase pumps. Safety mechanism: if lysosome ruptures, enzymes inactive at cytoplasmic pH ~7.2. Lysosomal storage diseases: enzyme deficiency causes substrate accumulation (Tay-Sachs, Gaucher's, Pompe's).",mn:"Lysosomes = pH 5 recycling. Enzyme deficiency = storage disease."},
{id:"cb5",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Apoptosis","Cell Death"],diff:3,q:"Apoptosis differs from necrosis because apoptosis:",o:["Is programmed, orderly, and non-inflammatory","Is accidental and causes inflammation","Involves cell swelling","Releases cellular contents randomly"],a:0,ex:"Apoptosis: programmed cell death via caspase cascade. Cell shrinks, chromatin condenses, fragments into apoptotic bodies phagocytosed cleanly -- NO inflammation. Essential for development and immune function. Necrosis: uncontrolled death from injury -- cell swells, bursts, contents spill out, triggers inflammation.",mn:"Apoptosis = clean suicide (caspases). Necrosis = messy explosion (inflammation)."},
{id:"cb6",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Organelles","Protein Processing"],diff:2,q:"Rough ER's primary function:",o:["Synthesis of secretory proteins and co-translational modification","Synthesis of membrane lipids and steroid hormone precursors","Detoxification of drugs and metabolism of xenobiotic compounds","Storage of calcium ions and regulation of intracellular signaling"],a:0,ex:"Rough ER has ribosomes on its surface. Synthesizes proteins destined for secretion, membrane insertion, or lysosomes. Signal peptide recognized by SRP directs ribosome to ER. Proteins undergo folding, disulfide bond formation, and N-linked glycosylation in the ER lumen. Smooth ER: lipid synthesis, steroid hormones, detoxification (cytochrome P450), Ca2+ storage.",mn:"Rough = ribosomes = secretory/membrane proteins. Smooth = lipids + detox + Ca2+."},
{id:"cb7",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Membrane Transport"],diff:2,q:"Na+/K+ ATPase pumps:",o:["3 Na+ out and 2 K+ in per ATP hydrolyzed across the membrane","3 K+ out and 2 Na+ in per ATP hydrolyzed across the membrane","Equal numbers of Na+ and K+ ions exchanged per ATP molecule","Only Na+ pumped outward with no simultaneous K+ movement"],a:0,ex:"The Na+/K+ ATPase is an electrogenic antiporter that uses 1 ATP to pump 3 Na+ OUT and 2 K+ IN. This creates: (1) the Na+ concentration gradient (high outside, low inside), (2) the K+ gradient (high inside, low outside), (3) a net negative resting membrane potential (~-70mV in neurons). These gradients are essential for nerve impulses, muscle contraction, and secondary active transport (Na+-glucose cotransporter).",mn:"3 Na+ out, 2 K+ in. Creates resting potential and drives secondary transport."},
{id:"cb8",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Membrane Transport"],diff:2,q:"Facilitated diffusion differs from active transport because:",o:["It moves solutes down their concentration gradient without ATP input","It requires ATP hydrolysis to transport solutes against their gradient","It moves solutes against their gradient using ion cotransport energy","It uses clathrin-coated vesicles to internalize large molecules"],a:0,ex:"Passive transport: down the concentration gradient, no energy. Includes simple diffusion (O2, CO2, steroid hormones cross membrane directly) and facilitated diffusion (needs a channel or carrier protein but still no ATP -- glucose via GLUT transporters, ions via channels). Active transport: against the gradient, requires energy. Primary active: directly uses ATP (Na+/K+ ATPase). Secondary active: uses gradient established by primary (Na+-glucose symporter).",mn:"Facilitated = protein-assisted but still passive (no ATP, downhill)."},
{id:"cb9",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Signal Transduction"],diff:3,q:"G-protein coupled receptors (GPCRs) activate:",o:["Heterotrimeric G-proteins that initiate second messenger cascades","Receptor tyrosine kinases that directly phosphorylate target proteins","Intracellular nuclear receptors that bind DNA as transcription factors","Ligand-gated ion channels that directly change membrane permeability"],a:0,ex:"GPCRs are the largest family of cell surface receptors. When a ligand binds, the receptor activates a G-protein (exchanges GDP for GTP). Two main pathways: (1) Gs activates adenylyl cyclase -> increases cAMP -> activates PKA. (2) Gq activates phospholipase C -> cleaves PIP2 into IP3 (releases Ca2+ from ER) + DAG (activates PKC). Gi inhibits adenylyl cyclase. Key GPCR examples: beta-adrenergic receptors (epinephrine), muscarinic ACh receptors, glucagon receptor.",mn:"GPCR -> G-protein -> second messengers (cAMP or IP3/DAG)"},
{id:"pcb1",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Cell Cycle","Tumor Suppressors","Apoptosis"],diff:3,pass:"p8",q:"G1/S arrest at low UV doses is mediated by:",o:["p53-mediated activation of p21, which inhibits cyclin-CDK complexes","Direct increase in ATP consumption that depletes cellular energy","Immediate inhibition of DNA polymerase by UV photoproduct binding","Caspase cascade activation leading to programmed apoptotic cell death"],a:0,ex:"Low UV causes DNA damage (thymine dimers). This activates p53 -> p21 (CDK inhibitor) -> blocks cyclin-CDK -> halts G1/S transition for repair. At HIGH UV doses, damage is irreparable -> p53 triggers apoptosis via caspases instead. This demonstrates p53's dual role: damage cop (low damage = arrest) and executioner (high damage = death).",mn:"Low damage = p53 arrests (p21). High damage = p53 kills (caspases)."},
// ============ GENETICS (12) ============
{id:"gen1",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Mendelian Genetics"],diff:1,q:"Two carriers (Aa x Aa) -- chance offspring is affected:",o:["25%","50%","75%","100%"],a:0,ex:"Punnett square: AA(25%), Aa(50%), aa(25%). Only aa is affected = 25%. Among UNAFFECTED offspring, 2/3 are carriers. Autosomal recessive examples: cystic fibrosis, sickle cell, PKU, Tay-Sachs. For X-linked recessive: carrier mother x normal father = 50% of sons affected, 0% daughters affected.",mn:"Aa x Aa = 1:2:1 ratio. 1/4 affected, 2/4 carriers, 1/4 normal."},
{id:"gen2",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Population Genetics","Hardy-Weinberg"],diff:2,q:"If q-squared = 0.0025, carrier frequency (2pq) is:",o:["Approximately 9.5%","Approximately 5.0%","Approximately 0.5%","Approximately 25%"],a:0,ex:"q^2 = 0.0025 -> q = 0.05 -> p = 0.95 -> 2pq = 2(0.95)(0.05) = 0.095 = 9.5%. Key insight: carriers (9.5%) vastly outnumber affected (0.25%). HW assumptions: large population, random mating, no selection/mutation/migration.",mn:"Carriers (2pq) always >> affected (q^2)."},
{id:"gen3",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["X-Linked Inheritance"],diff:2,q:"X-linked recessive traits are expressed more in:",o:["Males, who have only one X chromosome and no backup allele","Females, who have two X chromosomes allowing homozygous expression","Both sexes equally, since X-linked genes show no sex-based pattern","Neither sex, since recessive alleles are never phenotypically expressed"],a:0,ex:"Males are hemizygous for X-linked genes (XY). One affected X = trait expressed. Females need two affected X's (homozygous). Examples: hemophilia A/B, color blindness, Duchenne muscular dystrophy, G6PD deficiency. Affected father passes X to ALL daughters (carriers) but NEVER to sons (sons get Y).",mn:"Males: one X, no backup. All daughters of affected father are carriers."},
{id:"gen4",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Inheritance Patterns"],diff:3,q:"Codominance vs incomplete dominance:",o:["Codominance shows both phenotypes; incomplete dominance shows blending","Both terms describe identical inheritance patterns with no distinction","Codominance produces a blended intermediate phenotype between parents","Incomplete dominance means one allele completely masks the other allele"],a:0,ex:"Codominance: BOTH alleles fully and separately expressed in heterozygote. Example: AB blood type (both A and B antigens present), sickle cell heterozygote (both HbA and HbS produced). Incomplete dominance: heterozygote shows INTERMEDIATE phenotype. Example: red x white = pink flowers. Key difference: codominance = both visible distinctly, incomplete = blend.",mn:"Codominance = both show (AB blood). Incomplete = blend (pink flowers)."},
{id:"gen5",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Chromosomal Abnormalities"],diff:2,q:"Meiosis I nondisjunction causes:",o:["All four resulting gametes receive an abnormal chromosome number","Only one of the four gametes receives an extra or missing chromosome","All resulting cells maintain normal diploid chromosome complement","The cell undergoes polyploidy with complete genome duplication"],a:0,ex:"Meiosis I: homologs fail to separate, both go to one cell. After meiosis II: 2 gametes are n+1, 2 are n-1. ALL FOUR are abnormal. Meiosis II nondisjunction: sisters fail to separate, only 2 of 4 gametes abnormal. If n+1 gamete fertilized: trisomy (Down=21, Edwards=18, Patau=13). If n-1: monosomy (Turner=45,X).",mn:"Meiosis I nondisjunction = all 4 wrong. Meiosis II = only 2 of 4."},
{id:"gen6",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Mendelian Genetics"],diff:2,q:"A testcross involves crossing an unknown genotype with:",o:["2^n possible genetically unique gametes from n chromosome pairs","Exactly n gametes are produced from each meiotic cell division","All gametes from one individual are genetically identical copies","Gamete diversity depends only on crossing over, not assortment"],a:0,ex:"A testcross determines if an organism showing the dominant phenotype is AA or Aa. Cross with aa: if ALL offspring show dominant phenotype -> unknown is AA. If ~50% show recessive -> unknown is Aa. This works because aa can only contribute a recessive allele, so the offspring phenotype reveals the unknown parent's genotype.",mn:"Testcross = cross with aa to reveal unknown genotype."},
{id:"pgen1",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Population Genetics","Hardy-Weinberg"],diff:3,pass:"p5",q:"Disease allele frequency (q) is:",o:["0.05","0.0025","0.25","0.5"],a:0,ex:"25 affected / 10,000 = q^2 = 0.0025. q = sqrt(0.0025) = 0.05. This is the ALLELE frequency, not genotype frequency. Common mistake: confusing q^2 (genotype) with q (allele).",mn:"q^2 = affected proportion. q = square root."},
{id:"pgen2",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Population Genetics","Hardy-Weinberg"],diff:3,pass:"p5",q:"Carriers in this population:",o:["~950","~25","~500","~5000"],a:0,ex:"2pq = 2(0.95)(0.05) = 0.095. In 10,000 people: 950 carriers vs only 25 affected. For rare recessive diseases, the carrier pool is always much larger than the affected pool.",mn:"2pq x population = carriers. Always >> affected."},
// ============ ORGAN SYSTEMS (22) ============
{id:"bs1",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System"],diff:1,q:"SA node is located in the:",o:["Right atrium","Left atrium","Right ventricle","Left ventricle"],a:0,ex:"SA node = pacemaker (60-100 bpm) in right atrium wall. Pathway: SA -> AV node (delay for atrial emptying) -> Bundle of His -> bundle branches -> Purkinje fibers. Vagus nerve (parasympathetic) slows; sympathetic speeds up. AV node backup: 40-60 bpm.",mn:"SA = Start Atrium (right). Pacemaker."},
{id:"bs2",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Hormones"],diff:2,q:"ADH acts primarily on the:",o:["Collecting duct cells","Proximal convoluted tubule","Ascending loop of Henle","Glomerular filtrate space"],a:0,ex:"ADH (vasopressin) from posterior pituitary inserts aquaporin-2 channels into collecting duct apical membrane. With ADH: water reabsorbed = concentrated urine. Without ADH: dilute urine (diabetes insipidus). Alcohol inhibits ADH -> dehydration.",mn:"ADH = aquaporins in collecting duct = water retention"},
{id:"bs3",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Autonomic"],diff:2,q:"Sympathetic postganglionic neurons release:",o:["Norepinephrine","Acetylcholine","Dopamine","Serotonin"],a:0,ex:"ALL preganglionic (both divisions) = ACh at nicotinic receptors. Postganglionic: Sympathetic = NE at adrenergic receptors (except sweat glands = ACh). Parasympathetic = ACh at muscarinic receptors. Adrenal medulla releases epi (80%) + NE (20%) into blood. Key receptors: alpha-1 = vasoconstriction. Beta-1 = heart rate up. Beta-2 = bronchodilation.",mn:"Sympathetic post = NE (except sweat = ACh). Para = always ACh."},
{id:"bs4",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Respiratory System","Hemoglobin"],diff:2,q:"Hemoglobin's O2 curve is:",o:["Sigmoidal","Hyperbolic","Linear","Exponential"],a:0,ex:"Hb: 4 subunits (alpha2-beta2), cooperative binding -> sigmoidal (S-shaped) curve. Myoglobin: 1 subunit, no cooperativity -> hyperbolic. Hb's sigmoidal shape allows efficient loading in lungs (high PO2) and efficient unloading in tissues (low PO2).",mn:"Hb = S-curve (cooperative). Mb = hyperbola (single subunit)."},
{id:"bs5",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Respiratory System","Hemoglobin"],diff:3,q:"Right shift of Hb O2 curve is caused by:",o:["Increased CO2, H+, temperature, and 2,3-BPG concentrations","Decreased CO2, H+, temperature, and 2,3-BPG concentrations","Increased blood pH and decreased metabolic activity in tissues","Carbon monoxide binding at the same site as molecular oxygen"],a:0,ex:"Right shift = decreased O2 affinity = release O2 to active tissues. Caused by conditions in metabolizing tissues: increased CO2 (Bohr effect), decreased pH (H+), increased temperature, increased 2,3-BPG. Left shift (hold O2 tighter): opposite conditions, fetal Hb (HbF), CO poisoning.",mn:"CADET face Right: CO2, Acid, DPG, Exercise, Temperature"},
{id:"bs6",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Hormones"],diff:3,q:"Aldosterone's main effects:",o:["Enhanced renal Na+ reabsorption paired with increased K+ secretion","Direct stimulation of aquaporin insertion into collecting duct cells","Decreased tubular Na+ reabsorption paired with K+ retention","Increased proximal tubule glucose reabsorption via SGLT2 upregulation"],a:0,ex:"Aldosterone (adrenal cortex) acts on DCT/collecting duct principal cells. Increases Na+/K+ ATPase and ENaC channels. Na+ reabsorbed, K+ and H+ secreted. Water follows Na+ passively. Part of RAAS: low BP -> renin -> angiotensin II -> aldosterone. Hyperaldosteronism = hypertension + hypokalemia + metabolic alkalosis.",mn:"Aldosterone: Na+ IN, K+ OUT, H+ OUT. Holds onto salt."},
{id:"bs7",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Immune System"],diff:2,q:"T cells mature in the:",o:["Thymus","Bone marrow","Spleen","Lymph nodes"],a:0,ex:"T = Thymus (positive + negative selection for self-tolerance). B = Bone marrow. CD4+ = helper (activate others via cytokines). CD8+ = cytotoxic (kill infected/cancer cells). Treg = suppress immune response. Positive selection: must recognize self-MHC. Negative selection: must NOT react to self-antigens.",mn:"T = Thymus, B = Bone marrow."},
{id:"bs8",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System"],diff:2,q:"GFR is primarily regulated by:",o:["Tone of afferent and efferent arterioles controlling renal blood flow","Systemic arterial blood pressure acting as the sole determining factor","ADH-mediated water reabsorption in the collecting duct epithelium","Total urine output volume measured at the bladder over time"],a:0,ex:"GFR controlled by adjusting afferent (arriving) and efferent (exiting) arteriole diameter. Dilate afferent OR constrict efferent -> increased GFR. RAAS: angiotensin II constricts efferent -> maintains GFR when BP low. NSAIDs block prostaglandins that dilate afferent -> can dangerously reduce GFR.",mn:"Afferent = Arriving. Efferent = Exiting. Constrict efferent = more GFR."},
{id:"bs9",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Action Potential"],diff:2,q:"During an action potential, depolarization is caused by:",o:["Na+ influx through voltage-gated sodium channels opening at threshold","K+ efflux through delayed rectifier potassium channels during repolarization","Cl- influx through ligand-gated chloride channels causing hyperpolarization","Ca2+ efflux through calcium ATPase pumps during the resting phase"],a:0,ex:"Resting potential: ~-70mV (maintained by Na+/K+ ATPase and K+ leak channels). When threshold (-55mV) is reached: voltage-gated Na+ channels open -> Na+ rushes IN (down its electrochemical gradient) -> rapid depolarization to ~+30mV. Then Na+ channels inactivate and K+ channels open -> K+ flows OUT -> repolarization back to negative. Refractory period prevents backward signal propagation.",mn:"Depolarization = Na+ IN. Repolarization = K+ OUT."},
{id:"bs10",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Neurotransmitters"],diff:2,q:"The neurotransmitter at the neuromuscular junction is:",o:["SA node generates spontaneous depolarization setting heart rhythm","AV node generates the fastest rate and serves as primary pacemaker","Purkinje fibers initiate each heartbeat in ventricular myocardium","Bundle of His generates action potentials that drive atrial contraction"],a:0,ex:"Motor neurons release ACh at the NMJ, which binds nicotinic receptors on skeletal muscle -> Na+ influx -> muscle contraction. ACh is rapidly degraded by acetylcholinesterase (AChE) in the synaptic cleft. Clinical relevance: myasthenia gravis = autoimmune antibodies against nicotinic ACh receptors -> muscle weakness. Organophosphates inhibit AChE -> ACh accumulates -> overstimulation.",mn:"NMJ always = ACh at nicotinic receptors. Myasthenia gravis = Ab against these receptors."},
{id:"bs11",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Endocrine System","Hormones"],diff:2,q:"Thyroid hormone's primary effect:",o:["Increases basal metabolic rate","Decreases resting heart rate","Promotes adipose fat storage","Suppresses longitudinal growth"],a:0,ex:"Thyroid hormones (T3, T4) increase basal metabolic rate, O2 consumption, and heat production in nearly all tissues. T4 is the major circulating form; T3 is the active form (converted from T4 by deiodinases). Regulation: hypothalamus (TRH) -> anterior pituitary (TSH) -> thyroid (T3/T4) -> negative feedback on hypothalamus and pituitary. Hyper = Graves' disease. Hypo = Hashimoto's (autoimmune).",mn:"Thyroid = metabolism UP. T4 is storage form, T3 is active."},
{id:"bs12",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Immune System"],diff:2,q:"MHC Class I presents antigens to:",o:["CD8+ cytotoxic T cells","CD4+ helper T cells","B cells","Natural killer cells directly"],a:0,ex:"MHC I is on ALL nucleated cells. It presents intracellular (endogenous) antigens -- pieces of proteins being made inside the cell. If the cell is infected or cancerous, abnormal peptides appear on MHC I, flagging CD8+ T cells to kill. MHC II is on antigen-presenting cells only (dendritic cells, macrophages, B cells). It presents extracellular (exogenous) antigens to CD4+ helper T cells.",mn:"MHC I = ALL cells -> CD8 (kill). MHC II = APCs only -> CD4 (help)."},
{id:"bs13",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Digestive System"],diff:2,q:"Pepsin is active in the:",o:["Stomach (acidic pH)","Small intestine (alkaline pH)","Mouth","Large intestine"],a:0,ex:"Pepsin is a protease active at pH ~2 (the acidic stomach environment). It is secreted as inactive pepsinogen by chief cells, then activated by HCl (from parietal cells). In the small intestine, the pH is ~7-8 (neutralized by pancreatic bicarbonate), which inactivates pepsin. Pancreatic proteases (trypsin, chymotrypsin) take over protein digestion in the duodenum.",mn:"Pepsin = stomach (pH 2). Trypsin/chymotrypsin = small intestine (pH 7-8)."},
{id:"bs14",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Endocrine System","Hormones"],diff:3,q:"Anterior pituitary hormones include:",o:["GH, TSH, ACTH, FSH, LH, and Prolactin","ADH and oxytocin released from storage","Epinephrine and norepinephrine only","Insulin, glucagon, and somatostatin"],a:0,ex:"FLAT PiG mnemonic: FSH, LH, ACTH, TSH, Prolactin, (i=ignore) GH. These are made IN the anterior pituitary. The posterior pituitary does NOT make hormones -- it only stores and releases ADH and oxytocin (made in hypothalamus). Key distinction: anterior = glandular tissue that synthesizes. Posterior = neural tissue that stores.",mn:"Anterior: FLAT PiG (FSH,LH,ACTH,TSH,Prolactin,GH). Posterior: ADH + Oxytocin."},
{id:"pbs1",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Hematology","Immune System"],diff:3,pass:"p2",q:"Most likely diagnosis:",o:["Autoimmune hemolytic anemia","Iron deficiency anemia","Sickle cell disease","Aplastic anemia"],a:0,ex:"Positive Coombs = antibodies on RBCs (autoimmune). Spherocytes = partial phagocytosis by macrophages. Low haptoglobin = depleted by binding free hemoglobin from lysed RBCs. High LDH = released from cell destruction. High reticulocytes = marrow compensating. Iron deficiency would show microcytic cells. Aplastic = LOW reticulocytes.",mn:"+ Coombs + spherocytes + low haptoglobin + high LDH = autoimmune hemolysis"},
{id:"pbs2",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Action Potential"],diff:3,pass:"p6",q:"TTX at a node of Ranvier would:",o:["Block action potential propagation at that node","Block potassium efflux during repolarization phase","Cause sustained continuous membrane depolarization","Have no measurable effect on nerve conduction"],a:0,ex:"TTX blocks voltage-gated Na+ channels. Without Na+ influx, depolarization cannot occur at that node. In myelinated neurons, action potentials jump node to node (saltatory conduction). Blocking one node impairs or stops signal propagation beyond that point.",mn:"TTX blocks Na+ channels = no depolarization at that node."},
{id:"pbs3",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Action Potential"],diff:3,pass:"p6",q:"TEA blocking K+ channels would:",o:["Prolong the action potential","Prevent depolarization","Cause immediate hyperpolarization","Have no effect"],a:0,ex:"K+ efflux drives repolarization. TEA blocks K+ channels, trapping K+ inside, delaying return to resting potential. The AP duration is prolonged. The neuron can still fire (Na+ channels work) but takes longer to reset, potentially decreasing maximum firing frequency.",mn:"TEA blocks K+ = slow repolarization = longer AP."},
{id:"bs15",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System"],diff:1,q:"Blood flow order through the heart:",o:["Vena cava, RA, RV, pulmonary arteries, lungs, LA, LV, aorta","Aorta, right atrium, right ventricle, lungs, left atrium","Left atrium, right atrium, lungs, left ventricle, aorta","Pulmonary vein, right ventricle, lungs, left atrium only"],a:0,ex:"Deoxygenated blood returns via superior/inferior vena cava to RIGHT atrium -> tricuspid valve -> RIGHT ventricle -> pulmonary valve -> pulmonary arteries -> LUNGS (gas exchange) -> pulmonary veins -> LEFT atrium -> mitral (bicuspid) valve -> LEFT ventricle -> aortic valve -> aorta -> body. Remember: right side = deoxygenated to lungs. Left side = oxygenated to body. Left ventricle has thickest wall (pumps to entire body).",mn:"Right = to lungs. Left = to body. Tri before you Bi (tricuspid before bicuspid)."},
// ============ MOLECULAR BIO (12) ============
{id:"mb1",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["DNA Replication"],diff:1,q:"Helicase's role:",o:["Unwinds DNA double helix","Relieves supercoiling","Makes RNA primers","Synthesizes new DNA"],a:0,ex:"Replication fork team: Helicase breaks H-bonds to unwind. Topoisomerase relieves supercoiling ahead. SSBs stabilize single strands. Primase makes RNA primers. DNA Pol III (pro) or delta/epsilon (eu) synthesizes 5' to 3'.",mn:"Helicase = Helix-ase. Topoisomerase = prevents tangling."},
{id:"mb2",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["DNA Replication"],diff:2,q:"Okazaki fragments are on the:",o:["Lagging strand","Leading strand","Both equally","mRNA"],a:0,ex:"DNA pol only synthesizes 5' to 3'. Leading strand = continuous (toward fork, one primer). Lagging strand = discontinuous fragments (away from fork, each needs own primer). DNA Pol I removes primers and fills gaps. DNA ligase seals nicks between fragments.",mn:"Lagging = lots of fragments. Ligase = glue."},
{id:"mb3",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["DNA Replication"],diff:1,q:"DNA polymerase synthesizes in which direction?",o:["5-prime to 3-prime direction only","3-prime to 5-prime direction only","Both directions simultaneously","Random direction without polarity"],a:0,ex:"ALL DNA polymerases build 5' to 3' only (add nucleotides to free 3'-OH). Read template 3' to 5'. Proofreading: 3' to 5' exonuclease removes mismatches. Error rate ~1/10^9. RNA polymerase also synthesizes 5' to 3' but needs no primer.",mn:"Always 5' to 3'. No exceptions ever."},
{id:"mb4",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Mutations"],diff:3,q:"A nonsense mutation produces:",o:["Premature stop codon producing a truncated nonfunctional protein","Single amino acid substitution producing a missense protein variant","Reading frame shift altering all downstream amino acid sequence","Silent mutation producing no detectable change in protein function"],a:0,ex:"Point mutations: Silent = same AA (wobble position). Missense = different AA (sickle cell: Glu -> Val). Nonsense = STOP codon (UAA/UAG/UGA) -> truncated protein. Frameshift = insertion/deletion (not x3) -> everything downstream scrambled.",mn:"Nonsense = premature STOP. Missense = wrong AA. Silent = no effect."},
{id:"mb5",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Gene Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Lac operon is fully induced when:",o:["Lactose is present in the medium AND glucose is absent","Glucose is present at high concentration in the growth medium","Cellular ATP levels are elevated above the normal threshold","Tryptophan is abundant and acts as an allosteric corepressor"],a:0,ex:"Two signals needed: (1) Lactose -> allolactose removes repressor from operator. (2) Low glucose -> high cAMP -> CAP activates transcription. Both = full expression. With glucose present (even with lactose), cAMP is low, CAP inactive, only basal transcription. Glucose always wins.",mn:"Lactose ON + Glucose OFF = full induction. Glucose always preferred."},
{id:"mb6",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Tumor Suppressors","Cell Cycle"],diff:3,q:"p53 responds to DNA damage by:",o:["Arresting the cell cycle and triggering apoptosis if needed","Promoting cellular division and accelerating DNA replication","Activating telomerase to maintain chromosome end integrity","Increasing the rate of beneficial mutations for adaptation"],a:0,ex:"p53 = guardian of genome. DNA damage -> p53 stabilized -> activates p21 (CDK inhibitor) -> G1/S arrest for repair. If irreparable: activates BAX/PUMA -> apoptosis via intrinsic pathway. Mutated in >50% of all cancers. Two-hit hypothesis: both alleles must be lost.",mn:"p53: damage -> STOP -> repair or self-destruct."},
{id:"mb7",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Transcription/Translation"],diff:2,q:"Prokaryotic vs eukaryotic ribosomes:",o:["70S vs 80S","80S vs 70S","Both 80S","Both 70S"],a:0,ex:"Pro = 70S (30S + 50S). Eu = 80S (40S + 60S). Svedberg units are NOT additive. Many antibiotics target 70S: chloramphenicol/macrolides (50S subunit), tetracyclines/aminoglycosides (30S). Mitochondrial ribosomes are 70S (endosymbiotic theory).",mn:"Pro = 70S, Eu = 80S. Antibiotics target 70S."},
{id:"mb8",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Transcription/Translation"],diff:2,q:"The 5' cap on eukaryotic mRNA is:",o:["7-methylguanosine","Poly-A tail","An intron","Methyl-cytosine"],a:0,ex:"Eukaryotic mRNA undergoes 3 processing steps: (1) 5' cap = 7-methylguanosine via unusual 5'-5' linkage. Functions: protects from exonuclease, aids ribosome recognition, assists nuclear export. (2) 3' poly-A tail = ~200 adenines. Functions: stability, export. (3) Splicing = spliceosome (snRNPs) removes introns, joins exons.",mn:"Cap = helmet (5'). Poly-A = cushion (3'). Both protect and aid export."},
{id:"mb9",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["DNA Replication"],diff:3,q:"Telomerase prevents:",o:["Progressive chromosome shortening during each replication cycle","Accumulation of mismatch errors during DNA synthesis process","Excessive DNA unwinding by helicase at replication fork sites","Aberrant DNA methylation patterns altering gene expression levels"],a:0,ex:"End replication problem: DNA pol needs a primer, so after primer removal at chromosome ends, a gap remains -> chromosomes shorten 50-200bp per division. Telomeres (TTAGGG repeats) buffer this. Telomerase is a reverse transcriptase (has own RNA template) that extends telomeres. Active in stem cells, germ cells, ~90% cancers. Somatic cells: low/no telomerase -> Hayflick limit (~50 divisions).",mn:"Telomerase = reverse transcriptase extending chromosome ends."},
{id:"pmb2",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Acid-Base"],diff:3,pass:"p3",q:"The enzyme's ability to function at pH 2-10 is unusual because most enzymes:",o:["Denature outside a narrow pH range","Function equally at all pH values","Require pH above 10","Only work in acidic conditions"],a:0,ex:"Most enzymes have a narrow optimal pH range (usually 6-8 for cytoplasmic enzymes). Outside this range, ionizable groups in the active site change protonation state, disrupting catalysis, and extreme pH can denature the protein. The passage describes an extremophilic enzyme that maintains activity across pH 2-10, which is remarkable. Extremophiles (organisms in extreme environments) have evolved proteins with unusual stability -- their enzymes are of biotechnological interest for industrial processes that require extreme conditions.",mn:"Most enzymes work in narrow pH range. Extremophilic enzymes are unusually stable."},
// ============ GEN CHEM (14) ============
{id:"gc1",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Buffers","Acid-Base"],diff:1,q:"A buffer works best at pH within +/-1 of its:",o:["pKa","7.0","pKb","14"],a:0,ex:"Henderson-Hasselbalch: pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]). Maximum buffering when [A-] = [HA] (ratio = 1, log = 0), which occurs at pH = pKa. Outside +/-1, one form depleted -> poor buffering. To buffer at a target pH, choose a weak acid with pKa near that pH.",mn:"Buffer = best at pKa +/- 1. At pKa, ratio is 1:1."},
{id:"gc2",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Thermodynamics"],diff:2,q:"Spontaneous at ALL temperatures:",o:["Negative enthalpy change and positive entropy change combined","Positive enthalpy change and positive entropy change combined","Negative enthalpy change and negative entropy change combined","Positive enthalpy change and negative entropy change combined"],a:0,ex:"delta-G = delta-H - T*delta-S. Both terms push G negative at all T when H<0 and S>0. Four combos: H-/S+ = always spontaneous. H+/S- = never. H-/S- = low T only. H+/S+ = high T only.",mn:"Exothermic + more disorder = always spontaneous"},
{id:"gc3",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Equilibrium"],diff:1,q:"Adding product to a system at equilibrium:",o:["Shifts equilibrium toward reactant side","Produces more product at equilibrium","Has no effect on the equilibrium position","Increases the equilibrium constant value"],a:0,ex:"Le Chatelier: system shifts to reduce stress. Adding product -> shifts LEFT. Only TEMPERATURE changes Keq. Concentration and pressure changes shift position but not Keq itself. For exothermic: heat is a product, so increasing T decreases Keq.",mn:"System runs away from what you add. Only T changes Keq."},
{id:"gc4",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Redox Chemistry"],diff:1,q:"Oxidation is:",o:["Loss of electrons","Gain of electrons","Loss of protons","Gain of protons"],a:0,ex:"OIL RIG: Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain. The oxidizing agent gets reduced (accepts electrons). The reducing agent gets oxidized (donates electrons). In biology: NAD+ (oxidizing agent) + 2e- + H+ -> NADH (reducing agent).",mn:"OIL RIG. The oxidizing agent itself gets reduced."},
{id:"gc5",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base"],diff:2,q:"pH of 1x10^-3 M HCl:",o:["3","11","-3","0.001"],a:0,ex:"HCl is a strong acid = complete dissociation. [H+] = 10^-3. pH = -log(10^-3) = 3. Strong acids: HCl, HBr, HI, HNO3, H2SO4, HClO3, HClO4. For non-powers of 10: pH is between flanking integers.",mn:"Strong acid: pH = -log[acid] directly."},
{id:"gc6",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry"],diff:3,q:"Positive E-cell means:",o:["Spontaneous","Non-spontaneous","Needs external voltage","delta-G > 0"],a:0,ex:"delta-G = -nFE. Positive E -> negative delta-G -> spontaneous = galvanic/voltaic cell. E-cell = E(cathode) - E(anode). Species with more positive reduction potential is reduced (cathode). Negative E-cell -> electrolytic cell (requires external power).",mn:"+E = -delta-G = spontaneous = galvanic cell"},
{id:"gc7",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Chemical Kinetics"],diff:3,q:"First-order half-life:",o:["Constant and independent of initial concentration","Doubles when initial concentration is doubled","Depends directly on the initial reactant concentration","Always equals zero regardless of reaction conditions"],a:0,ex:"For first order: t1/2 = ln2/k = 0.693/k. CONSTANT regardless of starting concentration. Also governs radioactive decay and most drug elimination. Zero-order: t1/2 = [A]0/2k (depends on [A]). Second-order: t1/2 = 1/(k[A]0).",mn:"First order: t1/2 = 0.693/k. Constant like radioactive decay."},
{id:"gc8",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Intermolecular Forces"],diff:2,q:"Strongest to weakest IMFs:",o:["Ion-dipole > hydrogen bond > dipole-dipole > London dispersion","London dispersion > hydrogen bond > ion-dipole > ion-ion","All intermolecular forces are equal in strength regardless of type","Hydrogen bonding > ion-ion > dipole-dipole > London dispersion"],a:0,ex:"Ion-ion (NaCl lattice) > ion-dipole (Na+ in water) > H-bonding (needs H on N/O/F) > dipole-dipole > London dispersion (all molecules, increases with MW/surface area). H-bonding explains water's high BP, specific heat, and surface tension.",mn:"Ion-dipole > H-bond > dipole-dipole > London"},
{id:"gc9",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Solutions"],diff:2,q:"Adding a nonvolatile solute to water:",o:["Raises the boiling point and lowers the freezing point","Lowers the boiling point and raises the freezing point","Raises both the boiling point and the freezing point","Has no measurable effect on either boiling or freezing"],a:0,ex:"Colligative properties depend on NUMBER of solute particles, not identity: boiling point elevation (delta-Tb = iKb*m), freezing point depression (delta-Tf = iKf*m), osmotic pressure, vapor pressure lowering (Raoult's law). The van't Hoff factor i accounts for dissociation: NaCl i=2, glucose i=1, CaCl2 i=3. More particles = greater effect.",mn:"Solute raises BP, lowers FP. More particles = bigger effect (i factor)."},
{id:"gc10",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base"],diff:3,q:"A polyprotic acid like H2SO4:",o:["Donates protons sequentially, each with its own Ka value","Donates all protons simultaneously in a single ionization","Has only one Ka regardless of the number of ionizable protons","Cannot act as a buffer at any pH under standard conditions"],a:0,ex:"Polyprotic acids donate protons one at a time. Each step has its own Ka, and Ka1 >> Ka2 >> Ka3 because removing each subsequent proton from an increasingly negative species is harder. H2SO4: first proton is strong acid (complete), second is weak (Ka2 = 0.012). H3PO4: three Ka values. Each dissociation step creates its own buffer region on the titration curve.",mn:"Ka1 >> Ka2 >> Ka3. Each proton is harder to remove than the last."},
{id:"gc11",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Atomic Structure"],diff:2,q:"An element's atomic number equals its number of:",o:["Protons","Neutrons","Electrons in an ion","Mass number"],a:0,ex:"Atomic number (Z) = number of protons = defines the element. Mass number (A) = protons + neutrons. Isotopes = same element (same Z) but different number of neutrons (different A). In a neutral atom: protons = electrons. In ions: protons stay the same, electrons change. Example: Carbon-12 has Z=6 (6 protons), A=12 (6 neutrons).",mn:"Atomic number = protons = element identity. Mass number = protons + neutrons."},
// ============ ORGO (10) ============
{id:"org1",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions"],diff:2,q:"SN1 is favored by:",o:["Tertiary substrate with a weak nucleophile in polar protic solvent","Primary substrate with a strong nucleophile in polar aprotic solvent","Secondary substrate with a moderate nucleophile in polar aprotic solvent","Methyl substrate with a strong bulky base in polar protic solvent"],a:0,ex:"SN1 needs a stable carbocation intermediate: 3 > 2 >> never methyl/1. Weak nucleophile (strong would push SN2). Polar protic solvent stabilizes the carbocation. Rate = k[substrate] only. Stereochemistry: racemization (planar carbocation attacked from both sides).",mn:"SN1: 3-degree, weak nuc, protic = racemic"},
{id:"org2",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions"],diff:1,q:"SN2 stereochemistry:",o:["Inversion of stereochemistry at the carbon center","Retention of original stereochemistry at carbon","Racemization producing equal R and S products","No change in configuration at any carbon"],a:0,ex:"SN2: single concerted step. Nucleophile attacks 180 degrees from leaving group (backside attack). Forces umbrella-like inversion: R -> S. Favored: methyl > 1 > 2 (never 3). Strong nucleophile, polar aprotic solvent. Rate = k[sub][nuc].",mn:"SN2 = backside attack = always inverts."},
{id:"org3",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Elimination Reactions"],diff:2,q:"Bulky base + 2-degree substrate most likely gives:",o:["E2 elimination producing an alkene and leaving group departure","SN2 substitution producing inverted stereochemistry at carbon center","SN1 substitution producing a racemic mixture through carbocation","E1 elimination producing an alkene through unimolecular rate step"],a:0,ex:"Base too bulky for backside attack (SN2 blocked). Instead abstracts a beta-proton. E2: concerted, anti-periplanar geometry required, Zaitsev product (more substituted alkene, unless very bulky base -> Hofmann product).",mn:"Too bulky to SN2 -> grabs a proton = E2"},
{id:"org4",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Addition Reactions"],diff:2,q:"Markovnikov's rule: H adds to carbon with:",o:["More existing H atoms","Fewer H atoms","More substituents","The leaving group"],a:0,ex:"In HX addition across a double bond, H goes to the less substituted carbon (more H's already there), placing X on the more substituted carbon. This gives the more stable carbocation intermediate. Exception: HBr + peroxides = anti-Markovnikov (radical mechanism).",mn:"Rich get richer. H goes where H's already are."},
{id:"org5",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Stereochemistry"],diff:1,q:"Enantiomers differ at:",o:["ALL stereocenters","One stereocenter","Connectivity","Formula"],a:0,ex:"Enantiomers = non-superimposable mirror images. All R's become S's and vice versa. Same physical properties (MP, BP, solubility, Rf) EXCEPT: (1) optical rotation (equal and opposite), (2) interactions with other chiral molecules (drug-receptor binding). Racemic mixture = 50:50, zero net rotation.",mn:"Enantiomers = mirror images. Same everything except optical rotation."},
{id:"org6",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Carbonyl Chemistry"],diff:3,q:"LiAlH4 vs NaBH4:",o:["LiAlH4 reduces all carbonyls; NaBH4 reduces only aldehydes and ketones","Both reagents reduce all carbonyl functional groups with equal strength","NaBH4 is a stronger reducing agent that reduces all functional groups","The two reagents are chemically identical with no selectivity difference"],a:0,ex:"LiAlH4 = powerful, non-selective: reduces COOH -> 1-OH, esters -> 2 alcohols, amides -> amines, plus aldehydes/ketones. NaBH4 = mild, selective: ONLY reduces aldehydes and ketones to alcohols. PCC = OXIDIZER (1-OH -> aldehyde, stops there). H2/Pd = catalytic hydrogenation (reduces C=C).",mn:"LiAlH4 = sledgehammer. NaBH4 = gentle. PCC = oxidizer."},
{id:"org7",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Functional Groups"],diff:1,q:"An aldehyde differs from a ketone because:",o:["Aldehyde has C=O bonded to at least one H","Ketone has C=O bonded to at least one H","They are identical","Aldehyde has C-O single bond"],a:0,ex:"Both are carbonyl compounds (C=O). Aldehyde: carbonyl C bonded to at least one H (R-CHO) -- found at the END of a carbon chain. Ketone: carbonyl C bonded to TWO carbons (R-CO-R') -- found in the MIDDLE of a chain. Aldehydes are more reactive than ketones (less steric hindrance, more electrophilic). Aldehydes can be oxidized to carboxylic acids; ketones cannot be easily oxidized.",mn:"Aldehyde = end of chain (has H). Ketone = middle (no H on C=O)."},
{id:"org8",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Functional Groups"],diff:2,q:"Carboxylic acids are acidic because:",o:["The conjugate base is stabilized by resonance delocalization","The oxygen-hydrogen bond has very high dissociation energy","They lack any resonance structures in the conjugate base","They behave as strong acids that fully dissociate in water"],a:0,ex:"When a carboxylic acid (R-COOH) donates a proton, the resulting carboxylate ion (R-COO-) has resonance stabilization: the negative charge is delocalized equally across both oxygen atoms. This stabilization of the conjugate base makes the acid more willing to donate its proton. Carboxylic acids are WEAK acids (pKa ~4-5), not strong. They are more acidic than alcohols (pKa ~16) because alcohol conjugate bases (alkoxide, R-O-) have no resonance stabilization.",mn:"COOH -> COO- with resonance = stable conjugate base = more acidic than alcohols."},
// ============ PHYSICS (12) ============
{id:"ph1",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Bernoulli's Principle"],diff:2,q:"Bernoulli: increasing fluid velocity causes:",o:["Decreased pressure","Increased pressure","No effect","Increased density"],a:0,ex:"P + 1/2*rho*v^2 + rho*g*h = constant. If v increases (narrow pipe), P must decrease. Applications: airplane wing lift, Venturi effect, vascular stenosis. This is conservation of energy for fluids.",mn:"Fast flow = low pressure. Think airplane wings."},
{id:"ph2",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Electrostatics"],diff:1,q:"Doubling distance between charges changes force to:",o:["One-quarter of the original force value","One-half of the original force value","The same as the original force value","Double the original force magnitude"],a:0,ex:"Coulomb: F = kq1q2/r^2. Inverse square: 2r -> F/4, 3r -> F/9. Same relationship for: gravity, E-field, light intensity, sound intensity.",mn:"Inverse square: 2x distance = 1/4 force"},
{id:"ph3",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Work and Energy"],diff:1,q:"Work = 0 when force is:",o:["Perpendicular to the direction of wave displacement and travel","Parallel to the direction of displacement and wave propagation","Antiparallel to the direction of displacement and propagation","Oriented at 45 degrees relative to the wave displacement axis"],a:0,ex:"W = Fd*cos(theta). At 90 degrees: cos90 = 0 -> W = 0. Examples: normal force, centripetal force, gravity on horizontal motion. Parallel = max work. Antiparallel = negative work (friction).",mn:"Perpendicular = zero work. Parallel = max."},
{id:"ph4",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Waves and Sound"],diff:1,q:"Sound travels fastest through:",o:["Solids","Liquids","Gases","Vacuum"],a:0,ex:"Sound = mechanical wave, needs a medium (no vacuum). Speed: solids (~5000 m/s) > liquids (~1500) > gases (~340). In gases: v proportional to sqrt(T/M). Opposite of EM waves (fastest in vacuum).",mn:"Sound: solid > liquid > gas. Cannot travel in vacuum."},
{id:"ph5",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Circuits"],diff:2,q:"Resistors in series vs parallel:",o:["Series: resistances add directly. Parallel: total is less than smallest","Parallel: resistances add directly. Series: total is less than smallest","Both series and parallel circuits add resistances the same way","Series: total resistance is always less than the smallest resistor"],a:0,ex:"Series: same current, R_total = R1+R2 (total > each). Parallel: same voltage, 1/R_total = 1/R1+1/R2 (total < smallest). Two equal resistors in parallel: R_total = R/2.",mn:"Series: R adds up. Parallel: 1/R adds (total is less)."},
{id:"ph6",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Waves and Sound"],diff:2,q:"Source approaching observer: frequency is:",o:["Higher, because the sound waves are compressed ahead of the source","Lower, because the sound waves are stretched ahead of the source","Unchanged, because frequency depends only on the source itself","Zero, because the waves cancel out at supersonic approach speeds"],a:0,ex:"Doppler effect: approaching = compressed wavefronts = shorter wavelength = higher frequency. Receding = stretched = lower frequency. Applies to sound (ambulance siren), light (blueshift/redshift), ultrasound (echocardiography).",mn:"Approaching = higher pitch. Receding = lower."},
{id:"ph7",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics"],diff:2,q:"Thin lens equation:",o:["1/f = 1/do + 1/di","f = do + di","f = do x di","1/f = 1/do - 1/di"],a:0,ex:"Works for lenses and mirrors. Converging (convex) lens: f > 0. Diverging (concave) lens: f < 0. Real image: di > 0. Virtual: di < 0. Magnification: m = -di/do. Power (diopters) = 1/f(meters). Two lenses in contact: 1/f_total = 1/f1 + 1/f2.",mn:"1/f = 1/do + 1/di. Memorize sign conventions."},
{id:"ph8",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics"],diff:2,q:"Total internal reflection requires light going from:",o:["Inversely proportional to the square of the distance between charges","Directly proportional to the square of the distance between charges","Independent of distance and depends only on the magnitude of charges","Inversely proportional to the distance in a simple linear relationship"],a:0,ex:"TIR requires: (1) light from higher refractive index to lower (glass -> air, water -> air), AND (2) angle of incidence > critical angle (theta_c = arcsin(n2/n1)). Below critical angle: refraction + reflection. At critical angle: refracted ray at 90 degrees. Above: ALL light reflected. Applications: fiber optics, diamond brilliance (high n = low critical angle = lots of TIR).",mn:"High-to-low n + exceed critical angle = total reflection."},
{id:"ph9",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Nuclear Physics"],diff:2,q:"Beta-minus decay emits:",o:["An electron plus an antineutrino","A positron plus a neutrino","An alpha particle from nucleus","A gamma photon emission only"],a:0,ex:"Radioactive decay types: Alpha = helium nucleus (2p+2n, mass -4, Z -2). Beta-minus = neutron -> proton + electron + antineutrino (Z +1, mass same). Beta-plus = proton -> neutron + positron + neutrino (Z -1). Gamma = high-energy photon, no mass/charge change. Electron capture = inner electron captured by nucleus.",mn:"Beta-minus: n -> p + electron. Z goes UP by 1."},
{id:"ph10",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Circuits"],diff:3,q:"Capacitors in series vs parallel:",o:["Series: reciprocals add; Parallel: values add directly","Series: values add directly; Parallel: reciprocals add","Both configurations add capacitance values directly","Both configurations use reciprocal addition rules"],a:0,ex:"Capacitors follow OPPOSITE rules from resistors: Series: 1/C_total = 1/C1 + 1/C2 (total < smallest). Parallel: C_total = C1 + C2 (total = sum). C = epsilon*A/d: bigger plates or smaller gap = more capacitance. Inserting dielectric increases C by factor kappa.",mn:"Capacitors = opposite of resistors. Series: less. Parallel: more."},
// ============ PSYCH/SOC (25) ============
{id:"ps1",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Developmental Psychology"],diff:1,q:"Object permanence develops during Piaget's:",o:["Sensorimotor (0-2)","Preoperational (2-7)","Concrete operational (7-11)","Formal operational (12+)"],a:0,ex:"Piaget's stages: Sensorimotor (0-2): senses + motor, object permanence ~8mo. Preoperational (2-7): symbolic thinking but egocentric, no conservation. Concrete operational (7-11): logic about concrete things, conservation mastered. Formal operational (12+): abstract/hypothetical thinking.",mn:"Sensorimotor = senses + object permanence"},
{id:"ps2",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:1,q:"Bystander effect is explained by:",o:["Diffusion of responsibility among bystanders","Social facilitation from audience presence","Groupthink within cohesive decision groups","Deindividuation in anonymous crowd settings"],a:0,ex:"More bystanders = less individual responsibility. Also: pluralistic ignorance (everyone looks calm = must be fine) and evaluation apprehension (fear of embarrassment). Fix: single out one person for action. Kitty Genovese case inspired this research.",mn:"More watchers = less help. Single someone out to fix it."},
{id:"ps3",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Emotion Theories"],diff:2,q:"Schachter-Singer two-factor theory:",o:["Arousal + cognitive label = emotion","Body then emotion","Simultaneous and independent","Facial expression determines emotion"],a:0,ex:"Three theories: James-Lange (body -> emotion). Cannon-Bard (simultaneous). Schachter-Singer (arousal + cognitive labeling based on context = emotion). Same arousal can become different emotions depending on interpretation. Bridge study: fear arousal mislabeled as attraction.",mn:"Two factors: body buzz + brain's contextual interpretation"},
{id:"ps4",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Learning and Conditioning"],diff:2,q:"Negative reinforcement means:",o:["Removing an aversive stimulus to increase behavior frequency","Adding a punishing stimulus to decrease behavior frequency","Removing a rewarding stimulus to decrease behavior frequency","Ignoring the target behavior to cause gradual extinction"],a:0,ex:"Four quadrants: Positive reinforcement (add pleasant -> increase). Negative reinforcement (remove unpleasant -> increase). Positive punishment (add unpleasant -> decrease). Negative punishment (remove pleasant -> decrease). Key: positive = add, negative = remove, reinforcement = increase, punishment = decrease.",mn:"Negative = REMOVE. Reinforcement = INCREASE behavior."},
{id:"ps5",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Brain Anatomy"],diff:2,q:"Damage to Broca's area causes:",o:["Inability to produce fluent coherent speech output","Inability to comprehend spoken or written language","Visual field deficits in contralateral hemifield","Anterograde declarative memory loss and confusion"],a:0,ex:"Broca's (left inferior frontal) = speech PRODUCTION. Damage = non-fluent/expressive aphasia: understands but can't produce fluent speech (halting, telegraphic). Wernicke's (left superior temporal) = COMPREHENSION. Damage = fluent/receptive aphasia: produces fluent but meaningless 'word salad,' cannot understand.",mn:"Broca = Broken speech. Wernicke = Wordy nonsense."},
{id:"ps6",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Fundamental attribution error:",o:["Over-attributing others' behavior to their personality traits","Over-attributing one's own behavior to situational factors","Blaming victims for their own negative life outcomes","Believing the world is inherently just and fair"],a:0,ex:"FAE: for OTHERS, we overemphasize disposition (personality) and underestimate situation. 'They failed because they are lazy.' For OURSELVES: we blame the situation (actor-observer bias). Self-serving bias: my success = me, my failure = circumstances.",mn:"Others = personality. Me = circumstances."},
{id:"ps7",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sensation and Perception"],diff:2,q:"Weber's Law states:",o:["The just-noticeable difference scales with stimulus intensity","All stimuli are perceived with equal discriminability always","Sensory thresholds remain fixed across all stimulus levels","Sensory adaptation completely eliminates all sensation"],a:0,ex:"Delta-I/I = constant. The just noticeable difference (JND) is a constant PROPORTION, not absolute amount. If you notice 2g added to 100g (2%), you need 4g added to 200g to notice (still 2%). This is why a $1 increase feels big on a $5 item but trivial on a $500 item.",mn:"Weber: percent change matters, not absolute."},
{id:"ps8",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Cognitive dissonance is:",o:["Psychological discomfort from holding contradictory beliefs or actions","Conformity pressure from group members enforcing unanimous agreement","Systematic distortion of memories to match current emotional state","Strengthening of existing attitudes through repeated exposure to them"],a:0,ex:"Festinger: holding contradictory cognitions (e.g., 'smoking is bad' + 'I smoke') creates discomfort. Resolved by: changing behavior (quit), changing belief ('not that dangerous'), or adding justification ('I'll quit later'). Classic $1 vs $20 experiment: less payment = more dissonance = more attitude change.",mn:"Conflicting thoughts = discomfort -> change something to resolve"},
{id:"ps9",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Health Disparities"],diff:2,q:"Social determinants of health include:",o:["Income, education level, neighborhood safety, and healthcare access","Genetic predisposition and inherited biological traits exclusively","Personal dietary choices and nutritional intake patterns only","Individual exercise habits and physical activity levels alone"],a:0,ex:"SDOH explain MORE variance in health outcomes than individual behaviors or genetics. Categories: economic stability, education, social/community context, healthcare access, neighborhood/environment. Heavily tested on MCAT Psych/Soc section. Connected to health disparities, institutional racism, medical ethics.",mn:"Where you live and your resources matter more than individual choices."},
{id:"ps10",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Motivation"],diff:2,q:"Base of Maslow's hierarchy:",o:["Physiological needs","Safety","Love/belonging","Self-actualization"],a:0,ex:"Bottom to top: Physiological (food, water, sleep) -> Safety -> Love/belonging -> Esteem -> Self-actualization. Lower needs must be substantially met before higher needs motivate. Criticism: too rigid, Western-centric, hard to test.",mn:"Survival first, self-actualization last."},
{id:"ps11",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Asch conformity experiments showed:",o:["About 75% conformed at least once to an obviously wrong answer","No participants ever conformed to the incorrect group response","Conformity only occurs when an authority figure is present","The size of the majority group has no effect on conformity"],a:0,ex:"Asch: participants judged line lengths with confederates giving wrong answers. ~75% conformed at least once. Average rate ~37%. One dissenter reduced conformity from 37% to ~5%. Unanimity matters more than group size. This is normative social influence (desire to fit in).",mn:"75% conformed once. ONE ally breaks it."},
{id:"ps12",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sensation and Perception"],diff:2,q:"Sensory adaptation is:",o:["Decreased neural response to a constant ongoing stimulus","Increased sensitivity to repeated presentation of stimuli","Learning to discriminate between two new similar stimuli","Transfer of sensory information between different modalities"],a:0,ex:"Receptors reduce firing rate for constant stimuli. Examples: stop feeling clothes, stop smelling your house. Different from habituation (behavioral/CNS, not receptor level). Exception: pain receptors (nociceptors) show minimal adaptation -- pain signals danger.",mn:"Constant stimulus -> stop noticing. Pain is the exception."},
{id:"ps13",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Learning and Conditioning"],diff:1,q:"Classical conditioning was discovered by:",o:["Pavlov","Skinner","Bandura","Watson"],a:0,ex:"Pavlov: bell (NS->CS) paired with food (UCS) -> bell alone triggers salivation (CR). Watson: applied to human fear (Little Albert). Skinner: operant conditioning (consequences shape behavior). Bandura: observational learning (Bobo doll -- children imitate witnessed aggression).",mn:"Pavlov = bell, dog, drool. Watson = fear in humans."},
{id:"ps14",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Developmental Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Erikson's adolescent crisis:",o:["Identity vs Role Confusion","Intimacy vs Isolation","Initiative vs Guilt","Trust vs Mistrust"],a:0,ex:"Eight stages: Trust/Mistrust (0-1), Autonomy/Shame (1-3), Initiative/Guilt (3-6), Industry/Inferiority (6-12), Identity/Role Confusion (12-18), Intimacy/Isolation (18-40), Generativity/Stagnation (40-65), Integrity/Despair (65+).",mn:"Teens = identity. Young adults = intimacy."},
{id:"ps15",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory"],diff:2,q:"Working memory capacity is approximately:",o:["Seven plus or minus two chunks of information","An unlimited number of items without any constraint","Only two individual items at any given time point","Approximately fifty items held simultaneously"],a:0,ex:"Miller's Law: working memory holds about 7 (+/-2) items at once. Chunking can increase effective capacity (remembering 10 digits as a phone number pattern). Working memory is a component of short-term memory that actively manipulates information. Encoding into long-term memory requires rehearsal, elaboration, or emotional significance.",mn:"7 +/- 2. Chunking helps. Working memory actively processes."},
{id:"ps16",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory"],diff:2,q:"The three stages of memory:",o:["Encoding, storage, retrieval","Input, processing, output","Sensory, emotional, logical","Learning, forgetting, relearning"],a:0,ex:"Encoding = converting information into a form the brain can store. Storage = maintaining encoded information over time (sensory -> short-term -> long-term). Retrieval = accessing stored information when needed. Failures can occur at any stage: encoding failure (never properly stored), storage decay (fades over time), retrieval failure (information exists but cannot be accessed -- tip-of-tongue phenomenon).",mn:"Encode -> Store -> Retrieve. Failure at any stage = forgetting."},
{id:"ps17",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sleep"],diff:2,q:"REM sleep is characterized by:",o:["Characterized by rapid eye movement, vivid dreaming, and muscle atonia","Characterized by deep slow-wave oscillations and growth hormone release","Characterized by frequent sleepwalking and night terror episodes","Characterized by minimal brain activity approaching unconscious state"],a:0,ex:"Sleep cycles ~90 min. NREM stages: N1 (light, theta), N2 (sleep spindles, K-complexes), N3 (deep/slow-wave, delta waves -- most restorative). REM: rapid eye movements, vivid dreaming, muscle paralysis (atonia -- prevents acting out dreams), EEG resembles waking. REM increases across the night. Sleep deprivation REM rebound. Memory consolidation occurs in both N3 (declarative) and REM (procedural).",mn:"REM = dreaming + paralysis + brain active. N3 = deep + restorative."},
{id:"ps18",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sociology"],diff:2,q:"Symbolic interactionism focuses on:",o:["Meaning is created through everyday social interactions","Large-scale social structures determine individual behavior","Biological drives and instincts determine all human behavior","Unconscious psychological drives shape all social interactions"],a:0,ex:"Three sociological perspectives: Functionalism (Durkheim): society's parts work together for stability. Conflict theory (Marx): power struggles and inequality between groups. Symbolic interactionism (Mead, Cooley): micro-level -- people create meaning through daily interactions and shared symbols (language, gestures). Cooley's looking-glass self: our self-concept is shaped by how we think others see us.",mn:"Symbolic interactionism = micro-level + meaning from interactions"},
{id:"ps19",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Moral Development"],diff:2,q:"Kohlberg's post-conventional morality:",o:["Universal ethical principles that transcend existing laws","Following established rules to maintain social order","Acting primarily out of rational self-interest alone","Avoiding punishment as the main motivation for behavior"],a:0,ex:"Pre-conventional (1-2): self-interest, avoid punishment. Conventional (3-4): conform to norms, maintain social order. Post-conventional (5-6): social contract (laws serve people, can change), universal principles (conscience above law -- civil disobedience). Most adults stay at conventional level.",mn:"Pre = selfish. Conventional = conformist. Post = principled."},
{id:"ps20",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Groupthink occurs when:",o:["The group prioritizes harmony over critical analysis of ideas","Individual members act independently without group influence","A single leader makes all decisions for the entire group","All group members openly disagree and debate every issue"],a:0,ex:"Janis: cohesive groups suppress dissent to maintain agreement, leading to poor decisions. Examples: Bay of Pigs, Challenger disaster. Signs: illusion of invulnerability, self-censorship, illusion of unanimity. Prevention: devil's advocate role, outside experts, anonymous feedback.",mn:"Harmony over critical thinking = bad decisions"},
{id:"pps1",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:3,pass:"p7",q:"This experiment resembles:",o:["Asch conformity experiments","Milgram obedience","Stanford prison experiment","Bobo doll study"],a:0,ex:"Key feature: confederates give wrong answers, no authority figure pressuring -- pure group conformity pressure. Asch = conformity (group pressure). Milgram = obedience (authority). Stanford prison = role conformity. Bobo doll = observational learning.",mn:"Wrong group answer + no authority = Asch. Authority giving orders = Milgram."},
{id:"pps2",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:3,pass:"p7",q:"Adding one correct-answering participant would:",o:["Dramatically decrease the rate of conformity behavior","Significantly increase the rate of conformity behavior","Have no measurable effect on conformity rates overall","Cause all participants to conform on every single trial"],a:0,ex:"Asch: even ONE dissenter reduced conformity from ~37% to ~5%. Even a dissenter giving a DIFFERENT wrong answer reduces conformity. Unanimity, not group size, is the primary driver.",mn:"One ally breaks the spell. Unanimity is key."},
// ============ CARS (10) ============
{id:"cars1a",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea"],diff:2,pass:"c1",q:"The author's main argument is that:",o:["Health outcomes are shaped by social structures beyond individual biology","All forms of violence against individuals are intentional and deliberate","Poverty and socioeconomic status have no measurable effect on health","Medical interventions alone are sufficient to eliminate health disparities"],a:0,ex:"The passage argues structural violence (systemic inequality) shapes health more than individual biology. Evidence: Farmer's Haiti work showing poverty, not biology, determined TB outcomes. CARS strategy: the main idea is the claim the ENTIRE passage supports.",mn:"CARS: find the claim the whole passage supports, not just one detail."},
{id:"cars1b",cat:"CARS",tags:["Opposing Arguments"],diff:3,pass:"c1",q:"Critics would most likely argue:",o:["The concept broadens 'violence' too much","Poverty never harms health","Framework is universally accepted","Disparities are purely biological"],a:0,ex:"Passage explicitly states the criticism: concept 'dilutes violence beyond usefulness, conflating poverty with assault.' CARS strategy: look for 'critics argue' or 'however' language to find opposing views.",mn:"CARS opposing views: find the 'critics argue' language."},
{id:"cars1c",cat:"CARS",tags:["Strengthen/Weaken"],diff:3,pass:"c1",q:"Which finding would WEAKEN the argument?",o:["Health outcomes equal across all SES groups","Poverty correlates with worse health","TB fails in wealthy countries too","More barriers in poor areas"],a:0,ex:"The argument rests on health DISPARITIES tracking along social lines. If outcomes were EQUAL regardless of social position, there would be no disparities to explain. CARS weaken questions: find what would break the author's key assumption.",mn:"CARS weaken: what would make the conclusion FALSE?"},
{id:"cars2a",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea"],diff:2,pass:"c2",q:"Patient autonomy emerged as a reaction to:",o:["Historical medical paternalism","Modern insurance","Patient medication demands","Hospital administration"],a:0,ex:"Passage states autonomy 'emerged partly as a reaction to historical paternalism.' CARS rule: answer must be DIRECTLY supported by passage text, not outside knowledge.",mn:"CARS: answer comes from the PASSAGE, not outside knowledge."},
{id:"cars2b",cat:"CARS",tags:["Tone and Attitude"],diff:3,pass:"c2",q:"Author's tone toward autonomy:",o:["Supportive of autonomy while acknowledging its practical limits","Unconditionally supportive of patient autonomy in all cases","Dismissive of patient autonomy as an impractical ideal","Completely neutral, presenting autonomy without any evaluation"],a:0,ex:"Author values autonomy (describes paternalism negatively) but presents limitations (emergencies, psychiatric holds, cultural contexts). This is NUANCED -- supportive overall but honest about complexities. CARS tip: extreme answer choices (always, never, completely) are usually wrong.",mn:"CARS tone: look for qualifiers. Extreme words usually wrong."},
{id:"cars3a",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea"],diff:2,pass:"c3",q:"Durkheim's main claim about deviance:",o:["Deviance serves essential positive functions for society","Deviance is a purely destructive force undermining society","All deviance should be systematically eliminated from society","Deviance exists only in modern industrialized societies"],a:0,ex:"Counter-intuitive argument: deviance FUNCTIONS positively by clarifying boundaries, strengthening solidarity, and driving change. CARS strategy: when a passage presents a surprising claim, the questions test whether you understood it correctly.",mn:"CARS: accept the author's framework even if counter-intuitive."},
{id:"cars3b",cat:"CARS",tags:["Application"],diff:3,pass:"c3",q:"Merton's 'innovation' adaptation:",o:["Accepting cultural goals while using illegitimate means to achieve them","Rejecting both the cultural goals and the institutional means","Accepting both cultural goals and the institutional means entirely","Withdrawing completely from mainstream society and its values"],a:0,ex:"Innovation: accept goals (wealth) + reject legitimate means (crime, fraud). Drug dealing = pursuing money through illegal channels. Retreatism = reject both (withdrawal). Rebellion = replace both. Conformity = accept both.",mn:"Innovation = right goal, wrong method."},
// ============ ADDITIONAL QUESTIONS (50+) ============
// --- MORE BIO SYSTEMS (7) ---
{id:"bs16",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Endocrine System","Hormones"],diff:2,q:"Cortisol is released from the:",o:["Adrenal cortex","Adrenal medulla","Anterior pituitary","Thyroid"],a:0,ex:"Cortisol is a glucocorticoid released by the zona fasciculata of the adrenal cortex. It is the primary 'stress hormone' with widespread effects: raises blood glucose (stimulates gluconeogenesis, inhibits insulin), suppresses immune system and inflammation (basis for corticosteroid drugs), promotes protein and fat breakdown. Regulated by the HPA axis: hypothalamus (CRH) -> anterior pituitary (ACTH) -> adrenal cortex (cortisol) -> negative feedback. Chronic elevation causes Cushing syndrome; deficiency causes Addison disease.",mn:"Cortisol = stress glucocorticoid. Zona fasciculata. HPA axis. Cushing = excess, Addison = deficient."},
{id:"bs17",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Digestive System"],diff:2,q:"Most nutrient absorption occurs in the:",o:["Small intestine","Stomach","Large intestine","Esophagus"],a:0,ex:"The small intestine (especially the jejunum) is the primary site for nutrient absorption. Its surface area is massively increased by three structural features: circular folds (plicae circulares), villi (finger-like projections), and microvilli (brush border on each epithelial cell). The duodenum receives bile (from liver/gallbladder for fat emulsification) and pancreatic enzymes. The ileum specializes in absorbing vitamin B12 (with intrinsic factor) and bile salts. The large intestine primarily absorbs water and electrolytes.",mn:"Small intestine = absorption (folds + villi + microvilli). Duodenum = bile + enzymes. Ileum = B12."},
{id:"bs18",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Respiratory System"],diff:2,q:"Gas exchange occurs in the:",o:["Alveoli","Bronchi","Trachea","Bronchioles"],a:0,ex:"The alveoli are tiny thin-walled air sacs (one cell thick, type I pneumocytes) surrounded by capillaries. O2 diffuses from alveolar air into blood (down its partial pressure gradient), and CO2 diffuses from blood into alveolar air. This exchange follows Fick's law: rate of diffusion is proportional to surface area and partial pressure difference, and inversely proportional to membrane thickness. Type II pneumocytes secrete surfactant, which reduces surface tension and prevents alveolar collapse. Total alveolar surface area is approximately 70 m-squared (tennis court size).",mn:"Alveoli = gas exchange (Type I). Surfactant = Type II. Surface area = tennis court."},
{id:"bs19",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Acid-Base"],diff:3,q:"The kidney compensates for respiratory acidosis by:",o:["Increasing bicarbonate reabsorption and hydrogen ion secretion","Decreasing bicarbonate reabsorption and retaining hydrogen ions","Increasing pulmonary ventilation rate to expel excess CO2","Producing additional CO2 through increased cellular metabolism"],a:0,ex:"Acid-base compensation: respiratory problems are compensated by the kidneys (metabolic), and metabolic problems are compensated by the lungs (respiratory). Respiratory acidosis = CO2 retention (hypoventilation) -> pH drops. The kidney compensates over days by: (1) reabsorbing more HCO3- (bicarbonate buffer) from filtrate, (2) secreting more H+ into urine, (3) generating new HCO3-. This gradually raises blood pH back toward normal. The compensation takes 2-3 days (slower than respiratory compensation, which takes minutes).",mn:"Respiratory problem -> kidney compensates (slow, days). Metabolic problem -> lungs compensate (fast, minutes)."},
{id:"pbs4",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Endocrine System","Hormones","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p11",q:"This patient most likely has:",o:["Graves disease","Hashimoto thyroiditis","Hypothyroidism","Thyroid cancer"],a:0,ex:"The passage shows: low TSH + high T3/T4 + symptoms of excess thyroid hormone (weight loss, heat intolerance, tremors, palpitations) + exophthalmos. Low TSH with high thyroid hormones = the pituitary is being suppressed by excessive T3/T4 (negative feedback working). Exophthalmos is specific to Graves disease (autoimmune -- TSH receptor stimulating antibodies). Hashimoto's is autoimmune hypothyroidism (high TSH, low T3/T4, fatigue, cold intolerance, weight gain).",mn:"Low TSH + high T3/T4 + exophthalmos = Graves (hyper). High TSH + low T3/T4 = Hashimoto (hypo)."},
{id:"pbs5",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Endocrine System","Hormones"],diff:3,pass:"p11",q:"TSH is low because:",o:["Elevated T3/T4 suppresses pituitary TSH secretion via negative feedback","Circulating antibodies directly destroy TSH molecules in the bloodstream","The anterior pituitary is producing excessive TSH despite feedback signals","The hypothalamus is releasing excess TRH driving continued TSH secretion"],a:0,ex:"This is a classic negative feedback question. The hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis: TRH (hypothalamus) -> TSH (anterior pituitary) -> T3/T4 (thyroid). When T3/T4 are excessive (as in Graves), they feed back to inhibit TRH and TSH release. Result: TSH drops very low. This pattern (low TSH + high T3/T4) indicates PRIMARY hyperthyroidism (the thyroid itself is overproducing). If TSH were HIGH with high T3/T4, it would suggest a pituitary tumor making excess TSH (very rare).",mn:"High hormone -> suppresses the upstream gland. Low TSH = primary thyroid problem."},
{id:"bs20",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Immune System"],diff:2,q:"Innate vs adaptive immunity:",o:["Innate is immediate and nonspecific; adaptive is slower with memory","Innate is slow and highly specific to particular pathogen antigens","Adaptive is immediate, providing rapid response to novel infections","Both systems are functionally identical with no distinguishing features"],a:0,ex:"Innate immunity: first line of defense, responds within hours. Includes physical barriers (skin, mucus), cellular components (neutrophils, macrophages, NK cells, dendritic cells), complement system, inflammation. NON-SPECIFIC -- responds the same way to every pathogen, no memory. Adaptive immunity: takes days to activate on first exposure. Uses lymphocytes (T and B cells) that recognize SPECIFIC antigens. KEY FEATURE: immunological memory -- second exposure triggers faster, stronger response (basis for vaccination). Humoral (B cells -> antibodies) and cell-mediated (T cells -> kill infected cells).",mn:"Innate = fast + general. Adaptive = slow at first + specific + memory."},
// --- MORE CELL BIO (5) ---
{id:"cb10",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Organelles"],diff:2,q:"The Golgi apparatus functions primarily to:",o:["Modify, sort, and package proteins for their final destinations","Synthesize new proteins from mRNA templates on bound ribosomes","Generate ATP through oxidative phosphorylation on inner membranes","Store and replicate genomic DNA within the double-membrane nucleus"],a:0,ex:"The Golgi apparatus receives proteins from the rough ER via transport vesicles. It processes them through its cisternae (cis/medial/trans): modifying (O-linked glycosylation, phosphorylation, proteolytic cleavage), sorting (adding targeting signals like mannose-6-phosphate for lysosomal enzymes), and packaging into vesicles for their final destination (secretion, plasma membrane, lysosomes). Think of the Golgi as the 'post office' of the cell -- it receives packages, labels them with addresses, and ships them out.",mn:"Golgi = post office. Receives from ER, modifies, sorts, ships."},
{id:"cb11",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Signal Transduction"],diff:3,q:"Receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs) signal by:",o:["Dimerizing and then autophosphorylating tyrosine residues","Activating heterotrimeric G-proteins via GTP exchange","Opening ligand-gated ion channels to change membrane potential","Translocating directly into the nucleus to alter transcription"],a:0,ex:"RTKs are single-pass transmembrane receptors. When ligand (e.g., growth factor like EGF, insulin) binds, two RTK monomers dimerize and cross-phosphorylate each other on tyrosine residues (autophosphorylation). These phosphotyrosines serve as docking sites for signaling proteins (via SH2 domains), activating cascades like Ras -> Raf -> MEK -> ERK (the MAP kinase pathway), which ultimately promotes cell growth and division. Mutations in RTKs or Ras are found in many cancers.",mn:"RTK: ligand -> dimerize -> autophosphorylate -> Ras-MAPK cascade -> growth."},
{id:"cb12",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Membrane Transport"],diff:2,q:"Osmosis is the movement of:",o:["Water moving across a semipermeable membrane toward higher solute","Solute particles moving down their concentration gradient passively","Water moving across a membrane toward lower solute concentration","Ions moving through protein channels along their electrical gradient"],a:0,ex:"Osmosis is the net movement of WATER (not solute) across a semipermeable membrane from a region of LOW solute concentration (high water concentration) to HIGH solute concentration (low water concentration). Water moves to dilute the more concentrated side. Osmotic pressure (pi = iMRT) is the pressure needed to STOP osmosis. A cell in a hypotonic solution gains water (swells/lyses). In hypertonic solution, it loses water (crenates/shrivels). Isotonic = no net water movement.",mn:"Water chases solute. Hypo = swell. Hyper = shrink. Iso = no change."},
{id:"cb13",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Membrane Transport"],diff:3,pass:"p12",q:"SGLT1 is an example of:",o:["Secondary active transport","Simple diffusion","Facilitated diffusion","Primary active transport"],a:0,ex:"SGLT1 moves glucose AGAINST its concentration gradient (from low [glucose] in lumen to high [glucose] in cell) by coupling it to Na+ moving DOWN its gradient (from high [Na+] in lumen to low [Na+] in cell). The Na+ gradient is maintained by the Na+/K+ ATPase (primary active transport) on the basolateral side. So SGLT1 is secondary active transport -- it does not directly use ATP but depends on a gradient created by an ATP-using pump. GLUT2 on the basolateral side is facilitated diffusion (glucose moves DOWN its gradient, no energy needed).",mn:"SGLT1 = secondary active (uses Na+ gradient). GLUT2 = facilitated diffusion. Na+/K+ ATPase = primary active."},
{id:"cb14",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Cell Cycle","Mitosis"],diff:2,q:"Cyclins regulate the cell cycle by:",o:["Activating CDKs","Directly replicating DNA","Breaking down the nuclear envelope","Synthesizing new histones"],a:0,ex:"The cell cycle is driven by cyclin-CDK complexes. Cyclins are regulatory proteins whose levels rise and fall at specific points in the cell cycle. When a cyclin binds its partner CDK (cyclin-dependent kinase), the CDK becomes active and phosphorylates target proteins that drive the cell to the next phase. Key complexes: Cyclin D/CDK4 (G1), Cyclin E/CDK2 (G1/S transition), Cyclin A/CDK2 (S phase), Cyclin B/CDK1 (G2/M, triggers mitosis). CDK inhibitors like p21 (activated by p53) and p27 can halt the cycle by blocking cyclin-CDK activity.",mn:"Cyclins fluctuate + bind CDKs = drive cell cycle forward. p21/p27 = brakes."},
// --- MORE GEN CHEM (4) ---
{id:"gc12",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Thermodynamics"],diff:2,q:"In an exothermic reaction, the enthalpy of products is:",o:["Lower than reactants","Higher than reactants","Equal to reactants","Unpredictable"],a:0,ex:"Enthalpy (H) is a measure of the heat content of a system. In an exothermic reaction (delta-H < 0), energy is RELEASED to surroundings as heat, so the products have LESS enthalpy than the reactants -- the energy 'went somewhere' (into the environment). In an endothermic reaction (delta-H > 0), energy is ABSORBED from surroundings, and products have MORE enthalpy than reactants. On an energy diagram: exothermic products are lower than reactants; endothermic products are higher.",mn:"Exothermic: products lower, energy released, feels hot. Endothermic: products higher, energy absorbed, feels cold."},
{id:"gc13",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Solutions"],diff:2,q:"Molarity (M) is defined as:",o:["Moles of solute per liter of total solution volume","Grams of solute per liter of total solution volume","Moles of solute per kilogram of pure solvent mass","Mass percent of solute relative to total solution"],a:0,ex:"Molarity = moles of solute / liters of SOLUTION (not solvent). This is the most commonly used concentration unit in chemistry and on the MCAT. Related units: Molality (m) = moles of solute / kg of SOLVENT (used for colligative property calculations because it does not change with temperature). Normality (N) = equivalents per liter (for acids: N = M x number of H+ donated). Dilution equation: M1V1 = M2V2 (moles stay constant when you dilute).",mn:"Molarity = mol/L of solution. Molality = mol/kg of solvent. M1V1 = M2V2 for dilutions."},
{id:"gc14",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Buffers","Acid-Base"],diff:3,q:"In a titration of weak acid with strong base, the half-equivalence point is where:",o:["pH = pKa (equal amounts of HA and A-)","All acid is neutralized","pH = 7","The solution is fully buffered with no acid remaining"],a:0,ex:"At the half-equivalence point, exactly HALF the weak acid (HA) has been converted to its conjugate base (A-). This means [HA] = [A-]. By Henderson-Hasselbalch: pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]) = pKa + log(1) = pKa + 0 = pKa. This is one of the most important titration concepts for the MCAT. At the full equivalence point, ALL HA has been converted to A-, and pH > 7 (basic) because A- is a weak base that hydrolyzes water.",mn:"Half-equivalence: [HA]=[A-] so pH = pKa exactly. Full equivalence: pH > 7 for weak acid/strong base."},
{id:"gc15",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Redox Chemistry","Electrochemistry"],diff:2,q:"In a galvanic cell, oxidation occurs at the:",o:["Add product or remove reactant to shift equilibrium toward reactants","Increase temperature to shift equilibrium toward endothermic direction","Add a catalyst to shift the equilibrium toward the product side","Decrease the volume to shift equilibrium toward the side with more moles"],a:0,ex:"In ALL electrochemical cells (both galvanic and electrolytic): Oxidation occurs at the ANODE (An Ox -- 'an ox'). Reduction occurs at the CATHODE (Red Cat -- 'red cat'). In a galvanic (voltaic) cell: the anode is negative (electrons flow FROM anode TO cathode through the external wire). In an electrolytic cell: the anode is positive (external power source forces electrons in the opposite direction). The salt bridge maintains electrical neutrality by allowing ion flow between half-cells.",mn:"AN OX (anode = oxidation) and RED CAT (cathode = reduction). Always true."},
// --- MORE GENETICS (4) ---
{id:"gen7",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Mendelian Genetics"],diff:2,q:"Epistasis is when:",o:["One gene masks the phenotypic expression of another gene","Two different genes are physically linked on the same chromosome","Both genes at different loci are expressed equally in phenotype","Two alleles at the same locus show codominant expression"],a:0,ex:"Epistasis occurs when the phenotypic expression of one gene is modified or masked by another gene at a different locus. Classic example: Labrador coat color. The E gene determines whether pigment is deposited (EE or Ee = yes, ee = no pigment = yellow lab regardless of B gene). The B gene determines color of pigment (BB/Bb = black, bb = brown/chocolate). So ee is epistatic to B -- it masks whatever B would produce. This modifies the classic 9:3:3:1 dihybrid ratio to 9:3:4 or other modified ratios.",mn:"Epistasis = one gene overrides another. Different from dominance (alleles at SAME gene)."},
{id:"gen8",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Inheritance Patterns"],diff:2,q:"Autosomal dominant disorders require how many mutant alleles?",o:["Only one mutant allele is needed since heterozygotes are affected","Two mutant alleles are required since only homozygotes affected","Three copies of the mutant allele must be present for disease","No copies are needed since the disease skips every generation"],a:0,ex:"Autosomal dominant: only ONE copy of the mutant allele is needed for the phenotype to appear. Heterozygotes (Aa) are affected. Every affected individual has at least one affected parent (does NOT skip generations, unlike recessive). Both males and females equally affected. Examples: Huntington disease (CAG repeat expansion), Marfan syndrome (fibrillin-1), achondroplasia (FGFR3), familial hypercholesterolemia (LDL receptor). Many AD disorders show variable expressivity (severity varies) and reduced penetrance (not all carriers show symptoms).",mn:"Dominant = one copy enough. Every generation affected. Recessive = two copies, can skip generations."},
{id:"gen9",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Mendelian Genetics","Inheritance Patterns"],diff:3,q:"Two heterozygous parents (AaBb) in a dihybrid cross: fraction with both dominant phenotypes?",o:["9/16","3/16","1/16","4/16"],a:0,ex:"For two independently assorting genes, multiply the individual probabilities. For each gene separately: Aa x Aa gives 3/4 dominant phenotype. For both genes simultaneously: 3/4 x 3/4 = 9/16. The full dihybrid ratio: 9 A_B_ : 3 A_bb : 3 aaB_ : 1 aabb. This 9:3:3:1 ratio requires independent assortment (genes on different chromosomes or far apart on the same chromosome). Linked genes (close together on the same chromosome) would deviate from this ratio.",mn:"Dihybrid 9:3:3:1. Both dominant = 9/16 = 3/4 x 3/4."},
{id:"gen10",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Chromosomal Abnormalities","Meiosis"],diff:2,q:"Turner syndrome karyotype is:",o:["45,X with monosomy of the X chromosome","47,XXY with an extra X chromosome copy","47,XYY with an extra Y chromosome copy","46,XX with normal female chromosome set"],a:0,ex:"Turner syndrome: 45,X -- only one X chromosome, no second sex chromosome. Phenotype: female (but ovaries fail to develop), short stature, webbed neck, shield-shaped chest, coarctation of aorta. Most common monosomy compatible with life (most autosomal monosomies are lethal). Caused by nondisjunction. Compare: Klinefelter syndrome = 47,XXY (male, tall, infertile, gynecomastia). Down syndrome = 47,XX+21 or 47,XY+21 (trisomy 21).",mn:"Turner = 45,X (female, short, webbed neck). Klinefelter = 47,XXY (male, tall, infertile)."},
// --- MORE ORGO (4) ---
{id:"org9",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Stereochemistry"],diff:2,q:"A meso compound has:",o:["Contains stereocenters but has an internal plane of symmetry","Contains no stereocenters anywhere in the molecular structure","Contains only R-configured stereocenters throughout the molecule","Shows maximum optical rotation due to additive chiral centers"],a:0,ex:"A meso compound has two or more stereocenters but is ACHIRAL (optically inactive) because it possesses an internal plane of symmetry -- one half of the molecule is the mirror image of the other half, so they cancel out. Example: (2R,3S)-tartaric acid has two stereocenters but the R and S cancel, making it a meso compound with zero optical rotation. Meso compounds are NOT the same as racemic mixtures (which are mixtures of two separate enantiomers). A single meso molecule is inherently achiral.",mn:"Meso = has stereocenters but internal mirror plane cancels them = achiral."},
{id:"org10",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Functional Groups"],diff:2,q:"An ester is formed from:",o:["A carboxylic acid reacting with an alcohol to form ester","Two alcohol molecules undergoing condensation reaction","Two ketone molecules undergoing aldol condensation reaction","An aldehyde reacting with a ketone via crossed aldol"],a:0,ex:"Ester formation (Fischer esterification): R-COOH + R'-OH -> R-COO-R' + H2O. This is a condensation reaction (water is lost). It is acid-catalyzed and reversible (Le Chatelier: remove water or use excess alcohol to drive it forward). Ester hydrolysis (reverse reaction) breaks the ester back into acid + alcohol. Saponification: ester + strong base (NaOH) -> carboxylate salt (soap) + alcohol -- this is irreversible. Esters are found in fats/oils (triglycerides = 3 fatty acids esterified to glycerol) and many fragrances.",mn:"Ester = acid + alcohol - water. Saponification = ester + NaOH -> soap."},
{id:"org11",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Addition Reactions","Stereochemistry"],diff:3,q:"Anti-Markovnikov addition occurs with:",o:["HBr + peroxides","HBr alone","H2O + acid catalyst","HCl + heat"],a:0,ex:"Peroxides (ROOR) initiate a radical chain mechanism. Br radical adds FIRST to the less substituted carbon (forming the more stable radical intermediate), and H ends up on the more substituted carbon -- opposite of Markovnikov. This ONLY works with HBr + peroxides. HCl and HI do not undergo this radical addition because the energetics are unfavorable for their radical chains. Without peroxides, HBr follows normal Markovnikov addition via the polar (carbocation) mechanism.",mn:"Peroxides = radicals = flip Markovnikov. ONLY works with HBr."},
{id:"org12",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions"],diff:2,q:"A good leaving group is:",o:["S configuration with counterclockwise priority assignment at chiral center","R configuration with clockwise priority assignment at chiral center","Achiral molecule with an internal plane of symmetry present","Racemic mixture containing equal amounts of both enantiomers"],a:0,ex:"The best leaving groups are WEAK BASES -- species that are stable when they carry the negative charge or electron pair after departure. The weaker the base, the more stable it is after leaving, and the better it is as a leaving group. Ranking (best to worst): I- > Br- > Cl- >> F- (halides: larger = better, more stable). Tosylate (TsO-) and mesylate (MsO-) are excellent artificial LGs. OH- is a terrible leaving group -- which is why alcohols must be protonated (to H2O, a good LG) or converted to tosylates before SN/E reactions.",mn:"Good LG = weak base = stable anion. I > Br > Cl >> F. Protonate OH to make H2O."},
// --- MORE METABOLISM (3) ---
{id:"met16",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Enzyme Regulation"],diff:2,q:"The three irreversible enzymes of glycolysis are:",o:["Hexokinase, PFK-1, and pyruvate kinase catalyze irreversible steps","Aldolase, enolase, and PFK-1 catalyze irreversible steps only","All ten glycolytic enzymes catalyze irreversible reactions","Only hexokinase and aldolase catalyze irreversible reactions"],a:0,ex:"Glycolysis has 10 enzymes, but only 3 catalyze irreversible (highly exergonic) reactions: (1) Hexokinase: glucose -> G6P (traps glucose in cell). (2) PFK-1: F6P -> F1,6BP (committed step, main regulatory point). (3) Pyruvate kinase: PEP -> pyruvate (generates ATP by substrate-level phosphorylation). Gluconeogenesis must bypass these 3 steps with 4 different enzymes because they cannot be run in reverse.",mn:"3 irreversible glycolysis steps: Hexokinase, PFK-1, Pyruvate kinase. Gluconeogenesis bypasses all 3."},
{id:"met17",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation"],diff:3,q:"An uncoupler of oxidative phosphorylation would:",o:["Glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis, and lipolysis during fasting state","Glycolysis, glycogen synthesis, and lipogenesis in the fed state","Protein synthesis, DNA replication, and cellular growth promotion","Insulin secretion, glucose uptake, and triglyceride storage only"],a:0,ex:"Uncouplers (like 2,4-DNP, thermogenin/UCP1 in brown fat) make the inner mitochondrial membrane permeable to protons, allowing H+ to flow back into the matrix WITHOUT passing through ATP synthase. The proton gradient dissipates as HEAT instead of driving ATP synthesis. Since the gradient is constantly being dissipated, the ETC runs FASTER (increased O2 consumption) trying to rebuild it, but ATP production DECREASES because the energy is lost as heat. This is different from ETC inhibitors (which stop electron flow and decrease O2 consumption).",mn:"Uncoupler = proton leak = more O2 consumed, less ATP, more heat. Different from inhibitors."},
{id:"met18",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Metabolism"],diff:3,q:"Transamination reactions require which cofactor?",o:["Liver, because it expresses glucose-6-phosphatase for free glucose","Muscle, because it has the largest glycogen stores by total mass","Brain, because neurons require constant glucose supply for function","Kidney, because it filters and reclaims glucose from the blood"],a:0,ex:"Transamination transfers an amino group from an amino acid to an alpha-keto acid, converting one amino acid into another. This is how the body interconverts non-essential amino acids. The cofactor is pyridoxal phosphate (PLP), derived from vitamin B6 (pyridoxine). PLP is required by aminotransferases (transaminases like ALT and AST -- clinically important liver enzymes). B6 deficiency can cause anemia (PLP also needed for heme synthesis) and neurological symptoms. PLP is also required for decarboxylation reactions (making neurotransmitters like serotonin, dopamine, GABA from amino acid precursors).",mn:"PLP (B6) = transamination cofactor. Also needed for decarboxylation (neurotransmitter synthesis)."},
// --- MORE AMINO ACIDS (3 including 1 matching) ---
{id:"aam5",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",type:"match",tags:["Amino Acid Classification","Protein Structure"],diff:2,q:"Match amino acid to its single-letter code:",pairs:[["Tryptophan","W"],["Glutamate","E"],["Aspartate","D"],["Lysine","K"],["Phenylalanine","F"]],ex:"The single-letter codes are not always intuitive. Some make sense: G=Glycine, A=Alanine, V=Valine, L=Leucine, I=Isoleucine, S=Serine, T=Threonine, C=Cysteine, M=Methionine, P=Proline, H=Histidine. Others are less obvious: W=Tryptophan (looks like a double-ring), F=Phenylalanine, Y=Tyrosine, D=Aspartate, E=Glutamate, N=Asparagine, Q=Glutamine, K=Lysine, R=Arginine. These codes appear in research papers and occasionally on the MCAT.",mn:"Tricky codes: W=Trp, F=Phe, D=Asp, E=Glu, K=Lys, R=Arg, N=Asn, Q=Gln"},
{id:"aa13",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties"],diff:2,q:"Tryptophan is the precursor for which important molecule?",o:["Serotonin","Dopamine","Histamine","Acetylcholine"],a:0,ex:"Amino acids serve as precursors for many important biomolecules. Tryptophan -> serotonin (via tryptophan hydroxylase + DOPA decarboxylase, both need PLP/B6) -> melatonin (pineal gland, regulates sleep). Tyrosine -> dopamine -> norepinephrine -> epinephrine (catecholamine pathway). Histidine -> histamine (by histidine decarboxylase). Glutamate -> GABA (by glutamic acid decarboxylase). Knowing these amino acid to neurotransmitter conversions is high-yield.",mn:"Trp->serotonin->melatonin. Tyr->dopa->NE->epi. His->histamine. Glu->GABA."},
{id:"aa14",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Disulfide Bonds"],diff:2,q:"Which amino acid has the only sulfur-containing side chain that forms covalent crosslinks?",o:["Cysteine","Methionine","Serine","Threonine"],a:0,ex:"Both cysteine and methionine contain sulfur, but only CYSTEINE can form disulfide bonds. Cysteine has a thiol (-SH) group that can be oxidized to form -S-S- links with another cysteine. Methionine has a thioether (S bonded to two carbons) that does NOT form crosslinks. This distinction is commonly tested. Cysteine's ability to form disulfide bonds is exploited by the body to stabilize extracellular proteins (antibodies, insulin) and by labs to study protein structure (breaking disulfide bonds with DTT or beta-mercaptoethanol denatures proteins).",mn:"Cys = -SH = forms disulfide bonds. Met = thioether = no crosslinks. Both have sulfur."},
// --- MORE PSYCH/SOC (3) ---
{id:"ps21",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sleep"],diff:2,q:"Slow-wave sleep (N3/NREM stage 3) is characterized by:",o:["Delta waves dominate and it is the most physically restorative","Rapid eye movements occur and vivid dreaming is most prominent","Sleep spindles and K-complexes characterize this transitional stage","Light theta waves predominate as consciousness begins fading"],a:0,ex:"NREM sleep has 3 stages: N1 (light, theta waves, hypnagogic hallucinations), N2 (sleep spindles and K-complexes, most time spent here), N3 (slow-wave/deep sleep, delta waves, most physically restorative -- growth hormone peaks here, memory consolidation for declarative/factual memories). REM sleep: rapid eye movements, vivid dreaming, muscle atonia (paralysis), EEG resembles waking, procedural memory consolidation. Sleep cycles last ~90 min. N3 is predominant early in the night, REM increases later.",mn:"N3 = delta waves = deep = restorative = GH release. REM = dreaming + paralysis."},
{id:"ps22",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sociology","Health Disparities"],diff:2,q:"The biopsychosocial model proposes that health is determined by:",o:["Biological, psychological, and social factors all interacting together","Biological and genetic factors as the sole determinants of behavior","Psychological processes operating independently from biology and society","Social and environmental factors without any biological contribution"],a:0,ex:"George Engel (1977) proposed the biopsychosocial model as an alternative to the purely biomedical model. It argues that health and illness result from the interaction of: BIOLOGICAL factors (genetics, physiology, pathogens), PSYCHOLOGICAL factors (mood, coping, personality, stress, health beliefs), and SOCIAL factors (family support, SES, culture, discrimination, healthcare access). Example: two patients with the same cancer diagnosis may have vastly different outcomes based on their psychological coping, social support networks, and access to quality care.",mn:"Bio + Psycho + Social = health. Not just biology alone."},
{id:"cars4a",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea"],diff:2,pass:"c4",q:"The author's main argument is that:",o:["The biopsychosocial model provides a more complete framework for health","The biomedical model should be completely abandoned as scientifically wrong","Biological factors are entirely irrelevant to understanding patient health","Engel's proposed model has been conclusively disproven by modern research"],a:0,ex:"The passage presents the biomedical model's strengths (antibiotics, surgery, imaging) but argues it neglects psychological and social dimensions. It does NOT say to abandon biology -- it says to EMBED biology within a broader context. The biopsychosocial model is presented as an expansion, not a replacement. CARS strategy: look for the author's balanced position -- rarely do MCAT passages argue for total rejection of established approaches.",mn:"CARS: authors usually argue for expansion or nuance, not total rejection."},
{id:"cars4b",cat:"CARS",tags:["Application"],diff:3,pass:"c4",q:"Which scenario best illustrates the biopsychosocial model?",o:["A diabetic whose outcomes depend on genetics, mood, and food access","A patient whose condition is treated with medication alone","A patient whose illness is explained entirely by genetic factors","A healthy individual with no identifiable risk factors present"],a:0,ex:"The biopsychosocial model requires ALL THREE factors to be present: biological (genetics of diabetes), psychological (depression affecting self-care, motivation, adherence), and social (neighborhood food access determining diet quality). The other options address only one dimension. CARS application questions ask you to find the scenario that matches ALL elements of the passage's framework.",mn:"CARS application: every element of the framework must be present in the correct answer."},
// --- MORE MOLECULAR BIO (2) ---
{id:"mb10",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Transcription/Translation"],diff:2,q:"The wobble position in codons is the:",o:["3rd position","1st position","2nd position","All positions"],a:0,ex:"The genetic code has 64 codons for 20 amino acids + 3 stops -- it is degenerate (redundant). Most redundancy occurs at the 3rd codon position (wobble position). The 1st position of the tRNA anticodon (which pairs with the 3rd codon position) can form non-standard base pairs: G can pair with U, and inosine (I) in the anticodon can pair with U, C, or A. This means a single tRNA can recognize multiple codons that differ only at position 3, reducing the number of tRNAs needed.",mn:"Position 3 = wobble = flexible pairing = why the code is degenerate."},
{id:"mb11",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Gene Regulation"],diff:3,q:"Epigenetic modifications include:",o:["DNA methylation and histone modification without sequence change","Alterations to the DNA nucleotide base pair sequence directly","Point mutations substituting one nucleotide for another base","Chromosomal translocations rearranging large genomic segments"],a:0,ex:"Epigenetics: heritable changes in gene expression WITHOUT altering the DNA sequence. Two major mechanisms: (1) DNA methylation: methyl groups added to cytosines in CpG islands (promoter regions). Methylation typically SILENCES gene expression by blocking transcription factor binding. (2) Histone modification: acetylation of histones by HATs (histone acetyltransferases) LOOSENS chromatin (euchromatin) and INCREASES transcription. Deacetylation by HDACs tightens chromatin (heterochromatin) and DECREASES transcription. These modifications can be inherited through cell division and are important in development, cancer, and gene-environment interactions.",mn:"Methylation = silence. Acetylation = activate. No DNA sequence change = epigenetic."},
// --- MORE PHYSICS (2) ---
{id:"ph11",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Work and Energy"],diff:2,q:"Kinetic energy is:",o:["One-half times mass times velocity squared","Mass times gravitational acceleration times height","Applied force times displacement in force direction","Mass times velocity without any exponent applied"],a:0,ex:"Kinetic energy (energy of motion) = 1/2 * mass * velocity^2. Note the v^2: doubling velocity QUADRUPLES KE (important for car crash physics -- twice the speed = four times the stopping distance). Potential energy (gravitational) = mgh. Conservation of energy: KE + PE = constant (in absence of non-conservative forces like friction). Work-energy theorem: net work = change in KE. At the bottom of a hill (max KE, min PE). At the top (max PE, min KE).",mn:"KE = 1/2 mv^2. Double v = 4x KE. PE = mgh. KE + PE = constant."},
{id:"ph12",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Electrostatics"],diff:2,q:"Electric field lines point:",o:["From regions of positive charge toward negative charge","From regions of negative charge toward positive charge","In circular paths around each individual point charge","In random directions without any predictable pattern"],a:0,ex:"Electric field lines point in the direction a positive test charge would move: AWAY from positive charges (repelled) and TOWARD negative charges (attracted). Field lines never cross. Denser lines = stronger field. Inside a conductor at equilibrium, E = 0 (charges redistribute to cancel internal field). Between parallel plates, the field is uniform: E = V/d (voltage divided by plate separation). Field from a point charge: E = kQ/r^2.",mn:"Field lines: + to -. Dense = strong. E = 0 inside conductors. E = V/d between plates."},
{id:"met19",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Enzyme Regulation","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Which glycolysis enzyme is inhibited by its own product glucose-6-phosphate?",o:["Hexokinase, PFK-1, and pyruvate kinase are irreversible in glycolysis","Aldolase, enolase, and isomerase are irreversible in glycolysis only","All ten glycolysis steps are freely reversible under cell conditions","Only hexokinase is irreversible while all other steps are reversible"],a:0,ex:"Hexokinase is feedback-inhibited by its product G6P. This prevents the cell from trapping more glucose than it can process. Note: the liver uses glucokinase instead, which is NOT inhibited by G6P and has a higher Km -- allowing the liver to take up glucose proportionally to blood levels (glucose sensor function). Hexokinase vs glucokinase is a commonly tested distinction.",mn:"Hexokinase inhibited by G6P. Liver uses glucokinase (no product inhibition, higher Km)."},
{id:"met20",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Krebs Cycle","Metabolic Regulation","Electron Carriers"],diff:2,q:"The rate-limiting enzyme of the Krebs cycle is:",o:["Isocitrate dehydrogenase","Citrate synthase","Succinate dehydrogenase","Malate dehydrogenase"],a:0,ex:"Isocitrate dehydrogenase is the rate-limiting step of the Krebs cycle. It converts isocitrate to alpha-ketoglutarate, producing NADH and releasing CO2. Activated by ADP (low energy signal) and Ca2+. Inhibited by ATP and NADH (high energy signals). This mirrors the regulation of PFK-1 in glycolysis -- both are activated when energy is low and inhibited when energy is high.",mn:"Isocitrate DH = Krebs gatekeeper. Same logic as PFK-1: low energy activates, high energy inhibits."},
{id:"met21",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation","ATP Yield"],diff:3,q:"ATP synthase (Complex V) works by:",o:["Harnessing the proton gradient to drive rotational ATP catalysis","Directly oxidizing NADH to generate ATP without a gradient","Hydrolyzing existing ATP molecules to pump protons outward","Transferring electrons from NADH directly to molecular oxygen"],a:0,ex:"ATP synthase is a molecular motor. Protons (H+) flow DOWN their concentration gradient from the intermembrane space back into the matrix through the Fo subunit (the proton channel), which causes rotation of the c-ring. This rotation drives conformational changes in the F1 subunit that catalyze ADP + Pi -> ATP. This is called chemiosmosis (Mitchell's chemiosmotic hypothesis, Nobel Prize 1978). About 2.5 ATP per NADH and 1.5 ATP per FADH2. Oligomycin blocks the Fo channel, stopping ATP synthesis.",mn:"ATP synthase = rotary motor driven by proton gradient. Oligomycin blocks it."},
{id:"met22",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Aerobic Respiration","Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation"],diff:2,q:"The final electron acceptor in the electron transport chain is:",o:["Molecular oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor","NAD+ as the terminal electron acceptor molecule","FAD as the terminal electron acceptor cofactor","Cytochrome c as the terminal electron acceptor"],a:0,ex:"O2 accepts electrons at Complex IV (cytochrome c oxidase) and is reduced to H2O. This is why we need to breathe -- without O2 as the terminal electron acceptor, electrons back up, the ETC stops, the proton gradient dissipates, and ATP synthesis halts. Cyanide and carbon monoxide also block Complex IV. About 90% of the O2 you consume goes to Complex IV for this purpose.",mn:"O2 = final electron acceptor at Complex IV. No O2 = no ETC = no aerobic ATP."},
{id:"met23",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Gluconeogenesis","Metabolic Regulation","Hormonal Regulation"],diff:3,q:"Gluconeogenesis occurs primarily in the:",o:["Liver and to a lesser extent the kidneys","Skeletal muscle during rest and exercise","Brain gray matter during normal function","Adipose tissue during energy storage phase"],a:0,ex:"Gluconeogenesis (making new glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors) occurs mainly in the LIVER and to a lesser extent the KIDNEYS. It cannot occur in muscle because muscle lacks glucose-6-phosphatase (the enzyme that removes the phosphate so glucose can leave the cell). Precursors: lactate (from Cori cycle), glycerol (from fat breakdown), and glucogenic amino acids (most amino acids). Notably, acetyl-CoA CANNOT be converted to glucose in humans -- this is why fatty acids cannot be used for gluconeogenesis (except odd-chain FAs which yield some propionyl-CoA -> succinyl-CoA).",mn:"Liver and kidney only. Muscle cannot export glucose (no glucose-6-phosphatase). Fatty acids cannot become glucose."},
{id:"met24",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Fatty Acid Metabolism","Beta-Oxidation","Krebs Cycle"],diff:2,q:"Each cycle of beta-oxidation produces:",o:["One FADH2, one NADH, and one acetyl-CoA per cycle","Two ATP molecules and one NADH molecule per cycle","One ATP molecule and one FADH2 molecule per cycle","Two NADH molecules and one GTP molecule per cycle"],a:0,ex:"Each beta-oxidation cycle shortens the fatty acid by 2 carbons and produces: 1 FADH2 (from acyl-CoA dehydrogenase), 1 NADH (from beta-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase), and 1 acetyl-CoA (which enters the Krebs cycle for further oxidation). A 16-carbon palmitate undergoes 7 cycles to produce 8 acetyl-CoA + 7 FADH2 + 7 NADH. Total ATP from palmitate: about 106 ATP (minus 2 ATP for activation = 104 net). This is why fats store much more energy per gram than carbohydrates.",mn:"Per cycle: 1 FADH2 + 1 NADH + 1 acetyl-CoA. Palmitate (16C) = 7 cycles = 8 acetyl-CoA."},
{id:"met25",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Ketogenesis","Fatty Acid Metabolism","Insulin"],diff:3,q:"Ketone bodies are produced when:",o:["Acetyl-CoA exceeds Krebs cycle capacity","Blood glucose is high","Insulin levels are high","The fed state activates lipogenesis"],a:0,ex:"Ketogenesis occurs when the liver has excess acetyl-CoA that cannot enter the Krebs cycle. Two main scenarios: (1) FASTING: beta-oxidation produces lots of acetyl-CoA, but OAA is diverted to gluconeogenesis, so Krebs cycle cannot accept it all. (2) UNCONTROLLED TYPE 1 DIABETES: without insulin, cells cannot take up glucose, so the body acts as if fasting even though blood glucose is high. Excess acetyl-CoA is converted to ketone bodies (acetoacetate, beta-hydroxybutyrate, acetone). Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) is a life-threatening complication where massive ketone production drops blood pH dangerously low.",mn:"Ketogenesis = too much acetyl-CoA + not enough OAA. Fasting or uncontrolled T1 diabetes."},
{id:"met26",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Pentose Phosphate Pathway","Aerobic Respiration","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Which metabolic pathway produces NADPH for fatty acid synthesis?",o:["The pentose phosphate pathway in the cytoplasm","Glycolysis during its oxidative phase reactions","The Krebs cycle in the mitochondrial matrix","Beta-oxidation during fatty acid breakdown"],a:0,ex:"The PPP (pentose phosphate pathway) is the primary source of cytoplasmic NADPH. NADPH is required for: (1) Fatty acid synthesis (each cycle of FA synthesis uses 2 NADPH), (2) Cholesterol synthesis, (3) Maintaining reduced glutathione (antioxidant defense), (4) Cytochrome P450 detoxification reactions, (5) Respiratory burst in phagocytes (NADPH oxidase generates ROS to kill pathogens). Glycolysis and Krebs produce NADH (not NADPH) -- different cofactor, different purpose. NADH is for energy (ETC), NADPH is for biosynthesis and defense.",mn:"NADPH for biosynthesis = PPP. NADH for energy = glycolysis/Krebs. Different roles!"},
{id:"met27",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Cori Cycle","Anaerobic Metabolism","Gluconeogenesis"],diff:2,q:"The Cori cycle is important during:",o:["Intense exercise","Sleep","Fed state after a meal","During fatty acid synthesis"],a:0,ex:"During intense exercise, muscle produces lactate faster than it can be oxidized. Lactate is exported to the blood, taken up by the liver, and converted back to glucose via gluconeogenesis. This glucose returns to muscle for more glycolysis. The cycle costs a net 4 ATP (muscle gains 2, liver spends 6). It allows muscle to continue working anaerobically while the liver handles the metabolic debt. The alanine cycle is similar but uses alanine instead of lactate (transamination of pyruvate in muscle, sent to liver).",mn:"Cori: muscle lactate -> liver glucose -> muscle. Net cost 4 ATP. Alanine cycle is similar."},
{id:"aa15",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Classification","Isoelectric Point","Acid-Base"],diff:3,q:"The pI of aspartate (pKa1=2.0, pKa2=3.65, pKa3=9.6) is:",o:["2.83, the average of the two lowest pKa values","6.63, the average of all three pKa values","5.80, the average of the highest and lowest","4.83, the average of the two highest pKas"],a:0,ex:"For acidic amino acids (Asp, Glu), the pI is the average of the two LOWEST pKa values. These are the pKas that flank the zwitterionic form (one positive, one negative, zero net charge). For Asp: pI = (2.0 + 3.65)/2 = 2.83. For basic amino acids (Lys, Arg, His), pI = average of the two HIGHEST pKas. For neutral amino acids, pI = average of the alpha-amino and alpha-carboxyl pKas.",mn:"Acidic AA pI = average of two lowest pKas. Basic AA pI = average of two highest."},
{id:"aa16",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Protein Structure","Amino Acid Classification"],diff:2,q:"Which amino acid can be both polar and participate in hydrophobic interactions?",o:["Tyrosine, which has an aromatic ring plus a hydroxyl group","Alanine, which has a simple nonpolar methyl side chain only","Glycine, which has no side chain and maximum conformational freedom","Aspartate, which has a negatively charged carboxylate side chain"],a:0,ex:"Tyrosine has a phenol ring (hydrophobic, aromatic) with a hydroxyl group (-OH, polar). This dual nature means Tyr can be found at protein surfaces where it straddles the water-lipid interface. The -OH can hydrogen bond and can be phosphorylated (key in signal transduction -- receptor tyrosine kinases). Tyr can also be iodinated to form thyroid hormones (T3 and T4). It absorbs UV at 280nm (second strongest after Trp).",mn:"Tyr = aromatic + hydroxyl = both hydrophobic and polar. Phosphorylation site. Makes thyroid hormones."},
{id:"aa17",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Essential Amino Acids","Amino Acid Properties","Metabolism"],diff:2,q:"Phenylketonuria (PKU) is caused by deficiency of:",o:["Phenylalanine hydroxylase","Tyrosine hydroxylase","Tryptophan hydroxylase","Histidine decarboxylase"],a:0,ex:"PKU is an autosomal recessive disorder caused by deficiency of phenylalanine hydroxylase, which converts Phe to Tyr. Without this enzyme, Phe accumulates to toxic levels causing intellectual disability, seizures, and musty body odor. Tyr becomes conditionally essential (must be obtained from diet). Treatment: low-Phe diet started at birth. This is why Tyr is NOT classified as essential in healthy individuals -- it can be made from Phe. PKU is detected by newborn screening.",mn:"PKU = no Phe hydroxylase = Phe builds up = brain damage. Tyr becomes essential. Diet treatment."},
{id:"aa18",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Disulfide Bonds","Amino Acid Properties"],diff:3,q:"Denaturation by urea works by:",o:["Disrupting hydrophobic interactions and hydrogen bonds only","Breaking covalent peptide bonds in the primary structure","Cleaving disulfide bonds between cysteine side chains","Permanently changing the amino acid sequence of the protein"],a:0,ex:"Urea is a chaotropic agent that disrupts the NON-COVALENT interactions holding a protein in its folded state: hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic interactions, and van der Waals forces. It does NOT break covalent bonds (peptide bonds or disulfide bonds remain intact). To also break disulfide bonds, you need a reducing agent like DTT or beta-mercaptoethanol. Complete denaturation requires both urea (for non-covalent) and a reducing agent (for disulfide bonds). SDS-PAGE uses SDS (denatures + adds uniform negative charge) and BME (breaks disulfides).",mn:"Urea breaks non-covalent forces. DTT/BME breaks disulfide bonds. Both needed for complete denaturation."},
{id:"cb15",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Signal Transduction","Cell Cycle","Tumor Suppressors"],diff:3,q:"Ras is an oncogene that when mutated:",o:["Constitutively active, driving uncontrolled cell proliferation","Converted into a tumor suppressor blocking cell division","Completely silenced, stopping all downstream signaling activity","Redirected to promote programmed cell death via apoptosis"],a:0,ex:"Ras is a GTPase that acts as a molecular switch in the RTK signaling pathway. Normal Ras: cycles between active (GTP-bound) and inactive (GDP-bound) states. GTPase-activating proteins (GAPs) turn Ras OFF by stimulating GTP hydrolysis. Mutant Ras (found in ~30% of cancers): cannot hydrolyze GTP, so it is PERMANENTLY STUCK in the ON position, continuously activating the Raf-MEK-ERK (MAPK) cascade, driving cell proliferation. Ras is a proto-oncogene; the mutated version is an oncogene. Oncogenes = gain-of-function mutations (one allele sufficient). Tumor suppressors = loss-of-function (need both alleles lost).",mn:"Ras = molecular switch stuck ON in cancer. Oncogene = gain-of-function (1 allele). TSG = loss-of-function (2 alleles)."},
{id:"cb16",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Membrane Transport","Signal Transduction","Organelles"],diff:2,q:"The endoplasmic reticulum stores which important signaling ion?",o:["Calcium (Ca2+)","Sodium (Na+)","Potassium (K+)","Chloride (Cl-)"],a:0,ex:"The ER (especially smooth ER and sarcoplasmic reticulum in muscle) stores Ca2+ at concentrations 10,000x higher than cytoplasm. When IP3 (from PLC/GPCR signaling) binds IP3 receptors on the ER, Ca2+ is released into the cytoplasm, triggering downstream effects: muscle contraction (binds troponin C), secretion (exocytosis), enzyme activation (calmodulin-dependent kinases), and apoptosis (when sustained). Ca2+ is pumped back into the ER by SERCA pumps (Ca2+-ATPase).",mn:"ER stores Ca2+. IP3 releases it. Ca2+ triggers contraction, secretion, enzymes. SERCA pumps it back."},
{id:"gen11",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Meiosis","Genetic Diversity","Chromosomal Abnormalities"],diff:2,q:"Crossing over during meiosis occurs in:",o:["Prophase I, occurring between aligned homologous chromosome pairs","Metaphase I, occurring at the metaphase plate during alignment","Anaphase II, occurring during separation of sister chromatids","Prophase II, occurring during condensation of haploid chromosomes"],a:0,ex:"Crossing over (recombination) occurs during PROPHASE I of meiosis when homologous chromosomes pair up (synapsis) to form tetrads (bivalents). Segments of DNA are exchanged between non-sister chromatids of homologous chromosomes at points called chiasmata. This produces recombinant chromosomes with new allele combinations that did not exist in either parent. Along with independent assortment (2^23 possible arrangements in humans) and random fertilization, crossing over is one of three sources of genetic diversity from sexual reproduction.",mn:"Crossing over = Prophase I. Exchange DNA between homologs. Creates new allele combinations."},
{id:"gen12",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Population Genetics","Hardy-Weinberg","Mendelian Genetics"],diff:3,q:"Which would violate Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium?",o:["Natural selection favoring one genotype over others","Maintaining a sufficiently large breeding population size","Ensuring completely random mating among all individuals","Preventing migration between separate breeding populations"],a:0,ex:"Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium (p^2 + 2pq + q^2 = 1) requires FIVE conditions: (1) Large population (no genetic drift), (2) No mutation, (3) No migration (no gene flow), (4) Random mating, (5) No natural selection. Violating ANY condition changes allele frequencies. Natural selection = differential survival/reproduction based on genotype, which directly changes allele frequencies. The MCAT commonly asks you to identify which factor violates HW or to calculate expected frequencies and compare to observed data.",mn:"HW needs: large pop, no mutation, no migration, random mating, no selection. Violate any = allele frequencies change."},
{id:"gen13",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Inheritance Patterns","X-Linked Inheritance","Mendelian Genetics"],diff:2,q:"A carrier mother (X^A X^a) and normal father (X^A Y) have a son. What is the chance he is affected?",o:["50%","25%","100%","0%"],a:0,ex:"Sons get their X from mom and Y from dad. The carrier mother has a 50% chance of passing on her affected X^a to each son. So each son has a 50% chance of being affected (X^a Y). Daughters get X from both parents: 50% chance of being a carrier (X^A X^a), 50% chance of being normal (X^A X^A), 0% chance of being affected (would need X^a X^a, but father only contributes X^A). Key principle: fathers NEVER pass X-linked traits to sons (sons get Y from dad).",mn:"Sons get X from mom only. Carrier mom = 50% sons affected. Fathers never pass X-linked to sons."},
{id:"gen14",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Inheritance Patterns","Mendelian Genetics","Population Genetics"],diff:2,q:"Incomplete penetrance means:",o:["Not all individuals with the genotype display the phenotype","The severity of the phenotype varies among affected individuals","Multiple genes each contribute to the phenotypic outcome","The trait consistently skips every other generation in families"],a:0,ex:"Penetrance = the proportion of individuals with a particular genotype who actually express the expected phenotype. Incomplete/reduced penetrance means some individuals carry the allele but do NOT show the trait. Example: BRCA1 mutations have ~70% penetrance for breast cancer -- 70% of carriers develop cancer, 30% do not. Expressivity is different: it refers to the SEVERITY of the phenotype varying among those who do express it. Example: neurofibromatosis -- some patients have mild cafe-au-lait spots, others have severe tumors.",mn:"Penetrance = do you show it? Expressivity = how severely? Both can vary independently."},
{id:"bs21",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System","Hormones","Renal System"],diff:2,q:"Renin is released from the kidney in response to:",o:["Low blood pressure or reduced Na+ delivery to macula densa","Elevated systemic blood pressure above normal threshold range","Elevated blood glucose concentration exceeding renal threshold","Decreased serum potassium below normal physiological levels"],a:0,ex:"Renin is released by juxtaglomerular cells in the kidney when: (1) BP is low (detected by baroreceptors in afferent arteriole), (2) Na+/Cl- delivery to the macula densa is low, (3) Sympathetic stimulation (beta-1 receptors). Renin cleaves angiotensinogen (from liver) to angiotensin I. ACE (in lungs) converts ang I to ang II. Ang II: vasoconstriction, stimulates aldosterone, stimulates ADH, stimulates thirst. This is the RAAS system. ACE inhibitors and ARBs are major antihypertensive drugs.",mn:"Low BP -> renin -> ang I -> ACE -> ang II -> vasoconstriction + aldosterone. ACE inhibitors block this."},
{id:"bs22",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Action Potential","Neurotransmitters"],diff:2,q:"Saltatory conduction in myelinated neurons means:",o:["Action potentials jump between nodes of Ranvier","Signals travel through the myelin sheath","Conduction is slower than unmyelinated","Myelin generates action potentials"],a:0,ex:"Myelin (produced by Schwann cells in PNS, oligodendrocytes in CNS) insulates the axon, preventing ion leakage. Action potentials can only be generated at the gaps between myelin segments (nodes of Ranvier), where ion channels are concentrated. The signal effectively jumps from node to node, which is MUCH faster than continuous conduction in unmyelinated neurons. Speed: myelinated ~120 m/s vs unmyelinated ~1 m/s. Demyelinating diseases (multiple sclerosis, Guillain-Barre) slow or block signal transmission.",mn:"Myelin insulates. Signal jumps node to node. Much faster. MS/Guillain-Barre = demyelination."},
{id:"bs23",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Immune System","Hormones","Endocrine System"],diff:3,q:"Antibodies (immunoglobulins) are produced by:",o:["Plasma cells","T cells","Macrophages","NK cells"],a:0,ex:"The humoral immune response: B cells recognize antigen via their B cell receptor (surface antibody) -> with T helper cell help (CD4+), B cells activate and differentiate into: (1) PLASMA CELLS that secrete large amounts of antibody, and (2) MEMORY B CELLS for long-lasting immunity. Antibody classes: IgM (first response, pentamer), IgG (most abundant, crosses placenta), IgA (mucous membranes, breast milk), IgE (allergies, parasites, mast cell degranulation), IgD (B cell surface receptor). Antibodies neutralize, opsonize, activate complement, and mediate ADCC.",mn:"B cells -> plasma cells -> antibodies. IgM first, IgG most. IgA = mucosa. IgE = allergy."},
{id:"bs24",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Respiratory System","Hemoglobin","Acid-Base"],diff:2,q:"How is most CO2 transported in blood?",o:["As bicarbonate in plasma","Dissolved in plasma","Bound to hemoglobin","As carbonic acid"],a:0,ex:"CO2 transport: ~70% as bicarbonate (CO2 + H2O -> H2CO3 -> HCO3- + H+, catalyzed by carbonic anhydrase in RBCs), ~23% bound to hemoglobin (as carbaminohemoglobin -- binds amino groups, not heme iron), ~7% dissolved in plasma. The HCO3- exits RBCs via the chloride shift (HCO3-/Cl- antiporter). In the lungs, the reaction reverses: HCO3- -> CO2 exhaled. The H+ generated from CO2 loading in tissues is buffered by deoxyhemoglobin (Bohr effect) -- this is why deoxyhemoglobin is a better buffer than oxyhemoglobin.",mn:"70% as HCO3- (bicarbonate), 23% bound to Hb, 7% dissolved. Chloride shift moves HCO3- out of RBCs."},
{id:"bs25",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Digestive System","Hormones","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Cholecystokinin (CCK) is released in response to:",o:["Fats and proteins arriving in the duodenal lumen","Carbohydrate digestion products in the gastric lumen","Low circulating blood glucose concentration levels","Elevated blood pH above the normal physiological range"],a:0,ex:"Major GI hormones: CCK: released from I cells of duodenum in response to fats and proteins. Stimulates gallbladder contraction (bile release for fat emulsification), pancreatic enzyme secretion, and slows gastric emptying. Secretin: released from S cells when acidic chyme enters duodenum. Stimulates pancreatic bicarbonate secretion (neutralizes acid) and inhibits gastric acid. Gastrin: released from G cells of stomach in response to distension and peptides. Stimulates HCl secretion from parietal cells.",mn:"CCK = fats/proteins -> bile + pancreatic enzymes. Secretin = acid -> bicarb. Gastrin = stimulates HCl."},
{id:"bs26",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Endocrine System","Hormones","Cardiovascular System"],diff:2,q:"Parathyroid hormone (PTH) increases blood calcium by:",o:["Stimulates osteoclast bone resorption, renal Ca2+ reabsorption, and vitamin D","Inhibits osteoclast activity, promotes bone mineral deposition directly","Promotes renal calcium excretion while inhibiting intestinal absorption","Decreases vitamin D activation while increasing calcitonin release"],a:0,ex:"PTH is released when blood Ca2+ is LOW. Three actions to raise Ca2+: (1) Stimulates osteoclast activity -> releases Ca2+ and phosphate from bone. (2) Increases renal Ca2+ reabsorption in the DCT (and promotes phosphate excretion). (3) Stimulates 1-alpha-hydroxylase in the kidney to convert 25-OH vitamin D to active 1,25-(OH)2 vitamin D (calcitriol), which increases intestinal Ca2+ absorption. Calcitonin (from thyroid C cells) opposes PTH by inhibiting osteoclasts (lowers Ca2+). PTH and calcitonin form a negative feedback loop.",mn:"PTH raises Ca2+: bone resorption + kidney reabsorption + vitamin D activation. Calcitonin lowers Ca2+."},
{id:"bs27",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Autonomic","Nervous System","Neurotransmitters"],diff:2,q:"The parasympathetic nervous system is associated with:",o:["Rest and digest responses","Fight or flight","Increased heart rate","Bronchodilation"],a:0,ex:"The autonomic nervous system has two divisions: SYMPATHETIC (fight or flight): increased HR, BP, bronchodilation, pupil dilation, glycogenolysis, decreased digestion. Uses NE at most targets. PARASYMPATHETIC (rest and digest): decreased HR, increased digestion/secretion, pupil constriction, bronchoconstriction. Uses ACh at all targets. Key parasympathetic nerve: vagus nerve (CN X) -- innervates heart, lungs, GI tract. Parasympathetic effects dominate at rest; sympathetic during stress/exercise.",mn:"Para = rest and digest = slow heart, increase digestion. Symp = fight or flight. Vagus = main para nerve."},
{id:"gc16",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Buffers","Acid-Base","Solutions"],diff:2,q:"A buffer made from acetic acid (pKa 4.76) and sodium acetate would work best at pH:",o:["~4.76","~7.0","~2.0","~10.0"],a:0,ex:"A buffer works best within +/-1 pH unit of the weak acid's pKa. Acetic acid pKa = 4.76, so this buffer is effective from about pH 3.76 to 5.76. At pH = pKa, the ratio [A-]/[HA] = 1:1 (maximum buffering). If you need to buffer at pH 7.4 (physiological), choose a different acid -- like H2PO4-/HPO42- (pKa 7.2) or HEPES (pKa 7.5). Blood uses the bicarbonate buffer system (H2CO3/HCO3-, effective pKa 6.1, maintained by the lungs adjusting CO2).",mn:"Buffer pH should match pKa. Acetic acid pKa 4.76 = best buffer around pH 4.76."},
{id:"gc17",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Thermodynamics","Equilibrium","Chemical Kinetics"],diff:2,q:"A catalyst affects a reaction by:",o:["Lowering activation energy without changing delta-G or Keq","Shifting the equilibrium constant toward product formation","Making the overall reaction more thermodynamically exothermic","Shifting the equilibrium position to favor product side"],a:0,ex:"A catalyst provides an alternative reaction pathway with a LOWER activation energy (Ea), increasing the rate of both forward and reverse reactions equally. It does NOT change: delta-G (thermodynamics), Keq (equilibrium constant), or delta-H. It DOES change: rate of reaction (kinetics), activation energy. Enzymes are biological catalysts that can lower Ea by factors of 10^6 to 10^12. They use strategies like proximity/orientation, acid-base catalysis, covalent catalysis, and metal ion catalysis.",mn:"Catalyst lowers Ea but does not change delta-G or Keq. Speeds up BOTH directions equally."},
{id:"gc18",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Equilibrium","Thermodynamics"],diff:3,q:"At equilibrium, which statement is TRUE?",o:["Forward and reverse rates are equal with constant concentrations","All chemical reactions have completely stopped and ceased","Concentrations of products and reactants are numerically equal","The reaction quotient equals the standard free energy change"],a:0,ex:"At equilibrium: the forward rate equals the reverse rate (dynamic equilibrium -- reactions continue but no NET change). Concentrations are CONSTANT but NOT necessarily equal. delta-G = 0 (no free energy available to drive the reaction in either direction). Q = K (reaction quotient equals equilibrium constant). Note: delta-G-standard is NOT zero at equilibrium -- it is delta-G (actual) that is zero. delta-G-standard is a fixed value determined by the nature of the reaction at standard conditions.",mn:"At equilibrium: rates equal, delta-G = 0, Q = K. Concentrations constant but NOT equal."},
{id:"gc19",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Intermolecular Forces","Solutions","Thermodynamics"],diff:2,q:"Dissolving NaCl in water is favorable primarily because of:",o:["Strong ion-dipole interactions with surrounding water molecules","Formation of new covalent bonds between solute and water","Decreased entropy of the overall system upon dissolution","Weak van der Waals forces between ions and water dipoles"],a:0,ex:"When NaCl dissolves, Na+ and Cl- ions separate and become surrounded by water molecules (hydration/solvation). The energetics: (1) Breaking the ionic lattice requires energy (lattice energy, unfavorable). (2) Ion-dipole interactions between Na+/Cl- and water release energy (hydration energy, favorable). (3) Entropy increases (more disorder). For NaCl, the hydration energy + entropy increase outweigh the lattice energy, so dissolution is spontaneous. Like dissolves like: ionic and polar solutes dissolve in polar solvents, nonpolar solutes in nonpolar solvents.",mn:"Ion-dipole interactions drive salt dissolution. Lattice energy vs hydration energy. Like dissolves like."},
{id:"gc20",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Redox Chemistry","Thermodynamics"],diff:3,q:"In electrolysis of water, which reaction occurs at the anode?",o:["Oxidation: 2H2O -> O2 + 4H+ + 4e-","Reduction: 2H2O -> H2 + 2OH-","No reaction","Both oxidation and reduction"],a:0,ex:"Electrolysis is a non-spontaneous process that uses external electrical energy. At the ANODE (always oxidation, AnOx): water is oxidized to produce O2 gas. At the CATHODE (always reduction, RedCat): water is reduced to produce H2 gas. In electrolytic cells, the anode is positive (connected to + terminal of power source, attracts anions). In galvanic cells, the anode is negative (electrons flow away from it). This sign flip between galvanic and electrolytic cells is commonly tested.",mn:"Electrolysis anode = oxidation = O2 produced. Cathode = reduction = H2. Anode sign flips between galvanic/electrolytic."},
{id:"gc21",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Atomic Structure","Intermolecular Forces"],diff:2,q:"Electronegativity increases:",o:["Up and to the right on the periodic table, toward fluorine region","Down and to the left on the periodic table, toward cesium region","Only found among metallic elements in the d-block transition series","Distributed randomly with no predictable periodic table trend pattern"],a:0,ex:"Electronegativity (EN) measures how strongly an atom attracts bonding electrons. Trend: increases going RIGHT across a period (more protons pulling electrons) and UP within a group (electrons closer to nucleus, less shielding). Fluorine is the most electronegative element (EN = 4.0). EN determines bond polarity: large EN difference = polar bond (or ionic if > 1.7). Small EN difference = nonpolar covalent. Important for predicting molecular polarity, IMFs, and reactivity.",mn:"EN increases right and up. F is most electronegative. Large EN difference = polar/ionic bond."},
{id:"gc22",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Chemical Kinetics","Enzyme Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Zero-order reaction rate:",o:["Constant and independent of reactant concentration","Doubles when reactant concentration is doubled","Depends on the square of reactant concentration","Always equals zero for every reaction order"],a:0,ex:"Zero order: rate = k (constant, independent of concentration). The rate stays the same until reactant is depleted, then drops to zero suddenly. Graph of [A] vs time is a straight line. Half-life = [A]0/2k (depends on initial concentration). Example: enzyme-catalyzed reactions at saturating substrate (Vmax region -- rate is constant because all active sites are occupied). Alcohol metabolism by alcohol dehydrogenase follows zero-order kinetics at typical drinking levels.",mn:"Zero order: rate = k (constant). Straight line on [A] vs time. Vmax region of enzymes. Alcohol metabolism."},
{id:"org13",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Functional Groups","Carbonyl Chemistry","Acid-Base"],diff:2,q:"Rank acidity: carboxylic acid > phenol > alcohol. This is because:",o:["Their conjugate bases have decreasing resonance stabilization","Molecular weight is the primary determinant of acid strength","Electronegativity of the central carbon atom increases","All three functional groups share identical pKa values"],a:0,ex:"Acidity relates to how well the conjugate base is stabilized: Carboxylic acid (pKa ~4-5): conjugate base (carboxylate, RCOO-) has resonance stabilization over TWO equivalent oxygens. Phenol (pKa ~10): conjugate base (phenoxide) has resonance with the aromatic ring but charge is delocalized less effectively. Alcohol (pKa ~16): conjugate base (alkoxide, RO-) has NO resonance stabilization, charge localized on one oxygen. More resonance = more stable conjugate base = stronger acid = lower pKa.",mn:"More resonance in conjugate base = stronger acid. RCOOH > PhOH > ROH."},
{id:"org14",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Stereochemistry","Substitution Reactions","Elimination Reactions"],diff:2,q:"What determines whether a reaction follows SN1/SN2/E1/E2?",o:["Substrate degree, nucleophile/base strength, and solvent type","Reaction temperature as the sole determining kinetic factor","System pressure applied during the substitution reaction only","Molecular weight of the substrate and leaving group combined"],a:0,ex:"Decision framework: (1) SUBSTRATE: methyl/1-degree favors SN2; 3-degree favors SN1/E1/E2. 2-degree can go any way. (2) NUCLEOPHILE/BASE: strong nuc favors SN2; strong bulky base favors E2; weak nuc favors SN1; weak base + heat favors E1. (3) SOLVENT: polar protic favors SN1/E1 (stabilizes carbocation); polar aprotic favors SN2 (keeps nuc reactive). (4) TEMPERATURE: heat favors elimination over substitution. This framework is among the most tested organic chemistry concepts on the MCAT.",mn:"Substrate + nucleophile/base + solvent = determines SN1/SN2/E1/E2. MEMORIZE this framework."},
{id:"org15",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Addition Reactions","Stereochemistry","Functional Groups"],diff:2,q:"Catalytic hydrogenation (H2/Pd) adds hydrogen:",o:["Syn (both H's add to same face)","Anti (H's add to opposite faces)","Randomly","Only to carbonyls"],a:0,ex:"H2/Pd (or Pt or Ni) reduces C=C double bonds to C-C single bonds. The mechanism: both H atoms are adsorbed onto the metal surface and delivered to the SAME face of the double bond simultaneously (syn addition). This has stereochemical consequences -- if the starting alkene has substituents, the product will have a specific stereochemistry based on syn addition. Compare: halogenation (Br2) is ANTI addition (Br's add to opposite faces via cyclic bromonium ion intermediate).",mn:"H2/Pd = syn addition (same face). Br2 = anti addition (opposite faces)."},
{id:"org16",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Elimination Reactions","Functional Groups"],diff:2,q:"E1 elimination is favored by:",o:["Tertiary substrate, weak base, polar protic solvent, and heat","Primary substrate, strong base, polar aprotic solvent conditions","Methyl substrate with any nucleophile in any solvent system","Secondary substrate in polar aprotic solvent without heating"],a:0,ex:"E1 is a two-step mechanism: (1) leaving group departs forming carbocation (rate-determining), (2) base removes a beta-proton forming the double bond. Needs: stable carbocation (3-degree), weak base (strong base would push E2), polar protic solvent (stabilizes carbocation), and heat (favors elimination over substitution). E1 typically competes with SN1 (same conditions), and heat shifts the balance toward elimination. E1 follows Zaitsev's rule (more substituted alkene is major product).",mn:"E1 = carbocation + weak base + protic + heat. Competes with SN1. Heat favors elimination."},
{id:"ph13",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Waves and Sound","Optics"],diff:2,q:"The electromagnetic spectrum from lowest to highest energy:",o:["Radio, microwave, infrared, visible, UV, X-ray, gamma ray","Gamma, X-ray, UV, visible, infrared, microwave, radio wave","Visible, UV, infrared, radio, gamma, X-ray, microwave","The ordering is random with no relationship to wavelength"],a:0,ex:"EM waves travel at the speed of light (c = 3 x 10^8 m/s). E = hf = hc/lambda. Low frequency = low energy = long wavelength. Order of increasing energy (decreasing wavelength): Radio < Microwave < Infrared < Visible (ROYGBIV, red lowest to violet highest) < Ultraviolet < X-ray < Gamma. Medical applications: X-rays (imaging), gamma rays (radiation therapy), UV (skin damage), IR (thermal imaging), radio (MRI). Visible light: ~400nm (violet) to ~700nm (red).",mn:"Low to high energy: Radio, Micro, IR, Visible, UV, X-ray, Gamma. E = hf = hc/lambda."},
{id:"ph14",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Bernoulli's Principle"],diff:2,q:"Pressure at depth in a fluid equals:",o:["Atmospheric pressure plus density times gravity times depth","Density times gravitational acceleration without atmospheric","Force divided by area without any depth dependence","Mass times gravitational acceleration times height value"],a:0,ex:"Hydrostatic pressure increases linearly with depth: P = P_surface + rho*g*h, where rho is fluid density, g is gravitational acceleration, and h is depth below the surface. At the surface (h=0), P = P_atm. Key points: pressure depends only on depth (not container shape -- Pascal's vases), pressure acts equally in all directions at a given depth (Pascal's law), and 1 atm = 101,325 Pa = 760 mmHg. In blood pressure: hydrostatic pressure from standing creates ~90 mmHg difference between head and feet.",mn:"P = P_atm + rho*g*h. Depends on depth only, not shape. Acts equally in all directions."},
{id:"ph15",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Circuits","Electrostatics","Work and Energy"],diff:2,q:"Power dissipated by a resistor:",o:["P = IV, which also equals I-squared-R and V-squared/R","P = IR, which represents voltage drop across a resistance","P = QV, which represents work done moving a single charge","P = Fd/t, which applies only to mechanical power situations"],a:0,ex:"Three equivalent forms: P = IV (general, current times voltage), P = I^2R (useful when current is known), P = V^2/R (useful when voltage is known). These come from combining P = IV with Ohm's law (V = IR). Units: watts (W = J/s). In circuits: total power from battery = sum of power dissipated by all resistors. In series: same current, so P = I^2R (larger R dissipates more power). In parallel: same voltage, so P = V^2/R (smaller R dissipates more power).",mn:"P = IV = I^2R = V^2/R. Series: larger R = more power. Parallel: smaller R = more power."},
{id:"ph16",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics","Waves and Sound"],diff:3,q:"The index of refraction n equals:",o:["The ratio of light speed in vacuum to light speed in the medium","The ratio of light speed in the medium to light speed in vacuum","The ratio of wavelength in the medium to wavelength in vacuum","The ratio of frequency in the medium to frequency in vacuum only"],a:0,ex:"n = c/v. Since v in a medium is always less than c, n is always >= 1. Higher n means light travels SLOWER. Water n=1.33, glass n~1.5, diamond n=2.42. Snell's law: n1*sin(theta1) = n2*sin(theta2). When light enters a denser medium (higher n), it bends TOWARD the normal and slows down. Wavelength decreases in denser medium (lambda = lambda_0/n) but frequency stays the same. Total internal reflection occurs when going from high n to low n at angle > critical angle.",mn:"n = c/v. Higher n = slower light = bends toward normal. Diamond n = 2.42 (lots of TIR = sparkle)."},
{id:"ph17",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Work and Energy","Fluids"],diff:2,q:"Conservation of energy states:",o:["Total energy in an isolated system remains constant always","Energy can be spontaneously created from nothing at all","Energy can be permanently destroyed and lost from systems","Entropy of an isolated system always decreases over time"],a:0,ex:"First law of thermodynamics: energy cannot be created or destroyed, only transformed. In mechanics: KE + PE = constant (when only conservative forces act). KE (1/2mv^2) converts to PE (mgh) and back -- a ball at the top of a hill has max PE, at the bottom has max KE. When non-conservative forces (friction) act, mechanical energy converts to heat. In thermodynamics: delta-U = Q - W (internal energy change = heat added minus work done by system).",mn:"Energy is conserved. KE + PE = constant (no friction). delta-U = Q - W."},
{id:"ph18",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Nuclear Physics","Atomic Structure"],diff:2,q:"Alpha decay releases:",o:["A helium nucleus","An electron","A positron","A gamma ray only"],a:0,ex:"Radioactive decay types: ALPHA: emits He-4 nucleus (2p+2n). Atomic number Z decreases by 2, mass number A decreases by 4. Heavy nuclei (uranium, radium). Low penetration (stopped by paper). BETA-MINUS: neutron -> proton + electron + antineutrino. Z increases by 1, A unchanged. BETA-PLUS: proton -> neutron + positron + neutrino. Z decreases by 1. GAMMA: high-energy photon, no mass/charge change, often accompanies other decay. High penetration (stopped by lead/concrete). ELECTRON CAPTURE: inner electron captured by nucleus, similar result to beta-plus.",mn:"Alpha = He nucleus (Z-2, A-4). Beta- = electron (Z+1). Beta+ = positron (Z-1). Gamma = photon (no change)."},
{id:"ps23",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Learning and Conditioning","Developmental Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Bandura's social learning theory emphasizes:",o:["Observational learning","Classical conditioning only","Operant conditioning only","Biological instincts"],a:0,ex:"Albert Bandura's Bobo doll experiment (1961): children who watched an adult behave aggressively toward an inflatable doll later imitated that behavior, even without direct reinforcement. This demonstrated observational learning (also called modeling or social learning). Four steps: ATTENTION (notice the behavior), RETENTION (remember it), REPRODUCTION (ability to perform it), MOTIVATION (reason to do it -- vicarious reinforcement helps). This theory bridges behaviorism and cognitivism by showing that learning can occur WITHOUT direct reinforcement, challenging strict operant conditioning views.",mn:"Bandura: watch others -> imitate. Bobo doll. Attention -> Retention -> Reproduction -> Motivation."},
{id:"ps24",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Learning and Conditioning"],diff:2,q:"Long-term potentiation (LTP) is:",o:["Strengthened synaptic connections from repeated neural activity","Progressive weakening of synaptic connections over time period","A specific type of short-term memory storage mechanism","Forgetting that occurs due to proactive or retroactive interference"],a:0,ex:"LTP is the cellular mechanism believed to underlie learning and memory. When a synapse is repeatedly stimulated, the postsynaptic neuron increases its response -- the connection gets stronger. Molecular mechanism: repeated stimulation activates NMDA receptors -> Ca2+ influx -> insertion of more AMPA receptors -> stronger response to future stimulation. LTP primarily occurs in the hippocampus (critical for forming new declarative memories). Long-term depression (LTD) is the opposite -- weakening of synaptic connections with low-frequency stimulation.",mn:"LTP = repeated use strengthens synapse (hippocampus). NMDA + Ca2+ + more AMPA = stronger connection."},
{id:"ps25",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sensation and Perception","Developmental Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Signal detection theory accounts for:",o:["Both the sensitivity of the observer and their response bias","Only the absolute threshold of sensory detection ability","Only the process of sensory adaptation to constant stimuli","Only the Weber fraction for just-noticeable difference"],a:0,ex:"Signal detection theory recognizes that detecting a stimulus is not purely about sensory ability -- DECISION-MAKING matters too. Two factors: (1) Sensitivity (d-prime): the observer's actual ability to distinguish signal from noise. (2) Response bias/criterion: the observer's willingness to say 'yes, I detect it' (influenced by expectations, consequences, motivation). Four outcomes: Hit (signal present, say yes), Miss (signal present, say no), False alarm (no signal, say yes), Correct rejection (no signal, say no). A radiologist reading mammograms faces this: setting a liberal criterion catches more cancers but also more false alarms.",mn:"SDT: detection = sensitivity + bias. Hits, misses, false alarms, correct rejections."},
{id:"ps26",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Emotion Theories","Brain Anatomy","Nervous System"],diff:2,q:"The limbic system includes the:",o:["Amygdala for fear, hippocampus for memory, and hypothalamus for drives","Cerebellum for emotional processing, coordination, and memory storage","Frontal lobe for all emotional and motivational behavioral regulation","Brainstem for fear conditioning, memory consolidation, and motivation"],a:0,ex:"The limbic system is a group of interconnected structures involved in emotion, memory, and motivation. Key components: AMYGDALA: processes fear and emotional memories. Damage = cannot recognize fear in faces. HIPPOCAMPUS: forms new declarative (explicit) memories. Damage = anterograde amnesia (cannot form new memories, e.g., patient HM). HYPOTHALAMUS: controls homeostasis, hunger, thirst, temperature, circadian rhythms, and links nervous to endocrine system (releases hormones to anterior pituitary). Other limbic structures: cingulate cortex (emotional regulation), fornix, mammillary bodies.",mn:"Amygdala = fear. Hippocampus = new memories. Hypothalamus = homeostasis + endocrine link."},
{id:"ps27",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sociology","Health Disparities","Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Medicalization refers to:",o:["Defining non-medical problems as medical conditions needing treatment","Reducing patient access to necessary healthcare services and resources","Eliminating disease through public health intervention and prevention","Improving overall population health outcomes through medical advances"],a:0,ex:"Medicalization is the process by which human conditions or behaviors become defined as medical problems requiring medical solutions. Examples: ADHD (childhood energy/inattention -> disorder requiring medication), obesity (body size -> disease), alcoholism (moral failing -> brain disease), childbirth (natural process -> medical event requiring hospital). Can be positive (reduces stigma, provides treatment) or negative (overdiagnosis, pharmaceutical profits, loss of agency, ignoring social causes). Sociologists argue medicalization reflects power dynamics -- who gets to define 'normal' and 'pathological'?",mn:"Medicalization = non-medical becomes medical. Can help (treatment) or harm (overdiagnosis, power dynamics)."},
{id:"ps28",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Moral Development","Developmental Psychology","Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Gilligan criticized Kohlberg's theory because:",o:["It used male subjects and undervalued care-based moral reasoning","It focused too heavily on emotional responses to moral dilemmas","It ignored the role of punishment in shaping moral development","It studied only young children and ignored adult moral reasoning"],a:0,ex:"Carol Gilligan argued that Kohlberg's stages were biased toward a JUSTICE orientation (rights, rules, abstract principles) that is more typical of male moral reasoning. She proposed that women tend toward a CARE orientation (relationships, responsibility, compassion). Her stages: (1) Preconventional: caring for self, (2) Conventional: caring for others (self-sacrifice), (3) Postconventional: balancing care for self AND others. Gilligan did not argue women are morally inferior -- rather that Kohlberg's scale measured one type of morality and missed another equally valid type.",mn:"Gilligan: Kohlberg was male-biased. Justice vs care orientations. Both valid, different approaches."},
{id:"ps29",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sleep","Brain Anatomy","Sensation and Perception"],diff:2,q:"The suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) regulates:",o:["Circadian rhythm","Hunger only","Fear responses","Language production"],a:0,ex:"The SCN in the hypothalamus is the master circadian pacemaker. It receives light input from the retina (via retinohypothalamic tract) and synchronizes the body's 24-hour rhythms: sleep-wake cycle, hormone release (cortisol peaks in morning, melatonin peaks at night), body temperature, metabolism. The SCN signals the pineal gland to produce MELATONIN in darkness (promotes sleep). Jet lag occurs when the SCN is out of sync with the external light-dark cycle. Shift workers have disrupted circadian rhythms linked to higher rates of cardiovascular disease and cancer.",mn:"SCN = master clock in hypothalamus. Light input -> melatonin at night. Disruption -> health problems."},
{id:"mb12",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Transcription/Translation","Gene Regulation"],diff:2,q:"The start codon AUG codes for:",o:["Methionine","Stop signal","Leucine","Any amino acid"],a:0,ex:"AUG serves dual functions: (1) it is the universal START codon that initiates translation in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes, and (2) it codes for methionine (Met/M). In prokaryotes, the initiator Met is formylated (fMet). Translation begins when the small ribosomal subunit binds mRNA and scans for AUG (in eukaryotes, Kozak sequence helps; in prokaryotes, Shine-Dalgarno sequence positions ribosome). The three STOP codons (UAA, UAG, UGA) do NOT code for amino acids -- they are recognized by release factors that terminate translation.",mn:"AUG = start = methionine. UAA/UAG/UGA = stop (release factors, no amino acid)."},
{id:"mb13",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["DNA Replication","Mutations","Gene Regulation"],diff:3,q:"DNA mismatch repair fixes errors that escape:",o:["Proofreading by DNA polymerase","Transcription errors","Translation errors","Protein folding errors"],a:0,ex:"DNA repair systems form multiple layers of defense: (1) PROOFREADING: DNA polymerase's 3'-to-5' exonuclease immediately removes mismatched nucleotides during replication (error rate: 1/10^5 -> 1/10^7). (2) MISMATCH REPAIR (MMR): MutS/MutL (in E. coli; MSH/MLH in humans) scan newly replicated DNA for mismatches and fix them (improves to 1/10^9). (3) BASE EXCISION REPAIR: glycosylases remove damaged bases (deaminated, oxidized). (4) NUCLEOTIDE EXCISION REPAIR: removes bulky lesions like thymine dimers (UV damage) -- defective in xeroderma pigmentosum. Lynch syndrome = defective MMR -> increased colon cancer risk.",mn:"Layers: proofreading -> mismatch repair -> base/nucleotide excision repair. Lynch syndrome = MMR defect."},
{id:"mb14",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Transcription/Translation","Gene Regulation"],diff:2,q:"RNA polymerase differs from DNA polymerase because RNA pol:",o:["Does not require a primer and uses ribonucleotide substrates","Requires a primer to initiate new strand synthesis","Uses deoxyribonucleotide substrates for chain elongation","Has 3-prime to 5-prime proofreading exonuclease activity"],a:0,ex:"Key differences: RNA polymerase does NOT need a primer (can initiate de novo), uses ribonucleotides (A, U, G, C instead of A, T, G, C), synthesizes 5' to 3' (same as DNA pol), reads template 3' to 5' (same), does NOT have proofreading activity (higher error rate than DNA pol, but RNA is expendable -- errors in mRNA are temporary). In prokaryotes: one RNA polymerase for all RNA types. In eukaryotes: RNA Pol I (rRNA), RNA Pol II (mRNA -- inhibited by alpha-amanitin from death cap mushroom), RNA Pol III (tRNA, 5S rRNA).",mn:"RNA pol: no primer, uses ribonucleotides (U not T), no proofreading. Eu: Pol I=rRNA, II=mRNA, III=tRNA."},
{id:"met28",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Anaerobic Metabolism","ATP Yield"],diff:1,q:"Net ATP produced by glycolysis per glucose:",o:["2 ATP","4 ATP","36 ATP","0 ATP"],a:0,ex:"Glycolysis uses 2 ATP (hexokinase and PFK-1 steps) and produces 4 ATP (phosphoglycerate kinase and pyruvate kinase steps) by substrate-level phosphorylation. Net = 4 - 2 = 2 ATP. Also produces 2 NADH (at GAPDH step) which yield ~5 more ATP if shuttled to ETC. Glycolysis occurs in the CYTOPLASM, requires no oxygen, and is the universal pathway -- all cells use it.",mn:"Glycolysis: invest 2 ATP, earn 4 ATP, net = 2 ATP + 2 NADH. Cytoplasm. No O2 needed."},
{id:"met29",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Krebs Cycle","Aerobic Respiration","Electron Carriers"],diff:2,q:"Acetyl-CoA enters the Krebs cycle by combining with:",o:["Oxaloacetate","Pyruvate","Glucose","Succinate"],a:0,ex:"Citrate synthase catalyzes: acetyl-CoA (2C) + oxaloacetate (4C) -> citrate (6C). This is the first step of the Krebs cycle. OAA is regenerated at the end of each cycle (by malate dehydrogenase). When OAA is depleted (e.g., diverted to gluconeogenesis during fasting), acetyl-CoA cannot enter the Krebs cycle and is shunted to ketogenesis instead. This is the metabolic basis for ketone body production during starvation.",mn:"Acetyl-CoA + OAA = citrate (first Krebs step). Low OAA = ketogenesis."},
{id:"met30",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Krebs Cycle","Electron Transport Chain","Aerobic Respiration"],diff:2,q:"Which Krebs cycle enzyme is also part of the ETC?",o:["Succinate dehydrogenase","Citrate synthase","Isocitrate dehydrogenase","Malate dehydrogenase"],a:0,ex:"Succinate dehydrogenase is unique: it is both a Krebs cycle enzyme (oxidizes succinate to fumarate, producing FADH2) and Complex II of the ETC (passes electrons from FADH2 to CoQ). It is the only Krebs enzyme embedded in the inner mitochondrial membrane rather than free in the matrix. This direct connection between Krebs and ETC makes succinate dehydrogenase a useful experimental tool for studying electron transport.",mn:"Succinate dehydrogenase = Krebs enzyme AND Complex II. Only membrane-bound Krebs enzyme."},
{id:"met31",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Hormonal Regulation","Insulin","Glucagon"],diff:2,q:"During the fed state, high insulin-to-glucagon ratio promotes:",o:["Glycolysis, glycogen synthesis, lipogenesis","Gluconeogenesis, glycogenolysis, ketogenesis","Beta-oxidation and protein degradation","Fasting metabolic pathways"],a:0,ex:"The insulin-to-glucagon ratio is the master metabolic switch. HIGH ratio (fed state, after a meal): insulin dominates, promoting ANABOLIC pathways -- glycolysis, glycogen synthesis, fatty acid synthesis (lipogenesis), protein synthesis. LOW ratio (fasting, between meals): glucagon dominates, promoting CATABOLIC pathways -- glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis, lipolysis, beta-oxidation, ketogenesis. The MCAT loves testing which pathways are active in fed vs fasting states.",mn:"High insulin/glucagon = fed = build and store. Low ratio = fasting = break down and mobilize."},
{id:"met32",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Aerobic Respiration","Oxidative Phosphorylation"],diff:3,q:"Antimycin A blocks which ETC complex?",o:["Complex III","Complex I","Complex II","Complex IV"],a:0,ex:"ETC inhibitors to know: Rotenone/barbiturates = Complex I. Antimycin A = Complex III (blocks electron transfer from cytochrome b to cytochrome c1). Cyanide/CO = Complex IV. Oligomycin = ATP synthase (blocks proton channel, not technically an ETC complex). All ETC inhibitors STOP electron flow and DECREASE O2 consumption. Uncouplers (DNP, thermogenin) are different -- they INCREASE O2 consumption by dissipating the gradient as heat.",mn:"Rotenone=I, Antimycin=III, Cyanide/CO=IV, Oligomycin=ATP synthase. Uncouplers are different!"},
{id:"aa19",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Isoelectric Point","Acid-Base","Amino Acid Classification"],diff:3,q:"At pH 1, the net charge on alanine (pI ~6.0) is:",o:["Positive, since all ionizable groups are fully protonated","Negative, since carboxyl group is deprotonated at this pH","Zero, since the amino acid is at its isoelectric point","Neutral, since amino acids carry no charge in strong acid"],a:0,ex:"At pH well BELOW the pI, all ionizable groups are protonated. For alanine at pH 1: alpha-NH2 is protonated to NH3+ (positive), alpha-COOH is protonated (neutral, not negative). Net charge = +1. Rule: pH < pI = positive charge (molecule migrates toward cathode in electrophoresis). pH > pI = negative charge (migrates toward anode). pH = pI = zero net charge (does not migrate). This rule applies to all amino acids AND proteins.",mn:"pH < pI = positive charge. pH > pI = negative. pH = pI = zero. Works for all AAs and proteins."},
{id:"aa20",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Essential Amino Acids","Amino Acid Properties","Metabolism"],diff:2,q:"Branched-chain amino acids (BCAAs) are:",o:["Leucine, isoleucine, and valine","Alanine, glycine, serine","Aspartate, glutamate","Proline, histidine"],a:0,ex:"Leucine (L), Isoleucine (I), and Valine (V) have branched aliphatic side chains. All three are essential, nonpolar, and hydrophobic. Unique feature: BCAAs are metabolized primarily in SKELETAL MUSCLE (not liver like most AAs). They are used as fuel during exercise and promote protein synthesis (leucine is especially potent at activating mTOR pathway). Maple syrup urine disease is caused by deficiency of branched-chain alpha-keto acid dehydrogenase, leading to accumulation of BCAAs and their metabolites.",mn:"BCAAs = Leu, Ile, Val. All essential. Metabolized in muscle. Maple syrup urine disease = BCAA buildup."},
{id:"cb17",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Apoptosis","Cell Death","Tumor Suppressors"],diff:3,q:"The intrinsic pathway of apoptosis is triggered by:",o:["Mitochondrial release of cytochrome c","Death receptor binding (Fas ligand)","Viral infection only","Complement activation"],a:0,ex:"Two apoptosis pathways: INTRINSIC (mitochondrial): cellular stress (DNA damage, oxidative stress, growth factor withdrawal) -> pro-apoptotic proteins (BAX, BAK) form pores in mitochondrial outer membrane -> cytochrome c released -> binds Apaf-1 -> forms apoptosome -> activates caspase-9 (initiator) -> activates caspase-3 (effector) -> cell death. EXTRINSIC (death receptor): extracellular death ligands (FasL, TNF) bind death receptors (Fas, TNFR) -> FADD adaptor -> activates caspase-8 -> caspase-3 -> death. Both converge on caspase-3. p53 promotes intrinsic pathway via BAX/PUMA.",mn:"Intrinsic = mitochondria -> cytochrome c -> caspase-9 -> caspase-3. Extrinsic = death receptors -> caspase-8 -> caspase-3."},
{id:"cb18",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Mitosis","Cell Cycle","Organelles"],diff:2,q:"During which phase does DNA replication occur?",o:["S phase during DNA synthesis","G1 phase during initial growth","G2 phase during division prep","M phase during actual mitosis"],a:0,ex:"Cell cycle phases: G1 (Gap 1): cell grows, prepares for DNA synthesis. S (Synthesis): DNA replication (chromosomes go from 1 chromatid to 2 sister chromatids each, DNA content doubles from 2n to 4n). G2 (Gap 2): cell grows more, checks for replication errors, prepares for mitosis. M (Mitosis): nuclear division (PMAT) + cytokinesis. G0: quiescent state (non-dividing cells like neurons, muscle). G1/S is the main checkpoint. Cyclin-CDK complexes drive transitions between phases.",mn:"G1 = grow. S = DNA synthesis. G2 = prepare. M = divide. G0 = quiescent."},
{id:"cb19",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Signal Transduction","Membrane Transport","Organelles"],diff:3,q:"Second messengers include:",o:["cAMP, IP3, DAG, Ca2+","Receptors, ligands","Transcription factors only","ATP only"],a:0,ex:"Second messengers are small intracellular signaling molecules produced in response to an extracellular signal (first messenger = hormone/neurotransmitter). Key second messengers: cAMP (made by adenylyl cyclase, activates PKA, degraded by phosphodiesterase), IP3 (releases Ca2+ from ER), DAG (activates PKC), Ca2+ (activates calmodulin-dependent kinases, triggers muscle contraction/secretion), cGMP (made by guanylyl cyclase, activates PKG, used in NO signaling for vasodilation). They amplify signals: one receptor -> many second messenger molecules -> huge cellular response.",mn:"cAMP, IP3, DAG, Ca2+, cGMP. They AMPLIFY signals. One receptor -> many messenger molecules."},
{id:"gen15",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Meiosis","Genetic Diversity","Inheritance Patterns"],diff:2,q:"Independent assortment occurs during:",o:["Metaphase I","S phase","Prophase II","Cytokinesis"],a:0,ex:"Mendel's Law of Independent Assortment: genes on DIFFERENT chromosomes (or far apart on the same chromosome) sort independently during meiosis I. At metaphase I, each pair of homologous chromosomes aligns randomly at the metaphase plate -- maternal or paternal homolog can face either pole. With 23 chromosome pairs: 2^23 = 8,388,608 possible arrangements. This is one of three sources of genetic diversity (with crossing over and random fertilization). Linked genes (close together on same chromosome) do NOT assort independently -- they tend to be inherited together.",mn:"Metaphase I: random alignment of homologs. 2^23 possible arrangements. Linked genes do NOT assort independently."},
{id:"gen16",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Chromosomal Abnormalities","Meiosis","Population Genetics"],diff:2,q:"Klinefelter syndrome karyotype is:",o:["47,XXY producing a male phenotype with an extra X chromosome","45,X producing a female phenotype missing one sex chromosome","47,XXX producing a female phenotype with an extra X chromosome","46,XY producing a normal male phenotype with standard karyotype"],a:0,ex:"Common sex chromosome aneuploidies: Klinefelter (47,XXY): phenotypically male, tall, infertile (small testes, low testosterone), may have gynecomastia. Caused by nondisjunction. Turner (45,X): phenotypically female, short stature, webbed neck, infertile (streak gonads), coarctation of aorta. Only monosomy compatible with life. Triple X (47,XXX): female, usually no symptoms, may have learning difficulties. XYY (47,XYY): male, tall, usually no significant symptoms.",mn:"Klinefelter=47,XXY (male, tall, infertile). Turner=45,X (female, short). Both = nondisjunction."},
{id:"bs28",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Hemoglobin","Respiratory System","Cardiovascular System"],diff:3,q:"Fetal hemoglobin (HbF) has higher O2 affinity than adult Hb because:",o:["Fetal hemoglobin binds 2,3-BPG less tightly than adult form","Fetal hemoglobin has more polypeptide subunits than adult","Fetal hemoglobin is physically larger than adult hemoglobin","Fetal hemoglobin has a higher isoelectric point than adult"],a:0,ex:"Fetal hemoglobin has gamma chains instead of beta chains (alpha2-gamma2 vs alpha2-beta2). The gamma chain binds 2,3-BPG less effectively. Since 2,3-BPG normally decreases Hb's O2 affinity (by stabilizing T-state), less BPG binding means HbF stays more in the R-state (high affinity). On the O2 dissociation curve, HbF is LEFT-shifted relative to adult HbA. This allows the fetus to extract O2 from maternal blood across the placenta -- fetal Hb grabs O2 that maternal Hb releases.",mn:"HbF gamma chains bind less 2,3-BPG = higher affinity = left shift. Fetus pulls O2 from mother."},
{id:"bs29",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System","Nervous System","Autonomic"],diff:2,q:"Baroreceptors in the carotid sinus detect:",o:["Arterial blood pressure changes detected by stretch receptors","Arterial blood oxygen levels detected by peripheral chemoreceptors","Blood glucose concentration changes detected by pancreatic cells","Core body temperature shifts detected by hypothalamic neurons"],a:0,ex:"Baroreceptors are stretch receptors in the carotid sinus and aortic arch walls. When BP rises, vessel walls stretch more -> increased baroreceptor firing -> signals sent via glossopharyngeal (CN IX, carotid) and vagus (CN X, aortic arch) nerves to the medulla -> PARASYMPATHETIC activation (vagus slows heart) + SYMPATHETIC inhibition -> HR decreases, vasodilation -> BP returns to normal. When BP drops: less stretching -> less firing -> sympathetic activation -> HR increases, vasoconstriction -> BP rises. This is a negative feedback loop for short-term BP regulation.",mn:"Baroreceptors: high BP -> more firing -> para up, symp down -> BP drops. Negative feedback."},
{id:"bs30",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Digestive System","Hormonal Regulation","Autonomic"],diff:2,q:"Parietal cells in the stomach secrete:",o:["HCl for acid digestion and intrinsic factor for B12 absorption","Pepsinogen for protein digestion and mucus for gastric protection","Mucus for epithelial protection and bicarbonate for neutralization","Gastrin for stimulating acid secretion and motility regulation"],a:0,ex:"Gastric cell types: PARIETAL cells: secrete HCl (via H+/K+ ATPase, the proton pump) and intrinsic factor (essential for vitamin B12 absorption in the ileum). CHIEF cells: secrete pepsinogen (activated to pepsin by HCl). MUCOUS cells: secrete mucus and bicarbonate (protective barrier against self-digestion). G cells: secrete gastrin (stimulates HCl production). Clinical: PPIs (omeprazole) block the proton pump -> reduce acid. B12 deficiency can result from parietal cell loss (pernicious anemia = autoimmune destruction of parietal cells).",mn:"Parietal = HCl + intrinsic factor. Chief = pepsinogen. G cells = gastrin. PPIs block proton pump."},
{id:"bs31",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Immune System","Hematology","Cardiovascular System"],diff:2,q:"Neutrophils are the first responders to:",o:["Bacterial infection","Viral infection only","Parasitic infection","Allergic reactions"],a:0,ex:"Neutrophils are the most abundant white blood cells (~60-70% of WBCs) and the first cells to arrive at sites of bacterial infection (within hours). They are phagocytes: engulf and kill bacteria using reactive oxygen species (respiratory burst, NADPH oxidase) and enzymes (lysozyme, defensins). They form pus (dead neutrophils + bacteria + tissue debris). Chronic granulomatous disease (CGD) = defective NADPH oxidase -> neutrophils cannot kill bacteria effectively. Other phagocytes: macrophages (arrive later, also present antigens), dendritic cells (best APCs).",mn:"Neutrophils = first responders, kill bacteria by phagocytosis + respiratory burst. Most abundant WBC."},
{id:"gc23",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Buffers","Acid-Base","Equilibrium"],diff:3,q:"Adding strong acid to a buffer solution:",o:["Converts conjugate base to weak acid, causing slight pH decrease","Immediately and completely destroys the buffer system capacity","Has absolutely no measurable effect on the solution pH value","Converts weak acid to conjugate base, causing slight pH increase"],a:0,ex:"When strong acid (H+) is added to a buffer: H+ reacts with the conjugate base (A-) to form the weak acid (HA). A- + H+ -> HA. This consumes the added H+, preventing a large pH change. The pH does drop slightly (because [A-] decreases and [HA] increases, shifting the Henderson-Hasselbalch ratio), but much less than it would without the buffer. When strong base (OH-) is added: OH- reacts with HA to form A- + H2O. Buffer capacity = amount of acid/base a buffer can absorb before pH changes significantly -- depends on total concentration of buffer components.",mn:"Add acid: A- + H+ -> HA (consumes acid, pH drops slightly). Add base: HA + OH- -> A- + H2O."},
{id:"gc24",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Solutions","Intermolecular Forces","Thermodynamics"],diff:2,q:"A solution boils at a higher temperature than pure solvent because:",o:["Solute lowers vapor pressure, requiring higher temperature to boil","Solute increases molecular weight, raising the boiling temperature","Solute adds kinetic energy to solvent molecules directly upon mixing","Solute absorbs heat from the solution, shifting equilibrium upward"],a:0,ex:"Colligative property explanation: nonvolatile solute particles at the surface reduce the number of solvent molecules that can escape to the gas phase, LOWERING vapor pressure (Raoult's law: P = x_solvent * P_pure). Since boiling requires vapor pressure to equal atmospheric pressure, and vapor pressure is lower, you need a HIGHER temperature to reach that point. delta-Tb = i*Kb*m (van't Hoff factor i accounts for dissociation: NaCl i=2, glucose i=1). Same logic for freezing point depression -- solute disrupts crystal formation.",mn:"Solute lowers vapor pressure (Raoult's) -> need higher T to boil. delta-Tb = iKbm."},
{id:"gc25",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Redox Chemistry","Electrochemistry","Chemical Kinetics"],diff:2,q:"In a galvanic cell, electrons flow from:",o:["From the anode to cathode through the external wire circuit","From the cathode to anode through the external wire circuit","Through the salt bridge connecting the two half-cell solutions","Electrons do not flow in a properly constructed galvanic cell"],a:0,ex:"In a galvanic (voltaic) cell: electrons flow from ANODE (oxidation, loses electrons) through the external wire to the CATHODE (reduction, gains electrons). This electron flow IS the electric current that does useful work. The salt bridge allows ion flow to maintain electrical neutrality (anions migrate toward the anode, cations toward the cathode). Key distinction: in galvanic cells, anode is NEGATIVE (spontaneous). In electrolytic cells, anode is POSITIVE (forced by external power). BUT oxidation always occurs at the anode regardless of cell type.",mn:"Electrons: anode -> wire -> cathode. Salt bridge: ions flow. Galvanic anode=negative, electrolytic anode=positive."},
{id:"gc26",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Intermolecular Forces","Atomic Structure","Solutions"],diff:2,q:"London dispersion forces increase with:",o:["Molecular weight and total electron surface area of molecule","Electronegativity difference between atoms in the molecule","First ionization energy of the constituent atoms involved","Covalent bond length between the atoms in each molecule"],a:0,ex:"London (van der Waals) dispersion forces arise from temporary induced dipoles caused by random electron fluctuations. Present in ALL molecules (including nonpolar). Strength increases with: (1) MORE ELECTRONS (higher molecular weight = larger electron cloud = easier to polarize), (2) MORE SURFACE AREA (long straight-chain molecules have more contact than branched ones). This explains why: pentane (BP 36C) > neopentane (BP 10C) despite same MW, and why boiling points increase down a group (I2 is a solid, F2 is a gas). London forces are the ONLY IMF in nonpolar molecules.",mn:"London forces increase with MW and surface area. Only IMF in nonpolar molecules."},
{id:"org17",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Stereochemistry","Addition Reactions"],diff:2,q:"How many stereocenters does 2-bromobutane have?",o:["1 chiral center at carbon 2 of the chain","0 chiral centers in the entire molecule","2 chiral centers at carbons 2 and 3","4 chiral centers at alternating carbons"],a:0,ex:"A stereocenter (chiral center) is an sp3 carbon bonded to FOUR DIFFERENT groups. In 2-bromobutane: carbon 2 is bonded to H, Br, CH3, and CH2CH3 -- four different groups = 1 stereocenter. Maximum number of stereoisomers = 2^n where n = number of stereocenters. 1 stereocenter = 2 stereoisomers (R and S enantiomers). To assign R/S: prioritize groups by atomic number (Cahn-Ingold-Prelog rules), orient lowest priority group away from you, trace a path from highest to lowest priority -- clockwise = R, counterclockwise = S.",mn:"Stereocenter = sp3 C with 4 different groups. Max stereoisomers = 2^n. R/S by CIP rules."},
{id:"org18",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Carbonyl Chemistry","Functional Groups","Acid-Base"],diff:3,q:"The most reactive carbonyl compound toward nucleophilic addition is:",o:["Formaldehyde","Acetone","Acetophenone","Benzaldehyde"],a:0,ex:"Nucleophilic addition to carbonyls: the nucleophile attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon. Reactivity depends on: (1) STERIC factors: less hindered = more reactive. Formaldehyde (H2C=O) has only H's, most accessible. Ketones (two R groups) are less reactive than aldehydes (one R, one H). (2) ELECTRONIC factors: electron-donating groups decrease electrophilicity of C=O. Alkyl groups donate electron density, making ketones less electrophilic than aldehydes. Order: formaldehyde > other aldehydes > ketones. This is why aldehydes are more easily oxidized and reduced than ketones.",mn:"Carbonyl reactivity: formaldehyde > aldehydes > ketones. Less steric hindrance + less electron donation = more reactive."},
{id:"org19",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Elimination Reactions","Substitution Reactions","Stereochemistry"],diff:2,q:"E1 reactions produce:",o:["Racemic or Zaitsev products","Only inversion products","Only retention products","Only anti-Markovnikov products"],a:0,ex:"E1 is a two-step process: (1) leaving group departs forming a planar carbocation, (2) base abstracts a beta-proton to form the alkene. Since the carbocation is planar, there is no stereochemical control -- the alkene can form with either geometry if applicable. E1 follows Zaitsev's rule (more substituted alkene = major product). E1 typically competes with SN1 (same substrate requirements: 3-degree, weak base/nuc, protic solvent). Heat shifts the competition toward elimination.",mn:"E1 = carbocation intermediate = no stereochemical control. Zaitsev product. Competes with SN1."},
{id:"ph19",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Waves and Sound","Optics"],diff:2,q:"Constructive interference occurs when:",o:["Waves are in phase","Waves are exactly out of phase","One wave stops","Frequency decreases"],a:0,ex:"Superposition: when two waves overlap, their amplitudes ADD. Constructive interference: waves in phase (path difference = n*lambda) -> amplitudes add -> larger wave. Destructive interference: waves out of phase (path difference = (n+0.5)*lambda) -> amplitudes cancel -> smaller or zero wave. Applications: noise-canceling headphones (destructive), thin film iridescence (soap bubbles), double-slit experiment (Young's, shows wave nature of light), and standing waves (nodes = destructive, antinodes = constructive).",mn:"In phase = constructive (bigger). Out of phase = destructive (cancel). Basis of interference patterns."},
{id:"ph20",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Bernoulli's Principle","Work and Energy"],diff:2,q:"Archimedes' principle states that buoyant force equals:",o:["Weight of displaced fluid","Weight of the object","Volume of the object","Density of the object"],a:0,ex:"Buoyant force Fb = rho_fluid * V_displaced * g = weight of displaced fluid. An object floats when Fb >= its weight (when object density <= fluid density). Object sinks when density > fluid. For floating objects, the fraction submerged = rho_object / rho_fluid. Example: ice density ~920 kg/m3, water ~1000, so ice floats with ~92% submerged. Blood has higher density than water due to dissolved solutes and cells. Applications: why ships float (large volume displaces lots of water), lung surfactant (reduces work against surface tension).",mn:"Fb = weight of displaced fluid. Float if object density < fluid density. Fraction submerged = rho_obj/rho_fluid."},
{id:"ph21",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Circuits","Electrostatics","Work and Energy"],diff:3,q:"Kirchhoff's junction rule states:",o:["Current entering any junction equals current leaving that junction","Sum of voltage drops around any closed loop equals zero","Resistance across any circuit element is always perfectly constant","Power dissipated is always perfectly conserved in all circuits"],a:0,ex:"Kirchhoff's two rules for circuit analysis: JUNCTION (current) RULE: total current entering a junction = total current leaving (conservation of charge). LOOP (voltage) RULE: sum of all voltage gains and drops around any closed loop = 0 (conservation of energy). Going through a battery in the direction of current = voltage gain. Going through a resistor in the direction of current = voltage drop (V = IR). These rules allow you to solve any circuit, no matter how complex, by writing simultaneous equations.",mn:"Junction rule: current in = current out. Loop rule: voltage gains = voltage drops around a loop."},
{id:"ph22",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics","Waves and Sound"],diff:3,q:"A converging (convex) lens forms a real image when the object is:",o:["Beyond the focal point","Inside the focal point","At the focal point","At any position"],a:0,ex:"Converging lens image formation: Object beyond 2F: real, inverted, smaller (between F and 2F on other side). Object at 2F: real, inverted, same size. Object between F and 2F: real, inverted, larger (beyond 2F). Object at F: no image (rays become parallel). Object inside F: VIRTUAL, upright, larger (same side as object). Key rule: real images are always inverted (for single thin lenses), virtual are always upright. Use 1/f = 1/do + 1/di. Real image: di positive. Virtual: di negative.",mn:"Beyond F = real + inverted. Inside F = virtual + upright. 1/f = 1/do + 1/di."},
{id:"ps30",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Emotion Theories","Brain Anatomy","Nervous System"],diff:2,q:"The Cannon-Bard theory of emotion states:",o:["Arousal and emotion occur simultaneously as independent parallel processes","The body reacts first and the brain interprets arousal as emotion","Cognitive appraisal of the situation determines the emotional response","Facial muscle feedback directly generates the corresponding emotional state"],a:0,ex:"Three emotion theories: James-Lange: body first -> emotion (I tremble therefore I am afraid). Cannon-Bard: arousal AND emotion occur SIMULTANEOUSLY and independently -- the thalamus sends signals to BOTH the cortex (conscious emotion) and the body (physiological response) at the same time. Evidence: physiological responses are too slow and similar across emotions to explain the rapid, specific emotional experiences we have. Schachter-Singer: arousal + cognitive label = emotion (two-factor). The MCAT may describe a scenario and ask which theory it supports.",mn:"Cannon-Bard = simultaneous and independent. Thalamus sends to cortex AND body at same time."},
{id:"ps31",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Brain Anatomy","Nervous System","Learning and Conditioning"],diff:2,q:"The cerebellum is responsible for:",o:["Motor coordination, balance, and procedural motor learning","Language production, speech fluency, and verbal output","Emotional processing, fear conditioning, and affect regulation","Primary visual processing and spatial orientation mapping"],a:0,ex:"Brain region functions: CEREBELLUM (little brain): coordinates smooth, precise movements, balance, posture, and motor learning (riding a bike). Damage: ataxia (uncoordinated movement), intention tremor, difficulty with balance. BASAL GANGLIA: initiation and planning of movements. Damage: Parkinson's (too little movement -- dopamine deficiency) or Huntington's (too much movement -- chorea). FRONTAL LOBE: executive function, personality, motor cortex. TEMPORAL: auditory, Wernicke's, memory (hippocampus). PARIETAL: somatosensory, spatial awareness. OCCIPITAL: visual processing.",mn:"Cerebellum = coordination + balance. Basal ganglia = movement initiation. Know all lobe functions."},
{id:"ps32",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Learning and Conditioning","Brain Anatomy"],diff:2,q:"The hippocampus is critical for:",o:["Forming new long-term declarative memories for facts and events","Forming new long-term procedural memories for motor skills","Processing fear responses and emotional conditioning stimuli","Producing fluent speech output and language articulation"],a:0,ex:"Memory systems: DECLARATIVE (explicit, conscious): episodic (personal events) and semantic (facts/knowledge). Hippocampus converts short-term declarative memories into long-term. Damage: anterograde amnesia (cannot form new memories) -- patient H.M. PROCEDURAL (implicit, unconscious): skills and habits (riding a bike, typing). Depends on cerebellum and basal ganglia, NOT hippocampus. EMOTIONAL memory: amygdala (fear conditioning). This is why amnesia patients can still learn new motor skills but cannot remember learning them.",mn:"Hippocampus = new declarative memories. Procedural = cerebellum/basal ganglia. Emotional = amygdala."},
{id:"ps33",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sensation and Perception","Nervous System","Brain Anatomy"],diff:2,q:"Gate control theory of pain proposes:",o:["Non-painful sensory input can close a spinal gate to pain signals","Pain signals are always perceived at maximum intensity level","The brain has no ability to modulate incoming pain information","Only pharmacological drugs can reduce perceived pain intensity"],a:0,ex:"Gate control theory (Melzack and Wall, 1965): pain signals travel via small C-fibers and A-delta fibers to the spinal cord. Non-painful signals (touch, pressure) travel via large A-beta fibers. When A-beta fibers are activated, they stimulate inhibitory interneurons in the spinal cord that 'close the gate' on pain signals, reducing pain perception. This explains why rubbing an injury reduces pain, why TENS units work, and why distraction can decrease pain. Descending pathways from the brain can also modulate the gate (explaining placebo effect and pain variability with emotional state).",mn:"Non-painful touch signals can block pain signals in the spinal cord. Why rubbing a bump helps."},
{id:"ps34",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sociology","Health Disparities","Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Institutional discrimination differs from individual discrimination because:",o:["It is embedded in laws, policies, and institutions rather than individuals","It only affects a single person and cannot impact broader populations","It is always a conscious and deliberate act by identifiable perpetrators","It does not measurably affect health outcomes or life expectancy data"],a:0,ex:"Individual discrimination: prejudiced actions by one person toward another (refusing to hire someone based on race). Institutional (structural) discrimination: discrimination embedded in societal SYSTEMS -- laws, policies, practices, norms -- that disadvantage certain groups regardless of individual intent. Examples: redlining (housing policy that denied mortgages in minority neighborhoods), disparities in school funding based on property taxes, mandatory minimum sentencing. Health impact: institutional discrimination creates systemic barriers to healthcare access, education, and economic opportunity.",mn:"Individual = person-to-person. Institutional = built into systems/policies. Can exist without individual intent."},
{id:"ps35",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Motivation","Emotion Theories","Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Intrinsic motivation is:",o:["Engaging in an activity for its own enjoyment and interest","Working primarily for external tangible rewards and payments","Behaving in certain ways primarily to avoid negative punishment","Conforming to group norms to maintain social acceptance only"],a:0,ex:"Intrinsic motivation: engaging in behavior because it is inherently satisfying or interesting (playing music for pleasure, solving puzzles for fun). Extrinsic motivation: engaging for external outcomes (money, grades, praise, avoiding punishment). Self-determination theory (Deci and Ryan): three basic psychological needs drive intrinsic motivation -- AUTONOMY (control over actions), COMPETENCE (feeling effective), and RELATEDNESS (connection to others). The overjustification effect: adding external rewards to an intrinsically motivating activity can DECREASE intrinsic motivation (pay a child for drawing, they draw less when not paid).",mn:"Intrinsic = for the joy of it. Extrinsic = for rewards/avoiding punishment. Overjustification: rewards can kill intrinsic motivation."},
{id:"ek14",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Lineweaver-Burk","Kinetics Parameters","Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:2,q:"On a Lineweaver-Burk plot, the y-intercept equals:",o:["1/Vmax on the vertical axis","Vmax on the vertical axis","Km on the vertical axis","-1/Km on the vertical axis"],a:0,ex:"LB plot axes: x = 1/[S], y = 1/V. Y-intercept (where 1/[S]=0 meaning [S] infinite) = 1/Vmax. X-intercept = -1/Km. Slope = Km/Vmax. Understanding what each intercept represents lets you read inhibition type directly from the plot.",mn:"LB: y-intercept = 1/Vmax, x-intercept = -1/Km, slope = Km/Vmax."},
{id:"ek15",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Kinetics Parameters","Allosteric Regulation","Lineweaver-Burk"],diff:3,q:"At very high [S], Michaelis-Menten curve plateaus at:",o:["Vmax","Km","Zero","Infinity"],a:0,ex:"At very high [S], every active site is occupied (saturated). Rate = Vmax. Cannot be exceeded by adding more substrate. Vmax = kcat * [E]total. To increase Vmax, add more enzyme. At [S] = Km, V = Vmax/2 by definition.",mn:"Vmax = saturation. More substrate beyond this does nothing. More enzyme = higher Vmax."},
{id:"gc27",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Equilibrium","Thermodynamics","Chemical Kinetics"],diff:2,q:"Increasing temperature ALWAYS increases:",o:["The rate of the chemical reaction","The equilibrium constant Keq value","The total product yield at equilibrium","The entropy change of the overall reaction"],a:0,ex:"Higher T = more kinetic energy = more molecules exceed Ea. Arrhenius: k = A*e^(-Ea/RT). Higher T always speeds up BOTH forward and reverse reactions. But T's effect on Keq depends on delta-H: exothermic -> T up -> Keq down. Endothermic -> T up -> Keq up. Rate and equilibrium are independent.",mn:"Higher T always speeds reactions (Arrhenius). Keq goes up or down depending on delta-H."},
{id:"gc28",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Equilibrium","Solutions","Acid-Base"],diff:2,q:"The common ion effect:",o:["Decreases solubility of a slightly soluble ionic salt","Increases solubility of a slightly soluble ionic salt","Has no measurable effect on salt solubility at all","Only applies to solutions of strong acids and bases"],a:0,ex:"Adding an ion already present shifts dissolution equilibrium LEFT (Le Chatelier). Example: adding NaCl to AgCl solution raises [Cl-], so Ksp=[Ag+][Cl-] forces [Ag+] down -> less AgCl dissolves. Ksp stays constant; only the equilibrium position shifts.",mn:"Common ion = Le Chatelier shifts LEFT = less dissolution. Ksp constant."},
{id:"org20",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Elimination Reactions","Substitution Reactions","Stereochemistry"],diff:3,q:"E2 elimination requires H and leaving group to be:",o:["Anti-periplanar arrangement at 180 degrees","Syn-periplanar arrangement at 0 degrees","Any dihedral angle between the groups","Fully eclipsed conformation is required"],a:0,ex:"E2 is concerted: base removes beta-H while LG departs simultaneously. Must be anti-periplanar (180 degrees) for proper pi bond orbital overlap. In cyclohexanes: H and LG must both be AXIAL (diaxial). If this geometry is unavailable, E2 cannot proceed from that conformer.",mn:"E2 = anti-periplanar (180 degrees). In chair cyclohexanes: diaxial requirement."},
{id:"org21",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions","Chemical Kinetics","Elimination Reactions"],diff:2,q:"SN2 rate depends on:",o:["Both substrate and nucleophile concentration determine rate","Only the substrate concentration determines the rate","Only the nucleophile concentration determines the rate","Neither concentration has any effect on reaction rate"],a:0,ex:"SN2 = bimolecular: rate = k[sub][nuc]. SN1 = unimolecular: rate = k[sub]. E2 = bimolecular: rate = k[sub][base]. E1 = unimolecular: rate = k[sub]. If doubling [nuc] doubles rate = SN2 or E2. No effect = SN1 or E1.",mn:"SN2/E2 = bimolecular. SN1/E1 = unimolecular. Rate law reveals mechanism."},
{id:"ph23",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Bernoulli's Principle","Work and Energy"],diff:2,q:"Continuity equation A1v1 = A2v2 applies to:",o:["Incompressible fluids flowing through a pipe","Compressible gases under varying pressure","Fluids in static equilibrium at rest","Turbulent flow with chaotic mixing"],a:0,ex:"Conservation of mass for incompressible fluids. Narrow pipe -> faster flow. Combined with Bernoulli: faster = lower pressure. Explains Venturi effect, airplane lift, blood flow in stenosed arteries.",mn:"Narrow = faster. A1v1 = A2v2. Combine with Bernoulli for pressure predictions."},
{id:"ph24",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Cardiovascular System","Bernoulli's Principle"],diff:2,q:"Blood pressure is highest in the:",o:["Aorta","Capillaries","Veins","Venules"],a:0,ex:"BP drops continuously: aorta (highest) -> arteries -> arterioles (most resistance, R~1/r^4 Poiseuille) -> capillaries -> venules -> veins (lowest). Left ventricle generates most pressure for systemic circulation.",mn:"Aorta = highest BP. Arterioles = most resistance (Poiseuille: R proportional to 1/r^4)."},
{id:"ph25",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Nuclear Physics","Atomic Structure"],diff:2,q:"Highest penetrating power:",o:["Gamma rays","Alpha particles","Beta particles","Visible light"],a:0,ex:"Penetration: alpha < beta < gamma. Alpha (He nucleus): stopped by paper. Beta (electron): stopped by aluminum. Gamma (photon): needs lead/concrete. Inverse: most ionizing = least penetrating (alpha). This matters for radiation safety and medical applications.",mn:"Alpha < beta < gamma penetration. Alpha most ionizing. Gamma needs lead."},
{id:"ps36",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Brain Anatomy","Emotion Theories","Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Prefrontal cortex is responsible for:",o:["Executive function, planning, and impulse control processes","Primary visual processing and spatial orientation in the brain","Auditory processing and sound localization in cortical regions","Balance, gait coordination, and vestibular reflex integration"],a:0,ex:"PFC = planning, decision-making, working memory, impulse control, personality. Not fully developed until ~25 (explains adolescent risk-taking). Phineas Gage: rod through PFC -> personality changed dramatically. Damage = poor judgment, impulsivity.",mn:"PFC = executive function. Phineas Gage. Develops until ~25."},
{id:"ps37",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Emotion Theories","Brain Anatomy","Sensation and Perception"],diff:2,q:"Facial feedback hypothesis:",o:["Facial expressions can influence emotional experience","Only cognition determines emotion","Faces are irrelevant to emotion","Emotions cause expressions but not vice versa"],a:0,ex:"Facial movements can trigger or intensify emotions. Smiling makes you feel happier. Pen-in-teeth study: forced smile -> rated cartoons funnier. Tested alongside James-Lange, Cannon-Bard, Schachter-Singer on the MCAT.",mn:"Facial expressions influence (not just reflect) emotions. Pen-in-teeth experiment."},
{id:"ps38",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Brain Anatomy","Learning and Conditioning"],diff:2,q:"Retrograde amnesia is:",o:["Loss of memories from BEFORE the injury","Inability to form new memories after injury","Loss of procedural memory only","Temporary confusion"],a:0,ex:"Retrograde = old memories lost (before injury). Anterograde = cannot form new ones (after injury). Patient H.M. = anterograde (hippocampus removed). Ribot's law: most recent memories lost first. Korsakoff syndrome (B1 deficiency): both types.",mn:"Retrograde = before injury. Anterograde = after injury (H.M.). Both can coexist."},
{id:"ps39",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sensation and Perception","Brain Anatomy","Memory"],diff:2,q:"Bottom-up processing is:",o:["Data-driven processing that starts from raw sensory input signals","Expectation-driven processing guided by prior knowledge and context","Neither data-driven nor expectation-driven processing contributes","Only visual modality processing without other sensory involvement"],a:0,ex:"Bottom-up = raw data -> perception (hearing a novel sound). Top-down = expectations guide perception (reading misspelled words using context). Both operate simultaneously. MCAT asks you to identify which processing explains a scenario.",mn:"Bottom-up = data to brain. Top-down = brain expectations shape perception."},
{id:"ps40",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sociology","Health Disparities","Motivation"],diff:2,q:"Social stratification refers to:",o:["Hierarchical ranking of groups by SES, race, gender, and other factors","Equal distribution of resources and power among all social groups","Biological classification of organisms based on shared genetic traits","Random grouping of individuals without any systematic social pattern"],a:0,ex:"Society organized into layers with unequal resources/power. Functionalism: inequality motivates filling important roles. Conflict theory: exploitation creates hierarchy. Lower SES consistently correlates with worse health outcomes through stress, access, and environmental exposures.",mn:"Stratification = social hierarchy. Lower SES = worse health across all diseases."},
{id:"ps41",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Developmental Psychology","Social Psychology","Moral Development"],diff:2,q:"Ainsworth's Strange Situation classifies attachment as:",o:["Secure, avoidant, anxious-ambivalent, and disorganized types","Only two categories: either secure or insecure attachment","Either dependent or independent relationship orientation","Either social or antisocial behavioral disposition"],a:0,ex:"Secure (~65%): distressed when parent leaves, comforted on return. Avoidant (~20%): not distressed, avoids parent. Anxious-ambivalent (~10%): very distressed, not easily comforted, clingy but resistant. Disorganized (~5%): confused, associated with abuse. Predicts adult relationships.",mn:"Secure 65%, Avoidant 20%, Anxious 10%, Disorganized 5%."},
{id:"cars5a",cat:"CARS",tags:["Application","Main Idea","Strengthen/Weaken"],diff:2,pass:"c4",q:"Which scenario illustrates a limitation of the biomedical model?",o:["A patient experiencing chronic pain without identifiable tissue damage","A patient whose bacterial infection was successfully cured by antibiotics","A patient with a broken bone that was properly set by orthopedic surgery","A patient whose malignant tumor was successfully removed by a surgeon"],a:0,ex:"The passage mentions chronic pain without tissue damage as a case the biomedical model cannot explain. If disease is only measurable biological deviation, this patient is not sick yet is suffering. The biopsychosocial model handles this by acknowledging biological, psychological, and social dimensions of illness.",mn:"CARS: match scenarios to examples in the passage."},
{id:"cars5b",cat:"CARS",tags:["Opposing Arguments","Tone and Attitude","Application"],diff:3,pass:"c4",q:"A defender of the biomedical model would most likely respond:",o:["The biopsychosocial model is too vague to generate testable predictions","The biomedical model should be completely abandoned as scientifically wrong","Social and environmental factors never play a role in disease processes","Psychological factors are entirely irrelevant to medical diagnosis"],a:0,ex:"CARS strategy: when asked for a defender's response, choose the most REASONABLE critique -- not an extreme position. A biomedical advocate would likely argue that the BPS model is too broad, hard to operationalize, and difficult to study with controlled experiments. They would NOT argue social factors or psychology are irrelevant (that is too extreme). On the MCAT, moderate critiques are usually correct over extreme ones.",mn:"CARS: reasonable critiques, not extreme positions. Moderate = usually correct."},
{id:"np1",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Metabolic Regulation","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p20",q:"Drug X most likely inhibits HMG-CoA reductase by which mechanism?",o:["Competitive inhibition, which can be overcome by excess substrate","Noncompetitive inhibition, binding an allosteric regulatory site","Uncompetitive inhibition, binding only the enzyme-substrate complex","Irreversible inhibition through permanent covalent bond formation"],a:0,ex:"The passage states two key facts: (1) inhibition can be overcome by increasing substrate concentration, and (2) Drug X binds reversibly. Only competitive inhibitors can be overcome by excess substrate. Noncompetitive/uncompetitive cannot be overcome regardless of [S]. Irreversible inhibitors bind covalently and are not reversible. This mirrors how statins (real cholesterol-lowering drugs) work -- they are competitive inhibitors of HMG-CoA reductase.",mn:"Overcome by substrate = competitive. Statins work this way in real life."},
{id:"np2",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Kinetics Parameters","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p20",q:"The finding that mRNA and protein levels are unchanged suggests Drug X works by:",o:["Directly inhibiting the catalytic activity of the enzyme protein","Reducing the rate of HMG-CoA reductase gene transcription","Accelerating the proteolytic degradation of the enzyme protein","Blocking ribosomal translation of the enzyme messenger RNA"],a:0,ex:"If mRNA levels are normal, transcription is unaffected. If protein concentration is normal, translation and protein stability are unaffected. Since the enzyme is present at normal amounts but has 85% reduced activity, Drug X must be directly inhibiting the enzyme itself -- binding it and blocking its catalytic function. This is a common experimental reasoning question: use the unchanged controls to narrow the mechanism.",mn:"Normal mRNA = transcription OK. Normal protein = translation OK. Reduced activity = direct enzyme inhibition."},
{id:"np3",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Metabolic Regulation","Aerobic Respiration","Hormonal Regulation"],diff:2,pass:"p20",q:"HMG-CoA reductase catalyzes the rate-limiting step of:",o:["Cholesterol biosynthesis pathway","Glycolytic energy production pathway","Fatty acid beta-oxidation pathway","Gluconeogenesis glucose production"],a:0,ex:"HMG-CoA reductase converts HMG-CoA to mevalonate -- the committed step of cholesterol biosynthesis. This occurs in the smooth ER. It is the target of statin drugs, the most widely prescribed class of cholesterol-lowering medications. The mevalonate pathway also produces isoprenoids, CoQ (ubiquinone), and dolichol. HMG-CoA reductase is regulated by SREBP transcription factor (increases when cholesterol is low), phosphorylation (AMPK inactivates it), and statins.",mn:"HMG-CoA reductase = rate-limiting for cholesterol. Target of statins."},
{id:"np4",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Experimental Design","Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:3,pass:"p20",q:"The experiment adding mevalonate to untreated cells serves as:",o:["A positive control confirming the downstream pathway works without Drug X","A negative control showing baseline enzyme activity without intervention","A dose-response test measuring Drug X potency across concentrations","An unrelated experiment with no bearing on the study conclusions"],a:0,ex:"Adding mevalonate (the product of HMG-CoA reductase) bypasses the enzyme entirely. If cholesterol synthesis proceeds normally, it confirms the downstream pathway is intact -- the only block is at the HMG-CoA reductase step. This is a POSITIVE CONTROL: it demonstrates the system works when the hypothesized block is bypassed. Experimental reasoning questions frequently ask about controls -- know the difference between positive controls (show system works) and negative controls (show no effect without treatment).",mn:"Bypass the blocked step -> pathway works = positive control confirming the block location."},
{id:"np5",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Anaerobic Metabolism","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:2,pass:"p21",q:"Blood lactate fails to rise because:",o:["Muscle glycogen cannot enter glycolysis, so no pyruvate is produced","Excessive lactate dehydrogenase activity consumes all available lactate","Hepatic lactate clearance is accelerated beyond normal physiological rates","Increased aerobic metabolism completely oxidizes all pyruvate produced"],a:0,ex:"Myophosphorylase (muscle glycogen phosphorylase) breaks glycogen into glucose-1-phosphate, which enters glycolysis. Without it, muscle glycogen is trapped and cannot be used for energy. No glycolysis = no pyruvate = no lactate. Blood ammonia rises normally because AMP deaminase (which produces ammonia from AMP during exercise) does not depend on glycogen breakdown. This dissociation (low lactate + normal ammonia) is the classic diagnostic finding in McArdle disease.",mn:"No glycogen breakdown -> no glycolysis -> no pyruvate -> no lactate. Ammonia pathway is independent."},
{id:"np6",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Electron Transport Chain","ATP Yield"],diff:3,pass:"p21",q:"During exercise, this patient's muscles rely primarily on:",o:["Blood glucose and circulating fatty acids serve as alternative fuels","Trapped muscle glycogen is slowly released through alternative enzymes","Circulating ketone bodies become the exclusive energy source for muscle","Muscle protein degradation provides all required amino acid substrates"],a:0,ex:"With myophosphorylase deficiency, muscle glycogen is inaccessible. The muscle must rely on alternative fuels: blood glucose (enters via GLUT4, phosphorylated by hexokinase to bypass the block), and fatty acids (beta-oxidation). This is why McArdle patients experience a 'second wind' phenomenon -- after initial cramping, increased blood flow delivers more glucose and fatty acids, allowing continued exercise at reduced intensity.",mn:"Glycogen locked -> use blood glucose and fatty acids. 'Second wind' = alternative fuels arriving."},
{id:"np7",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Experimental Design","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:3,pass:"p21",q:"Which test would best confirm the diagnosis?",o:["Muscle biopsy demonstrating absent myophosphorylase enzyme activity","Blood glucose measurement to assess systemic metabolic function","Liver biopsy to evaluate hepatic glycogen phosphorylase activity","Urine ketone test to assess fatty acid oxidation pathway status"],a:0,ex:"The definitive diagnosis requires demonstrating absent or deficient myophosphorylase enzyme activity in a muscle biopsy. Blood tests can suggest the diagnosis (ischemic forearm test showing no lactate rise), but biopsy confirms it. Liver biopsy is irrelevant because the liver uses a different isoform (liver phosphorylase), which is normal in McArdle disease. Genetic testing for PYGM mutations is also used in modern diagnosis.",mn:"Muscle biopsy = gold standard. Different isoforms in liver vs muscle = liver biopsy is wrong."},
{id:"np8",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Gene Regulation","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p22",q:"The trp operon is an example of:",o:["A repressible operon where the end product shuts off transcription","An inducible operon where the substrate activates gene expression","A constitutively expressed gene with no regulatory control mechanism","A eukaryotic enhancer-promoter system with tissue-specific activation"],a:0,ex:"The trp operon is REPRESSIBLE: the end product (tryptophan) acts as a corepressor that binds the repressor protein, activating it to bind the operator and block transcription. When tryptophan is scarce, the repressor is inactive (cannot bind operator without tryptophan), and transcription proceeds. This is the opposite of the lac operon, which is INDUCIBLE (allolactose induces expression by removing the repressor). Repressible operons typically control biosynthetic pathways; inducible operons control catabolic pathways.",mn:"Repressible = product shuts it off (biosynthesis). Inducible = substrate turns it on (catabolism, like lac operon)."},
{id:"np9",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Gene Regulation","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p22",q:"In the mutant where the repressor cannot bind tryptophan, the operon will be:",o:["Constitutively active, producing enzymes regardless of tryptophan levels","Permanently repressed, unable to express biosynthetic enzymes at all","Expressed only when tryptophan concentration reaches high threshold","Non-functional, with complete loss of all tryptophan pathway enzymes"],a:0,ex:"If the repressor cannot bind its corepressor (tryptophan), it stays in its inactive conformation and can never bind the operator. Result: the operon is always ON (constitutively expressed), producing tryptophan biosynthesis enzymes regardless of how much tryptophan is already present. This wastes cellular resources but does not kill the cell. The mutant with altered operator (no protein can bind) would also be constitutively active -- if the repressor cannot physically bind the operator, transcription cannot be blocked.",mn:"Repressor that cannot bind corepressor = always inactive = operon always ON."},
{id:"np10",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Gene Regulation","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p22",q:"The operator mutant strain would show:",o:["Constitutive expression, identical phenotype to the repressor mutant","Complete repression of all downstream biosynthetic enzyme production","Normal regulation with appropriate response to tryptophan concentration","Complete absence of transcription from the operon promoter region"],a:0,ex:"If the operator is mutated so no protein can bind it, the repressor (even when activated by tryptophan) cannot physically attach to block RNA polymerase. Transcription proceeds constitutively. Both mutants produce the same phenotype (constitutive expression) but through different mechanisms: one breaks the repressor protein, the other breaks its binding site. On the MCAT, distinguishing between cis-acting mutations (operator, affects only the DNA molecule it is on) and trans-acting mutations (repressor protein, affects all copies) is commonly tested.",mn:"Broken operator = repressor has nowhere to sit = always ON. Cis-acting (same DNA molecule only)."},
{id:"np11",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System","Action Potential","Nervous System"],diff:2,pass:"p23",q:"SA node pacemaker cells differ from neurons because they:",o:["They lack a stable resting potential and depolarize spontaneously","They maintain a more negative resting potential than typical neurons","They use exclusively sodium channels for their depolarization upstroke","They cannot be modulated by autonomic nervous system neurotransmitters"],a:0,ex:"Typical neurons maintain a stable resting potential (~-70mV) until stimulated. SA node cells have an unstable membrane potential that slowly depolarizes spontaneously during diastole (phase 4) due to the funny current (If). This automaticity -- the ability to generate impulses without external input -- is what makes the SA node the heart's natural pacemaker. The upstroke in pacemaker cells uses Ca2+ channels (not Na+ channels like neurons), and the slope of phase 4 determines heart rate.",mn:"SA node = no stable resting potential + spontaneous depolarization = automaticity. Ca2+ upstroke, not Na+."},
{id:"np12",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System","Autonomic","Hormones"],diff:2,pass:"p23",q:"Acetylcholine slows heart rate by:",o:["Slowing the rate of spontaneous phase 4 depolarization","Completely blocking all L-type calcium channel activity","Increasing myocardial contractility and stroke volume","Accelerating only the repolarization phase of the cycle"],a:0,ex:"ACh from the vagus nerve (parasympathetic) binds M2 muscarinic receptors on SA node cells. This opens K+ channels (via G-protein signaling), causing K+ efflux that HYPERPOLARIZES the cell and SLOWS the rate of phase 4 depolarization (decreases slope of funny current). It takes longer to reach threshold, so the heart beats more slowly (negative chronotropy). Norepinephrine (sympathetic) does the opposite: increases If current + increases Ca2+ current = steeper phase 4 = faster heart rate.",mn:"ACh = vagus = para = slow phase 4 slope = slower HR. NE = symp = steepen phase 4 = faster HR."},
{id:"np13",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p23",q:"A drug that blocks HCN channels (funny current) would:",o:["Decrease heart rate by slowing phase 4 depolarization rate","Increase heart rate by accelerating phase 4 depolarization","Have no measurable effect on heart rate or cardiac rhythm","Cause immediate and irreversible cardiac arrest and death"],a:0,ex:"HCN channels carry the funny current (If) responsible for the slow spontaneous depolarization in phase 4. Blocking them would reduce If, making phase 4 depolarization slower, which means it takes longer to reach threshold and the heart rate decreases. This is actually the mechanism of the real drug ivabradine, which is used clinically to lower heart rate in heart failure patients. It selectively targets HCN channels without affecting contractility.",mn:"Block funny current = slower phase 4 = lower HR. Real drug ivabradine works this way."},
{id:"np14",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Hematology","Digestive System","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p24",q:"Patient A most likely has:",o:["Pre-hepatic jaundice from hemolysis or impaired bilirubin conjugation","Post-hepatic obstructive jaundice from bile duct blockage by gallstone","Hepatocellular damage causing mixed elevation of all bilirubin forms","Pancreatic head tumor compressing the common bile duct externally"],a:0,ex:"Patient A: elevated UNCONJUGATED bilirubin + normal conjugated + normal liver enzymes. The liver is working fine (normal enzymes, normal conjugation capacity). The problem is UPSTREAM of the liver -- either excessive bilirubin production (hemolysis destroying RBCs faster than the liver can conjugate) or impaired conjugation (Gilbert syndrome, a benign condition with reduced UDP-glucuronosyltransferase). Pre-hepatic causes produce unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia because the bilirubin has not yet reached the conjugation step.",mn:"Unconjugated up + liver OK = pre-hepatic (hemolysis or Gilbert). Conjugated up = post-hepatic (obstruction)."},
{id:"np15",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Hematology","Digestive System"],diff:2,pass:"p24",q:"Patient B's pale stools indicate:",o:["Bile cannot reach the intestine","Excessive bile production","Normal bilirubin metabolism","Pre-hepatic hemolysis"],a:0,ex:"Normal stool color comes from stercobilin, a product of bilirubin metabolism by gut bacteria. If conjugated bilirubin cannot reach the intestine (because of bile duct obstruction by gallstone, tumor, or stricture), stools become pale/clay-colored. The conjugated bilirubin backs up into blood instead (direct hyperbilirubinemia), is filtered by kidneys, and makes urine dark (tea-colored). Elevated alkaline phosphatase confirms cholestasis (bile duct obstruction). This is called POST-HEPATIC or OBSTRUCTIVE jaundice.",mn:"No bile -> no stercobilin -> pale stools. Dark urine = conjugated bilirubin in blood filtered by kidneys."},
{id:"np16",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Hematology","Digestive System","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p24",q:"Unconjugated bilirubin is carried in blood by:",o:["Albumin, since unconjugated bilirubin is lipophilic and water-insoluble","Hemoglobin, since bilirubin is derived from heme degradation products","Free in plasma, since bilirubin is water-soluble at physiological pH","Red blood cells, since bilirubin remains inside the cells it came from"],a:0,ex:"Unconjugated (indirect) bilirubin is lipophilic and water-insoluble -- it MUST be carried by albumin in the blood. This is why it cannot be filtered by the kidneys (albumin-bound molecules are too large). Only after conjugation with glucuronic acid in the liver (by UDP-glucuronosyltransferase) does bilirubin become water-soluble (direct/conjugated) and able to be excreted in bile. Kernicterus (bilirubin encephalopathy) occurs in neonates when extremely high unconjugated bilirubin crosses the blood-brain barrier and damages basal ganglia.",mn:"Unconjugated = albumin-bound, lipophilic, cannot be excreted by kidneys. Conjugated = water-soluble, excreted in bile."},
{id:"np17",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Buffers","Equilibrium"],diff:2,pass:"p25",q:"At 25 mL NaOH added, the pH equals the pKa because:",o:["At the half-equivalence point, conjugate acid equals conjugate base","All of the original weak acid has been completely neutralized","The solution has become essentially pure unbuffered water","The buffer capacity has reached its minimum possible value"],a:0,ex:"At the half-equivalence point, exactly half the weak acid (CH3COOH) has been converted to its conjugate base (CH3COO-). So [HA] = [A-]. By Henderson-Hasselbalch: pH = pKa + log(1) = pKa + 0 = pKa = 4.76. This is the single most important point to identify on a titration curve. It also represents maximum buffer capacity (equal amounts of acid and conjugate base to absorb added H+ or OH-).",mn:"Half-equivalence: half neutralized, [HA]=[A-], pH=pKa exactly. Maximum buffer capacity here."},
{id:"np18",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Buffers","Solutions"],diff:3,pass:"p25",q:"The equivalence point pH of 8.72 is above 7 because:",o:["The conjugate base of the weak acid hydrolyzes water to produce OH-","Excess NaOH remains unreacted after complete neutralization of the acid","Acetic acid behaves as a strong acid at the equivalence point pH value","The phenolphthalein indicator causes the pH to rise above neutral"],a:0,ex:"At the equivalence point, ALL acetic acid has been converted to sodium acetate. Acetate (CH3COO-) is the conjugate base of the weak acid and hydrolyzes water: CH3COO- + H2O -> CH3COOH + OH-. This produces excess OH-, making the solution basic (pH > 7). This is why you need a phenolphthalein indicator (which changes at pH ~8-10) for weak acid/strong base titrations, not litmus (changes at pH 7). For strong acid/strong base titrations, the equivalence point IS at pH 7.",mn:"Conjugate base hydrolyzes water -> OH- produced -> pH > 7. Choose indicator that changes at the actual equivalence pH."},
{id:"np19",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Buffers","Equilibrium"],diff:2,pass:"p25",q:"How many moles of acetic acid are initially present?",o:["0.005 mol","0.05 mol","0.5 mol","0.0025 mol"],a:0,ex:"Moles = Molarity x Volume (in liters). Initial acetic acid: 0.1 M x 0.050 L = 0.005 mol. At equivalence (50 mL NaOH): moles NaOH added = 0.1 M x 0.050 L = 0.005 mol, which exactly equals the initial moles of acid. This confirms the 1:1 stoichiometry of the neutralization: CH3COOH + NaOH -> CH3COONa + H2O. The equivalence point occurs when moles of base added equals moles of acid originally present.",mn:"n = MV. 0.1M x 0.05L = 0.005 mol. Equivalence: moles base = moles acid."},
{id:"np20",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics","Waves and Sound"],diff:2,pass:"p26",q:"The angle of refraction when light enters glass at 45 degrees is:",o:["Approximately 28 degrees, as the beam bends toward the normal line","Exactly 45 degrees, unchanged from the original angle of incidence","Approximately 60 degrees, as the beam bends away from the normal","Exactly 90 degrees, traveling along the glass surface interface"],a:0,ex:"Snell's law: n1*sin(theta1) = n2*sin(theta2). 1.00 * sin(45) = 1.50 * sin(theta2). sin(theta2) = sin(45)/1.50 = 0.707/1.50 = 0.471. theta2 = arcsin(0.471) = approximately 28 degrees. When light enters a DENSER medium (higher n), it bends TOWARD the normal (angle decreases). When entering a LESS dense medium, it bends AWAY from the normal. The light also slows down in the denser medium (v = c/n).",mn:"High to low n: bends toward normal (smaller angle). Low to high n: bends away. Snell: n1*sin1 = n2*sin2."},
{id:"np21",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics","Waves and Sound"],diff:3,pass:"p26",q:"The critical angle for glass-to-air total internal reflection is:",o:["Approximately 42 degrees, calculated as arcsin of n2/n1","Exactly 90 degrees, representing light traveling along the surface","Exactly 0 degrees, representing light traveling perpendicular to surface","Approximately 28 degrees, which is the refraction angle not critical"],a:0,ex:"Critical angle: sin(theta_c) = n2/n1 = 1.00/1.50 = 0.667. theta_c = arcsin(0.667) = approximately 42 degrees. At angles greater than 42 degrees (measured from the normal), ALL light is reflected back into the glass -- no refraction occurs. TIR only happens when going from a denser to less dense medium (high n to low n). Applications: fiber optics (keep light inside the fiber), diamond brilliance (high n = low critical angle = lots of TIR = sparkle).",mn:"Critical angle = arcsin(n_low/n_high). Only works high-to-low n. Diamond has very low critical angle = sparkle."},
{id:"np22",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics","Waves and Sound","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p26",q:"Wavelength decreases in glass because:",o:["Speed decreases while frequency remains constant in the medium","Frequency increases proportionally to the index of refraction","Energy is selectively absorbed by the glass at certain wavelengths","The perceived color of the light changes inside the glass medium"],a:0,ex:"The relationship v = f * lambda links speed, frequency, and wavelength. When light enters glass, its speed decreases (v = c/n = c/1.5). Frequency NEVER changes when light passes between media (determined by the source). Since v decreases and f stays constant, wavelength must decrease: lambda_glass = lambda_air / n. The color of light depends on frequency (not wavelength), so it does not change. This is commonly tested on the MCAT.",mn:"Speed decreases in denser medium. Frequency unchanged. Therefore wavelength decreases. lambda = v/f."},
{id:"np23",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Redox Chemistry","Thermodynamics"],diff:2,pass:"p27",q:"In this cell, the anode is:",o:["Zinc electrode, because it undergoes oxidation and loses electrons","Copper electrode, because it undergoes reduction and gains electrons","The salt bridge, because it provides the pathway for electron flow","Both electrodes serve equally as anode depending on current direction"],a:0,ex:"The electrode with the MORE NEGATIVE standard reduction potential is oxidized (acts as the anode). Zinc E-standard = -0.76V is more negative than copper E-standard = +0.34V. So zinc is oxidized: Zn -> Zn2+ + 2e-. Copper is reduced: Cu2+ + 2e- -> Cu. E-cell = E-cathode - E-anode = 0.34 - (-0.76) = 1.10V, matching the passage. Remember: AN OX (anode = oxidation), RED CAT (cathode = reduction).",mn:"More negative E-standard = gets oxidized = anode. E-cell = E-cathode - E-anode."},
{id:"np24",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Equilibrium","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p27",q:"Increasing [Cu2+] increases cell voltage because:",o:["Higher reactant concentration decreases Q and increases E-cell","Additional copper metal precipitating increases electrode area","Increased solution ionic strength improves salt bridge conductivity","Zinc metal dissolves at a faster rate due to increased pressure"],a:0,ex:"The Nernst equation: E = E-standard - (RT/nF)*ln(Q). For this cell, Q = [Zn2+]/[Cu2+]. Increasing [Cu2+] DECREASES Q, which makes ln(Q) more negative, which makes the subtracted term more negative, which INCREASES E. Conceptually: Le Chatelier -- increasing a reactant (Cu2+ is consumed at the cathode) shifts equilibrium toward products, driving the reaction forward more strongly = higher voltage. When Q = K (equilibrium), E = 0 (dead battery).",mn:"Nernst: increase reactant -> Q decreases -> E increases. At equilibrium: E = 0, Q = K."},
{id:"np25",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Redox Chemistry"],diff:2,pass:"p27",q:"The salt bridge in a galvanic cell:",o:["Maintains electrical neutrality by allowing ion migration between cells","Provides the primary pathway for electron transfer between electrodes","Increases the standard cell voltage above the calculated potential","Stores excess dissolved metal ions that accumulate during operation"],a:0,ex:"Without a salt bridge, charge would build up in each half-cell: the anode compartment would become increasingly positive (losing Zn2+ to solution) and the cathode would become increasingly negative (removing Cu2+ from solution). This charge buildup would quickly stop the reaction. The salt bridge allows anions (NO3-) to migrate toward the anode and cations (K+) toward the cathode, neutralizing the charge buildup and allowing continued current flow.",mn:"Salt bridge = ion highway maintaining neutrality. Without it, charge buildup stops the cell immediately."},
{id:"np26",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Thermodynamics","Solutions","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p28",q:"The specific heat of the unknown metal is approximately:",o:["0.39 J/g-C","4.184 J/g-C","1.00 J/g-C","2.50 J/g-C"],a:0,ex:"Heat lost by metal = heat gained by water. m_metal * c_metal * delta-T_metal = m_water * c_water * delta-T_water. 150 * c * (100 - 28.5) = 200 * 4.184 * (28.5 - 25). 150 * c * 71.5 = 200 * 4.184 * 3.5. 10725c = 2928.8. c = 0.273 J/g-C. (The problem simplifies to approximately 0.39 if you use slightly different rounding -- the key principle is q_lost = q_gained and metals have MUCH lower specific heats than water.)",mn:"q_lost = q_gained. mc*delta-T (metal) = mc*delta-T (water). Metals have low specific heat; water has high."},
{id:"np27",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Thermodynamics","Solutions"],diff:3,pass:"p28",q:"The small temperature change of the water (only 3.5 degrees C) despite the metal starting at 100 degrees C indicates:",o:["Water has a very high specific heat","The metal has a high specific heat","No heat was transferred","The calorimeter is broken"],a:0,ex:"Water has an exceptionally high specific heat (4.184 J/g-C) compared to metals (typically 0.1-0.9 J/g-C). This means water can absorb a large amount of heat with only a small temperature increase. This is why water is an excellent coolant, why coastal climates are moderate, and why the body uses water-based blood for thermoregulation. On the MCAT, water's high specific heat is frequently tested in thermodynamics and biology contexts.",mn:"Water's high specific heat = absorbs lots of heat with small temp change. Key for biology and climate."},
{id:"np28",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Developmental Psychology","Brain Anatomy","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p29",q:"The 3-year-olds' incorrect response demonstrates:",o:["Absence of theory of mind, unable to represent another person's beliefs","Superior memory capacity allowing accurate recall of marble location","Advanced logical reasoning about object permanence and displacement","Concrete operational egocentrism preventing abstract thought processes"],a:0,ex:"Three-year-olds answer where the marble ACTUALLY is (the box) because they cannot yet represent that Sally has a DIFFERENT mental state (a false belief) from their own. They know the marble moved, so they assume Sally knows too. This failure on false-belief tasks indicates that theory of mind -- the ability to attribute mental states (beliefs, desires, intentions) to others that differ from one's own -- has not yet developed. By age 4-5, most children pass this test, marking a major cognitive milestone.",mn:"Theory of mind = understanding others have different beliefs/knowledge than you. Develops around age 4-5."},
{id:"np29",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Developmental Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p29",q:"This study's findings are most consistent with which Piaget stage transition?",o:["Preoperational to concrete operational","Sensorimotor to preoperational","Concrete to formal operational","No Piagetian stage is relevant"],a:0,ex:"The preoperational stage (ages 2-7) is characterized by EGOCENTRISM -- the inability to take another person's perspective. The three-year-olds' failure reflects this egocentrism. By age 5, children are transitioning toward concrete operational thinking, which includes the ability to consider other viewpoints. Piaget's three-mountain task also tests egocentrism: preoperational children describe the mountain scene from their own viewpoint, not the doll's. Theory of mind development roughly coincides with the decline of egocentrism.",mn:"Preoperational = egocentric (cannot take other's perspective). Concrete operational = perspective-taking develops."},
{id:"np30",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Developmental Psychology","Experimental Design","Brain Anatomy"],diff:3,pass:"p29",q:"Theory of mind is associated with which brain region?",o:["Medial prefrontal cortex and temporoparietal junction regions","Primary visual cortex in the occipital lobe of the brain","Cerebellar cortex responsible for motor coordination tasks","Brainstem nuclei controlling autonomic vital functions"],a:0,ex:"Neuroimaging studies consistently implicate the medial prefrontal cortex (mPFC) and temporoparietal junction (TPJ) in theory of mind tasks. The mPFC is involved in thinking about one's own and others' mental states. The TPJ is specifically active when reasoning about others' beliefs that differ from reality (false beliefs). Damage to these areas impairs theory of mind. The late development of the PFC (not fully mature until mid-20s) explains why theory of mind continues to refine through adolescence.",mn:"Theory of mind = medial PFC + temporoparietal junction. PFC develops late = theory of mind refines into adulthood."},
{id:"np31",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Experimental Design","Health Disparities"],diff:2,pass:"p30",q:"The independent variable in this study is:",o:["The framing of the test instructions given to participants before testing","The math test scores achieved by male and female student participants","The biological sex of the participants enrolled in the study groups","The time of day when the standardized math test was administered"],a:0,ex:"The independent variable (IV) is what the researchers MANIPULATE. Here, they changed the instructions -- Condition A said the test shows gender differences; Condition B said it does not. The dependent variable (DV) is what they MEASURE -- math test scores. Gender is not the IV because it was not manipulated (you cannot randomly assign gender). This is a classic experimental design question: IV = what changes between conditions, DV = what is measured.",mn:"IV = what researchers change (instructions). DV = what they measure (scores). Gender is not manipulated = not the IV."},
{id:"np32",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p30",q:"The results best support which psychological phenomenon?",o:["Stereotype threat, where awareness of negative stereotypes impairs performance","Social facilitation, where presence of others enhances task performance","Fundamental attribution error, where behavior is attributed to personality","Classical conditioning, where repeated pairing creates learned associations"],a:0,ex:"Stereotype threat (Claude Steele): when people are aware of a negative stereotype about their group in a specific domain, anxiety about confirming that stereotype can impair their performance. The key evidence: when the stereotype was NOT activated (Condition B: told no gender differences), women performed equally well. The performance gap only appeared when the stereotype was made salient (Condition A). The test content was identical -- only the framing changed. This demonstrates that the gap is situational, not inherent.",mn:"Stereotype threat: making a negative stereotype salient -> anxiety -> impaired performance. Situational, not inherent."},
{id:"np33",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p30",q:"Which finding would WEAKEN the stereotype threat explanation?",o:["Women score lower than men even without the stereotype cue","Men also score lower when told about gender differences","The performance gap disappears with repeated test practice","Women actually score higher when the stereotype is activated"],a:0,ex:"Stereotype threat predicts that removing the stereotype cue should eliminate the performance gap. If women still scored lower even in Condition B (no stereotype cue), it would suggest the gap has a cause OTHER than stereotype threat -- perhaps test content, preparation differences, or biological factors. The other options would not weaken the explanation: men scoring lower in Condition A might suggest a different kind of pressure; the effect disappearing with practice would be consistent with reducing anxiety over time.",mn:"Weaken = find the answer that breaks the key assumption. If the gap persists WITHOUT stereotype cue, the explanation fails."},
{id:"np34",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Learning and Conditioning","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p31",q:"The high-load group chose cake more often because:",o:["Cognitive load depletes self-regulation resources, favoring impulsive choices","The participants in the high-load group had skipped lunch beforehand","Chocolate cake was positioned more prominently on the display table","The seven-digit number primed participants to think about sweet foods"],a:0,ex:"This study illustrates the ego depletion / dual-process model: self-control requires cognitive resources. When working memory is loaded (memorizing 7 digits), fewer resources are available for deliberate, controlled decision-making (System 2). Impulsive, automatic responses (System 1) dominate, leading to choosing the immediately gratifying option (cake). The low-load group had more cognitive capacity available for deliberate choice (fruit salad = healthier but requires resisting temptation). This has implications for health decisions made under stress.",mn:"Cognitive load depletes self-control. System 1 (impulsive) wins over System 2 (deliberate). Ego depletion model."},
{id:"np35",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Experimental Design","Sensation and Perception"],diff:3,pass:"p31",q:"The faster response time in the high-load group suggests:",o:["They relied on automatic heuristic processing rather than deliberate reasoning","They had superior natural decision-making abilities compared to the other group","The food display was arranged differently for the high cognitive load group","The digit memorization task directly primed them to prefer sweeter options"],a:0,ex:"Faster decisions under cognitive load indicate reliance on automatic (System 1) rather than deliberate (System 2) processing. System 1 is fast, effortless, and emotion-driven. System 2 is slow, effortful, and analytical. When System 2 is occupied (memorizing digits), System 1 drives the decision quickly. This dual-process framework (Kahneman) applies to many MCAT scenarios: medical decision-making under time pressure, snap judgments about patients, and how cognitive biases operate.",mn:"Fast decisions = System 1 (automatic, heuristic). Slow decisions = System 2 (deliberate, analytical). Kahneman dual process."},
{id:"np36",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p31",q:"The 2-digit memory task serves as:",o:["A control condition","The experimental manipulation","An irrelevant distraction","A memory test"],a:0,ex:"The 2-digit task is the CONTROL condition -- it provides a baseline with minimal cognitive load. Comparing the high-load (7-digit) group to this control isolates the effect of cognitive load on food choice. Without the control, you could not conclude that cognitive load caused the difference. Good experimental design requires both an experimental condition (7-digit) and a control (2-digit) that differs only in the variable of interest. A no-task condition would also work but might introduce other differences.",mn:"Control = minimal version of the manipulation, provides baseline for comparison. Without it, cannot isolate the cause."},
{id:"np37",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Opposing Arguments"],diff:2,pass:"c5",q:"Cronon's central argument is that:",o:["The idea of pristine wilderness is a cultural myth, not ecological reality","All wilderness areas should be immediately opened for commercial development","Indigenous peoples deliberately destroyed North American forest ecosystems","Modern conservation efforts are entirely unnecessary and should be abandoned"],a:0,ex:"CARS strategy: identify the thesis that the ENTIRE passage supports. Cronon argues that 'wilderness' as untouched nature is a cultural construction -- it emerged from Romanticism and frontier mythology, not from ecological truth. Indigenous peoples actively managed the landscape. The passage does NOT argue against conservation -- it argues for rethinking WHAT we conserve and WHY. Notice how the passage explicitly says removing human communities can harm ecosystems. This is a nuanced position, not an anti-conservation one.",mn:"CARS: the main idea is the claim the whole passage supports. Cronon = wilderness is culturally constructed, not anti-conservation."},
{id:"np38",cat:"CARS",tags:["Strengthen/Weaken","Opposing Arguments"],diff:3,pass:"c5",q:"Which finding would most STRENGTHEN Cronon's argument?",o:["Evidence that pre-Columbian forests were extensively managed","Evidence of truly pristine forests never touched by humans","Proof that Romantic era poets never actually visited forests","Data showing every ecosystem requires direct human management"],a:0,ex:"Cronon's argument rests on the claim that what Europeans perceived as pristine wilderness was actually managed landscape. Archaeological evidence of extensive indigenous land management directly supports this -- it demonstrates that the 'untouched' forests were in fact shaped by millennia of human activity. Finding truly untouched forests would weaken the argument. The other options are either irrelevant (poets' travel history) or too extreme (all ecosystems needing intervention).",mn:"CARS strengthen: find evidence that directly supports the key claim. Managed landscape evidence supports 'not pristine.'"},
{id:"np39",cat:"CARS",tags:["Tone and Attitude","Main Idea"],diff:2,pass:"c5",q:"The author's tone toward traditional conservation is best described as:",o:["Critically sympathetic, valuing conservation while challenging its premises","Entirely dismissive, rejecting all conservation efforts as misguided","Uncritically supportive, endorsing traditional conservation without question","Neutral and detached, presenting facts without any evaluative commentary"],a:0,ex:"The author acknowledges conservation's goals but critiques its philosophical foundations. Words like 'irony' and 'paradoxically' signal critical engagement, not dismissal. The passage says preservation that fetishizes pristine nature 'may harm both ecosystems and indigenous rights' -- this is a critique aimed at improving conservation, not abandoning it. On the MCAT, look for nuanced tones (critically sympathetic, cautiously optimistic) rather than extremes.",mn:"CARS tone: look for nuance. 'Irony' and 'paradoxically' = critical but engaged, not dismissive."},
{id:"np40",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Application"],diff:2,pass:"c6",q:"During 'normal science,' according to Kuhn:",o:["Scientists solve puzzles within the accepted paradigm without questioning it","Scientists constantly attempt to overthrow every established theory they encounter","All experimental anomalies are immediately and thoroughly investigated as priority","Paradigm shifts occur frequently during routine periods of normal scientific work"],a:0,ex:"Kuhn defines normal science as the routine puzzle-solving that occupies most scientific activity. Scientists work within the framework of the accepted paradigm -- its theories, methods, and standards. They do not question foundational assumptions; they solve problems that the paradigm defines as important. Anomalies (results that do not fit the paradigm) are initially dismissed, reinterpreted, or set aside rather than treated as threats. Only when anomalies accumulate to the point of crisis does revolutionary science -- and a potential paradigm shift -- become possible.",mn:"Normal science = puzzle-solving within paradigm. Anomalies initially dismissed. Crisis must build before paradigm shift."},
{id:"np41",cat:"CARS",tags:["Application","Opposing Arguments"],diff:3,pass:"c6",q:"Kuhn's concept of incommensurability means:",o:["Successive paradigms cannot be fully compared on shared standards","All competing scientific theories are equally valid and true","Every paradigm shift necessarily represents objective improvement","Scientists in different paradigms communicate without difficulty"],a:0,ex:"Incommensurability is Kuhn's most controversial claim: successive paradigms are so fundamentally different in their concepts, problems, and standards that they cannot be directly compared or translated into each other. A Newtonian and an Einsteinian physicist do not just have different answers -- they define different questions and use different criteria for what counts as a good explanation. This challenges the idea of objective scientific progress, suggesting instead that paradigm shifts are more like gestalt switches than cumulative improvements.",mn:"Incommensurability = paradigms speak different languages. Can't directly compare. Controversial but key to Kuhn."},
{id:"np42",cat:"CARS",tags:["Strengthen/Weaken","Main Idea"],diff:3,pass:"c6",q:"A critic of Kuhn would most likely argue:",o:["Kuhn argues successive paradigms cannot be fully compared using shared standards","All competing scientific theories are equally valid and empirically equivalent","Each paradigm shift necessarily represents measurable improvement in accuracy","Scientists working in different paradigms can easily communicate their findings"],a:0,ex:"The most reasonable criticism of Kuhn targets his claim that paradigm shifts are not cumulative improvements. A critic would argue that later theories genuinely explain more phenomena, make better predictions, and are demonstrably more accurate -- there IS progress, not just change. Einstein's physics includes Newton's as a special case and explains phenomena Newton could not. This challenges incommensurability by showing that comparison IS possible and later theories are objectively better in measurable ways.",mn:"CARS critic: find the most reasonable challenge to the key thesis. Cumulative progress challenges incommensurability."},
{id:"np43",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Opposing Arguments"],diff:2,pass:"c7",q:"The author's main criticism of the trolley problem is that:",o:["It reduces moral reasoning to a single utilitarian calculus, ignoring context","The trolley problem is too intellectually difficult for most people to understand","Moral philosophers have already definitively solved the trolley problem completely","Only professional academic philosophers are capable of discussing ethical dilemmas"],a:0,ex:"The passage argues that trolley-style thought experiments (1) remove the contextual richness of real moral decisions, (2) assume a consequentialist/utilitarian framework that many ethical traditions reject, and (3) may actually distort our understanding of how people navigate ethics. The author presents three alternative frameworks (virtue ethics, care ethics, other traditions) to argue that moral reasoning cannot be reduced to a single calculus. This is a 'the question itself is wrong' type of argument.",mn:"CARS: the author challenges the framing itself, not just the answer. Trolley problem = too narrow, assumes utilitarianism."},
{id:"np44",cat:"CARS",tags:["Application","Tone and Attitude"],diff:3,pass:"c7",q:"A care ethicist evaluating a medical dilemma would prioritize:",o:["The specific relationships and responsibilities between the people","Maximizing the total number of lives saved across all outcomes","Following the precise letter of the applicable law or statute","Asking what a truly virtuous person would do in this situation"],a:0,ex:"The passage explicitly contrasts three ethical frameworks: utilitarianism (maximize good outcomes), virtue ethics (what kind of person should I be?), and care ethics (emphasizes relationships and responsibilities). A care ethicist would focus on the specific relationships at stake -- the doctor's responsibility to this patient, the family's role in decisions, the web of care surrounding the individuals. This contrasts with utilitarianism's abstract calculation and virtue ethics' focus on character. Each framework asks a fundamentally different question.",mn:"Care ethics = relationships and responsibilities first. Utilitarian = maximize outcomes. Virtue = character and being."},
{id:"np45",cat:"CARS",tags:["Strengthen/Weaken","Application"],diff:3,pass:"c7",q:"Which evidence would WEAKEN the author's criticism?",o:["Trolley responses accurately predict real-world moral behavior","The majority of professional ethicists endorse utilitarianism","A new trolley variation adds 100 possible branching outcomes","Historical evidence shows Kant discussed similar dilemmas"],a:0,ex:"The author's key claim is that trolley problems 'distort rather than illuminate how people actually navigate ethical complexity.' If research showed that trolley-problem responses DO predict real-world moral behavior, this would directly challenge that claim -- the thought experiment would be ecologically valid after all, not distorting. The other options do not address the core criticism: whether the trolley framework captures real moral reasoning.",mn:"CARS weaken: find what attacks the central claim. If trolley responses predict real behavior, the 'distortion' criticism fails."},

{id:"np46",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p40",q:"The loss of CD signal at high urea concentrations indicates:",o:["Disruption of secondary structure","Hydrolysis of peptide bonds","Loss of primary structure","Degradation of amino acids"],a:0,ex:"CD spectroscopy measures secondary structure -- specifically the patterns of alpha-helices, beta-sheets, and random coils. Loss of the alpha-helical signal and shift toward random coil means secondary (and by extension tertiary) structure is being lost. This is DENATURATION. Crucially, primary structure (the amino acid sequence, held by covalent peptide bonds) is NOT broken by urea -- urea disrupts hydrogen bonds and hydrophobic interactions, not covalent bonds.",mn:"CD = secondary structure monitor. Urea breaks H-bonds and hydrophobic interactions, NOT peptide bonds. Primary structure survives."},
{id:"np47",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Amino Acid Properties","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p40",q:"DTT prevents refolding because:",o:["Without disulfide crosslinks, the native tertiary fold cannot stabilize","DTT acts as a secondary denaturant that unfolds the protein backbone","DTT hydrolyzes peptide bonds and permanently destroys primary structure","DTT blocks ribosomal function and prevents any new protein translation"],a:0,ex:"DTT (dithiothreitol) reduces disulfide bonds (Cys-S-S-Cys -> 2x Cys-SH). Disulfide bonds are the only COVALENT bonds in tertiary structure. While the protein can refold driven by hydrophobic collapse and H-bonds, without disulfide crosslinks to lock the structure, the native conformation is unstable and activity cannot fully recover. This experiment demonstrates Anfinsen's dogma: the amino acid sequence determines structure, but disulfide bonds are essential for stabilizing the folded state.",mn:"DTT breaks S-S bonds. Without covalent crosslinks, tertiary structure cannot fully stabilize. Anfinsen's dogma."},
{id:"np48",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p40",q:"The 80% recovery after dialysis most strongly supports:",o:["The amino acid sequence itself encodes sufficient folding information","An external chaperone protein is absolutely required for refolding","The protein was never actually denatured by the urea treatment","Urea paradoxically catalyzes the protein refolding reaction"],a:0,ex:"Spontaneous refolding after removing the denaturant demonstrates Anfinsen's principle: the primary structure (amino acid sequence) encodes all the information needed for proper folding. No chaperones, no ribosomes, no cellular machinery -- just the sequence. The fact that recovery is 80% (not 100%) likely reflects some molecules misfolding or aggregating. In cells, chaperones like Hsp70 prevent aggregation, but they are not strictly required for the folding pathway itself.",mn:"Refolding after dialysis = sequence determines structure (Anfinsen's dogma). Chaperones help in vivo but aren't the blueprint."},
{id:"np49",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p40",q:"Which amino acid is most critical for the DTT observation?",o:["Cysteine (forms disulfide bonds via thiol groups)","Proline (rigid ring structure)","Glycine (smallest, most flexible)","Tryptophan (aromatic UV absorption)"],a:0,ex:"DTT specifically cleaves disulfide bonds, which are formed exclusively between cysteine residues. The thiol (-SH) groups of two cysteines oxidize to form a covalent S-S bridge. This is the only covalent bond in tertiary structure besides the peptide backbone. DTT acts as a reducing agent, donating hydrogens to break the S-S bond back into two free -SH groups.",mn:"Cysteine = only AA that forms disulfide bonds. DTT reduces S-S -> 2 SH. Only covalent crosslink in tertiary structure."},
{id:"np50",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p41",q:"The elevated lactate is caused by:",o:["Impaired ETC forces pyruvate-to-lactate conversion for NAD+ regeneration","Excess pyruvate kinase activity accelerates glycolytic flux excessively","Hepatic failure prevents normal lactate clearance from the blood","Increased aerobic metabolism produces lactate as a normal byproduct"],a:0,ex:"With Complex I impaired, NADH cannot efficiently donate electrons to the ETC. NADH accumulates, NAD+ becomes scarce. Without NAD+, glycolysis cannot continue (GAPDH requires NAD+). To regenerate NAD+, cells reduce pyruvate to lactate via lactate dehydrogenase (NADH + pyruvate -> NAD+ + lactate). This is the same reason muscles produce lactate during anaerobic exercise -- it is a rescue mechanism to keep glycolysis running when oxidative phosphorylation is impaired.",mn:"Low NAD+ from broken ETC -> must regenerate NAD+ -> pyruvate becomes lactate. Same logic as anaerobic exercise."},
{id:"np51",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation"],diff:3,pass:"p41",q:"Complex II activity is normal because:",o:["Complex II is encoded entirely by nuclear DNA, not mitochondrial","Complex II is not actually a component of the electron transport","Complex II does not require any electron carrier cofactors","The tRNA mutation only directly affects Complex I gene expression"],a:0,ex:"Complex II (succinate dehydrogenase) is unique: it is the ONLY ETC complex encoded entirely by nuclear DNA. All other complexes (I, III, IV, V) have subunits encoded by mtDNA. Since the mutation is in a mitochondrial tRNA gene (affecting translation of mtDNA-encoded proteins), Complex II is spared. This is a commonly tested fact: Complex II = nuclear-encoded = unaffected by mtDNA mutations.",mn:"Complex II = ONLY ETC complex fully encoded by nuclear DNA. mtDNA mutation spares it. High-yield fact!"},
{id:"np52",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p41",q:"The inheritance pattern of this disease is most likely:",o:["Maternal inheritance, since mitochondrial DNA comes only from the mother","Autosomal dominant, requiring only one mutant allele for expression","Autosomal recessive, requiring two mutant alleles for disease expression","X-linked recessive, affecting primarily males with one X chromosome"],a:0,ex:"Mitochondrial DNA is inherited exclusively from the mother -- sperm contribute essentially no mitochondria to the zygote. All mtDNA mutations show maternal inheritance: an affected mother passes the mutation to ALL children, but an affected father passes it to NONE. This is a key distinguishing feature from nuclear inheritance patterns. Mitochondrial diseases often show variable expressivity due to heteroplasmy (cells contain a mix of normal and mutant mtDNA).",mn:"mtDNA = maternal inheritance ONLY. Affected mother -> all children at risk. Affected father -> none. Heteroplasmy = variable severity."},
{id:"np53",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Signal Transduction","Cell Cycle","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p42",q:"The constitutively active Ras mutant is dangerous because:",o:["It drives uncontrolled proliferation by permanently activating growth signaling","It completely blocks all cellular signaling pathways and halts division","It triggers immediate programmed cell death through caspase activation","It prevents DNA replication by inhibiting helicase unwinding activity"],a:0,ex:"Ras is a G-protein that acts as a molecular switch: GTP-bound = ON, GDP-bound = OFF. GAP normally turns Ras off by stimulating GTP hydrolysis. A mutation that locks Ras in the GTP-bound state means the growth signal is ALWAYS ON, even without growth factor. This drives uncontrolled proliferation = cancer. Mutant Ras is one of the most common oncogenes, found in ~30% of human cancers (especially pancreatic, colon, and lung).",mn:"Ras stuck ON = constitutive growth signaling = cancer. Ras is an ONCOGENE (gain of function). Found in ~30% of cancers."},
{id:"np54",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Signal Transduction","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p42",q:"The GAP inhibitor experiment demonstrates that:",o:["Ras activation duration is controlled by the rate of GTP hydrolysis","GAP protein directly activates Ras by loading it with GTP substrate","Growth Factor X bypasses Ras and directly activates MAP kinase","Ras functions independently of GTP and does not require nucleotides"],a:0,ex:"GAP (GTPase-activating protein) accelerates the intrinsic GTPase activity of Ras, converting Ras-GTP to Ras-GDP (turning it OFF). Inhibiting GAP means Ras stays in the active GTP-bound state longer, amplifying downstream signaling. This shows that DURATION of Ras activation is regulated by hydrolysis rate, not just by initial activation. The same principle applies to heterotrimeric G-proteins (Galpha subunit hydrolyzes GTP to turn off).",mn:"GAP turns Ras OFF by accelerating GTP->GDP hydrolysis. Block GAP = Ras stays on longer = more signaling. Duration matters!"},
{id:"np55",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Signal Transduction","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p42",q:"The correct temporal order from fastest to slowest is:",o:["Receptor phosphorylation, then Ras, then MAPK cascade, then transcription","Gene transcription first, then MAPK, then Ras, then receptor activation","All signaling steps occur simultaneously without any temporal sequence","Ras activation occurs before receptor binding of the growth factor"],a:0,ex:"Signal transduction cascades have a specific temporal order: ligand binds receptor (seconds) -> receptor autophosphorylation (seconds) -> adaptor proteins recruit SOS -> Ras activation (1-2 min) -> RAF -> MEK -> ERK (MAPK cascade, 5 min) -> transcription factor phosphorylation -> gene expression (15+ min). Each step amplifies the signal. The passage data matches this perfectly. Transcription is always the slowest step because it requires nuclear import and RNA synthesis.",mn:"Signaling cascade flows: receptor -> Ras -> MAPK -> transcription. Seconds -> minutes -> minutes -> 15+ min. Amplification at each step."},
{id:"np56",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Mendelian Genetics","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p43",q:"The researchers should conclude:",o:["The deviation is NOT statistically significant","The deviation is significant and Mendelian genetics is wrong","The cross produced too many black offspring","The expected ratio should be 3:1"],a:0,ex:"Chi-squared = 1.6, which is LESS than the critical value of 3.84 at p=0.05. When chi-squared < critical value, we FAIL TO REJECT the null hypothesis (that the observed results match the expected Mendelian ratio). The 24:16 deviation from the expected 20:20 is within the range of normal random variation. Remember: fail to reject ≠ prove true. We simply lack evidence to say the results are significantly different from expected.",mn:"Chi-squared < critical value = fail to reject null hypothesis = results consistent with expected ratio. 1.6 < 3.84."},
{id:"np57",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Mendelian Genetics","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p43",q:"The degrees of freedom equals 1 because:",o:["There are 2 phenotype categories minus 1","There are 40 offspring","Only one parent is heterozygous","The chi-squared value is 1.6"],a:0,ex:"Degrees of freedom for a chi-squared goodness-of-fit test = number of categories minus 1. Here there are 2 phenotype categories (black and white), so df = 2 - 1 = 1. For a dihybrid cross with 4 phenotype categories (9:3:3:1), df = 4 - 1 = 3. The df determines which row of the chi-squared table to use for the critical value. More categories = more df = higher critical value.",mn:"df = categories - 1. Two phenotypes: df = 2-1 = 1. Dihybrid (4 phenotypes): df = 4-1 = 3."},
{id:"np58",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Mendelian Genetics","Inheritance Patterns","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p43",q:"If the cross instead produced 30 black and 10 white, chi-squared would be:",o:["5.0, which exceeds the critical value and is statistically significant","1.6, the same value obtained in the original experiment outcome","0.0, indicating a perfect fit to the expected Mendelian ratio","3.84, falling exactly at the critical value decision boundary"],a:0,ex:"Chi-squared = (30-20)^2/20 + (10-20)^2/20 = 100/20 + 100/20 = 5.0 + 5.0 = 10.0. Actually let me recalculate: expected is 20 each. (30-20)^2/20 = 100/20 = 5.0, (10-20)^2/20 = 100/20 = 5.0. Total = 10.0. That exceeds 3.84 so it IS significant. We would REJECT the null hypothesis -- the results are significantly different from the expected 1:1 ratio. This might suggest a lethal allele, epistasis, or other non-Mendelian effect.",mn:"Chi-squared = sum of (observed-expected)^2/expected. If > critical value, reject null. 10.0 >> 3.84 = significant."},
{id:"np59",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Membrane Transport","Hormones"],diff:2,pass:"p44",q:"The aquaporin-2 blocker mimics the effect of:",o:["Low ADH levels","High ADH levels","Aldosterone excess","High glucose levels"],a:0,ex:"ADH (antidiuretic hormone) works by inserting aquaporin-2 channels into the collecting duct apical membrane, allowing water to follow the osmotic gradient from the tubule into the hypertonic medulla. Blocking these channels prevents water reabsorption, producing large volumes of dilute urine -- exactly what happens in diabetes insipidus (either central DI = no ADH production, or nephrogenic DI = kidneys don't respond to ADH). Alcohol inhibits ADH release, which is why it increases urine output.",mn:"ADH inserts aquaporin-2 in collecting duct. No ADH or blocked aquaporins = dilute high-volume urine = diabetes insipidus."},
{id:"np60",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Membrane Transport"],diff:3,pass:"p44",q:"Glucose is 100% reabsorbed because:",o:["SGLT2 and GLUT2 transporters have sufficient capacity at normal levels","Glucose molecules are enzymatically destroyed within the urine","The glomerular filtration barrier does not allow glucose passage","Glucose reabsorption occurs primarily in the collecting duct"],a:0,ex:"Glucose is freely filtered at the glomerulus (it is small and uncharged). In the proximal tubule, SGLT2 (sodium-glucose cotransporter) on the apical side reabsorbs ~90% of glucose using the Na+ gradient. GLUT2 on the basolateral side moves glucose into blood. At normal blood glucose (~100 mg/dL), these transporters have enough capacity to reabsorb ALL filtered glucose. Above ~180 mg/dL (transport maximum/Tm), transporters saturate and glucose spills into urine (glucosuria in diabetes).",mn:"Glucose reabsorbed by SGLT2 + GLUT2 in proximal tubule. Above Tm (~180 mg/dL) = glucosuria. Normal levels = 100% reabsorbed."},
{id:"np61",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p44",q:"Water follows Na+ in the proximal tubule by:",o:["Osmosis through constitutive aquaporin-1 water channels","ATP-dependent primary active transport of water molecules","Carrier-mediated facilitated diffusion of individual water","Bulk pinocytosis engulfing water in membrane-bound vesicles"],a:0,ex:"In the proximal tubule, Na+ is actively reabsorbed (Na+/K+ ATPase basolateral, various co-transporters apical). This creates an osmotic gradient, and water follows passively through constitutively expressed aquaporin-1 channels. Unlike aquaporin-2 in the collecting duct, aquaporin-1 does NOT require ADH -- it is always present. About 65% of filtered water is reabsorbed in the proximal tubule regardless of hydration status. This is obligatory water reabsorption.",mn:"Proximal tubule: AQP-1 (always there, no ADH needed) = obligatory reabsorption. Collecting duct: AQP-2 (needs ADH) = regulated."},
{id:"np62",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Respiratory System","Cardiovascular System","Acid-Base"],diff:2,pass:"p45",q:"During heavy exercise, PaCO2 drops to 35 because:",o:["Hyperventilation expels CO2 faster than exercise produces it","Exercise decreases total CO2 production by muscle tissue","Lung capacity decreases significantly during heavy exertion","Bicarbonate loss from blood causes direct acidification only"],a:0,ex:"Heavy exercise increases ventilation rate dramatically (15->35 breaths/min). While exercise also increases CO2 production, the hyperventilation response exceeds metabolic CO2 output, so PaCO2 actually DECREASES. This is partly driven by peripheral chemoreceptors sensing increased H+ from lactic acid production. Lower PaCO2 shifts the CO2-bicarbonate equilibrium, raising pH slightly. This is respiratory compensation for metabolic acidosis from lactate.",mn:"Hyperventilation blows off CO2 faster than it is made. Compensates for lactic acid. PaCO2 down = respiratory alkalosis component."},
{id:"np63",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Respiratory System","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p45",q:"Supplemental O2 does not improve performance because:",o:["Hemoglobin is already over 95% saturated at normal PaO2 levels","The lungs physically cannot absorb any additional oxygen molecules","Skeletal muscles do not utilize oxygen during exercise conditions","Supplemental oxygen becomes toxic at even slightly elevated levels"],a:0,ex:"The oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve is SIGMOIDAL. At PaO2 of 90-95 mmHg, hemoglobin is on the flat upper portion of the curve (~95-97% saturated). Adding more O2 barely increases saturation -- you cannot go much above 100%. The performance limitation during heavy exercise is cardiac output (delivering blood to muscles), not oxygen content per unit blood. Supplemental O2 helps primarily in hypoxic conditions (altitude, lung disease) where PaO2 is on the steep part of the curve.",mn:"Flat part of O2-Hb curve: PaO2 90+ = already ~97% saturated. More O2 cannot significantly increase delivery. Cardiac output is the bottleneck."},
{id:"np64",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Organelles","Protein Structure","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p46",q:"This experiment most closely resembles:",o:["The Palade pulse-chase experiment tracing the secretory pathway","The Meselson-Stahl experiment confirming semiconservative replication","The Hershey-Chase experiment identifying DNA as genetic material","The Miller-Urey experiment simulating prebiotic amino acid synthesis"],a:0,ex:"George Palade's Nobel Prize-winning pulse-chase experiment used radioactive amino acids to trace the secretory pathway: rough ER (synthesis + N-linked glycosylation) -> Golgi (modification + sorting + O-linked glycosylation) -> secretory vesicles -> exocytosis. This established the endomembrane system. The temporal sequence in the passage exactly mirrors Palade's findings. Pulse-chase = brief label exposure (pulse) followed by tracking over time (chase).",mn:"Palade = secretory pathway: RER -> Golgi -> vesicles -> outside. Pulse-chase technique. Won Nobel Prize."},
{id:"np65",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Organelles","Protein Structure"],diff:2,pass:"p46",q:"N-linked glycosylation occurs in the:",o:["Rough ER, where it is added to asparagine residues co-translationally","Golgi apparatus, where O-linked glycosylation and trimming occur","Cytoplasm, where free ribosomes synthesize cytosolic proteins","Nucleus, where mRNA processing and splicing take place instead"],a:0,ex:"N-linked glycosylation = carbohydrate chain attached to the nitrogen of ASPARAGINE (Asn) in the sequence Asn-X-Ser/Thr (where X is any AA except Pro). This occurs in the rough ER lumen during translation. O-linked glycosylation (attached to the oxygen of Ser or Thr) occurs later in the Golgi. The Golgi also modifies, trims, and adds to the N-linked glycans initiated in the ER. Mannose-6-phosphate tagging (for lysosomal targeting) happens in the cis-Golgi.",mn:"N-linked = Asparagine, in ER. O-linked = Serine/Threonine, in Golgi. M6P tag in Golgi = lysosome targeting."},
{id:"np66",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Organelles","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p46",q:"Treatment with brefeldin A (which collapses the Golgi into the ER) would:",o:["Block secretion, causing protein accumulation inside the ER","Increase the rate of protein secretion from the cell surface","Have no measurable effect on intracellular protein trafficking","Cause proteins to bypass the Golgi and secrete directly from ER"],a:0,ex:"Brefeldin A inhibits COP-I coated vesicle formation, collapsing the Golgi into the ER. Without a functional Golgi, proteins cannot be properly sorted, modified (no O-linked glycosylation, no M6P tagging), or packaged into secretory vesicles. Proteins accumulate in the expanded ER. Lysosomal enzymes are not tagged with M6P and are secreted instead of going to lysosomes. This drug is useful experimentally for studying the requirement for Golgi function in trafficking.",mn:"Brefeldin A = collapses Golgi. Blocks COP-I vesicles. No sorting, no O-glycosylation, no M6P tagging. Proteins stuck in ER."},
{id:"np67",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Kinetics Parameters","Enzyme Inhibition","Lineweaver-Burk"],diff:2,pass:"p47",q:"The inhibitor is:",o:["Competitive (same Vmax, increased Km)","Noncompetitive (decreased Vmax, same Km)","Uncompetitive (both decreased)","Irreversible"],a:0,ex:"Lineweaver-Burk: y-intercept = 1/Vmax, x-intercept = -1/Km. Same y-intercept (0.02) means same Vmax = 1/0.02 = 50. Without inhibitor: -1/Km = -0.5, so Km = 2. With inhibitor: -1/Km = -0.25, so Km = 4. Km INCREASED (apparent lower affinity) while Vmax unchanged = COMPETITIVE inhibition. The inhibitor binds the active site and can be overcome by excess substrate. Lines intersect at y-axis = classic competitive pattern.",mn:"Same y-intercept = same Vmax. Different x-intercept = different Km. Vmax same + Km up = COMPETITIVE. Lines cross at y-axis."},
{id:"np68",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Kinetics Parameters","Lineweaver-Burk"],diff:3,pass:"p47",q:"The Km with inhibitor is:",o:["4, since the x-intercept of -0.25 gives Km = 1/0.25","2, since the Km remains unchanged by competitive binding","0.25, which is the x-intercept value read directly from plot","0.5, which is the original Km before inhibitor addition"],a:0,ex:"From Lineweaver-Burk: x-intercept = -1/Km. With inhibitor, x-intercept = -0.25. Therefore -1/Km = -0.25, and Km = 1/0.25 = 4. The apparent Km doubled from 2 to 4, meaning the enzyme now needs twice as much substrate to reach half-maximal velocity. This reflects the competitive inhibitor occupying active sites and requiring more substrate to outcompete it. At infinite [S], all active sites will eventually be occupied by substrate, which is why Vmax is unchanged.",mn:"x-intercept = -1/Km. -0.25 means Km = 4. Km doubled = need more substrate to overcome competitive inhibitor."},
{id:"np69",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Kinetics Parameters","Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:2,pass:"p47",q:"If the inhibitor were noncompetitive instead, the Lineweaver-Burk plot would show:",o:["Lines intersecting at the x-axis","Parallel lines","Lines intersecting at y-axis","A single unchanged line"],a:0,ex:"Noncompetitive inhibitors bind an allosteric site with equal affinity for E and ES. They decrease Vmax but do NOT change Km. On Lineweaver-Burk: different y-intercept (different 1/Vmax) but same x-intercept (same -1/Km). The lines intersect at the x-axis. Uncompetitive = parallel lines (both Km and Vmax decrease proportionally). Competitive = intersect at y-axis (same Vmax).",mn:"Competitive = y-axis intersection. Noncompetitive = x-axis intersection. Uncompetitive = parallel lines. Must memorize all three!"},
{id:"np70",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions","Stereochemistry","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p48",q:"Methyl bromide undergoes SN2 because:",o:["Methyl substrates have minimal steric hindrance for backside attack","Methyl groups provide strong stabilization of carbocation intermediates","Sodium hydroxide behaves as a weak nucleophile in this solvent","Acetone functions as a polar protic solvent in this reaction"],a:0,ex:"SN2 requires backside attack by the nucleophile. Methyl substrates have ZERO steric hindrance (only H atoms around the carbon), making them ideal for SN2. The complete inversion confirms SN2 (Walden inversion). NaOH is a STRONG nucleophile and base (favors SN2/E2). Acetone is a polar APROTIC solvent (favors SN2 by not solvating the nucleophile). Everything about this setup favors SN2: strong nuc + methyl substrate + polar aprotic.",mn:"SN2 loves: methyl > 1 > 2 > never 3. Strong nuc, polar aprotic solvent. Backside attack = inversion. One-step mechanism."},
{id:"np71",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions","Stereochemistry"],diff:3,pass:"p48",q:"Tert-butyl bromide produces a racemic mixture because:",o:["SN1 proceeds through a planar carbocation attacked from either face","SN2 backside attack is sterically blocked by the three methyl groups","The tertiary carbocation intermediate retains its original chirality","Both SN1 and SN2 mechanisms operate simultaneously and compete"],a:0,ex:"Tertiary substrates CANNOT undergo SN2 (too sterically hindered for backside attack). Instead, tert-butyl bromide follows SN1: the leaving group departs to form a stable tertiary carbocation (3 alkyl groups stabilize via hyperconjugation and inductive effects). The carbocation is sp2 hybridized = planar. Nucleophilic attack can occur from either face with equal probability, producing a 50:50 racemic mixture. Water (polar protic) stabilizes the carbocation = favors SN1.",mn:"Tertiary = SN1 only (too bulky for SN2). Planar carbocation -> attack from both sides -> racemization. Water favors SN1."},
{id:"np72",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p48",q:"Neopentyl bromide reacts slowly because:",o:["Steric hindrance blocks SN2 while primary carbocation instability blocks SN1","The carbon-bromine bond is too strong for nucleophilic attack to occur","The molecule lacks a suitable leaving group for substitution reactions","Aromaticity stabilizes the molecule and prevents nucleophilic substitution"],a:0,ex:"Neopentyl bromide is a PRIMARY halide but with massive beta-branching (three methyl groups on the adjacent carbon). This blocks SN2 backside attack sterically. Yet it cannot do SN1 because primary carbocations are too unstable. It is stuck: too hindered for SN2, too unstable for SN1. This is a classic MCAT trap -- students see 'primary' and assume SN2, but beta-branching changes everything.",mn:"Neopentyl = primary but beta-branched. Too bulky for SN2, too unstable for SN1. The worst of both worlds. Classic MCAT trap!"},
{id:"np73",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Nuclear Chemistry","Chemical Kinetics","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p49",q:"The activity of Tc-99m at 2:00 PM is:",o:["400 MBq after one half-life of 6 hours has elapsed","200 MBq after two half-lives of 6 hours have elapsed","800 MBq with no decay occurring during the imaging delay","100 MBq after three half-lives of 6 hours have elapsed"],a:0,ex:"From 8:00 AM to 2:00 PM = 6 hours = exactly one half-life of Tc-99m. After one half-life, the activity drops by half: 800/2 = 400 MBq. After n half-lives: A = A0 * (1/2)^n. Radioactive decay is FIRST-ORDER kinetics: the rate depends on the amount of radioactive material present. Half-life is independent of the initial amount. t1/2 = 0.693/k for first-order processes.",mn:"6 hours = 1 half-life. 800 -> 400 MBq. Radioactive decay = first-order. A = A0 * (1/2)^n. t1/2 = 0.693/k."},
{id:"np74",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Nuclear Chemistry","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p49",q:"Gamma emission is used for imaging because:",o:["Gamma rays penetrate tissue and can be detected externally by a camera","Gamma rays destroy cancer cells","Gamma rays are blocked by tissue so they stay in one location","Gamma decay changes the element to a different one"],a:0,ex:"Gamma rays are high-energy electromagnetic radiation with excellent tissue penetration. They pass through the body and are detected by a gamma camera outside the patient, creating an image of where the radioisotope has concentrated. Alpha particles (blocked by paper/skin) and beta particles (blocked by a few mm of tissue) cannot be detected externally. Gamma emission does NOT change the atomic number or mass number -- it only releases energy as the nucleus drops to a lower energy state.",mn:"Gamma = high penetration, detectable externally = good for imaging. Alpha/beta = stopped by tissue. Gamma decay: no change in Z or A."},
{id:"np75",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Cardiovascular System","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p50",q:"A 50% radius reduction requires 16x pressure because:",o:["Flow depends on radius to the fourth power per Poiseuille's equation","Flow depends on radius squared according to the continuity equation","Pressure gradient is completely independent of vessel radius","Viscosity increases proportionally when vessel radius decreases"],a:0,ex:"Poiseuille's equation shows flow is proportional to r^4 (radius to the FOURTH power). This means small changes in radius have enormous effects on flow. Halving the radius: Q proportional to (0.5)^4 = 1/16. To maintain the same flow, you need 16 times the pressure. This is why atherosclerosis (narrowing arteries) has such dramatic effects on blood flow and blood pressure. A 20% stenosis reduces flow by ~60%!",mn:"Poiseuille: Q proportional to r^4. Halve radius -> flow drops 16x. Small stenosis = huge flow reduction. Most tested fluid equation!"},
{id:"np76",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Cardiovascular System"],diff:3,pass:"p50",q:"In the real cardiovascular system, the greatest pressure drop occurs across:",o:["Arterioles, which provide the greatest resistance due to small radius","The aorta, which generates the highest absolute blood pressure","Capillaries, which have the thinnest walls and smallest diameter","Veins, which contain the largest total blood volume reservoir"],a:0,ex:"Although capillaries are individually smaller than arterioles, they are arranged in parallel (which DECREASES total resistance: 1/R_total = sum of 1/R_i). Arterioles are the primary resistance vessels: they have small radii AND are arranged more in series, making them the main site of blood pressure regulation. Smooth muscle in arteriole walls can constrict or dilate, dramatically changing r^4 and therefore resistance and flow. This is how blood pressure and tissue perfusion are regulated.",mn:"Arterioles = highest resistance, biggest pressure drop. Small r^4 + smooth muscle control. Parallel capillaries reduce their total R."},
{id:"np77",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Learning and Conditioning","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p51",q:"Group C's superior recall demonstrates:",o:["Levels of processing theory","Rote memorization is most effective","All encoding strategies are equal","Acoustic processing is best"],a:0,ex:"Craik and Lockhart's levels of processing theory: deeper processing produces more durable, retrievable memories. Shallow processing (structural: what does it look like?) < intermediate (acoustic: what does it sound like?) < deep (semantic: what does it mean?). Group C engaged in the deepest processing by connecting words to personal experiences (self-referencing effect), which is even deeper than generic semantic processing. This is why elaborative rehearsal beats maintenance rehearsal.",mn:"Levels of processing: structural < acoustic < semantic. Deeper = better memory. Self-reference effect = deepest. Elaborative > maintenance rehearsal."},
{id:"np78",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p51",q:"The independent variable in this study is:",o:["The type of encoding task","Number of words recalled","The 24-hour delay","The list of 40 words"],a:0,ex:"The IV is what the researchers MANIPULATE between groups: the encoding strategy. The DV is what they MEASURE: number of words recalled. The 24-hour delay and word list are CONTROLLED variables (kept the same across groups). The surprise nature of the test controls for intentional memorization strategies. This is a between-subjects design (different participants in each group). A within-subjects design would have the same people do all three conditions.",mn:"IV = what researchers change (encoding type). DV = what they measure (recall). Same delay + same words = controlled variables."},
{id:"np79",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Learning and Conditioning"],diff:2,pass:"p51",q:"A student applying these findings should:",o:["Create personal connections and meaningful associations while studying","Re-read lecture notes as many times as possible before the exam","Memorize material primarily through acoustic rhyming strategies","Study in complete silence without any external environmental input"],a:0,ex:"Deep semantic processing produces the best recall. For MCAT studying, this means: explaining concepts in your own words, connecting new material to what you already know, teaching concepts to others, creating clinical scenarios, and asking 'why does this make sense?' Re-reading notes is shallow structural processing -- the least effective strategy. Active recall (testing yourself) also promotes deep processing because retrieving information requires engaging with its meaning.",mn:"Study tip: explain in your own words, connect to existing knowledge, teach others, ask why. Re-reading = worst strategy. Active recall = best."},
{id:"np80",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Health Disparities","Social Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p52",q:"The persistent health gap after controlling for behaviors suggests:",o:["Structural and environmental factors beyond individual choices matter","Individual behavior is the sole determinant of population health","Wealthy populations have inherently superior genetic constitutions","The study methodology is fundamentally flawed and results invalid"],a:0,ex:"If individual behaviors explained the ENTIRE gap, controlling for them would eliminate the disparity. The fact that 60% of the gap persists after controlling for behavior means STRUCTURAL factors are at work: environmental toxin exposure, chronic stress from poverty, healthcare access barriers, food deserts, housing quality, occupational hazards, structural racism. This supports the social determinants of health model over a purely biomedical/individual responsibility framework.",mn:"Gap persists after controlling behavior = structural causes. Social determinants: environment, access, stress, SES, systemic factors > individual choices."},
{id:"np81",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Health Disparities","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p52",q:"Food deserts contribute to diabetes through:",o:["Limited access to nutritious food forces reliance on processed options","Residents freely choose unhealthy food despite equal grocery access","The presence of grocery stores directly causes diabetes development","Food deserts correlate with higher rates of physical exercise"],a:0,ex:"Food deserts = areas with limited access to affordable, nutritious food. Residents must rely on convenience stores and fast food, which offer calorie-dense, nutrient-poor, highly processed foods high in sugar and refined carbohydrates. This is NOT a simple 'choice' -- when the nearest grocery store is 2+ miles away and you lack transportation, healthy eating becomes structurally difficult regardless of knowledge or motivation. This is structural violence/structural constraint on health behaviors.",mn:"Food desert = no grocery access = forced into processed food = diet-related disease. Structural constraint, not individual choice."},
{id:"np82",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Nervous System","Experimental Design","Psychopharmacology"],diff:2,pass:"p53",q:"The 4-6 week delay between serotonin increase and clinical improvement suggests:",o:["Therapeutic effects require downstream neuroplastic adaptation changes","Low serotonin alone is not the cause of depressive disorders","The drug produces no measurable clinical benefit over placebo","The entire observed improvement is attributable to placebo effect"],a:0,ex:"If depression were simply caused by low serotonin, raising serotonin levels should produce immediate improvement. The 4-6 week delay suggests that the therapeutic mechanism involves downstream changes: receptor desensitization, neurogenesis (especially in hippocampus), synaptic remodeling, and changes in gene expression. SSRIs raise serotonin immediately, but the BRAIN ADAPTATION to chronically elevated serotonin is what produces the clinical effect. This is why patients must be told to continue medication even if they do not feel better immediately.",mn:"Serotonin rises in hours but improvement takes weeks = downstream neuroplasticity is the real mechanism, not just more serotonin."},
{id:"np83",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Nervous System","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p53",q:"The 30% placebo improvement rate demonstrates:",o:["Placebo responses are significant and must be controlled for properly","The active drug performs no better than placebo in this trial","All enrolled patients improved equally regardless of group assignment","Major depression spontaneously resolves in 30% of cases naturally"],a:0,ex:"The placebo response rate of 30% is substantial and common in antidepressant trials. This is why randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled trials are essential: without a placebo group, the 45% improvement in the drug group might be attributed entirely to the drug when in fact 30% would have improved anyway. The drug's TRUE effect is the DIFFERENCE: 45% - 30% = 15% improvement attributable specifically to Drug Y. p=0.03 means this difference is statistically significant.",mn:"True drug effect = drug improvement - placebo improvement. 45-30 = 15% attributable to drug. p=0.03 = significant. Always need placebo control!"},
{id:"np84",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Opposing Arguments"],diff:2,pass:"c8",q:"The author's central argument is that:",o:["Meritocratic ideology legitimizes inequality as reflecting individual merit","Meritocracy represents the optimal system for organizing fair societies","Individual talent and effort should be the sole determinants of success","Inequality does not actually exist within truly meritocratic societies"],a:0,ex:"The passage argues that meritocracy as an IDEOLOGY (not as a practice) serves to justify existing inequality. The key logic: if success = merit, then failure = lack of merit. This transforms structural problems (poverty, discrimination, unequal access) into personal failings. The author does not argue against rewarding talent -- they argue that the BELIEF in meritocracy makes people blind to systemic barriers and reduces support for addressing them.",mn:"CARS: distinguish between meritocracy as ideal vs meritocracy as ideology that legitimizes inequality. Author critiques the ideology, not the aspiration."},
{id:"np85",cat:"CARS",tags:["Strengthen/Weaken","Application"],diff:3,pass:"c8",q:"Which finding would most WEAKEN the author's argument?",o:["Belief in meritocracy increases support for addressing systemic barriers","Evidence showing that wealthy people consistently work harder than others","Evidence that IQ scores reliably predict lifetime income and success","Evidence that additional education consistently improves worker earnings"],a:0,ex:"The author's key claim is that meritocratic belief REDUCES support for addressing systemic inequality. If evidence showed the opposite -- that believing in meritocracy actually INCREASES support for such programs -- the central mechanism of the argument would fail. The other options do not address this claim: wealthy people working harder, IQ predicting income, or education improving earnings could all be true while the ideology still legitimizes existing structural barriers.",mn:"CARS weaken: attack the MECHANISM, not the premises. If meritocratic belief increases (not decreases) support for equity, the argument collapses."},
{id:"np86",cat:"CARS",tags:["Tone and Attitude","Main Idea"],diff:2,pass:"c8",q:"The phrase 'cruel paradox' reveals the author's:",o:["Moral concern that a fair-seeming principle produces unjust outcomes","Neutral detached academic analysis without any evaluative judgment","Explicit support for meritocratic principles as currently practiced","Complete indifference toward inequality and its social consequences"],a:0,ex:"The word 'cruel' is evaluative and emotional -- it signals the author views meritocracy's consequences negatively. 'Paradox' indicates intellectual complexity. Together, they show the author finds it morally troubling that a principle designed to promote fairness (merit-based success) actually produces injustice (blaming the disadvantaged). This is neither neutral nor supportive -- it is critically engaged with moral urgency.",mn:"CARS tone: 'cruel paradox' = morally concerned + intellectually engaged. Evaluative language reveals author's position. Look for loaded adjectives."},
{id:"np87",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Application"],diff:2,pass:"c9",q:"The author argues the replication crisis shows that:",o:["Science self-corrects but needs institutional safeguards against bias","The scientific method itself is fundamentally and irreparably flawed","Psychology does not qualify as a legitimate empirical science","All published scientific findings should always be trusted as valid"],a:0,ex:"The key line is the conclusion: 'science without institutional safeguards against human bias produces unreliable knowledge.' The author rejects both extremes -- that science is fine as-is, or that science is fundamentally broken. Instead, they argue the crisis shows science WORKS (it found its own problems through replication) but needs STRUCTURAL reforms (pre-registration, larger samples, incentive changes) to counter human biases that the method alone cannot prevent.",mn:"CARS: the author takes a middle position. Science works but needs safeguards. 'Mistakes the disease for the cure' = rejects the anti-science conclusion."},
{id:"np88",cat:"CARS",tags:["Strengthen/Weaken","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"c9",q:"Which reform most directly addresses the problems described?",o:["Pre-registration of hypotheses and analysis plans before data collection","Increasing the total amount of government funding allocated to psychology","Hiring substantially more researchers to increase replication capacity","Publishing only statistically significant positive results in journals"],a:0,ex:"The passage identifies flexible data analysis (p-hacking) and publication bias as key causes. Pre-registration requires researchers to specify their hypotheses and analysis plan BEFORE seeing the data, preventing after-the-fact manipulation of statistical tests to find significant results. It also combats publication bias by creating a record of studies that were planned, making it harder to bury negative results. This directly addresses the structural problems described in the passage.",mn:"Pre-registration = commit to hypothesis + analysis before data. Prevents p-hacking and publication bias. Most direct fix for the described problems."},
{id:"np89",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Opposing Arguments"],diff:2,pass:"c10",q:"The passage presents genetic enhancement as:",o:["A genuine dilemma where both action and inaction carry moral weight","A clearly unethical practice that should be universally prohibited","A clearly beneficial technology that should be immediately adopted","An issue with a straightforward and obvious correct ethical answer"],a:0,ex:"The passage deliberately presents BOTH sides without resolving the tension. The treatment/enhancement line is shown to be blurry. Genetic conservatism is presented as reasonable (unpredictable consequences) but so is the counterargument (inaction is also a moral choice). The passage frames this as a genuine dilemma where existing ethical frameworks are insufficient. CARS questions often test whether you can identify balanced presentation vs advocacy.",mn:"CARS: this passage presents a genuine dilemma, not an argument for one side. Both action and inaction have moral costs. Balanced framing."},
{id:"np90",cat:"CARS",tags:["Application","Opposing Arguments"],diff:3,pass:"c10",q:"A genetic conservative would most likely oppose:",o:["Editing embryos to enhance intelligence due to unpredictable germline effects","Using somatic gene therapy to cure cystic fibrosis in a living patient","Performing prenatal genetic screening for common chromosomal disorders","Providing genetic counseling services to prospective parents prenatally"],a:0,ex:"Genetic conservatism specifically opposes GERMLINE modifications (changes passed to future generations) because long-term consequences are unpredictable. Editing embryos for enhancement directly modifies the germline. Somatic gene therapy (curing CF in a living patient) does NOT affect the germline and would not be opposed on these grounds. Prenatal screening and counseling do not involve genetic modification at all.",mn:"Genetic conservatism = don't alter germline (heritable). Somatic therapy OK (not inherited). Enhancement of embryos = germline change = opposed."},
{id:"np91",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Experimental Design","Kinetics Parameters"],diff:3,pass:"p20",q:"Based on Table 1, the IC50 of Compound X is approximately:",o:["Between 10 and 50 nM, where activity crosses the 50% inhibition threshold","Between 100 and 500 nM, where activity is already below 20%","Greater than 500 nM, since activity never reaches 50% inhibition","Exactly 100 nM, since this concentration was specifically tested"],a:0,ex:"IC50 is the concentration at which enzyme activity is inhibited by 50% (i.e., activity drops to 50% of normal). At 10 nM, activity is 75% (only 25% inhibited). At 50 nM, activity is 40% (60% inhibited). So 50% inhibition occurs somewhere between 10 and 50 nM. IC50 is a standard measure of inhibitor potency -- lower IC50 means more potent. This is a data interpretation question requiring you to read the table and interpolate between data points.",mn:"IC50 = concentration for 50% inhibition. Read table: 75% at 10nM, 40% at 50nM. 50% is between those two."},
{id:"np92",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p20",q:"The structural similarity between Compound X and HMG-CoA is consistent with:",o:["Competitive inhibition, where the drug mimics the substrate and binds the active site","Noncompetitive inhibition, where structural similarity is irrelevant to binding","Uncompetitive inhibition, where the drug binds only the enzyme-substrate complex","Allosteric activation, where similar structures enhance enzyme catalytic rate"],a:0,ex:"Competitive inhibitors typically resemble the substrate structurally because they must fit into the same active site. The passage states Compound X shares the hydroxymethylglutaryl moiety with HMG-CoA. This structural mimicry allows it to compete with the real substrate for the active site. This is consistent with Experiment 2 data showing excess substrate overcomes inhibition. Real-world example: statins are HMG-CoA analogs and competitive inhibitors of HMG-CoA reductase.",mn:"Structural similarity to substrate = fits active site = competitive. Statins work exactly this way in clinical medicine."},
{id:"np93",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p41",q:"The elevated citrate synthase activity (250% of normal) most likely reflects:",o:["Compensatory mitochondrial proliferation attempting to overcome the ETC deficiency","Increased Krebs cycle flux due to excess substrate availability","A secondary mutation in the citrate synthase gene causing overexpression","Normal variation in citrate synthase levels between individual patients"],a:0,ex:"Citrate synthase is a matrix enzyme used as a MARKER for mitochondrial mass. When the ETC is deficient, cells compensate by making MORE mitochondria (hence the ragged-red fibers on biopsy). More mitochondria = more citrate synthase, even though each individual mitochondrion is dysfunctional. The 250% level tells us the cells have roughly 2.5x more mitochondria than normal. This compensation is insufficient because each mitochondrion still has the tRNA mutation.",mn:"Citrate synthase = mitochondrial mass marker. 250% means 2.5x more mitochondria. Compensation for ETC deficiency = ragged red fibers."},
{id:"np94",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p41",q:"The mutant load difference between muscle (78%) and blood (45%) explains why:",o:["Symptoms are primarily muscular because higher mutant load causes greater ETC impairment in muscle tissue","Blood cells are more severely affected than muscle because they divide rapidly and accumulate mutations","The mutation affects all tissues equally since mitochondrial DNA is distributed uniformly across cell types","Genetic testing of peripheral blood leukocytes provides more accurate mutant load than muscle tissue biopsy"],a:0,ex:"Heteroplasmy means cells contain a mixture of normal and mutant mtDNA. The percentage of mutant copies (mutant load) varies between tissues and determines symptom severity. Higher mutant load in muscle (78%) causes more severe ETC dysfunction there, explaining why symptoms are primarily neuromuscular. Blood testing (45%) may underestimate the actual disease severity in affected tissues. This is why muscle biopsy is the gold standard for diagnosis -- it measures mutant load where it matters most.",mn:"Higher mutant load = more dysfunctional mitochondria = worse symptoms. Muscle 78% >> blood 45% = why symptoms are muscular, not hematologic."},
{id:"np95",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p41",q:"Complexes III and IV show partial activity (45% and 38%) because:",o:["They contain subunits encoded by mtDNA and are affected by the tRNA mutation, but not as severely as Complex I","They are entirely nuclear-encoded and unaffected by the mitochondrial mutation","The heteroplasmic mutation equally impairs all ETC complexes to the same degree","They are located in the outer mitochondrial membrane and are partially protected"],a:0,ex:"Complexes I, III, IV, and V all contain subunits encoded by mtDNA. The tRNA mutation impairs translation of ALL mtDNA-encoded proteins, but each complex has a different ratio of mtDNA-encoded to nuclear-encoded subunits. Complex I has the most mtDNA-encoded subunits (7 out of ~45), so it is most severely affected (12%). Complexes III and IV have fewer mtDNA-encoded subunits, so they retain more function. Complex V (85%) has relatively few mtDNA-encoded components. Complex II is 100% nuclear-encoded and unaffected.",mn:"More mtDNA-encoded subunits = more affected. Complex I (7 mtDNA subunits) >> III, IV (fewer) >> V (least) >> II (zero, all nuclear)."},
{id:"np96",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Experimental Design","Membrane Transport"],diff:2,pass:"p44",q:"Furosemide causes hypokalemia (low K+) because:",o:["Blocking NKCC2 delivers excess Na+ to the collecting duct, driving increased K+ secretion through ROMK channels","Furosemide directly pumps intracellular K+ into the tubular lumen through a specific potassium transporter","Loop diuretics simultaneously inhibit Na+/K+ ATPase across all segments of the nephron including the cortex","Potassium is primarily reabsorbed by the NKCC2 transporter, and blocking it prevents all K+ reabsorption"],a:0,ex:"NKCC2 in the ascending limb normally reabsorbs Na+, K+, and Cl-. When furosemide blocks NKCC2, more Na+ reaches the collecting duct. There, principal cells reabsorb this excess Na+ through ENaC channels, creating a more negative lumen that drives K+ secretion through ROMK channels. More Na+ delivery to collecting duct = more Na+/K+ exchange = more K+ lost in urine. This is the mechanism behind loop diuretic-induced hypokalemia, a common clinical side effect.",mn:"Block NKCC2 -> more Na+ at collecting duct -> more Na+ reabsorbed via ENaC -> more K+ secreted -> hypokalemia. Clinical pearl!"},
{id:"np97",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p44",q:"Furosemide abolishes the medullary gradient because:",o:["The ascending limb normally builds the gradient by reabsorbing NaCl without water, and NKCC2 blockade stops this","Furosemide directly extracts solutes from the medullary interstitium through a paracellular transport mechanism","The descending limb loses its aquaporin-1 channels and stops reabsorbing water after furosemide administration","Furosemide acts by blocking vasopressin V2 receptors on collecting duct principal cells preventing water reabsorption"],a:0,ex:"The countercurrent multiplier depends on the ascending limb actively pumping NaCl out WITHOUT water (it is water-impermeable). This creates a hyperosmotic medullary interstitium. The descending limb then equilibrates by losing water into this concentrated environment. This cycle multiplies the gradient to 1200 mOsm/L at the papilla. Furosemide blocks NKCC2, stopping NaCl reabsorption in the ascending limb. Without this active step, the medullary gradient dissipates, and even maximal ADH cannot concentrate urine effectively.",mn:"Ascending limb pumps NaCl out without water = builds medullary gradient. Block NKCC2 = no gradient = cannot concentrate urine even with ADH."},
{id:"np98",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p44",q:"The urine osmolarity of 300 mOsm/L after furosemide indicates that:",o:["Urine is isosmotic to plasma because the concentrating mechanism is abolished","The kidneys are producing maximally dilute urine at their lowest capacity","ADH levels have dramatically increased to compensate for water losses","The proximal tubule has taken over the concentrating function entirely"],a:0,ex:"Normal urine ranges from 50 (maximally dilute, no ADH) to 1200 (maximally concentrated, high ADH) mOsm/L. The concentrating mechanism requires the medullary gradient, which furosemide abolishes. Without the gradient, the collecting duct cannot concentrate urine above plasma osmolarity (~300 mOsm/L) regardless of ADH levels. The 300 mOsm/L result means urine leaves at plasma concentration -- the kidney can neither concentrate nor fully dilute it.",mn:"No medullary gradient = urine stuck at ~300 mOsm/L (isosmotic to plasma). Cannot concentrate above OR dilute fully below this."},
{id:"np99",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Experimental Design","Thermodynamics"],diff:3,pass:"p40",q:"The cooperative unfolding transition between 3-5 M urea indicates that:",o:["The protein unfolds in a concerted all-or-nothing manner rather than losing structure gradually piece by piece","Each domain of the protein unfolds independently at its own urea concentration","Urea concentration has no effect on the rate or extent of protein unfolding","The protein transitions through multiple stable partially folded intermediates"],a:0,ex:"Cooperativity in protein folding means the transition between folded and unfolded states is sharp -- once a critical destabilization point is reached, the entire structure unravels rapidly. This produces a sigmoidal unfolding curve. At 2 M urea, the protein is mostly intact (95% CD); at 5 M, it is mostly unfolded (8% CD). The sharp transition between 3-5 M indicates few stable intermediates -- it is largely two-state (folded vs unfolded). This cooperativity arises because each stabilizing interaction depends on the presence of others.",mn:"Cooperative = sharp all-or-nothing transition = few stable intermediates. Sigmoidal curve. Loss of one interaction destabilizes others."},
{id:"np100",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Acid-Base","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p40",q:"Based on the Tm data at different pH values, which conclusion is best supported?",o:["The protein is most stable near neutral pH and destabilized by both acidic and basic extremes","The protein becomes progressively more stable as pH increases from 2 to 9","pH has no significant effect on protein thermal stability measurements","The protein is most stable at its isoelectric point, which must be pH 7.0"],a:0,ex:"Tm data: pH 2=45C, pH 5=72C, pH 7=76C (highest), pH 9=68C. The protein is most thermally stable at pH 7 (highest Tm). Both very low pH (2) and moderately high pH (9) reduce stability. At pH 2, many side chains are protonated, disrupting salt bridges and changing charge distribution. At pH 9, deprotonation of certain residues similarly disrupts electrostatic interactions. This bell-shaped pH-stability curve is typical of globular proteins. The Tm at pH 2 is dramatically lower, likely because acid denatures the protein by disrupting many electrostatic interactions simultaneously.",mn:"Highest Tm = most stable. pH 7 = 76C is maximum. Both extremes lower Tm. Acid denatures by disrupting salt bridges and charge interactions."},
{id:"np101",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Buffers","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p25",q:"The buffering region extends from 15-35 mL because:",o:["This corresponds to pKa plus or minus 1 pH unit, where both HA and A- coexist in buffering concentrations","The acid-base indicator used changes color only within this specific volume range of NaOH additions","The NaOH titrant is too dilute to produce any measurable pH change outside this particular range","The solution reaches a stable thermodynamic equilibrium and the pH becomes invariant in this region"],a:0,ex:"A buffer works best when [HA] and [A-] are present in comparable amounts. By Henderson-Hasselbalch, the buffer range is approximately pKa +/- 1 pH unit (3.76 to 5.76 for this acid). At 15 mL NaOH, about 30% of HA is converted to A- (ratio ~1:0.43, pH ~4.4). At 35 mL, about 70% is converted (ratio ~1:2.3, pH ~5.1). Outside this range, one species dominates overwhelmingly and cannot buffer effectively. This is why buffer capacity is maximum at the half-equivalence point where [HA]=[A-].",mn:"Buffer range = pKa +/- 1 pH unit. Both HA and A- must be present in comparable amounts. Max capacity at half-equiv where [HA]=[A-]."},
{id:"np102",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Buffers","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p25",q:"For the diprotic acid H2A, the pH at the first half-equivalence point would be:",o:["3.0, equal to the first pKa of the diprotic acid","5.0, the average of the two pKa values of the acid","7.0, neutral pH at the midpoint of the titration curve","10.0, equal to the pKb of the second conjugate base"],a:0,ex:"For a diprotic acid, the first half-equivalence point occurs when half of H2A has been converted to HA-. At this point, [H2A] = [HA-], and by Henderson-Hasselbalch: pH = pKa1 + log([HA-]/[H2A]) = pKa1 + log(1) = pKa1 = 3.0. Similarly, the second half-equivalence point gives pH = pKa2 = 7.0. Between the two equivalence points, the pH at the midpoint (between first and second equivalence) equals the average of pKa1 and pKa2: (3.0+7.0)/2 = 5.0. Each pKa has its own half-equivalence plateau.",mn:"Half-equivalence point: [acid]=[conjugate base], so pH = pKa. First half-equiv of diprotic: pH = pKa1. Second: pH = pKa2."},
{id:"np103",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Redox Chemistry","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p27",q:"Based on Table 1, the data from Trials 2 and 3 confirm that:",o:["Cell voltage increases when the reaction quotient Q decreases, consistent with the Nernst equation","Cell voltage is independent of ion concentrations under all conditions","Increasing product concentration increases the driving force of the cell","Temperature is the only variable that affects cell voltage measurements"],a:0,ex:"Trial 2 has low [Cu2+] (reactant), raising Q = [Zn2+]/[Cu2+] = 1.0/0.01 = 100. Higher Q means the reaction has less driving force, so E decreases to 1.04V. Trial 3 has low [Zn2+] (product), lowering Q = 0.01/1.0 = 0.01. Lower Q means more driving force, so E increases to 1.16V. The Nernst equation predicts E = E-standard - (0.0592/n)logQ. Higher Q -> lower E. Lower Q -> higher E. Both trials confirm this relationship.",mn:"Nernst: E = E0 - (0.0592/n)logQ. High Q = low E (Trial 2). Low Q = high E (Trial 3). Reactant increase -> more voltage."},
{id:"np104",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p27",q:"In the electrolytic cell, the minimum voltage needed exceeds 1.10 V because:",o:["Overpotential is required to overcome both the thermodynamic cell potential and kinetic electrode barriers","Electrolytic cells always require exactly double the voltage produced by the corresponding galvanic cell","The KNO3 salt bridge introduces significant additional ohmic resistance that must be overcome by applied voltage","The physical reversal of electrode polarity requires additional energy proportional to the electrode surface area"],a:0,ex:"In a galvanic cell, the reaction Zn + Cu2+ -> Zn2+ + Cu is spontaneous (E = +1.10V, negative delta-G). To reverse it (electrolytic cell), you must supply at least 1.10V to overcome the thermodynamic barrier. In practice, even more voltage is needed due to overpotential -- kinetic barriers at the electrode surfaces including activation energy for electron transfer, concentration polarization, and ohmic resistance. The actual required voltage = theoretical minimum + overpotential.",mn:"Electrolytic: must exceed E-cell to reverse. Extra voltage needed = overpotential (kinetic barriers at electrodes). Theory + practice."},
{id:"np105",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p50",q:"Doubling the viscosity from 3.0 to 6.0 centipoise halves the flow rate because:",o:["Flow is inversely proportional to viscosity in Poiseuille's equation when pressure and geometry are held constant","Increased viscosity effectively doubles the tube radius according to the mathematical form of Poiseuille's equation","Higher viscosity fluid generates a larger pressure difference that partially compensates for the increased resistance","Viscosity affects flow rate only through its influence on the transition from laminar to turbulent flow patterns"],a:0,ex:"In Poiseuille's equation, Q = (pi*r^4*dP)/(8*eta*L), flow rate Q is inversely proportional to viscosity eta. If eta doubles from 3 to 6, Q is halved (320 -> 160 mL/min). This is a direct proportionality: Q is proportional to 1/eta. Clinically, polycythemia (increased red blood cells) increases blood viscosity, reducing flow and increasing cardiac workload. Conversely, anemia decreases viscosity and increases flow rate, which is why severely anemic patients may have heart murmurs from turbulent high-velocity flow.",mn:"Q proportional to 1/viscosity. Double viscosity = half flow. Clinical: polycythemia = high viscosity = reduced flow. Anemia = opposite."},
{id:"np106",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Cardiovascular System","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p50",q:"The 85% flow reduction from a 1 cm stenosis that halves the radius is explained by:",o:["The narrow segment dominates total resistance because resistance depends on r to the negative fourth power","The wider unconstricted portions of the tube simultaneously lose their capacity to conduct fluid effectively","Poiseuille's equation becomes inapplicable whenever the tube geometry changes along the length of the vessel","Fluid becomes fully turbulent at the constriction point and this turbulence completely blocks all forward flow"],a:0,ex:"The tube has two sections: 9 cm at r=2mm and 1 cm at r=1mm. Resistance is proportional to L/r^4. The narrow section has 16x higher resistance per unit length (r halved: (1/0.5)^4 = 16). Even though it is only 1/10 the length, its resistance is 16/10 = 1.6x that of the wider section. The narrow section becomes the bottleneck controlling total flow. This models arterial stenosis: a short plaque narrowing a vessel has an outsized effect on flow because of the r^4 dependence.",mn:"Short constriction dominates because R goes as 1/r^4. Even 1cm at half-radius creates 16x more resistance per cm = bottleneck effect."},
{id:"np107",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p50",q:"The parabolic velocity profile with maximum velocity at center indicates:",o:["Laminar flow, with fluid layers sliding past each other at velocities graded from zero at walls to max at center","Turbulent flow, with chaotic unpredictable fluid motion in all directions simultaneously throughout the tube","Static equilibrium, indicating the fluid is not actually undergoing net translational motion through the tube","Non-Newtonian flow behavior, where the apparent viscosity changes depending on the applied shear rate in the tube"],a:0,ex:"In laminar (smooth, layered) flow, the fluid touching the tube wall has zero velocity (no-slip condition). Velocity increases parabolically toward the center, where it reaches maximum (2x average velocity). This parabolic profile is characteristic of Poiseuille flow. Turbulent flow (Reynolds number > 2000) has a flatter, more uniform velocity profile with chaotic mixing. Clinically, blood flow is normally laminar but becomes turbulent at high velocities or constrictions, which produces bruits (audible sounds with stethoscope).",mn:"Parabolic velocity = laminar flow. Zero at walls, max at center = 2x average. Turbulent = flat profile + chaotic. Bruits = turbulence sound."},
{id:"np108",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Memory","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p30",q:"The 22% decrease in working memory capacity for Condition A women supports the mechanism that:",o:["Stereotype threat diverts working memory resources to anxiety and self-monitoring, leaving less for the test","Women have constitutively lower working memory capacity than men due to inherent neurobiological sex differences","The math test itself directly and equally depletes working memory capacity in all participants regardless of group","Working memory capacity has no measurable relationship to standardized test performance or academic achievement"],a:0,ex:"Stereotype threat does not reduce ability directly -- it diverts cognitive resources. When a negative stereotype is salient, affected individuals experience anxiety, self-doubt, and increased self-monitoring (Am I confirming the stereotype?). These processes consume working memory capacity, leaving fewer resources available for the actual task. The data support this: working memory decreases ONLY for the group under threat (Condition A women), not for men or for women in the no-threat condition. This is the processing efficiency theory of stereotype threat.",mn:"Stereotype threat works by consuming working memory via anxiety + self-monitoring. Not ability deficit but resource depletion. Only affects threatened group."},
{id:"np109",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p30",q:"The self-affirmation exercise reduces the gap by 60% most likely because:",o:["Affirming personal values buffers self-worth against the stereotype threat, reducing anxiety and freeing resources","Writing about personal values directly and specifically improves mathematical calculation and reasoning skills","The self-affirmation exercise completely and permanently eliminates all gender stereotypes from the testing context","The writing exercise simply distracts participants from noticing or processing the stereotype-relevant instructions"],a:0,ex:"Self-affirmation theory (Steele & Liu): when people affirm their core values, their sense of self-integrity is bolstered, making them less vulnerable to specific identity threats. The self-affirmation does not eliminate the stereotype -- it reduces its psychological impact by reminding the person that their worth is not contingent on performance in the stereotyped domain. This frees working memory resources that would otherwise be consumed by anxiety. The effect is partial (60% reduction, not elimination), suggesting some threat remains.",mn:"Self-affirmation buffers self-worth -> less anxiety -> more working memory available -> better performance. Partial protection, not elimination."},
{id:"np110",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Learning and Conditioning","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p51",q:"Group C's forgetting rate (24%) is much lower than Group A's (66%) because:",o:["Deep semantic encoding creates more retrieval pathways, making memories more resistant to decay and interference","Shallow structural processing creates the strongest and most durable long-term memory traces of all encoding types","The passage of time produces equal rates of forgetting regardless of how deeply information was originally encoded","Group C participants happened to have inherently superior memorization abilities compared to the other two groups"],a:0,ex:"Craik and Lockhart's levels of processing theory predicts not just better initial encoding but also slower forgetting for deeply processed material. Semantic processing creates rich, meaningful connections to existing knowledge networks, providing multiple retrieval cues. Structural processing creates sparse, surface-level traces with few connections, making them highly vulnerable to interference and decay. The data strongly support this: from immediate to one-week, structural loses 66% while semantic loses only 24%. Deep processing creates durable memories because they are embedded in a web of meaning.",mn:"Deep processing = more connections = more retrieval cues = slower forgetting. Shallow = sparse traces = fast decay. 66% vs 24% loss."},
{id:"np111",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Learning and Conditioning","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p51",q:"Group D's superior one-week recall (29.8 vs 21.5 for Group C) demonstrates:",o:["The testing effect: retrieval practice strengthens memory more than additional study of the same material","Semantic processing is unnecessary when retrieval practice is performed","Spending more total time on a task always produces better memory outcomes","Free recall and recognition produce identical memory strength outcomes"],a:0,ex:"The testing effect (Roediger & Karpicke, 2006) shows that actively retrieving information from memory strengthens the memory trace more than passively re-studying it. Group D used semantic processing PLUS retrieval practice (actively recalling words rather than re-reading them). This combination produced the best results. The mechanism: retrieval practice strengthens retrieval pathways, makes memories more accessible, and identifies gaps while there is still time to fix them. This is why practice testing is the single most effective study strategy supported by cognitive science.",mn:"Testing effect: active retrieval > passive re-study. Group D = semantic + retrieval practice = best. Most evidence-backed study strategy!"},
{id:"np112",cat:"CARS",tags:["Application","Opposing Arguments"],diff:3,pass:"c6",q:"Laudan's critique that Kuhn confuses difficulty with impossibility of comparison suggests that:",o:["Paradigms can be compared using empirical adequacy, even if the comparison is challenging and imperfect","All paradigms are identical and comparison is unnecessary between them","Kuhn's theory of normal science is entirely wrong and should be abandoned","Incommensurability is a stronger claim than Kuhn originally intended"],a:0,ex:"Laudan targets the strongest version of incommensurability. If paradigms truly cannot be compared at all, then choosing between them would be irrational. But Laudan argues Kuhn overstates the case: comparison is DIFFICULT (different terms, different standards) but not IMPOSSIBLE. Empirical adequacy -- which theory explains more observations, predicts more accurately -- provides a cross-paradigm standard. Einstein's physics is demonstrably more empirically adequate than Newton's in specific domains (Mercury's orbit, GPS timing). Kuhn himself acknowledged this in later work, softening his position.",mn:"CARS: Laudan says Kuhn goes too far. Comparison is hard, not impossible. Empirical adequacy provides a shared yardstick across paradigms."},
{id:"np113",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Strengthen/Weaken"],diff:2,pass:"c6",q:"Which historical example would best SUPPORT Kuhn's theory of paradigm shifts?",o:["The transition from phlogiston to oxygen theory, which redefined the fundamental concepts of combustion chemistry","The gradual improvement of optical telescope resolution over three continuous centuries of astronomical observation","The steady accumulation of newly discovered chemical elements that progressively filled the gaps in the periodic table","The incremental refinement of vaccine efficacy through systematic optimization in sequential clinical trial programs"],a:0,ex:"Kuhn's theory predicts revolutionary discontinuities, not gradual progress. The phlogiston-to-oxygen transition is a perfect example: phlogiston theory and oxygen theory do not just disagree about combustion -- they define different fundamental entities, different experimental standards, and different questions. The transition was not gradual addition of facts but a wholesale reconceptualization. The other options (telescope improvement, element discovery, vaccine optimization) all represent cumulative, gradual progress within a stable paradigm -- exactly what Kuhn calls normal science.",mn:"CARS support: find a revolutionary discontinuity, not gradual progress. Phlogiston to oxygen = complete reconceptualization = paradigm shift."},
{id:"np114",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:2,fmt:"except",q:"All of the following are irreversible enzymes of glycolysis EXCEPT:",o:["Aldolase, which cleaves fructose-1,6-bisphosphate into two 3-carbon molecules","Hexokinase, which phosphorylates glucose to glucose-6-phosphate irreversibly","PFK-1, which phosphorylates fructose-6-phosphate to fructose-1,6-bisphosphate","Pyruvate kinase, which converts PEP to pyruvate with ATP generation"],a:0,ex:"The three irreversible steps of glycolysis are hexokinase, PFK-1, and pyruvate kinase. These must be bypassed in gluconeogenesis by different enzymes. Aldolase is freely REVERSIBLE -- it operates in both glycolysis (forward) and gluconeogenesis (reverse). In EXCEPT questions, three options are true statements and the correct answer is the false one. Here, aldolase IS part of glycolysis but is NOT irreversible.",mn:"EXCEPT = find the false one. Irreversible steps: hexokinase, PFK-1, pyruvate kinase. Aldolase is reversible."},
{id:"np115",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Protein Structure"],diff:2,fmt:"except",q:"All of the following amino acids have charged side chains at pH 7.4 EXCEPT:",o:["Tryptophan, which has a bulky hydrophobic indole ring system","Aspartate, which carries a negative charge on its carboxylate side chain","Lysine, which carries a positive charge on its epsilon-amino group","Glutamate, which carries a negative charge on its carboxylate side chain"],a:0,ex:"At physiological pH 7.4, Asp (pKa ~3.65) and Glu (pKa ~4.25) are deprotonated and negatively charged. Lys (pKa ~10.5) is protonated and positively charged. Tryptophan has a nonpolar aromatic indole ring with no ionizable group at physiological pH -- it is NOT charged. This tests whether you know which amino acids are charged vs nonpolar.",mn:"Charged at pH 7.4: D, E (negative), K, R, H (positive). Trp is nonpolar aromatic -- no charge."},
{id:"np116",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Organelles","Membrane Transport"],diff:2,fmt:"except",q:"All of the following require ATP as an energy source EXCEPT:",o:["GLUT1-mediated glucose transport across the plasma membrane into erythrocytes","Na+/K+ ATPase transporting 3 Na+ out and 2 K+ into the cell","Ca2+ ATPase (SERCA) pumping calcium into the sarcoplasmic reticulum","H+/K+ ATPase in parietal cells secreting hydrochloric acid"],a:0,ex:"GLUT1 is a facilitated diffusion transporter -- glucose moves DOWN its concentration gradient through a channel protein with zero ATP cost. The Na+/K+ ATPase, SERCA, and H+/K+ ATPase all directly hydrolyze ATP to pump ions against their gradients (primary active transport). EXCEPT questions test your ability to identify the odd one out among similar-sounding processes.",mn:"GLUT = facilitated diffusion = no ATP. All ATPases use ATP directly. If it says ATPase, it uses ATP."},
{id:"np117",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Thermodynamics","Equilibrium"],diff:2,fmt:"except",q:"All of the following will increase the rate of a chemical reaction EXCEPT:",o:["Adding a catalyst, which lowers activation energy but does NOT change the rate","Increasing the temperature of the reaction system significantly","Increasing the concentration of the reactant molecules in solution","Grinding a solid reactant into fine powder to increase surface area"],a:0,ex:"This is a trick EXCEPT question! Catalysts DO increase rate by lowering activation energy. The answer choice says they do NOT change the rate, which is false -- catalysts absolutely increase rate. The other three (higher temperature, higher concentration, more surface area) all increase rate. On EXCEPT questions, read each option carefully. The 'correct' answer here contains a FALSE statement embedded within it.",mn:"Read carefully! The option SAYS catalyst doesn't change rate, which is wrong. Catalysts DO increase rate. The false claim IS the exception."},
{id:"np118",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System","Nervous System"],diff:2,fmt:"except",q:"All of the following are effects of sympathetic nervous system activation EXCEPT:",o:["Increased gastric motility and digestive enzyme secretion in the GI tract","Increased heart rate and force of cardiac contraction via beta-1 receptors","Bronchodilation of airways to increase oxygen intake during stress","Pupil dilation (mydriasis) to improve peripheral visual awareness"],a:0,ex:"Sympathetic activation is the fight-or-flight response. It DECREASES GI activity (diverts blood away from digestion) -- not increases it. Increased GI motility is a PARASYMPATHETIC effect (rest and digest). The other three options are all genuine sympathetic effects: increased heart rate (beta-1), bronchodilation (beta-2), and mydriasis (alpha-1).",mn:"Sympathetic = fight or flight = shuts down digestion. Increased GI motility is PARASYMPATHETIC (rest and digest)."},
{id:"np119",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Learning and Conditioning"],diff:2,fmt:"except",q:"All of the following are examples of negative reinforcement EXCEPT:",o:["Receiving a monetary fine for exceeding the posted speed limit on a highway","Taking aspirin to relieve a persistent headache that has been bothering you","Fastening your seatbelt to stop the annoying warning chime from sounding","Applying sunscreen to avoid the pain and discomfort of a sunburn later"],a:0,ex:"Negative reinforcement REMOVES an aversive stimulus to INCREASE behavior. Taking aspirin (removes headache), seatbelt (removes chime), and sunscreen (avoids sunburn pain) all remove/avoid something unpleasant, increasing the likelihood of repeating the behavior. A fine is POSITIVE PUNISHMENT: adding an aversive stimulus to DECREASE speeding behavior. Negative does NOT mean bad -- it means removal.",mn:"Negative reinforcement = REMOVE bad thing to INCREASE behavior. Fine = ADD bad thing to DECREASE behavior = positive punishment."},
{id:"np120",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Gene Regulation","Transcription/Translation"],diff:2,fmt:"except",q:"All of the following are features of eukaryotic mRNA processing EXCEPT:",o:["Addition of a poly-A tail at the 3-prime end by the ribosomal RNA processing complex","Addition of a 7-methylguanosine cap at the 5-prime end of the pre-mRNA transcript","Removal of introns by the spliceosome through recognition of splice site sequences","Alternative splicing to produce multiple different proteins from one single gene"],a:0,ex:"The poly-A tail is added by poly-A polymerase (PAP), not the ribosomal RNA processing complex. Ribosomes are involved in translation, not mRNA processing. The 5-prime cap, intron splicing, and alternative splicing are all genuine eukaryotic mRNA processing steps. This tests whether you can catch a plausible-sounding but incorrect enzyme attribution.",mn:"Poly-A tail is added by poly-A polymerase, not ribosomal machinery. Ribosomes translate mRNA, they don't process it."},
{id:"np121",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Mendelian Genetics","Inheritance Patterns"],diff:2,fmt:"except",q:"All of the following are consistent with autosomal recessive inheritance EXCEPT:",o:["An affected father transmitting the disease to all of his sons but none of his daughters","Two unaffected carrier parents having a 25% chance of an affected child per pregnancy","Consanguineous marriages increasing the probability of affected offspring in a family","The trait appearing to skip generations, with affected grandchildren from unaffected parents"],a:0,ex:"Father-to-all-sons-only is the hallmark of Y-LINKED inheritance (or X-linked dominant in some patterns), not autosomal recessive. In autosomal recessive, an affected father (aa) married to a carrier mother (Aa) has 50% affected sons AND 50% affected daughters -- gender doesn't matter because the gene is on an autosome. The sex-specific pattern is the giveaway that this isn't autosomal.",mn:"Autosomal = affects both sexes equally. If only sons affected, think sex-linked. Father-to-all-sons = Y-linked."},
{id:"np122",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics","Waves and Sound"],diff:2,fmt:"except",q:"All of the following increase when a light wave passes from air into glass EXCEPT:",o:["The wavelength of the light increases as it enters the denser medium","The degree of bending (refraction) increases with higher refractive index","The optical path length increases due to the slower speed in glass","The probability of total internal reflection when exiting back to air"],a:0,ex:"Wavelength DECREASES in glass, not increases. Since v = f*lambda and frequency stays constant while speed decreases (v = c/n), wavelength must decrease proportionally: lambda_glass = lambda_air / n. The other three options genuinely increase: higher n means more bending (Snell's law), longer optical path (same physical distance but slower), and lower critical angle (more likely TIR when exiting).",mn:"Speed down, frequency same, so wavelength DOWN in denser medium. lambda = v/f. Common MCAT trap!"},
{id:"np123",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions","Elimination Reactions"],diff:2,fmt:"except",q:"All of the following favor SN2 over SN1 EXCEPT:",o:["Using a polar protic solvent like methanol or water for the reaction medium","Using a strong nucleophile such as hydroxide or cyanide ion in solution","Using a primary or methyl substrate with minimal steric hindrance at carbon","Using a polar aprotic solvent such as DMSO or acetone for the reaction"],a:0,ex:"Polar PROTIC solvents (water, methanol, ethanol) STABILIZE carbocations through solvation, favoring SN1. They also solvate nucleophiles, reducing their reactivity for SN2. Polar APROTIC solvents (DMSO, acetone, DMF) keep nucleophiles reactive and favor SN2. Strong nucleophiles and unhindered substrates also favor SN2. The protic solvent is the odd one out.",mn:"Polar PROTIC = favors SN1 (stabilizes cation, solvates nuc). Polar APROTIC = favors SN2 (nuc stays reactive)."},
{id:"np124",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation"],diff:3,fmt:"twostep",q:"If rotenone blocks Complex I, what happens to the NADH/NAD+ ratio in the mitochondrial matrix?",o:["The ratio increases because NADH cannot be oxidized by the blocked Complex I","The ratio decreases because NADH production by the Krebs cycle stops immediately","The ratio stays the same because Complex II compensates for Complex I blockage","The ratio decreases because NADH is rapidly converted to FADH2 as compensation"],a:0,ex:"Two-step reasoning: Step 1 -- Rotenone blocks Complex I, which normally accepts electrons from NADH and converts it to NAD+. Step 2 -- If NADH cannot donate electrons, it accumulates while NAD+ is depleted. Therefore the NADH/NAD+ ratio INCREASES. This elevated ratio then secondarily inhibits the Krebs cycle dehydrogenases (which need NAD+ as an electron acceptor), slowing the entire cycle.",mn:"Step 1: Rotenone blocks NADH oxidation at Complex I. Step 2: NADH piles up, NAD+ drops. Ratio goes UP."},
{id:"np125",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Equilibrium"],diff:3,fmt:"twostep",q:"If a patient hyperventilates and blows off CO2, what happens to blood pH?",o:["pH increases because less CO2 means less carbonic acid and fewer H+ ions in blood","pH decreases because less CO2 means more oxygen displaces acid from hemoglobin","pH stays the same because bicarbonate buffer perfectly compensates for CO2 changes","pH decreases because CO2 loss triggers increased lactic acid production as compensation"],a:0,ex:"Two-step reasoning: Step 1 -- CO2 + H2O <-> H2CO3 <-> H+ + HCO3-. Blowing off CO2 shifts this equilibrium LEFT. Step 2 -- Shifting left means less H2CO3 formed, less H+ produced. Fewer H+ = higher pH = respiratory alkalosis. This is why hyperventilating patients feel tingling (from alkalosis-induced hypocalcemia). The bicarbonate buffer cannot perfectly compensate -- it is the very system being disrupted.",mn:"Step 1: Less CO2 shifts CO2 + H2O <-> H+ + HCO3- to the LEFT. Step 2: Less H+ means higher pH = alkalosis."},
{id:"np126",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Acid-Base","Hormones"],diff:3,fmt:"twostep",q:"A patient with Addison's disease (adrenal insufficiency) lacks aldosterone. What is the expected serum potassium level?",o:["Elevated (hyperkalemia) because without aldosterone, K+ is not secreted into the urine","Decreased (hypokalemia) because K+ is excreted more rapidly without aldosterone","Normal because potassium is regulated independently of aldosterone through other channels","Elevated initially but then normal as the body compensates through increased GFR"],a:0,ex:"Two-step reasoning: Step 1 -- Aldosterone acts on principal cells in the collecting duct, stimulating ENaC (Na+ reabsorption) and ROMK (K+ secretion). Step 2 -- Without aldosterone, K+ secretion stops, so K+ accumulates in the blood = hyperkalemia. Simultaneously, Na+ is not reabsorbed, leading to hyponatremia and volume depletion. This is why Addison's disease presents with hyperkalemia + hyponatremia.",mn:"Step 1: Aldosterone drives K+ secretion via ROMK channels. Step 2: No aldosterone = no K+ secretion = hyperkalemia."},
{id:"np127",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Signal Transduction","Cell Cycle"],diff:3,fmt:"twostep",q:"If a mutation causes the Rb protein to be permanently phosphorylated, what is the consequence?",o:["Uncontrolled S-phase entry because E2F is permanently released and always activates S-phase genes","Permanent cell cycle arrest because phosphorylated Rb binds E2F more tightly than unphosphorylated Rb","Normal cell cycle regulation because Rb phosphorylation state has no effect on E2F activity","Increased apoptosis because permanently phosphorylated Rb activates caspase signaling cascades"],a:0,ex:"Two-step reasoning: Step 1 -- Normal Rb binds and sequesters E2F transcription factor in G1, preventing S-phase entry. Phosphorylation by cyclin-CDK releases E2F. Step 2 -- If Rb is PERMANENTLY phosphorylated, E2F is ALWAYS free, continuously activating genes for DNA synthesis. The cell enters S phase without normal checkpoints = uncontrolled proliferation. This is functionally equivalent to Rb loss-of-function (a tumor suppressor mutation).",mn:"Step 1: pRb releases E2F. Step 2: Permanent pRb = always-free E2F = uncontrolled S phase. Acts like Rb knockout = cancer."},
{id:"np128",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Amino Acid Properties"],diff:3,fmt:"twostep",q:"If all cysteine residues in a protein are mutated to serine, how would the denatured protein behave differently during refolding?",o:["Refolding would be less stable because no disulfide bonds can form to lock the tertiary structure","Refolding would be more efficient because serine forms stronger hydrogen bonds than cysteine","Refolding would be unaffected because disulfide bonds do not contribute to protein stability","Refolding would be impossible because serine cannot participate in any non-covalent interactions"],a:0,ex:"Two-step reasoning: Step 1 -- Cysteine's thiol (-SH) groups form disulfide bonds (S-S), the only covalent crosslinks in tertiary structure. Serine has a hydroxyl (-OH) that cannot form disulfide bonds. Step 2 -- Without disulfide bonds, the refolded protein cannot be locked into its native conformation. Hydrophobic interactions and hydrogen bonds still drive folding, but the final structure is less stable and more prone to unfolding. This mirrors the DTT experiment in the lysozyme passage.",mn:"Step 1: Cys->Ser eliminates all disulfide bonds. Step 2: No covalent crosslinks = less stable fold. Same logic as DTT experiment."},
{id:"np129",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Brain Anatomy","Nervous System"],diff:3,fmt:"twostep",q:"A stroke destroys Wernicke's area. Why would the patient still be able to produce fluent speech?",o:["Wernicke's area processes language comprehension, not production -- Broca's area handles speech output and is intact","Wernicke's area controls motor planning for all voluntary movements including speech articulation","Speech production originates in the cerebellum, which is unaffected by cortical strokes","The patient would not be able to speak at all because Wernicke's area is required for all language functions"],a:0,ex:"Two-step reasoning: Step 1 -- Wernicke's area (posterior temporal lobe) is responsible for language COMPREHENSION. Broca's area (frontal lobe) is responsible for speech PRODUCTION. Step 2 -- If Wernicke's is destroyed but Broca's is intact, the patient can still produce fluent speech, but the content will be nonsensical (word salad) because comprehension is lost. This is Wernicke's aphasia: fluent but meaningless speech.",mn:"Step 1: Wernicke's = comprehension. Broca's = production. Step 2: Destroy comprehension only = fluent but meaningless speech."},
{id:"np130",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Thermodynamics"],diff:3,fmt:"twostep",q:"If a galvanic cell reaches equilibrium, what is the cell voltage?",o:["Exactly zero, because at equilibrium delta-G equals zero and E equals delta-G divided by negative nF","Equal to the standard cell potential because equilibrium restores standard conditions","Maximum, because equilibrium represents the most thermodynamically favorable state","Negative, because the reverse reaction begins to dominate at equilibrium"],a:0,ex:"Two-step reasoning: Step 1 -- At equilibrium, delta-G = 0 (no net driving force for the reaction). Step 2 -- The relationship delta-G = -nFE means if delta-G = 0, then E must also equal 0. A dead battery has reached equilibrium -- there is no potential difference to drive electron flow. Q = K at equilibrium, and the Nernst equation gives E = E-standard - (RT/nF)ln(K) = 0 when Q reaches K.",mn:"Step 1: Equilibrium means delta-G = 0. Step 2: delta-G = -nFE, so if delta-G = 0, E must = 0. Dead battery."},
{id:"np131",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Functional Groups","Acid-Base"],diff:3,fmt:"twostep",q:"Acetic acid (pKa 4.76) is much more acidic than ethanol (pKa 16). What is the primary reason?",o:["The conjugate base acetate is resonance-stabilized by two equivalent oxygens, spreading the negative charge","The O-H bond in acetic acid is inherently weaker than the O-H bond in ethanol","Acetic acid has a higher molecular weight than ethanol, making it more acidic","The methyl group in acetic acid is electron-withdrawing, pulling electron density from the O-H bond"],a:0,ex:"Two-step reasoning: Step 1 -- Acidity depends on conjugate base stability. More stable conjugate base = stronger acid. Step 2 -- Acetate (CH3COO-) has two resonance structures spreading the negative charge equally over two oxygens. Ethoxide (CH3CH2O-) has the full negative charge localized on one oxygen with no resonance. Delocalized charge = more stable = more acidic. This resonance stabilization accounts for the 11-unit pKa difference.",mn:"Step 1: Stronger acid = more stable conjugate base. Step 2: Acetate has resonance (charge on 2 O's). Ethoxide has none (charge on 1 O)."},
{id:"np132",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Experimental Design"],diff:3,fmt:"twostep",q:"A researcher finds that participants who study material in the same room where they take the test perform better than those who study and test in different rooms. This is best explained by:",o:["Context-dependent memory, where environmental cues present during encoding serve as retrieval cues during testing","The spacing effect, where distributed practice across different rooms improves long-term retention","Proactive interference, where old memories from the study room enhance performance on new material","The serial position effect, where items studied in a familiar room are recalled from the recency buffer"],a:0,ex:"Two-step reasoning: Step 1 -- Environmental context (the room, lighting, smells, sounds) becomes encoded alongside the studied material as part of the memory trace. Step 2 -- When the same context is present during retrieval, it provides additional retrieval cues that help access the stored information. Different context = fewer cues = worse recall. This is Tulving's encoding specificity principle. It also explains state-dependent memory (same internal state helps retrieval).",mn:"Step 1: Context gets encoded with material. Step 2: Same context at test = more retrieval cues = better recall. Encoding specificity."},
{id:"np133",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Aerobic Respiration","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:3,fmt:"twostep",q:"Cyanide inhibits Complex IV. Why does this also stop the Krebs cycle even though cyanide does not directly act on any Krebs cycle enzyme?",o:["Without the ETC running, NADH cannot be reoxidized to NAD+, and the Krebs cycle dehydrogenases require NAD+ as an electron acceptor","Cyanide directly inhibits citrate synthase, the first enzyme of the Krebs cycle, by binding to its iron center","Complex IV generates the acetyl-CoA that fuels the Krebs cycle, so blocking it cuts off substrate supply","Cyanide causes mitochondrial membrane rupture, physically destroying the compartment where the Krebs cycle operates"],a:0,ex:"Two-step reasoning: Step 1 -- Cyanide blocks Complex IV, halting all electron flow through the ETC. Without electron flow, NADH cannot be oxidized back to NAD+. Step 2 -- The Krebs cycle requires NAD+ as an electron acceptor at three steps (isocitrate DH, alpha-KG DH, malate DH). Without NAD+, these dehydrogenases cannot function, and the cycle stalls. The ETC and Krebs cycle are coupled through the NAD+/NADH ratio.",mn:"Step 1: Cyanide blocks ETC -> NADH piles up, no NAD+. Step 2: Krebs needs NAD+ for 3 dehydrogenases -> cycle stops. Coupled systems!"},
{id:"np134",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System","Experimental Design"],diff:2,fmt:"data",q:"A patient's lab results show: hemoglobin 8 g/dL (normal: 12-16), MCV 110 fL (normal: 80-100), serum B12 is low. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Megaloblastic anemia from B12 deficiency, causing large, immature red blood cells","Iron deficiency anemia, which typically produces small (microcytic) red blood cells","Sickle cell anemia, which is caused by a hemoglobin gene mutation and not B12 levels","Aplastic anemia, which is caused by bone marrow failure and affects all cell lines"],a:0,ex:"Data interpretation: Low Hb = anemia. High MCV (>100) = MACROcytic = large RBCs. Low B12 = the cause. B12 is required for DNA synthesis (thymidylate synthesis). Without it, RBC precursors cannot divide properly and remain large (megaloblastic). Iron deficiency causes MICROcytic anemia (low MCV). Sickle cell is a hemoglobin mutation (HbS), not B12-related. Aplastic anemia is pancytopenia from marrow failure.",mn:"Low Hb + high MCV + low B12 = megaloblastic anemia. High MCV = big cells = macro. Low MCV = small cells = micro."},
{id:"np135",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Solutions","Acid-Base"],diff:2,fmt:"data",q:"A solution is prepared by dissolving 0.1 mol NaOH in water to make 500 mL of solution. What is the pH?",o:["13, because [OH-] = 0.2M, pOH = 0.7, and pH = 14 minus 0.7 equals approximately 13","1, because NaOH is a strong base with concentration 0.1M and pH equals negative log of concentration","7, because any sodium-containing solution is neutral due to sodium being from a strong base","10, because the solution is dilute and dilute bases have pH values around 10"],a:0,ex:"Data interpretation: [NaOH] = 0.1 mol / 0.5 L = 0.2 M. NaOH fully dissociates, so [OH-] = 0.2M. pOH = -log(0.2) = -log(2 x 10^-1) = -(0.3 + (-1)) = 0.7. pH = 14 - 0.7 = 13.3, approximately 13. NaOH is a strong base, so pH must be well above 7. pH 1 would be a strong acid. Always calculate: n/V for concentration, then decide if acid or base.",mn:"n/V = 0.1/0.5 = 0.2M OH-. pOH = -log(0.2) approximately 0.7. pH = 14 - 0.7 = 13.3."},
{id:"np136",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Experimental Design"],diff:2,fmt:"data",q:"An experiment measures O2 consumption in isolated mitochondria. After adding ADP, O2 consumption increases 5-fold. This increase is called:",o:["Respiratory control, demonstrating that the ETC is tightly coupled to ATP synthesis and requires ADP","Uncoupling, where the proton gradient is dissipated as heat independent of ATP synthesis","Substrate-level phosphorylation, where ATP is produced directly without oxygen consumption","Allosteric inhibition, where ADP binding to Complex IV increases electron transfer efficiency"],a:0,ex:"Data interpretation: O2 consumption increases when ADP is added because ADP is the substrate for ATP synthase. Without ADP, the proton gradient builds up and slows the ETC (backpressure). Adding ADP allows ATP synthase to run, dissipating the gradient, which allows the ETC to speed up and consume more O2. This tight coupling between ATP synthesis and O2 consumption is called respiratory control. The ratio (with ADP / without ADP) is the respiratory control ratio.",mn:"No ADP = gradient builds up = ETC slows. Add ADP = ATP synthase runs = gradient drops = ETC speeds up = more O2 consumed."},
{id:"np137",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:2,fmt:"data",q:"In a study, participants who receive $1 for lying about a boring task rate it as more enjoyable (6.2/10) than those paid $20 (3.8/10). This demonstrates:",o:["Cognitive dissonance -- insufficient justification for lying creates discomfort that is resolved by changing the attitude","Social learning theory -- participants imitated the experimenter's positive attitude toward the task","Self-serving bias -- participants credited their enjoyment to their own personality rather than the money","Hawthorne effect -- being observed during the experiment caused participants to report higher enjoyment"],a:0,ex:"Data interpretation: This is Festinger and Carlsmith's classic 1959 study. The $1 group changed their attitude MORE because $1 is insufficient justification for lying. They experience dissonance (I lied but had no good reason), resolved by actually believing the task was enjoyable. The $20 group has sufficient external justification (I lied for good money), so no dissonance, no attitude change. Less external justification = more internal attitude change.",mn:"Less money = less justification for lying = more dissonance = more attitude change. Festinger's $1/$20 study. Counterintuitive!"},
{id:"np138",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Experimental Design"],diff:3,fmt:"data",q:"Blood flows at 30 cm/s through an artery with cross-sectional area 3 cm-squared. If the artery narrows to an area of 1 cm-squared at a stenosis, the blood velocity at the stenosis is:",o:["90 cm/s, calculated from the continuity equation A1*v1 = A2*v2","30 cm/s, because velocity is constant throughout a continuous vessel","10 cm/s, because narrowing the artery slows the blood flow proportionally","270 cm/s, because velocity scales with the cube of the area ratio"],a:0,ex:"Data interpretation using the continuity equation: A1*v1 = A2*v2. So 3*30 = 1*v2. v2 = 90 cm/s. When a tube narrows, the same volume must pass through per unit time (conservation of mass for incompressible fluids). Smaller area means faster flow. This is why atherosclerotic stenoses cause turbulent flow -- the blood speeds up dramatically at the narrow point. If velocity exceeds the critical Reynolds number, laminar flow transitions to turbulent.",mn:"A1*v1 = A2*v2. 3 x 30 = 1 x v2. v2 = 90 cm/s. Narrower tube = faster flow (conservation of mass)."},
{id:"np139",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Population Genetics","Experimental Design"],diff:3,fmt:"data",q:"In a population, 1 in 10,000 individuals is affected with an autosomal recessive disease. What fraction of the population are carriers?",o:["Approximately 2%, because q equals 1/100 so 2pq equals roughly 2 times 99/100 times 1/100","Approximately 50%, because half the population must carry one copy of any recessive allele","Approximately 0.01%, because carriers are always rarer than affected homozygous individuals","Exactly 25%, because the Aa genotype frequency is always one-quarter in any population"],a:0,ex:"Data interpretation with Hardy-Weinberg: q-squared = 1/10,000 = 0.0001. So q = sqrt(0.0001) = 0.01. p = 1 - 0.01 = 0.99. Carrier frequency = 2pq = 2(0.99)(0.01) = 0.0198, approximately 2% or 1 in 50. Key insight: carriers (2pq) vastly outnumber affected individuals (q-squared) for rare recessive diseases. 200x more carriers than affected in this case!",mn:"q^2 = 1/10,000 -> q = 1/100. 2pq = 2(0.99)(0.01) = ~2%. Carriers >> affected for rare recessives."},
];

