// PROMPT 2: NEW CONTENT (20 passages, 62 questions)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════
Object.assign(PASSAGES, {
"p60":{"text":"Researchers investigate the urea cycle in a patient presenting with hyperammonemia and altered mental status. Blood tests reveal plasma ammonia of 340 micromol/L (normal: 11-32), glutamine elevated at 1200 micromol/L (normal: 390-650), and low plasma citrulline at 5 micromol/L (normal: 20-50). Urine orotic acid is within normal range. The urea cycle converts toxic ammonia to urea through five enzymatic steps: carbamoyl phosphate synthetase I (CPS I) produces carbamoyl phosphate in the mitochondrial matrix, which condenses with ornithine via ornithine transcarbamylase (OTC) to form citrulline. Citrulline exits to the cytoplasm where argininosuccinate synthetase adds aspartate, argininosuccinate lyase cleaves to form arginine, and arginase releases urea, regenerating ornithine. Table 1 shows enzyme activities in the patient's liver biopsy compared to controls: CPS I activity is 12% of normal, OTC is 98%, argininosuccinate synthetase is 95%, argininosuccinate lyase is 102%, and arginase is 97%. The researchers note that N-acetylglutamate (NAG), an obligate activator of CPS I, was undetectable in the patient's liver tissue. Administration of carglumic acid, a synthetic NAG analog, reduced plasma ammonia to 45 micromol/L within 48 hours."},
"p61":{"text":"A research team studies the molecular basis of sickle cell disease (SCD) by comparing hemoglobin structure and oxygen-binding properties in normal (HbA) and sickle (HbS) erythrocytes. SCD results from a single nucleotide substitution (GAG to GTG) in codon 6 of the beta-globin gene, replacing glutamic acid with valine. The researchers perform hemoglobin electrophoresis at pH 8.6 on cellulose acetate and observe that HbS migrates more slowly toward the anode than HbA. In Experiment 1, oxygen dissociation curves are measured for purified HbA and HbS. Both show sigmoidal curves with similar P50 values (26 mmHg for HbA, 28 mmHg for HbS) under oxygenated conditions. However, when deoxygenated, HbS polymerizes into rigid fibers visible on electron microscopy, while HbA remains soluble. In Experiment 2, the team measures sickling rates at varying oxygen tensions. At PO2 of 40 mmHg (venous), 15% of HbS erythrocytes show sickling. At PO2 of 25 mmHg (exercising muscle), sickling increases to 62%. At PO2 of 100 mmHg (arterial), sickling is 0%. In Experiment 3, cells from a patient heterozygous for HbS (sickle cell trait, HbAS) show only 3% sickling at PO2 40 mmHg. Co-inheritance of alpha-thalassemia reduces sickling by 40% in HbSS patients."},
"p62":{"text":"Researchers study cardiac electrophysiology by recording action potentials from isolated ventricular cardiomyocytes. A standard ventricular action potential has five phases: Phase 0 (rapid depolarization) results from opening of voltage-gated Na+ channels, producing a sharp upstroke from -90 mV to +20 mV. Phase 1 (early repolarization) involves transient outward K+ current. Phase 2 (plateau) is maintained by balance between inward L-type Ca2+ channels and outward delayed rectifier K+ channels. Phase 3 (repolarization) occurs when K+ efflux exceeds Ca2+ influx. Phase 4 (resting potential) is maintained by K+ leak channels and the Na+/K+ ATPase. In Experiment 1, the team applies tetrodotoxin (TTX), a voltage-gated Na+ channel blocker. Phase 0 upstroke velocity decreases from 200 V/s to 30 V/s, and conduction velocity slows from 0.5 m/s to 0.1 m/s. In Experiment 2, nifedipine (L-type Ca2+ channel blocker) is applied. The plateau phase shortens from 250 ms to 80 ms, and contractile force decreases by 75%. In Experiment 3, the researchers measure action potentials from sinoatrial (SA) node cells and find no fast Na+ upstroke; instead, Phase 0 depends on slow Ca2+ channels, producing a slower upstroke velocity of 5 V/s."},
"p63":{"text":"A study examines protein misfolding in neurodegenerative diseases by comparing normal cellular prion protein (PrPC) with its pathological conformer (PrPSc). PrPC is a GPI-anchored glycoprotein expressed on neuronal surfaces, predominantly alpha-helical in structure (42% alpha-helix, 3% beta-sheet). PrPSc adopts a beta-sheet-rich conformation (30% alpha-helix, 43% beta-sheet) that is resistant to protease digestion and detergent solubilization. In Experiment 1, researchers incubate purified PrPC with catalytic amounts of PrPSc in vitro. After 72 hours, protease-resistant PrP increases 100-fold, demonstrating that PrPSc templates the conversion of PrPC without any nucleic acid involvement. In Experiment 2, transgenic mice expressing PrPC are inoculated with PrPSc. Mice develop spongiform encephalopathy at 180 days. Knockout mice lacking the PrPC gene (Prnp-/-) inoculated with PrPSc show no disease even after 600 days. In Experiment 3, PrPSc aggregates are treated with increasing concentrations of guanidinium hydrochloride (GdnHCl). At 3M GdnHCl, PrPSc unfolds completely and loses both its protease resistance and its ability to convert PrPC in vitro. Refolding from 3M GdnHCl produces PrPC-like structure, not PrPSc."},
"p64":{"text":"Students construct a galvanic cell using zinc and copper half-cells connected by a salt bridge containing KNO3 solution. The zinc electrode (Zn/Zn2+, E0 = -0.76 V) serves as the anode, and the copper electrode (Cu2+/Cu, E0 = +0.34 V) serves as the cathode. The standard cell potential is E0cell = E0cathode - E0anode = +0.34 - (-0.76) = +1.10 V. In Experiment 1, both solutions are 1.0 M at 25C. The measured cell potential is 1.10 V, matching the calculated standard potential. In Experiment 2, the Zn2+ concentration is increased to 10.0 M while Cu2+ remains at 1.0 M. The measured potential decreases to 1.07 V. In Experiment 3, Cu2+ is increased to 10.0 M while Zn2+ remains at 1.0 M. The measured potential increases to 1.13 V. In Experiment 4, the salt bridge is removed. The voltage immediately drops to 0 V. In Experiment 5, the temperature is raised to 50C with both solutions at 1.0 M. The cell potential decreases slightly to 1.08 V. The students note that over time, the zinc electrode loses mass while the copper electrode gains mass."},
"p65":{"text":"A clinical study examines blood pH regulation in patients with different acid-base disorders. Normal arterial blood has pH 7.40, PCO2 40 mmHg, and HCO3- 24 mEq/L. The Henderson-Hasselbalch equation relates these values: pH = 6.1 + log([HCO3-] / (0.03 x PCO2)). At normal values: pH = 6.1 + log(24 / 1.2) = 6.1 + log(20) = 6.1 + 1.3 = 7.4. Patient A presents after a heroin overdose with respiratory depression: pH 7.18, PCO2 70, HCO3- 26. Patient B has uncontrolled diabetes with Kussmaul breathing: pH 7.10, PCO2 15, HCO3- 5. Patient C has severe vomiting for 3 days: pH 7.55, PCO2 48, HCO3- 38. Patient D is hyperventilating due to anxiety: pH 7.52, PCO2 24, HCO3- 22. The bicarbonate buffer system works in conjunction with the kidneys (which regulate HCO3- reabsorption over hours to days) and the lungs (which regulate CO2 elimination within minutes). Carbonic anhydrase catalyzes the reaction CO2 + H2O to H2CO3, which rapidly dissociates to H+ and HCO3-."},
"p66":{"text":"Researchers use spectroscopic techniques to identify an unknown organic compound. In UV-visible spectroscopy, the compound shows strong absorption at 254 nm (pi to pi-star transition) and a weaker absorption at 330 nm (n to pi-star transition). In infrared spectroscopy, prominent peaks appear at 3300 cm-1 (broad, O-H stretch), 1710 cm-1 (strong, C=O stretch), 1600 and 1500 cm-1 (aromatic C=C stretches), and 1250 cm-1 (C-O stretch). Proton NMR reveals the following signals: a singlet at 11.8 ppm (1H, exchangeable with D2O), a doublet at 8.1 ppm (2H), a doublet at 7.5 ppm (2H), and a singlet at 3.9 ppm (3H). The molecular formula determined by mass spectrometry is C8H8O3 with a molecular weight of 152. The degree of unsaturation is calculated as (2x8 + 2 - 8) / 2 = 5, consistent with a benzene ring (4 degrees) plus one additional degree of unsaturation. The para-substitution pattern is evident from the two doublets in the aromatic region, each integrating for 2H."},
"p67":{"text":"A psychology department replicates a modified version of Milgram's obedience experiments to study situational factors affecting compliance with authority. In the original 1963 study, 65% of participants administered the maximum 450-volt shock to a confederate learner when instructed by an experimenter in a lab coat. In the replication, Condition A (baseline) places the participant in an adjacent room from the learner with audio feedback only; 61% reach maximum voltage. In Condition B (proximity), the participant is in the same room as the learner; obedience drops to 40%. In Condition C (touch), the participant must physically place the learner's hand on a shock plate; obedience drops to 30%. In Condition D (absent authority), the experimenter gives instructions by telephone rather than in person; obedience drops to 21%. In Condition E (peer rebellion), two confederate teachers refuse to continue at 150V and 210V respectively; only 10% of real participants continue to maximum voltage. In Condition F (ordinary setting), the experiment is conducted in a plain office building rather than a university lab; obedience drops to 48%. Across all conditions, participants show visible signs of distress including sweating, trembling, and nervous laughter."},
"p68":{"text":"Researchers investigate stereotype threat effects on standardized test performance across multiple demographic groups. In Experiment 1, Black and White college students take a difficult verbal test. In the diagnostic condition (told it measures intellectual ability), Black students score significantly lower than White students (mean difference = 1.2 SD). In the non-diagnostic condition (described as a problem-solving exercise), the gap narrows to 0.3 SD, a non-significant difference. In Experiment 2, women and men take a challenging math test. When told the test typically shows gender differences, women score 15% lower than men. When told the test is gender-fair, women and men score equally. In Experiment 3, the researchers measure working memory capacity during testing using a dual-task paradigm. Stereotype-threatened participants show a 20% reduction in working memory capacity compared to non-threatened controls, suggesting that stereotype threat consumes cognitive resources through anxiety and self-monitoring. In Experiment 4, a simple intervention is tested: before the exam, students write a brief essay affirming their personal values (self-affirmation). This reduces the performance gap by 40%. The researchers propose that stereotype threat creates an extra cognitive load of rumination and vigilance that depletes the executive resources needed for complex problem-solving."},
"p69":{"text":"A longitudinal study examines the relationship between chronic psychological stress, cortisol dysregulation, and immune function in 200 medical students over their four-year training. Salivary cortisol is measured at waking, 30 minutes post-waking (cortisol awakening response, or CAR), and at bedtime. Immune function is assessed via natural killer (NK) cell activity, T-cell proliferation response to mitogen stimulation, and secretory IgA levels. At baseline (Year 1), students show a normal diurnal cortisol pattern: low at waking (8 nmol/L), peak at 30 minutes (18 nmol/L), declining to 2 nmol/L at bedtime. During exam periods, the pattern shifts: waking cortisol rises to 14 nmol/L and bedtime cortisol fails to suppress (remaining at 7 nmol/L), indicating a flattened diurnal curve. Table 1 shows immune changes during exam weeks versus baseline: NK cell activity decreases 35%, T-cell proliferation decreases 22%, secretory IgA decreases 18%, and upper respiratory infections increase 3-fold. Students reporting the highest perceived stress (top quartile on the Perceived Stress Scale) show the greatest immune suppression. By Year 4, students with consistently high stress show a chronically flattened cortisol curve even during non-exam periods."},
"p70":{"text":"Pharmacologists study the absorption, distribution, metabolism, and elimination of Drug Y, a weak acid with pKa 4.5 and molecular weight 320 Da. In Experiment 1, oral bioavailability is measured by comparing area-under-the-curve (AUC) after oral versus intravenous administration. Oral bioavailability is 72%. The drug is absorbed primarily in the stomach (pH 1.5-3.5) and proximal duodenum (pH 5-6). Using the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation for weak acids: at stomach pH 2, the ratio of protonated (HA) to deprotonated (A-) forms is: pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]), so 2 = 4.5 + log([A-]/[HA]), giving [A-]/[HA] = 1/316. Thus 99.7% of the drug is in the protonated (uncharged) form, which crosses lipid membranes readily. At intestinal pH 6, the ratio reverses: [A-]/[HA] = 31.6/1, so 97% is ionized and poorly absorbed. In Experiment 2, the drug is found to be 95% plasma protein-bound. Only the free (unbound) fraction is pharmacologically active. In Experiment 3, the drug is metabolized by hepatic CYP3A4 via Phase I oxidation, then conjugated with glucuronic acid (Phase II). Co-administration of grapefruit juice (a CYP3A4 inhibitor) increases AUC by 180%."},
"p71":{"text":"Audiologists investigate the mechanics of sound transduction by measuring hearing thresholds and cochlear responses in patients with different types of hearing loss. Sound waves enter the external ear, vibrate the tympanic membrane, and are transmitted through the ossicles (malleus, incus, stapes) to the oval window. The ossicles amplify sound pressure by approximately 22x through two mechanisms: the area ratio of the tympanic membrane to the oval window (17:1) and the lever action of the ossicle chain (1.3:1). In the cochlea, pressure waves in the perilymph cause displacement of the basilar membrane. The basilar membrane is tonotopically organized: the base (narrow, stiff) responds to high frequencies (20,000 Hz) and the apex (wide, flexible) responds to low frequencies (20 Hz). Inner hair cells transduce mechanical displacement into electrical signals via mechanically-gated K+ channels on their stereocilia. Patient A has conductive hearing loss (otosclerosis, stapes fixation): bone conduction thresholds are normal (0-10 dB) but air conduction thresholds are elevated (40-50 dB) across all frequencies. Patient B has sensorineural hearing loss (noise-induced): both air and bone conduction thresholds are elevated (50-60 dB), primarily at 4000 Hz. Patient C has presbycusis (age-related): bilateral symmetric high-frequency sensorineural loss, with thresholds of 10 dB at 250 Hz rising to 65 dB at 8000 Hz."},
"c11":{"text":"Thomas Kuhn's The Structure of Scientific Revolutions challenged the prevailing view that science progresses through a steady accumulation of knowledge. Kuhn argued instead that scientific development follows a cyclical pattern of normal science punctuated by revolutionary upheavals. During periods of normal science, researchers work within an accepted paradigm -- a framework of theories, methods, and standards that defines legitimate problems and acceptable solutions. Scientists engaged in normal science do not seek to test the paradigm but rather to extend its application, a process Kuhn compared to puzzle-solving rather than discovery. Anomalies inevitably accumulate -- results that resist explanation within the reigning paradigm. Initially, these anomalies are dismissed, attributed to experimental error, or shelved as problems for future investigation. Only when anomalies become sufficiently severe and numerous does a crisis emerge, opening the field to competing theoretical frameworks. The resolution of a crisis through adoption of a new paradigm constitutes a scientific revolution. Crucially, Kuhn argued that paradigm shifts are not purely rational events decided by evidence alone. Competing paradigms are incommensurable: they define problems differently, employ different standards of evaluation, and even perceive data through different conceptual lenses. Scientists working in different paradigms literally see the world differently. The choice between paradigms therefore involves sociological and psychological factors alongside empirical ones -- a claim that provoked fierce criticism from philosophers committed to scientific rationality."},
"c12":{"text":"The integration of artificial intelligence into clinical medicine raises questions that existing bioethical frameworks struggle to accommodate. Traditional medical ethics rests on four principles: autonomy (the patient's right to make informed decisions), beneficence (acting in the patient's best interest), non-maleficence (avoiding harm), and justice (fair distribution of resources). Each principle encounters novel complications when algorithms participate in diagnosis and treatment decisions. Consider autonomy: informed consent requires that patients understand how decisions about their care are made. Yet many AI diagnostic systems operate as opaque processes whose reasoning cannot be fully explained even by their developers. When an algorithm recommends against a particular treatment, can a patient meaningfully consent to or refuse that recommendation without understanding its basis? The principle of beneficence similarly strains under algorithmic medicine. AI systems trained on historical data inevitably encode the biases present in that data. If past clinical decisions reflected racial or socioeconomic disparities in care, an AI system will learn to perpetuate those disparities unless explicitly corrected. Some scholars argue that deploying such systems violates beneficence by systematically disadvantaging already vulnerable populations. Others counter that imperfect algorithms may still outperform imperfect human judgment, and that withholding AI assistance itself causes harm. The challenge for bioethics is not merely to apply existing principles to new technology but to determine whether the principles themselves require revision in an era of algorithmic decision-making."},
"c13":{"text":"When photography emerged in the 1830s, it was almost universally regarded as a mechanical process rather than an art form. The camera, critics argued, merely recorded what was already there; the photographer exercised no more creative judgment than the operator of a printing press. Charles Baudelaire's 1859 essay on the Salon exhibitions dismissed photography as the refuge of every would-be painter too ill-endowed or too lazy to complete his studies. The prejudice rested on a particular theory of art: that authentic artistic creation requires the transformation of raw material through imagination and manual skill. A painting, however realistic, bears the unmistakable imprint of the painter's interpretive vision; a photograph, by contrast, was thought to offer nothing but transparent reproduction. This argument began to collapse as photographers demonstrated that their medium involved choices fully as consequential as those facing painters. Framing, timing, exposure, depth of field, perspective -- each decision shapes the viewer's experience of the subject and reveals the photographer's interpretive stance. Alfred Stieglitz and the Photo-Secession movement deliberately employed soft focus, unusual angles, and careful printing techniques to emphasize the expressive potential of the medium. Later, documentary photographers like Dorothea Lange showed that even apparently straightforward images embody moral and political perspectives through their selection of subjects and moments. The question was never really whether photography could be art but what theory of art could accommodate it -- a theory that locates creativity not exclusively in manual transformation but in the act of selection, arrangement, and presentation."},
"c14":{"text":"Democratic theorists have long debated whether citizen participation in governance should be maximized or carefully channeled. Participatory democrats, following Rousseau and later Carole Pateman, argue that widespread direct engagement in political decisions is intrinsically valuable: it cultivates civic virtue, develops political competence, and produces decisions that more accurately reflect the public interest. On this view, representative institutions are at best a necessary compromise with scale and at worst a mechanism for elite capture of public authority. Deliberative democrats offer a more nuanced position. Jurgen Habermas and his followers contend that the quality of democratic outcomes depends not on the quantity of participation but on the quality of public deliberation. What matters is not that every citizen votes on every issue but that decisions emerge from inclusive, reason-giving discourse in which participants are willing to revise their positions in light of better arguments. Aggregative democrats, by contrast, adopt a minimalist view inspired by Joseph Schumpeter: democracy is fundamentally a method for selecting leaders through competitive elections. Citizens need not be informed, virtuous, or deliberative; they need only be able to choose between competing elites at regular intervals. The attempt to demand more of citizens, Schumpeter warned, leads either to frustration or to manipulation by demagogues who exploit participatory enthusiasm. Each tradition implies different institutional prescriptions. Participatory democrats favor referenda, town halls, and decentralized governance. Deliberative democrats champion citizens' assemblies and structured public forums. Aggregative democrats defend existing representative institutions against reforms they consider naive."},
"c15":{"text":"Academic tracking -- the practice of sorting students into different curricular paths based on perceived ability -- remains among the most contested practices in American education. Proponents argue that grouping students by skill level allows teachers to tailor instruction appropriately: advanced students are challenged rather than held back, while struggling students receive targeted support rather than being overwhelmed. This efficiency argument draws support from studies showing modest achievement gains for high-track students in tracked versus untracked schools. Critics respond that the benefits of tracking accrue almost exclusively to students in the highest tracks, while those in lower tracks experience a cascade of disadvantages. Lower-track classes typically receive less experienced teachers, cover less rigorous material, emphasize rote learning over critical thinking, and create peer environments with lower academic expectations. Students placed in low tracks rarely move upward, creating what sociologist Jeannie Oakes termed a self-fulfilling prophecy: the system designed to accommodate differences in ability actively produces and reinforces them. The equity implications are stark. Track placement correlates strongly with race and socioeconomic status even after controlling for prior achievement. Black and Latino students are disproportionately assigned to lower tracks, while White and Asian students are overrepresented in honors and advanced courses. This pattern persists in part because track placement often depends on teacher and counselor recommendations, which research shows are influenced by implicit bias. Schools that have implemented detracking -- replacing separate tracks with heterogeneous classes supported by differentiated instruction -- report narrowing achievement gaps without measurable harm to high-achieving students, though such reforms frequently encounter resistance from affluent parents who perceive detracking as a threat to their children's competitive advantage."},
"c16":{"text":"Narrative medicine, a movement pioneered by physician-literary scholar Rita Charon, proposes that the practice of close reading and reflective writing can address deficiencies in contemporary medical training. Charon argues that clinical medicine has become excessively focused on biological mechanisms, diagnostic algorithms, and evidence-based protocols at the expense of the patient's subjective experience of illness. The biomedical model treats disease as a deviation from measurable physiological norms; it has little conceptual space for suffering, meaning, or the disruption that illness inflicts on a person's life narrative. Narrative competence -- the ability to recognize, absorb, interpret, and be moved by stories -- is, on Charon's account, a clinical skill as essential as auscultation or suturing. When a physician listens attentively to a patient's account of illness, something more than data collection occurs: the physician enters the patient's world of meaning and acknowledges the patient as a fellow subject rather than merely an object of clinical scrutiny. This recognition has measurable clinical consequences. Studies suggest that physicians trained in narrative practices demonstrate greater empathy, elicit more complete patient histories, and achieve higher patient satisfaction scores. Critics of narrative medicine raise several concerns. Some question whether literary training translates reliably into clinical skill, noting that many sensitive readers make indifferent physicians and many excellent clinicians have no literary interests. Others worry that narrative approaches may privilege articulate patients who can construct compelling stories while further marginalizing those whose cultural backgrounds, cognitive limitations, or communication styles make narrative self-presentation difficult."},
"c17":{"text":"The sanitary reform movement of the nineteenth century illustrates how public health advances depend not merely on scientific discovery but on the political mobilization of knowledge. By the 1840s, physicians and statisticians in Britain had documented striking correlations between poverty, overcrowding, and infectious disease. Edwin Chadwick's 1842 Report on the Sanitary Condition of the Labouring Population marshaled mortality statistics demonstrating that average life expectancy in Liverpool's poorest districts was seventeen years, compared to thirty-five in its wealthiest neighborhoods. Yet correlation alone could not compel action. The prevailing miasma theory attributed disease to foul air emanating from decaying organic matter -- a framework that, while scientifically incorrect, proved politically useful because it directed attention toward environmental conditions amenable to public intervention. Sanitary reformers leveraged miasma theory to advocate for sewer construction, clean water supply, and refuse removal -- measures that reduced disease transmission even though the underlying causal mechanism was misunderstood. John Snow's 1854 demonstration that cholera spread through contaminated water rather than miasma was initially resisted precisely because it threatened the political coalition built around atmospheric explanations. The germ theory that eventually replaced miasma theory arrived not as a straightforward triumph of evidence over ignorance but as a paradigm that required new institutional arrangements: bacteriological laboratories, trained public health officers, and surveillance systems capable of tracking specific pathogens. The lesson for public health is sobering: scientifically correct explanations do not automatically generate effective policy. Effective public health requires not only accurate knowledge but also political frameworks that connect knowledge to institutional action."},
"c18":{"text":"Universal basic income, the proposal to provide every citizen with a regular unconditional cash payment sufficient to meet basic needs, has attracted support from remarkably diverse ideological quarters. Libertarians appreciate its potential to replace the sprawling bureaucracy of means-tested welfare programs with a single transparent mechanism. Progressives see it as a foundation for economic security in an era of precarious employment and technological displacement. Silicon Valley technologists advocate it as a necessary response to automation that may eliminate millions of jobs. Yet the apparent consensus dissolves upon examination. Supporters disagree fundamentally about UBI's purpose, scale, and relationship to existing social programs. A libertarian UBI that replaces all other welfare provisions -- food assistance, housing subsidies, Medicaid -- would leave many vulnerable people worse off than the current patchwork system, since a flat payment cannot accommodate the variable costs of disability, chronic illness, or urban housing markets. A progressive UBI generous enough to provide genuine economic security would require tax increases that fundamentally alter the relationship between labor and income. The most revealing empirical evidence comes from pilot programs in Finland, Kenya, and Stockton, California. Recipients generally maintain or increase employment, contradicting predictions of mass idleness. Mental health and life satisfaction improve. Children's school attendance rises. But pilot programs operate within existing economic structures; they cannot predict the systemic effects of universal implementation on labor markets, prices, and political dynamics. The question UBI raises is ultimately not economic but philosophical: whether a decent society guarantees its members material security as a right of citizenship or only as a reward for productive contribution."}});
QS.push(
{id:"np140",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Metabolic Regulation","Amino Acid Properties","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p60",q:"Based on Table 1 and the clinical findings, the most likely diagnosis for this patient is:",o:["N-acetylglutamate synthase (NAGS) deficiency, since CPS I requires NAG as an obligate activator","CPS I deficiency, since the enzyme itself has only 12% residual activity in the biopsy","OTC deficiency, which would explain the low citrulline and hyperammonemia","Arginase deficiency, causing accumulation of arginine and secondary ammonia elevation"],a:0,ex:"The key is that NAG was undetectable and carglumic acid (NAG analog) rescued enzyme activity. CPS I has only 12% activity not because the enzyme is defective but because it lacks its obligate activator NAG. Without NAG, CPS I cannot function. NAGS deficiency is the only urea cycle disorder where the defective enzyme is not one of the five cycle enzymes themselves. OTC deficiency would show elevated orotic acid (which is normal here) because carbamoyl phosphate diverts to the pyrimidine pathway.",mn:"No NAG = CPS I cannot activate = ammonia builds up. NAGS deficiency is unique: the activator is missing, not the enzyme."},
{id:"np141",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Metabolic Regulation","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p60",q:"The finding that carglumic acid restores enzyme activity most strongly supports which conclusion?",o:["CPS I protein is structurally normal but catalytically inactive without its allosteric activator","Carglumic acid directly converts ammonia to urea, bypassing the urea cycle entirely","The patient's CPS I gene contains a missense mutation that carglumic acid corrects","NAG is a competitive inhibitor of CPS I, and carglumic acid displaces it from the active site"],a:0,ex:"Carglumic acid is a synthetic analog of NAG. It works because CPS I is present and structurally normal -- it just needs its activator. This confirms that the enzyme protein is fine (not mutated) but cannot function without allosteric activation. NAG is an activator, not an inhibitor.",mn:"The drug replaces the missing activator. Enzyme is fine, activator is missing = NAGS deficiency."},
{id:"np142",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:3,pass:"p60",q:"Why is glutamine elevated in this patient?",o:["Glutamine synthetase converts excess ammonia and glutamate to glutamine as a detoxification mechanism","Glutamine is a direct product of the urea cycle that accumulates when the cycle is blocked","Elevated ammonia inhibits glutaminase, preventing glutamine from being broken down","The liver releases glutamine as an acute-phase protein during metabolic stress"],a:0,ex:"When the urea cycle cannot remove ammonia, glutamine synthetase in astrocytes and other tissues acts as a backup system: NH3 + glutamate -> glutamine (requires ATP). This is why brain glutamine rises in hyperammonemia, causing astrocyte swelling and cerebral edema. Glutamine is NOT a urea cycle intermediate.",mn:"Ammonia backup plan: glutamine synthetase converts NH3 + glutamate -> glutamine. Brain astrocytes swell = encephalopathy."},
{id:"np143",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Metabolic Regulation","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p60",q:"Normal urine orotic acid in this patient helps rule out which diagnosis?",o:["OTC deficiency, because blocked OTC causes carbamoyl phosphate to divert into pyrimidine synthesis producing orotic acid","CPS I deficiency, because CPS I normally produces orotic acid as a minor byproduct","Arginase deficiency, because arginine is converted to orotic acid when arginase is absent","NAGS deficiency, because NAG is a precursor to orotic acid in the pyrimidine pathway"],a:0,ex:"In OTC deficiency, carbamoyl phosphate cannot combine with ornithine, so it accumulates in the mitochondria and leaks into the cytoplasm where it enters pyrimidine synthesis: carbamoyl phosphate -> carbamoyl aspartate -> dihydroorotate -> orotate -> orotic acid. Elevated urine orotic acid is the hallmark distinguishing OTC deficiency from CPS I deficiency.",mn:"OTC deficiency = carbamoyl phosphate has nowhere to go = enters pyrimidine pathway = orotic acid in urine."},
{id:"np144",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Metabolic Regulation"],diff:3,pass:"p60",fmt:"except",q:"Which of the following is NOT a characteristic of the urea cycle?",o:["All five enzymatic steps occur in the cytoplasm of hepatocytes","The cycle consumes 3 ATP equivalents per molecule of urea produced","One nitrogen in urea comes from free ammonia and the other from aspartate","The cycle is found primarily in the liver, with partial expression in kidney"],a:0,ex:"EXCEPT question: The first two steps (CPS I and OTC) occur in the mitochondrial matrix, not the cytoplasm. The remaining three steps occur in the cytoplasm. This compartmentalization is functionally important because CPS I uses mitochondrial ammonia. The other three statements are all true: 3 ATP per urea (2 for CPS I + 1 for argininosuccinate synthetase, which cleaves ATP to AMP+PPi = 2 ATP equivalents), one N from NH3 and one from aspartate, and the liver is the primary site.",mn:"NOT all cytoplasmic: CPS I and OTC are in the mitochondrial matrix. Steps 3-5 are cytoplasmic."},
{id:"np145",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Protein Structure","Mendelian Genetics","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p61",q:"HbS migrates more slowly than HbA on electrophoresis at pH 8.6 because:",o:["The glutamic acid to valine substitution removes a negative charge, reducing the overall negative charge of HbS","Valine is larger than glutamic acid, increasing the molecular weight and slowing migration","HbS polymerizes during electrophoresis, forming aggregates that migrate more slowly","The substitution changes the isoelectric point of HbS above pH 8.6, making it positively charged"],a:0,ex:"At pH 8.6, proteins migrate toward the anode (positive electrode) based on net negative charge. Glutamic acid (pKa ~4) is negatively charged at pH 8.6, while valine is uncharged. Replacing Glu with Val removes one negative charge per beta chain (two per tetramer), so HbS has less net negative charge and migrates more slowly toward the anode. Size differences are negligible for electrophoresis at this scale.",mn:"Glu (negative charge) -> Val (no charge) = less negative = slower migration toward positive electrode."},
{id:"np146",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Protein Structure","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p61",q:"The Experiment 2 data showing increased sickling at lower PO2 most directly supports which conclusion?",o:["HbS polymerization is triggered by the conformational change from R-state to T-state upon deoxygenation","Lower oxygen tension destabilizes the alpha-beta subunit interface, causing the tetramer to dissociate","Sickling is an irreversible process once initiated, regardless of subsequent oxygen exposure","The Val-6 substitution only affects oxygen binding affinity, not protein-protein interactions"],a:0,ex:"HbS polymerization requires deoxygenation because the T-state (deoxy) conformation exposes a hydrophobic patch created by the Val-6 substitution. In the R-state (oxy), this patch is buried. As PO2 drops, more Hb shifts to T-state, exposing more hydrophobic patches, which interlock between adjacent HbS molecules forming rigid fibers. This is why sickling occurs in venous circulation and exercising muscle (low PO2) but not in arteries (high PO2).",mn:"Deoxy (T-state) exposes the Val-6 hydrophobic patch. Oxy (R-state) hides it. Lower O2 = more T-state = more polymerization = more sickling."},
{id:"np147",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Mendelian Genetics","Protein Structure"],diff:2,pass:"p61",q:"The Experiment 3 finding that HbAS individuals show only 3% sickling at venous PO2 is best explained by:",o:["Intracellular HbA dilutes HbS concentration below the critical threshold for polymer nucleation","HbA and HbS form hybrid tetramers that are unable to deoxygenate under normal conditions","Sickle trait carriers have a compensatory increase in 2,3-BPG that shifts the O2 curve leftward","The single functional beta-A gene produces twice the normal amount of HbA protein per cell"],a:0,ex:"HbS polymerization is a nucleation-dependent process requiring a critical concentration of deoxyHbS. In sickle trait (HbAS), approximately 60% of hemoglobin is HbA and 40% is HbS. HbA does not participate in polymer formation and effectively dilutes the HbS concentration below the nucleation threshold. This is why sickle trait is generally asymptomatic except under extreme hypoxia.",mn:"HbAS: ~60% HbA + 40% HbS. HbA dilutes HbS below the critical concentration needed for polymer nucleation."},
{id:"np148",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Protein Structure","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p61",q:"Based on the passage, which experimental approach would most directly test whether HbS polymerization requires specific protein-protein contacts rather than general hydrophobic aggregation?",o:["Introduce a second mutation near Val-6 that adds a charged residue, then measure polymerization rates","Increase the temperature to 45C to promote hydrophobic interactions, then measure sickling","Add a nonspecific protein aggregation agent and observe whether it increases sickling","Remove all oxygen to maximize T-state formation and observe maximum possible sickling rate"],a:0,ex:"If polymerization depends on specific Val-6 contacts rather than general hydrophobic aggregation, then disrupting the specific contact site should eliminate polymerization even though the protein is still hydrophobic. Adding a charged residue near Val-6 would disrupt the specific contact geometry. If sickling stops, it proves the contact is specific. Increasing temperature or adding aggregation agents tests general aggregation, not specific contacts.",mn:"Specific contact = disrupting the contact site stops polymerization. General hydrophobic = any hydrophobic agent would work. Test by mutating the contact site."},
{id:"np149",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Membrane Transport","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p62",q:"TTX application in Experiment 1 slows conduction velocity because:",o:["Blocking Na+ channels reduces the magnitude and speed of Phase 0 depolarization, which generates the local currents that depolarize adjacent cells","TTX directly blocks gap junctions between cardiomyocytes, preventing electrical signal transmission between adjacent cells","Na+ channel blockade prevents the Na+/K+ ATPase from maintaining resting potential, eliminating the electrochemical gradient","TTX converts the ventricular action potential to a pacemaker-type potential that is entirely dependent on slow Ca2+ channels"],a:0,ex:"Conduction velocity depends on Phase 0 upstroke velocity. Fast Na+ channels create a rapid depolarization that generates strong local currents, which depolarize neighboring cells past threshold. When TTX slows the upstroke from 200 to 30 V/s, the local currents are weaker and take longer to bring adjacent cells to threshold, so the wave propagates more slowly. TTX does not affect gap junctions or the Na+/K+ ATPase.",mn:"Faster Phase 0 upstroke = stronger local currents = faster conduction. TTX slows upstroke = weaker currents = slower conduction."},
{id:"np150",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p62",q:"Nifedipine's effect on contractile force in Experiment 2 occurs because:",o:["L-type Ca2+ channels provide the trigger Ca2+ that activates ryanodine receptors, releasing sarcoplasmic reticulum Ca2+ stores needed for contraction","Blocking Ca2+ channels prevents actin-myosin cross-bridge formation by removing the troponin-C binding signal","Nifedipine directly inhibits the sarcoplasmic reticulum Ca2+ ATPase (SERCA), preventing Ca2+ reuptake","Ca2+ channel blockade causes the resting membrane potential to hyperpolarize, preventing any depolarization"],a:0,ex:"Cardiac excitation-contraction coupling requires Ca2+-induced Ca2+ release (CICR). L-type Ca2+ entering during Phase 2 acts as a trigger that opens ryanodine receptors (RyR2) on the sarcoplasmic reticulum, releasing a much larger Ca2+ store. This amplified Ca2+ binds troponin-C, enabling contraction. Block the trigger (nifedipine) and the SR release is minimal, reducing contractile force by 75%.",mn:"L-type Ca2+ = trigger for CICR. Block trigger = no SR release = no contraction. Ca2+-induced Ca2+ release."},
{id:"np151",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Membrane Transport"],diff:3,pass:"p62",q:"SA node cells differ from ventricular cells in that SA node Phase 0 depends on slow Ca2+ channels. This explains why SA node conduction is:",o:["Slower than ventricular conduction, because Ca2+ channels open and close more slowly than Na+ channels","Faster than ventricular conduction, because Ca2+ carries more charge per ion than Na+","Identical to ventricular conduction, because both ions carry the same single positive charge","Independent of ion channel kinetics, because SA node conduction relies entirely on gap junction density"],a:0,ex:"SA node upstroke velocity is only 5 V/s compared to 200 V/s in ventricular cells. Slower upstroke = weaker local currents = slower conduction through the SA and AV nodes. This slow conduction through the AV node creates the PR interval delay that allows atria to finish contracting before ventricles begin. Ca2+ channels are inherently slower (hence called L-type for long-lasting) compared to fast Na+ channels.",mn:"SA/AV node: slow Ca2+ upstroke (5 V/s) = slow conduction. Ventricles: fast Na+ upstroke (200 V/s) = fast conduction. AV delay = PR interval."},
{id:"np152",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p62",q:"A drug that selectively blocks delayed rectifier K+ channels would most likely:",o:["Prolong the QT interval by extending Phase 3 repolarization and increasing action potential duration","Shorten the QT interval by accelerating Phase 3 repolarization","Eliminate the Phase 2 plateau by removing the opposing outward current that balances Ca2+ influx","Have no effect on the action potential because K+ channels are only active during Phase 4"],a:0,ex:"Delayed rectifier K+ channels are responsible for Phase 3 repolarization. Blocking them delays repolarization, prolonging the action potential duration and therefore the QT interval on ECG. This is the mechanism of Class III antiarrhythmics (amiodarone, sotalol) and also the mechanism of dangerous drug-induced long QT syndrome. Prolonged QT can cause torsades de pointes.",mn:"Block K+ repolarization channels = slower repolarization = longer action potential = longer QT interval. Class III antiarrhythmics do this."},
{id:"np153",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Protein Structure","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p63",q:"Experiment 2 demonstrates that PrPC knockout mice are resistant to prion disease. This finding most strongly supports which model of prion propagation?",o:["The protein-only model, in which PrPSc converts endogenous PrPC substrate into more PrPSc","The viral model, in which a slow-acting virus uses PrP as a receptor for cell entry","The spontaneous misfolding model, in which PrPSc arises from random conformational errors","The nucleic acid model, in which a small RNA associated with PrPSc encodes the pathogenic conformation"],a:0,ex:"If PrPSc causes disease by converting host PrPC into more PrPSc (template-directed misfolding), then removing the substrate (PrPC) should prevent disease even when PrPSc is introduced. This is exactly what Experiment 2 shows. A viral model would predict that the virus could still cause disease through PrPC-independent mechanisms. The spontaneous model does not explain why exogenous PrPSc is required.",mn:"No PrPC substrate = nothing for PrPSc to convert = no disease. Protein-only hypothesis: PrPSc is both the pathogen and the template."},
{id:"np154",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Protein Structure","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p63",q:"Experiment 3 shows that denatured PrPSc cannot convert PrPC. Combined with Experiment 1, this suggests that prion infectivity depends on:",o:["The specific beta-sheet-rich tertiary structure of PrPSc, which acts as a template for conformational conversion","The primary amino acid sequence of PrPSc, which differs from PrPC due to post-translational modifications","Covalent chemical modifications present on PrPSc that are destroyed by GdnHCl treatment","A nucleic acid cofactor that is destroyed by the denaturing conditions"],a:0,ex:"PrPSc and PrPC have identical amino acid sequences (same gene product). The difference is purely conformational: alpha-helix-rich vs beta-sheet-rich. GdnHCl unfolds PrPSc, destroying the beta-sheet template. Refolding produces PrPC-like structure, not PrPSc, showing that the specific PrPSc conformation is required for templated conversion. No sequence or covalent differences exist.",mn:"Same sequence, different fold. The beta-sheet conformation IS the infectious agent. Unfold it = lose infectivity. Refold = get PrPC back, not PrPSc."},
{id:"np155",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Equilibrium","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p64",q:"In Experiment 2, increasing Zn2+ concentration decreased cell potential. This is consistent with the Nernst equation because:",o:["Increasing product concentration (Zn2+ is produced at the anode) shifts equilibrium toward reactants, reducing the driving force","Higher Zn2+ concentration increases the resistance of the solution, causing an ohmic voltage drop","Zinc ions block the copper electrode surface, preventing the reduction reaction","The Nernst equation predicts that cell potential always decreases when any ion concentration increases"],a:0,ex:"The overall reaction is Zn(s) + Cu2+(aq) -> Zn2+(aq) + Cu(s). Zn2+ is a product. By Le Chatelier's principle and the Nernst equation (Ecell = E0 - (RT/nF)ln(Q)), increasing [Zn2+] increases Q, which increases the ln(Q) term, which decreases Ecell. Conversely, Experiment 3 shows increasing [Cu2+] (a reactant) decreases Q and increases Ecell.",mn:"Nernst: E = E0 - (RT/nF)ln(Q). Q = [Zn2+]/[Cu2+]. More Zn2+ = bigger Q = lower E. More Cu2+ = smaller Q = higher E."},
{id:"np156",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p64",q:"The salt bridge in Experiment 4 is essential because it:",o:["Maintains electrical neutrality in each half-cell by allowing ion migration between compartments","Provides a pathway for electron flow between the zinc and copper solutions","Supplies the Cu2+ ions that are reduced at the cathode during the cell reaction","Prevents the two solutions from mixing, which would cause a short circuit"],a:0,ex:"As the cell operates, the anode compartment gains positive charge (Zn2+ dissolves) and the cathode compartment loses positive charge (Cu2+ plates out). Without the salt bridge, charge builds up and the reaction stops immediately. The salt bridge allows K+ to migrate toward the cathode and NO3- toward the anode, maintaining electroneutrality. Electrons flow through the external wire, not the salt bridge.",mn:"Salt bridge = ion highway that balances charges. Anode gets positive (Zn2+ dissolves), cathode gets negative (Cu2+ deposits). Without it, charge buildup stops the reaction."},
{id:"np157",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Thermodynamics"],diff:2,pass:"p64",q:"The zinc electrode loses mass during operation because:",o:["Zinc metal is oxidized to Zn2+ ions that dissolve into solution, removing solid mass from the electrode","Zinc atoms migrate through the salt bridge to deposit on the copper electrode","The current flowing through the electrode gradually erodes the metal surface","Zinc reacts with the KNO3 from the salt bridge, forming soluble zinc nitrate"],a:0,ex:"At the anode: Zn(s) -> Zn2+(aq) + 2e-. Solid zinc loses two electrons and becomes aqueous Zn2+, leaving the electrode. Each mole of Zn oxidized removes 65.4 g from the anode. Simultaneously, at the cathode: Cu2+(aq) + 2e- -> Cu(s). Cu2+ deposits as solid copper, so the copper electrode gains mass. This is a direct demonstration of the oxidation and reduction half-reactions.",mn:"Anode: Zn(s) -> Zn2+(aq) + 2e- = mass leaves. Cathode: Cu2+(aq) + 2e- -> Cu(s) = mass arrives. Oxidation loses mass, reduction gains mass."},
{id:"np158",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p65",q:"Patient A's arterial blood gas values (pH 7.18, PCO2 70, HCO3- 26) indicate:",o:["Acute respiratory acidosis from hypoventilation, with minimal renal compensation","Metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation shown by the elevated PCO2","Mixed respiratory and metabolic acidosis occurring simultaneously","Chronic respiratory acidosis with complete renal compensation"],a:0,ex:"pH is low (acidemia). PCO2 is high (respiratory cause). HCO3- is near normal (26, barely above 24), indicating the kidneys have not yet compensated significantly. In acute respiratory acidosis from hypoventilation (heroin OD depresses respiratory drive), PCO2 rises quickly but renal compensation (HCO3- retention) takes hours to days. This is classic acute respiratory acidosis.",mn:"Low pH + high CO2 + normal HCO3- = acute respiratory acidosis. Kidneys haven't had time to compensate. Heroin suppresses breathing."},
{id:"np159",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p65",q:"Patient B (pH 7.10, PCO2 15, HCO3- 5) is hyperventilating. This Kussmaul breathing represents:",o:["Respiratory compensation for primary metabolic acidosis, attempting to lower PCO2 and raise pH","Primary respiratory alkalosis causing a secondary metabolic acidosis","The direct cause of the low pH through excessive CO2 elimination","An ineffective compensation because the pH has not returned to normal range"],a:0,ex:"Patient B has diabetic ketoacidosis: low HCO3- (5, severely depleted by ketoacids) is the primary metabolic acidosis. The body compensates by hyperventilating (Kussmaul breathing) to blow off CO2, lowering PCO2 to 15. This respiratory compensation partially raises pH but cannot fully normalize it when the metabolic derangement is severe. Winter's formula predicts expected PCO2 for metabolic acidosis: PCO2 = 1.5(HCO3-) + 8 +/- 2 = 1.5(5) + 8 = 15.5, confirming appropriate compensation.",mn:"DKA: ketoacids consume HCO3- (metabolic acidosis). Lungs compensate by hyperventilating (lower CO2). Kussmaul breathing = deep rapid breathing to blow off acid."},
{id:"np160",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base"],diff:3,pass:"p65",q:"Using the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation, verify Patient C's values (pH 7.55, PCO2 48, HCO3- 38). The primary disorder is:",o:["Metabolic alkalosis with partial respiratory compensation by hypoventilation","Respiratory acidosis that has been overcompensated by the kidneys","Respiratory alkalosis with secondary metabolic alkalosis","A lab error, because these values are internally inconsistent"],a:0,ex:"Check: pH = 6.1 + log(38 / (0.03 x 48)) = 6.1 + log(38/1.44) = 6.1 + log(26.4) = 6.1 + 1.42 = 7.52. Close to 7.55 (rounding). Primary disorder: pH is high (alkalemia), HCO3- is high (38, metabolic cause). Vomiting causes loss of HCl, raising HCO3-. The body partially compensates by hypoventilating (raising PCO2 to 48) to retain acid. This is metabolic alkalosis with appropriate respiratory compensation.",mn:"High pH + high HCO3- = metabolic alkalosis. Vomiting loses HCl. Compensation: hypoventilate to raise CO2 (retain acid). PCO2 48 > 40 = compensation."},
{id:"np161",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Spectroscopy","Functional Groups","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p66",q:"Based on the IR and NMR data, the unknown compound is most likely:",o:["4-methoxybenzoic acid (para-anisic acid), containing a carboxylic acid, aromatic ring, and methoxy group","Methyl benzoate, an ester with an aromatic ring and methyl group bonded to the carbonyl oxygen","4-hydroxybenzaldehyde, containing a phenol hydroxyl group, an aldehyde, and a para-substituted aromatic ring","Acetophenone, a methyl ketone directly attached to a benzene ring with no additional substituents"],a:0,ex:"The 11.8 ppm signal exchangeable with D2O = carboxylic acid O-H (not aldehyde, which would be 9-10 ppm and non-exchangeable). The 1710 cm-1 IR = C=O of carboxylic acid. The 3.9 ppm singlet (3H) = OCH3 (methoxy group). Two aromatic doublets (2H each) = para-substituted benzene. Formula C8H8O3 fits 4-methoxybenzoic acid: PhOCH3 + COOH on opposite sides of the ring. Degree of unsaturation = 5 (ring=4, C=O=1).",mn:"11.8 ppm D2O exchangeable = COOH. 3.9 ppm singlet 3H = OCH3. Two 2H aromatic doublets = para substitution. Put it together: para-methoxybenzoic acid."},
{id:"np162",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Spectroscopy","Functional Groups"],diff:2,pass:"p66",q:"The UV absorption at 254 nm corresponds to a pi to pi-star transition. This absorption is observed because the compound contains:",o:["A conjugated aromatic ring system with extended pi electron delocalization","A saturated carbon chain with sigma bonds that absorb in the UV region","An isolated carbonyl group with no conjugation to adjacent pi systems","Free electron pairs on oxygen atoms that undergo n to sigma-star transitions"],a:0,ex:"The 254 nm absorption is characteristic of aromatic pi to pi-star transitions (benzene absorbs at 254 nm). The conjugation between the ring and the carboxylic acid extends the pi system. Sigma bonds absorb in the far UV (<200 nm) and would not appear at 254 nm. The n to pi-star transition at 330 nm is from the carbonyl lone pairs, which is a separate, weaker transition.",mn:"254 nm = aromatic pi-pi* transition. Benzene's characteristic absorption. Conjugation with COOH extends and intensifies it."},
{id:"np163",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p67",q:"The decrease in obedience from Condition A (61%) to Condition C (30%) most directly demonstrates the influence of:",o:["Physical proximity to the victim, which increases empathic distress and makes the consequences of obedience more salient","Diffusion of responsibility, which decreases when fewer people are present in the room","The bystander effect, which is reduced when the participant must physically interact with the victim","Social facilitation, which enhances dominant responses when others are watching"],a:0,ex:"Conditions A through C vary only the proximity between participant and victim: adjacent room (audio only) -> same room -> physical touch required. As the victim becomes more proximate and the consequences more viscerally apparent, obedience drops. This is not diffusion of responsibility (group size is constant) or bystander effect (there are no bystanders). It demonstrates that psychological distance from harm facilitates obedience.",mn:"Closer to victim = harder to harm them. Distance makes obedience easier because consequences feel abstract. Proximity makes them real."},
{id:"np164",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p67",q:"Condition E (peer rebellion, 10% obedience) shows the strongest reduction in obedience. This finding best illustrates:",o:["Social influence through informational and normative conformity, as peers model disobedience and validate the participant's reluctance","Deindividuation, in which the presence of peers reduces personal responsibility for actions","Groupthink, which causes the participant to suppress dissent in favor of group consensus","The fundamental attribution error, causing participants to attribute their peers' disobedience to the situation"],a:0,ex:"When confederate peers refuse to continue, they provide both informational influence (their refusal signals that disobedience is appropriate) and normative influence (the participant no longer feels alone in wanting to stop). This dramatically reduces obedience from 61% to 10%. Peer behavior defines the social norm -- once obedience is no longer the group norm, participants feel empowered to resist the authority.",mn:"Peers refusing = new social norm of disobedience. Both informational (it's okay to stop) and normative (others are stopping) influence."},
{id:"np165",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p67",fmt:"except",q:"A researcher argues that Milgram's findings can be explained by agentic state theory. Which observation from the passage LEAST supports this theory?",o:["Participants show visible signs of distress including sweating, trembling, and nervous laughter across all conditions","Obedience drops when the experimenter gives instructions by telephone rather than in person","Peer rebellion dramatically reduces obedience from 61% to 10%","Moving the experiment from a university lab to an office building reduces obedience"],a:0,ex:"EXCEPT/LEAST question: Agentic state theory proposes that people shift from autonomous to agentic state when following authority, essentially becoming instruments of the authority's will. If participants were truly in an agentic state (feeling no personal responsibility), they should NOT show distress. Visible sweating, trembling, and nervous laughter indicate that participants retain their moral judgment and experience conflict -- they feel responsible even while obeying. This observation undermines pure agentic state theory.",mn:"Agentic state = I'm just following orders, not responsible. But distress symptoms show they DO feel responsible. Distress = moral conflict, not blind obedience."},
{id:"np166",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Memory","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p68",q:"Experiment 3's finding that stereotype threat reduces working memory capacity suggests the performance gap is caused by:",o:["Cognitive resource depletion from anxiety, self-monitoring, and suppression of stereotype-related thoughts","Reduced motivation to perform well when negative stereotypes are made salient","Lower baseline cognitive ability in stereotype-threatened groups that becomes apparent under testing conditions","A testing artifact in which threatened participants deliberately underperform to avoid confirming the stereotype"],a:0,ex:"The working memory finding is key: threatened participants have 20% less working memory capacity available. This suggests that stereotype threat creates an extra cognitive load (anxiety, rumination, vigilance about confirming the stereotype) that consumes executive resources needed for the test. It is not about ability, motivation, or deliberate underperformance -- the cognitive machinery is literally occupied by threat-related processing.",mn:"Stereotype threat = cognitive tax. Anxiety and self-monitoring consume working memory, leaving fewer resources for the actual test. Not about ability -- about available bandwidth."},
{id:"np167",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p68",q:"The self-affirmation intervention in Experiment 4 likely works by:",o:["Bolstering the individual's sense of self-worth from domains unrelated to the threatened identity, reducing vulnerability to the stereotype","Increasing cognitive ability through positive thinking and enhanced neural plasticity","Eliminating the stereotype entirely from the participant's awareness through cognitive distraction","Providing evidence that contradicts the stereotype, thereby disproving it in the participant's mind"],a:0,ex:"Self-affirmation theory (Steele): when people affirm their values in domains unrelated to the threat (e.g., writing about family, creativity, or spirituality before a math test), it buffers their self-concept against the specific stereotype. They think: I am a person of worth regardless of this test outcome. This reduces the stakes of the test and frees cognitive resources from threat management. The stereotype still exists -- the person is just less vulnerable to it.",mn:"Self-affirmation = shore up your identity from other sources so one test can't threaten your entire self-worth. Lower stakes = less anxiety = more working memory for the test."},
{id:"np168",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Hormones","Immune System","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p69",q:"The flattened diurnal cortisol curve observed during exam periods indicates:",o:["Chronic HPA axis activation with failure of normal negative feedback, resulting in sustained rather than pulsatile cortisol secretion","Adrenal fatigue causing inability to produce cortisol, leading to low levels throughout the day","Normal physiological adaptation to stress that enhances immune function through constant cortisol exposure","A measurement artifact caused by irregular sleep patterns during exam periods"],a:0,ex:"Normal cortisol follows a circadian rhythm: low at waking, peaks 30 min post-waking, lowest at bedtime. Chronic stress activates the HPA axis (hypothalamus -> CRH -> anterior pituitary -> ACTH -> adrenal cortex -> cortisol). Sustained activation impairs normal negative feedback, so cortisol remains elevated at night when it should be suppressed. The flat curve (high waking + high bedtime) indicates dysregulated HPA axis, not adaptation.",mn:"Normal: cortisol peaks in morning, drops at night. Chronic stress: stays elevated at night = flat curve = HPA axis dysregulation = broken negative feedback."},
{id:"np169",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Hormones","Immune System","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p69",q:"Cortisol suppresses immune function through which primary mechanism?",o:["Inhibiting NF-kB transcription factor, thereby reducing expression of pro-inflammatory cytokines and immune cell activation","Directly lysing NK cells and T-cells through cortisol-induced apoptosis via the mitochondrial death pathway","Blocking antibody production by destroying B-cell precursors in the bone marrow before they can mature and differentiate","Competing with antigens for binding to MHC receptors on antigen-presenting cells, preventing T-cell activation"],a:0,ex:"Cortisol (a glucocorticoid) enters cells and binds intracellular glucocorticoid receptors, which translocate to the nucleus and inhibit NF-kB, a key transcription factor for inflammatory genes (IL-1, IL-6, TNF-alpha, etc.). This reduces cytokine production, decreases immune cell activation and proliferation, and suppresses inflammation. This is why corticosteroids are used as anti-inflammatory and immunosuppressive drugs. It does not directly lyse immune cells.",mn:"Cortisol -> binds glucocorticoid receptor -> inhibits NF-kB -> fewer cytokines -> less immune activation. This is why prednisone works as immunosuppressant."},
{id:"np170",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p70",q:"Drug Y is absorbed primarily in the stomach rather than the intestine because:",o:["At stomach pH 2, 99.7% of the weak acid drug is protonated (uncharged) and can cross lipid membranes by passive diffusion","The stomach has a larger surface area than the intestine, providing more absorption opportunity","Active transport proteins in the stomach lining specifically recognize weak acid drugs","The stomach pH denatures plasma proteins, increasing the free fraction available for absorption"],a:0,ex:"Using Henderson-Hasselbalch for a weak acid with pKa 4.5 at pH 2: the HA/A- ratio strongly favors the protonated (uncharged) form. Uncharged molecules cross lipid bilayers by passive diffusion. At intestinal pH 6 (above the pKa), the drug is mostly ionized (A-) and cannot cross membranes easily. This is the ion trapping principle: weak acids are absorbed in acidic environments, weak bases in basic environments.",mn:"Weak acids: protonated (HA) at low pH = uncharged = crosses membranes. Ionized (A-) at high pH = charged = trapped. pKa 4.5 drug is mostly HA at stomach pH 2."},
{id:"np171",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p70",q:"If a patient takes an antacid that raises stomach pH to 5, how would this affect Drug Y absorption?",o:["Absorption would decrease because more drug would be in the ionized form at pH 5, reducing membrane permeability","Absorption would increase because the higher pH activates acid-sensitive transport proteins","Absorption would be unchanged because the pKa of the drug does not change with pH","Absorption would increase because higher pH improves drug solubility in the gastric fluid"],a:0,ex:"At pH 5 (above pKa 4.5): using H-H, [A-]/[HA] = 10^(5-4.5) = 10^0.5 = 3.16. So ~76% is ionized (A-) and only ~24% is uncharged (HA). Compare to pH 2 where 99.7% is uncharged. The ionized fraction cannot cross membranes, so stomach absorption would drop dramatically. The drug might still be absorbed in the proximal intestine where other factors (larger surface area, longer transit time) partially compensate.",mn:"pH 5 > pKa 4.5 means mostly ionized (76% A-). Ionized = charged = cannot cross membranes = less absorption. Antacids reduce weak acid drug absorption."},
{id:"np172",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p70",q:"Grapefruit juice increases Drug Y's AUC by 180% by inhibiting CYP3A4. This means the effective drug concentration:",o:["Nearly triples, which could cause toxicity if the dose is not reduced","Decreases by 180%, requiring dose escalation to maintain therapeutic effect","Remains the same because AUC measures distribution, not concentration","Increases but only for the first dose, with subsequent doses showing normal metabolism"],a:0,ex:"AUC (area under the plasma concentration-time curve) is the gold standard measure of total drug exposure. A 180% increase means AUC is 2.8x normal. CYP3A4 inhibition by grapefruit juice reduces first-pass metabolism in the gut wall and liver, so more drug reaches systemic circulation intact. This can cause dangerous toxicity with drugs like statins, calcium channel blockers, and immunosuppressants. The effect persists as long as grapefruit is consumed.",mn:"CYP3A4 inhibition = less drug destroyed by liver = more reaches bloodstream = higher AUC = potential toxicity. 180% increase = 2.8x normal exposure."},
{id:"np173",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Inference"],diff:2,pass:"c11",q:"According to the passage, Kuhn's most controversial claim was that:",o:["Paradigm shifts involve sociological and psychological factors beyond pure evidence, challenging scientific rationality","Normal science resembles puzzle-solving more than genuine discovery or innovation","Anomalies are initially dismissed rather than immediately investigated by working scientists","Scientific revolutions follow a predictable cyclical pattern of crisis and resolution"],a:0,ex:"The passage states this claim 'provoked fierce criticism from philosophers committed to scientific rationality.' The idea that paradigm choice involves non-rational factors (sociology, psychology) directly challenged the view that science is purely objective and evidence-driven. The other claims were less controversial because they describe observable patterns in scientific practice.",mn:"Kuhn's bombshell: science isn't purely rational. Paradigm choice involves social/psychological factors, not just evidence. This outraged rationalist philosophers."},
{id:"np174",cat:"CARS",tags:["Inference","Application"],diff:2,pass:"c11",q:"Based on the passage, Kuhn would most likely argue that the transition from Newtonian to Einsteinian physics:",o:["Was not simply a matter of Einstein having better evidence, but involved a fundamental reconceptualization of space, time, and gravity","Occurred smoothly as accumulating evidence gradually convinced all physicists to adopt relativity","Was driven entirely by Einstein's personal charisma and institutional power within the physics community","Demonstrated that scientific progress is linear and cumulative, with each theory building on the last"],a:0,ex:"Kuhn argued paradigms are incommensurable: they define problems differently and see data through different lenses. Newton and Einstein did not just disagree about equations -- they had fundamentally different concepts of space and time. The shift required not just new evidence but a new way of seeing. The passage explicitly states paradigm shifts are not purely rational and involve reconceptualization, not just accumulation.",mn:"Incommensurable paradigms: Newton and Einstein don't just disagree on answers, they disagree on what the questions mean. Different conceptual worlds."},
{id:"np175",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Strengthen/Weaken"],diff:3,pass:"c11",q:"Which finding would most weaken Kuhn's incommensurability thesis?",o:["A historical case where scientists from competing paradigms agreed on objective criteria for evaluating each theory's predictions","Evidence that most scientific revolutions were led by younger researchers less invested in the old paradigm","Documentation showing that anomalies in classical physics accumulated for decades before relativity","Studies showing that scientists in different fields use different experimental methods"],a:0,ex:"Incommensurability means competing paradigms cannot be evaluated by shared standards because they define problems and evidence differently. If scientists from both sides agreed on neutral criteria for comparison, that would demonstrate commensurability and directly undermine Kuhn's claim. The other options are either consistent with Kuhn (B, C) or irrelevant to incommensurability (D).",mn:"Incommensurable = no shared yardstick. Finding a shared yardstick that both sides accept would directly refute this."},
{id:"np176",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Inference"],diff:2,pass:"c12",q:"The passage suggests that AI diagnostic systems challenge the principle of autonomy primarily because:",o:["Patients cannot give truly informed consent when the reasoning behind AI recommendations is opaque","AI systems are designed to override patient preferences in favor of statistically optimal outcomes","Physicians who rely on AI lose the ability to make independent clinical judgments","The high accuracy of AI systems makes patient consent unnecessary for routine diagnoses"],a:0,ex:"The passage explicitly asks: 'can a patient meaningfully consent to or refuse that recommendation without understanding its basis?' Informed consent requires understanding. If neither doctors nor patients can explain how the AI reached its recommendation (opaque/black-box systems), then the 'informed' component of informed consent is compromised.",mn:"Autonomy requires informed consent. Informed means understanding. Black-box AI = nobody understands the reasoning = consent is not truly informed."},
{id:"np177",cat:"CARS",tags:["Strengthen/Weaken","Application"],diff:3,pass:"c12",q:"Which scenario would best illustrate the tension between beneficence and non-maleficence that the passage describes?",o:["An AI system that improves average diagnostic accuracy by 15% but systematically underdiagnoses a rare condition in elderly Black women","A hospital that implements AI screening to reduce waiting times in the emergency department","A physician who uses AI to generate treatment options but makes the final decision independently","A regulatory agency that requires all AI diagnostic tools to pass accuracy benchmarks before approval"],a:0,ex:"This scenario embodies the exact tension described: the AI does net good (beneficence -- 15% better accuracy overall) while simultaneously causing specific harm to a vulnerable subgroup (non-maleficence violated -- bias against elderly Black women). The passage discusses how AI trained on biased historical data can perpetuate disparities, and how some argue imperfect AI still beats imperfect humans. This scenario forces both principles into direct conflict.",mn:"Beneficence (helps most patients) vs non-maleficence (harms a specific vulnerable group). The passage's core tension: aggregate benefit can coexist with targeted harm."},
{id:"np178",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Inference"],diff:2,pass:"c15",q:"The passage's characterization of academic tracking as a 'self-fulfilling prophecy' means that:",o:["The system creates the very ability differences it claims to merely accommodate, by providing unequal resources based on initial placement","Teachers accurately predict student performance based on standardized test scores and prior grades","Students in lower tracks deliberately underperform because they believe they are less capable","Tracking reflects pre-existing ability differences that would exist regardless of school policy"],a:0,ex:"The passage cites Jeannie Oakes: 'the system designed to accommodate differences in ability actively produces and reinforces them.' Students placed in low tracks receive worse instruction, less rigorous material, and lower expectations. These conditions create genuine skill gaps that confirm the original placement, making the initial sorting appear justified when it actually caused the outcome it predicted.",mn:"Self-fulfilling prophecy: put students in low track -> give them worse teaching -> they fall behind -> 'see, they belong in the low track.' The system creates what it claims to measure."},
{id:"np179",cat:"CARS",tags:["Inference","Application"],diff:2,pass:"c15",q:"According to the passage, affluent parents resist detracking reforms most likely because:",o:["They perceive homogeneous high-track classes as providing competitive advantages that heterogeneous classes would dilute","Research conclusively shows that high-achieving students perform worse in detracked classrooms","Affluent parents have more educational expertise and recognize the pedagogical superiority of tracking","Detracking would force their children to attend different schools with unfamiliar peer groups"],a:0,ex:"The passage says affluent parents 'perceive detracking as a threat to their children's competitive advantage.' They benefit from the current system (their children are overrepresented in high tracks) and fear that mixing ability levels will reduce the quality of instruction their children receive. The passage notes detracking does NOT measurably harm high achievers, but parents perceive a threat regardless.",mn:"Affluent parents defend tracking because their kids are disproportionately in high tracks. Detracking feels like losing an advantage, even though research shows no harm to high achievers."},
{id:"np180",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Strengthen/Weaken"],diff:2,pass:"c18",q:"The passage identifies the fundamental limitation of UBI pilot programs as:",o:["They operate within existing economic structures and cannot predict the systemic effects of universal implementation","They consistently show that recipients stop working, undermining the program's feasibility","They are too small in scale to produce statistically significant results about employment effects","They only study wealthy populations who do not represent the typical UBI recipient"],a:0,ex:"The passage states: 'pilot programs operate within existing economic structures; they cannot predict the systemic effects of universal implementation on labor markets, prices, and political dynamics.' A pilot gives UBI to some people within a normal economy. Universal implementation would change the entire economy -- labor supply, price levels, wage negotiations -- effects no pilot can model.",mn:"Pilot = some people get UBI in a normal economy. Universal = everyone gets UBI, changing the whole economy. You can't predict system-level effects from individual-level pilots."},
{id:"np181",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Inference"],diff:2,pass:"c18",q:"The passage concludes that the UBI debate is 'ultimately not economic but philosophical' because:",o:["It hinges on whether material security is a right of citizenship or a reward for productivity -- a value question that empirical data cannot resolve","Economists have proven unable to agree on the fiscal costs of UBI programs across different countries","The philosophical traditions supporting UBI are incompatible with modern economic theory","Political philosophers have shown that UBI would undermine the work ethic essential to democratic societies"],a:0,ex:"The final sentence frames UBI as a question about whether society guarantees security as a right or only as a reward for contribution. This is a normative question about values, not a factual question that data can answer. Even if pilots show UBI works economically, the deeper question -- should we do it? -- requires a philosophical commitment about the relationship between citizenship and material security.",mn:"The core question: is a living a RIGHT or a REWARD? Data can show if UBI works. It can't tell us if we should value security as a right. That's philosophy, not economics."},
{id:"np182",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Thermodynamics"],diff:2,q:"For a spontaneous galvanic cell reaction, which combination of thermodynamic values is correct?",o:["Positive E-cell, negative delta-G, and K greater than 1","Negative E-cell, positive delta-G, and K greater than 1","Positive E-cell, positive delta-G, and K less than 1","Negative E-cell, negative delta-G, and K less than 1"],a:0,ex:"The three thermodynamic quantities are linked: delta-G = -nFE. If E is positive (spontaneous cell), delta-G must be negative (spontaneous process). The relationship delta-G = -RTlnK means negative delta-G requires K > 1 (products favored at equilibrium). All three must be self-consistent: +E, -delta-G, K>1 for spontaneous. Reverse for non-spontaneous.",mn:"+E, -deltaG, K>1 = spontaneous. All linked by deltaG = -nFE and deltaG = -RTlnK. If one is spontaneous, all three agree."},
{id:"np183",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics"],diff:2,q:"A convex lens with focal length 10 cm forms an image of an object placed 15 cm from the lens. The image is:",o:["Real, inverted, and located 30 cm from the lens on the opposite side from the object","Virtual, upright, and located 30 cm from the lens on the same side as the object","Real, inverted, and located 6 cm from the lens on the opposite side from the object","Virtual, upright, and located 6 cm from the lens on the same side as the object"],a:0,ex:"Thin lens equation: 1/f = 1/do + 1/di. 1/10 = 1/15 + 1/di. 1/di = 1/10 - 1/15 = 3/30 - 2/30 = 1/30. di = +30 cm. Positive di means real image (opposite side from object). Magnification m = -di/do = -30/15 = -2. Negative m means inverted. The image is 2x magnified, real, and inverted.",mn:"1/f = 1/do + 1/di. 1/10 = 1/15 + 1/di. di = 30 cm (positive = real, opposite side). m = -30/15 = -2 (negative = inverted, magnified 2x)."},
{id:"np184",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Nuclear Chemistry"],diff:2,q:"A radioactive isotope has a half-life of 6 hours. If you start with 80 mg, how much remains after 24 hours?",o:["5 mg, because 24 hours equals 4 half-lives and 80 divided by 2-to-the-4th equals 5","20 mg, because 24 hours equals 4 half-lives and each half-life removes 15 mg","10 mg, because 24 hours equals 2.4 half-lives","0 mg, because 24 hours is long enough for complete decay of any isotope"],a:0,ex:"Number of half-lives = 24/6 = 4. After each half-life, the amount halves: 80 -> 40 -> 20 -> 10 -> 5 mg. Formula: remaining = initial x (1/2)^n = 80 x (1/2)^4 = 80/16 = 5 mg. Each half-life removes HALF of what remains, not a fixed amount.",mn:"24 hours / 6 hour half-life = 4 half-lives. 80 x (1/2)^4 = 80/16 = 5 mg. Each half-life halves what's left, not a fixed amount."},
{id:"np185",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Solutions","Thermodynamics"],diff:2,q:"Adding 1 mole of NaCl to 1 kg of water raises the boiling point more than adding 1 mole of glucose because:",o:["NaCl dissociates into 2 ions (Na+ and Cl-), giving an effective particle concentration twice that of molecular glucose","NaCl has a higher molecular weight than glucose, which directly increases the boiling point elevation proportionally","NaCl forms stronger hydrogen bonds with water molecules than glucose does, disrupting the solvent structure more","NaCl is an electrolyte that increases the thermal conductivity of the solution, requiring more heat to boil"],a:0,ex:"Boiling point elevation: delta-Tb = i x Kb x m. The van't Hoff factor (i) accounts for dissociation. NaCl dissociates into Na+ and Cl- (i = 2), while glucose is a nonelectrolyte (i = 1). Same molality but i = 2 for NaCl means twice the colligative effect. Colligative properties depend on NUMBER of solute particles, not their identity. More particles = greater boiling point elevation.",mn:"delta-Tb = i x Kb x m. NaCl: i=2 (two ions). Glucose: i=1 (no dissociation). Same m but double the particles = double the boiling point elevation."},
{id:"np186",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Thermodynamics","Equilibrium"],diff:2,q:"A reaction has delta-H = -40 kJ/mol and delta-S = -100 J/(mol-K). At what temperature does this reaction become non-spontaneous?",o:["Above 400 K, because delta-G becomes positive when T exceeds delta-H divided by delta-S","Below 400 K, because lower temperatures favor entropy-driven reactions","At all temperatures, because both delta-H and delta-S are negative","The reaction is always spontaneous because exothermic reactions are always favorable"],a:0,ex:"delta-G = delta-H - T(delta-S). Convert units: delta-S = -100 J/(mol-K) = -0.1 kJ/(mol-K). At equilibrium: 0 = -40 - T(-0.1) = -40 + 0.1T. T = 400 K. Below 400K: delta-G = -40 + 0.1(300) = -10 (spontaneous). Above 400K: delta-G = -40 + 0.1(500) = +10 (non-spontaneous). The reaction is enthalpy-driven (exothermic) but entropy-opposed (negative delta-S), so high T makes it non-spontaneous.",mn:"deltaG = deltaH - TdeltaS = -40 - T(-0.1) = -40 + 0.1T. Set to 0: T = 400K. Below 400K = spontaneous. Above 400K = non-spontaneous."},
{id:"np187",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Immune System"],diff:2,q:"A patient with a deficiency in MHC class I molecules would have impaired:",o:["CD8+ cytotoxic T-cell responses, because CD8+ T-cells require MHC I to recognize intracellular antigens","CD4+ helper T-cell responses, because all T-cells use MHC I for antigen recognition","B-cell antibody production, because MHC I is required for B-cell activation","Natural killer cell activity, because NK cells only kill cells that express MHC I"],a:0,ex:"MHC class I presents intracellular peptides (from viruses, tumors) to CD8+ cytotoxic T-cells. Without MHC I, CD8+ T-cells cannot recognize infected or cancerous cells. CD4+ helper T-cells use MHC class II (not I). B-cells are activated through BCR and T-cell help, not directly through MHC I. NK cells actually kill cells that LACK MHC I (missing-self hypothesis), so NK activity would increase, not decrease.",mn:"MHC I -> CD8+ T-cells (kill infected cells). MHC II -> CD4+ T-cells (help). No MHC I = no CD8+ response. NK cells kill cells MISSING MHC I."},
{id:"np188",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Hormones","Endocrine System"],diff:2,q:"Graves' disease involves autoantibodies that mimic TSH by binding and activating the TSH receptor. A patient with Graves' disease would show:",o:["Elevated T3/T4 with suppressed TSH, because excess thyroid hormone inhibits the anterior pituitary via negative feedback","Elevated T3/T4 with elevated TSH, because the autoantibodies stimulate both the thyroid and pituitary","Low T3/T4 with elevated TSH, because the autoantibodies block thyroid hormone synthesis","Normal T3/T4 with elevated TSH, because the body compensates for the autoantibody stimulation"],a:0,ex:"TSH receptor-stimulating antibodies activate the thyroid independently of TSH, causing excess T3/T4 production. The elevated T3/T4 feeds back to the hypothalamus and anterior pituitary, suppressing TRH and TSH release (negative feedback is intact). So TSH is LOW despite the thyroid being hyperactive. Key distinction: the thyroid is stimulated by antibodies, not by TSH, so TSH suppression does not stop the hyperthyroidism.",mn:"Graves': antibodies mimic TSH -> thyroid makes excess T3/T4 -> T3/T4 suppresses TSH via negative feedback. High T3/T4 + low TSH = hyperthyroid with suppressed TSH."},
{id:"np189",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Membrane Transport"],diff:2,q:"In the nephron, glucose is normally completely reabsorbed in the proximal convoluted tubule via SGLT2 transporters. Glucose appears in urine (glucosuria) when:",o:["Blood glucose exceeds the transport maximum (Tm) of SGLT2, saturating all available carriers","ADH secretion is insufficient, allowing too much water to dilute the tubular glucose below reabsorption threshold","The glomerular filtration rate drops below normal, concentrating glucose in the filtrate","Aldosterone levels are elevated, promoting glucose secretion into the tubular lumen"],a:0,ex:"SGLT2 has a finite number of transporters (transport maximum, Tm, ~375 mg/min). At normal blood glucose (~100 mg/dL), all filtered glucose is reabsorbed. When blood glucose exceeds ~180 mg/dL (the renal threshold), the filtered glucose load exceeds Tm, and the excess spills into urine. This is the basis of glucosuria in uncontrolled diabetes. SGLT2 inhibitors (e.g., empagliflozin) intentionally lower Tm to cause therapeutic glucosuria.",mn:"Glucose Tm = maximum reabsorption capacity. Blood glucose > ~180 mg/dL = filtered load exceeds Tm = glucose spills into urine. Diabetes = blood sugar too high for kidneys to reclaim."},
{id:"np190",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System"],diff:2,q:"A patient with damage to the left Broca's area would most likely present with:",o:["Non-fluent (expressive) aphasia: impaired speech production with intact comprehension","Fluent (receptive) aphasia: impaired comprehension with intact but meaningless speech","Global aphasia: complete loss of both speech production and comprehension","Anomic aphasia: difficulty finding specific words with otherwise normal speech and comprehension"],a:0,ex:"Broca's area (left inferior frontal gyrus) controls speech production/motor planning. Damage produces non-fluent aphasia: effortful, telegraphic speech (short phrases, missing function words) with relatively preserved comprehension. The patient knows what they want to say but cannot produce it fluently. Wernicke's area (left superior temporal gyrus) handles comprehension -- damage there produces fluent but meaningless speech.",mn:"Broca's = production (front of brain, frontal lobe). Wernicke's = comprehension (back, temporal lobe). Broca's damage = can understand, can't speak fluently."},
{id:"np191",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Cell Cycle","Mendelian Genetics"],diff:2,q:"The tumor suppressor Rb (retinoblastoma protein) prevents cell cycle progression by:",o:["Binding and inhibiting E2F transcription factors, blocking expression of genes needed for S-phase entry","Directly degrading cyclin D-CDK4 complexes through its intrinsic ubiquitin ligase activity","Activating p53, which then triggers apoptosis in cells attempting to divide","Phosphorylating CDK inhibitors like p21, enhancing their ability to arrest the cell cycle"],a:0,ex:"Rb in its hypophosphorylated (active) state binds E2F transcription factors and blocks their ability to activate genes needed for S-phase (DNA polymerase, thymidine kinase, cyclins E and A). When growth signals activate cyclin D-CDK4/6, they phosphorylate Rb, releasing E2F, and the cell progresses past the restriction point into S-phase. Loss of Rb = E2F always active = uncontrolled proliferation.",mn:"Active Rb = holds E2F hostage = no S-phase genes. Cyclin D-CDK4 phosphorylates Rb = releases E2F = cell enters S-phase. Rb loss = permanent E2F activation = cancer."},
{id:"np192",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Research Methods","Experimental Design"],diff:2,q:"A researcher finds a correlation of r = -0.72 between hours of social media use and GPA. This means:",o:["There is a strong negative linear relationship, but social media use may not cause lower GPA","Social media use causes lower GPA with 72% certainty based on the correlation coefficient","There is a weak relationship because the correlation is negative","Approximately 72% of GPA variation is explained by social media use"],a:0,ex:"A correlation of -0.72 is strong (close to -1). Negative means as one variable increases, the other decreases. However, correlation does not establish causation. Confounding variables (e.g., conscientiousness, time management) could explain both. R-squared (0.72^2 = 0.52) gives the proportion of variance explained -- about 52%, not 72%. Negative sign indicates direction, not weakness.",mn:"r = -0.72: strong negative correlation. But correlation =/= causation! R^2 = 0.52 = 52% of variance explained. The negative sign means inverse relationship, not weak."},
{id:"np193",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Learning and Conditioning"],diff:2,q:"According to the elaboration likelihood model, a person who carefully evaluates the logical arguments in a political speech is using:",o:["The central route to persuasion, which produces more durable and resistant attitude change","The peripheral route to persuasion, which relies on superficial cues like speaker attractiveness","Cognitive dissonance reduction by seeking information consistent with pre-existing beliefs","The availability heuristic by focusing on the most memorable parts of the speech"],a:0,ex:"The elaboration likelihood model (Petty & Cacioppo) has two routes: central (careful evaluation of argument quality, facts, logic) and peripheral (reliance on superficial cues like speaker credibility, emotional appeals, number of arguments). Central route requires motivation and ability to process. It produces longer-lasting, more resistant attitude change. Peripheral route produces less durable change.",mn:"Central route = carefully evaluating arguments = durable attitude change. Peripheral route = relying on cues (attractiveness, emotions) = temporary change."},
{id:"np194",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Health Disparities"],diff:2,q:"Fundamental cause theory (Link and Phelan) argues that socioeconomic status (SES) is a fundamental cause of disease because:",o:["SES provides differential access to resources (money, knowledge, power) that can be deployed to avoid risks across changing disease profiles","Low SES directly causes biological changes that increase susceptibility to all diseases","SES correlates with disease only because both are caused by genetic factors inherited across generations","The association between SES and disease exists only in societies with unequal healthcare access"],a:0,ex:"Link and Phelan's fundamental cause theory: SES is a fundamental cause because it embodies resources (money, knowledge, social connections, power) that protect health regardless of the specific disease mechanisms in play. When new diseases emerge or old ones are conquered, SES-health gradients persist because high-SES people can always deploy resources to avoid whatever the current threats are. The association is not about any single mechanism but about flexible resources.",mn:"Fundamental cause: SES = access to flexible resources (money, knowledge, power). Whatever the disease threat, high-SES people can mobilize resources to avoid it. The gradient persists across changing disease profiles."},
{id:"np195",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Brain Anatomy","Psychological Disorders"],diff:2,q:"A patient experiences vivid visual hallucinations of animals that she knows are not real. She has no history of psychiatric illness but was recently diagnosed with Parkinson's disease. These hallucinations are most likely related to:",o:["Dopaminergic medication side effects or Lewy body pathology in visual processing areas","Schizophrenia developing concurrently with Parkinson's disease","Temporal lobe epilepsy triggered by the neurodegenerative process","Conversion disorder manifesting as visual symptoms due to psychological stress of the diagnosis"],a:0,ex:"Visual hallucinations with retained insight (knowing they aren't real) are common in Parkinson's disease and Lewy body dementia. They result from: (1) Lewy body pathology in visual cortex and association areas, and (2) dopaminergic medications (L-DOPA, dopamine agonists) which can cause hallucinations. Unlike schizophrenia hallucinations (usually auditory), Parkinson's hallucinations are typically visual and often involve animals or people.",mn:"Parkinson's visual hallucinations: Lewy bodies in visual cortex + dopamine medication side effects. Visual (not auditory like schizophrenia). Often retains insight."},
{id:"np196",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Identity"],diff:2,q:"According to Erikson's psychosocial stages, an adolescent who feels uncertain about their values, goals, and place in society is experiencing the crisis of:",o:["Identity vs. role confusion, the central developmental challenge of adolescence","Intimacy vs. isolation, which emerges when young adults form close relationships","Industry vs. inferiority, which develops during the school-age years through academic achievement","Generativity vs. stagnation, which concerns contributing to future generations in middle adulthood"],a:0,ex:"Erikson's Stage 5 (adolescence, ~12-18 years): Identity vs. Role Confusion. The adolescent must integrate various self-images and social roles into a coherent identity. Failure leads to role confusion -- uncertainty about who they are and what they stand for. This is distinct from intimacy (Stage 6, young adulthood), industry (Stage 4, school age), and generativity (Stage 7, middle adulthood).",mn:"Erikson Stage 5: Identity vs Role Confusion (adolescence). Must figure out who you are. Failure = confused about values, goals, identity. Stages: trust, autonomy, initiative, industry, IDENTITY, intimacy, generativity, integrity."},
{id:"np197",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Carbonyl Chemistry","Functional Groups"],diff:2,q:"A nucleophilic acyl substitution reaction occurs readily with an acid chloride but not with an amide because:",o:["The Cl leaving group is much more stable than the NH2 leaving group, making acid chlorides far more reactive","Amides have a higher molecular weight that prevents nucleophilic attack","Acid chlorides are aromatic while amides are not, and aromaticity drives the reaction","The carbonyl carbon in amides is more electrophilic than in acid chlorides"],a:0,ex:"Nucleophilic acyl substitution requires a leaving group that can depart after the tetrahedral intermediate forms. Cl- is an excellent leaving group (stable, weak base). NH2- is a terrible leaving group (strong base, unstable). This is why acid chlorides are the most reactive acyl derivatives and amides are the least: reactivity order = acid chloride > anhydride > ester > amide. The nitrogen lone pair also donates into the carbonyl via resonance, reducing electrophilicity.",mn:"Reactivity of acyl derivatives = leaving group ability: Cl- (great) > RCOO- > RO- > NH2- (terrible). Acid chlorides most reactive, amides least."},
{id:"np198",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Stereochemistry"],diff:2,q:"A Fischer projection shows a sugar with the hydroxyl group on the right at the highest-numbered chiral center. This sugar is classified as:",o:["D-configuration, which refers to the stereochemistry at the penultimate carbon relative to glyceraldehyde","L-configuration, because right-sided hydroxyl groups always indicate L-sugars","R-configuration, using Cahn-Ingold-Prelog priority rules applied to the chiral center","Dextrorotatory, meaning it rotates plane-polarized light to the right"],a:0,ex:"D/L nomenclature for sugars: look at the LAST (highest-numbered) chiral center in the Fischer projection. If the OH is on the RIGHT, it is D-sugar. If on the LEFT, it is L-sugar. This is defined by comparison to D-glyceraldehyde. D/L is NOT the same as R/S (different systems) and does NOT predict optical rotation direction (D-fructose is levorotatory despite being D-configured).",mn:"D/L in sugars: last chiral center OH on RIGHT = D. LEFT = L. Named after D-glyceraldehyde. D/L does NOT predict rotation direction! D-fructose rotates left."},
{id:"np199",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions","Stereochemistry"],diff:2,q:"An SN2 reaction at a chiral center produces:",o:["Inversion of configuration (Walden inversion), because the nucleophile attacks from the backside","Retention of configuration, because the nucleophile enters through the leaving group's position","A racemic mixture, because the planar carbocation intermediate allows attack from both sides","Either inversion or retention with equal probability, depending on solvent polarity"],a:0,ex:"SN2 is a concerted (one-step) mechanism where the nucleophile attacks the electrophilic carbon 180 degrees opposite the leaving group (backside attack). This inverts the stereochemistry, like an umbrella flipping in the wind. SN1 produces racemization (via planar carbocation). SN2 always gives inversion at the reaction center.",mn:"SN2 = backside attack = inversion (like an umbrella flipping). One step, concerted. SN1 = carbocation intermediate = racemization."},
{id:"np200",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Functional Groups","Lab Techniques"],diff:2,q:"Extraction of an organic acid from an organic solvent layer into an aqueous layer is best accomplished by:",o:["Washing with aqueous NaOH, which deprotonates the acid to form its water-soluble sodium salt","Washing with aqueous HCl, which protonates the acid to increase its water solubility","Adding anhydrous sodium sulfate to the organic layer to absorb the acid","Heating the organic layer to increase the acid's volatility for collection"],a:0,ex:"Organic acids (RCOOH) are soluble in organic solvents in their protonated (neutral) form. Adding aqueous NaOH deprotonates the acid: RCOOH + NaOH -> RCOO-Na+ + H2O. The resulting sodium carboxylate salt is ionic and water-soluble, so it transfers from the organic layer to the aqueous layer. This is the basis of acid-base extraction in organic chemistry labs.",mn:"Acid-base extraction: RCOOH (organic soluble, neutral) + NaOH -> RCOO-Na+ (water soluble, ionic). Deprotonate to move from organic to aqueous layer."},
{id:"np201",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Carbonyl Chemistry","Functional Groups"],diff:2,q:"In an aldol condensation, the alpha-carbon of one carbonyl compound attacks the carbonyl carbon of another. The driving force for this reaction is:",o:["Formation of a conjugated enone (alpha,beta-unsaturated carbonyl) through dehydration, which is stabilized by extended pi conjugation","The high electronegativity of oxygen, which makes all carbonyl reactions thermodynamically favorable","Release of water as a byproduct, which drives equilibrium to the right by Le Chatelier's principle","Formation of a new C-C bond, which is always exothermic regardless of other structural changes"],a:0,ex:"The aldol condensation involves two steps: (1) aldol addition (forming a beta-hydroxy carbonyl), then (2) dehydration to form an alpha,beta-unsaturated carbonyl (enone). The conjugated system (C=C-C=O) is thermodynamically stabilized by extended pi delocalization. Both the new C-C bond AND the conjugation contribute to the driving force, but the dehydration/conjugation step is what distinguishes condensation from simple addition.",mn:"Aldol condensation: aldol addition + dehydration. Product = conjugated enone (C=C-C=O). Extended pi conjugation stabilizes the product. New C-C bond + conjugation = thermodynamic driving force."});
Object.assign(WX_DATA, {
"np140":[null,"CPS I protein is present at near-normal levels; its low activity is due to missing activator NAG, not enzyme deficiency.","OTC deficiency causes elevated urine orotic acid because excess carbamoyl phosphate enters pyrimidine synthesis. This patient has normal orotic acid.","Arginase deficiency causes elevated arginine, not low citrulline. The biopsy shows normal arginase activity."],
"np141":[null,"Carglumic acid activates CPS I; it does not bypass the urea cycle. The cycle still runs normally once CPS I is activated.","Carglumic acid is a drug, not a gene therapy. It does not correct mutations; it substitutes for the missing activator molecule.","NAG is an obligate activator of CPS I, not an inhibitor. Without NAG, CPS I has zero activity."],
"np142":[null,"Glutamine is not part of the urea cycle. The cycle intermediates are carbamoyl phosphate, citrulline, argininosuccinate, arginine, ornithine, and urea.","Glutaminase activity is not directly inhibited by ammonia. The elevation is due to increased synthesis, not decreased breakdown.","Glutamine is an amino acid, not an acute-phase protein. Acute-phase proteins include CRP, ferritin, and fibrinogen."],
"np143":[null,"CPS I does not produce orotic acid. Orotic acid comes from the pyrimidine synthesis pathway, which uses carbamoyl phosphate as a substrate.","Arginine is not converted to orotic acid. Arginase converts arginine to urea + ornithine.","NAG is not a precursor to orotic acid. NAG activates CPS I; it has no role in pyrimidine synthesis."],
"np144":["This is the EXCEPTION -- CPS I and OTC are mitochondrial, not cytoplasmic.",null,null,null],
"np145":[null,"Electrophoresis separates by charge-to-size ratio, and Val vs Glu differ by only a few daltons -- this has negligible effect on migration. Charge is the dominant factor.","HbS does not polymerize during electrophoresis because samples are oxygenated and dilute. Polymerization requires deoxygenation and high concentration.","The pI of HbS is slightly higher than HbA but still well below 8.6, so HbS remains negatively charged. It is not positively charged at pH 8.6."],
"np146":[null,"HbS does not dissociate into subunits upon deoxygenation. The tetramer remains intact; the problem is that tetramers polymerize into fibers via intermolecular contacts.","Sickling is initially reversible -- oxygenation resolves the polymer. Only after repeated cycles does the membrane become permanently damaged (irreversibly sickled cells).","The Val-6 substitution specifically creates a hydrophobic contact site that mediates protein-protein interactions between HbS molecules. It does affect intermolecular interactions."],
"np147":[null,"Hybrid tetramers (alpha2-betaA-betaS) do form but can still deoxygenate normally. They participate minimally in polymerization because they have only one Val-6 contact site instead of two.","2,3-BPG is not increased in sickle trait, and a left-shifted curve would actually reduce O2 delivery, which is the opposite of what would help.","Gene dosage compensation does not occur -- one beta-A gene produces roughly half the normal HbA. The protection comes from dilution of HbS below the polymer nucleation threshold."],
"np148":[null,"Increasing temperature promotes all hydrophobic interactions nonspecifically. This would not distinguish specific contacts from general aggregation.","A nonspecific aggregation agent would not distinguish specific from nonspecific mechanisms -- it would cause general protein aggregation regardless of HbS-specific contacts.","Maximizing T-state tests whether deoxygenation promotes sickling (already known from Experiment 2) but does not address whether the contacts are specific or general."],
"np149":[null,"TTX specifically blocks voltage-gated Na+ channels. It does not affect gap junctions (connexins), which are the actual intercellular connections.","The Na+/K+ ATPase uses ATP, not voltage-gated Na+ channels. TTX blocks voltage-gated channels, not the pump.","While the upstroke does slow, it does not fully convert to a Ca2+-dependent potential. Some residual Na+ current remains at the TTX concentration described."],
"np150":[null,"This describes the downstream effect correctly but not the mechanism. The key is that Ca2+ entry through L-type channels triggers SR release via CICR, not just direct binding to troponin.","Nifedipine blocks L-type Ca2+ channels in the plasma membrane, not SERCA. SERCA inhibitors include thapsigargin.","Ca2+ channel blockade shortens the action potential plateau but does not significantly hyperpolarize the resting potential, which depends on K+ channels and the Na+/K+ ATPase."],
"np151":[null,"Both Ca2+ and Na+ carry +2 and +1 charges respectively, but the charge per ion is not what determines conduction velocity. The opening/closing kinetics of the channels determine upstroke velocity and thus conduction speed.","While both carry positive charge, the kinetics of the channels differ dramatically. L-type Ca2+ channels open and close much more slowly than fast Na+ channels.","While gap junction density does affect conduction, the primary reason SA/AV node conduction is slow is the Ca2+-dependent upstroke. The passage data directly shows this: 5 V/s vs 200 V/s."],
"np152":[null,"Blocking repolarizing K+ current would slow repolarization, not speed it up. This would lengthen the QT, not shorten it.","Delayed rectifier K+ channels contribute to Phase 3, not Phase 2. Phase 2 balance involves L-type Ca2+ inward and early K+ outward currents.","K+ channels are active during multiple phases, especially Phase 3 repolarization and Phase 4 resting potential maintenance, not just Phase 4."],
"np153":[null,"If a virus caused the disease, removing PrPC might slow entry but would not necessarily prevent all disease, since viruses can use alternative receptors or cause direct cytopathic effects.","Spontaneous misfolding would not require exogenous PrPSc inoculation, but Experiment 2 specifically tests resistance to inoculated PrPSc, not spontaneous formation.","If a nucleic acid encoded the disease, removing PrPC should not prevent disease caused by the nucleic acid replicating independently."],
"np154":[null,"PrPSc and PrPC have identical primary sequences -- they are encoded by the same PRNP gene. The difference is entirely conformational, not sequence-based.","GdnHCl is a chaotropic agent that disrupts non-covalent interactions (hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic interactions). It does not break covalent bonds, so this explanation is incorrect.","The passage specifically states that conversion occurs without nucleic acid involvement (Experiment 1, in vitro). GdnHCl does not specifically destroy nucleic acids."],
"np155":[null,"Solution resistance causes ohmic drops but is negligible at these concentrations. The Nernst equation quantitatively predicts the voltage change based on concentration ratios.","Zn2+ does not plate onto or block the copper electrode. Zn2+ stays in solution at the anode compartment.","This is wrong -- increasing reactant concentration (Cu2+) increases cell potential (Experiment 3). The effect depends on whether the ion is a reactant or product."],
"np156":[null,"Electrons flow through the external wire connecting the electrodes, not through the salt bridge. The salt bridge carries ions, not electrons.","The salt bridge contains KNO3 solution, not Cu2+. Cu2+ is already present in the cathode half-cell.","The salt bridge actually connects the solutions (allowing ion flow). Mixing would not cause a short circuit; it would cause direct electron transfer at the solution interface, which is different from the organized cell reaction."],
"np157":[null,"Zinc atoms do not physically migrate. The Zn2+ ions formed at the anode stay in the anode solution. The salt bridge only carries spectator ions (K+, NO3-).","Current does not mechanically erode electrodes. Mass change is due to the chemical reaction: oxidation dissolves zinc into ions.","While zinc nitrate is soluble, the mass loss is due to electrochemical oxidation, not a reaction with KNO3. The salt bridge ions are spectator ions."],
"np158":[null,"In metabolic acidosis, HCO3- is the primary problem (low). The body compensates by hyperventilating to lower PCO2. Here PCO2 is elevated, making it the primary problem.","Both the pH and PCO2 are consistent with a single primary respiratory acidosis. HCO3- is not significantly low, so there is no concurrent metabolic acidosis.","Chronic respiratory acidosis shows significant renal compensation with HCO3- typically 30-35 mEq/L. This patient's HCO3- of 26 shows minimal compensation, indicating an acute process."],
"np159":[null,"The primary problem is metabolic (HCO3- is critically low at 5). Respiratory alkalosis would show high pH and low PCO2 as the primary event, not as compensation.","Low PCO2 from hyperventilation actually helps raise pH. Without it, the pH would be even lower. CO2 elimination is the compensation, not the cause of acidosis.","The compensation IS effective -- it raised pH from what would have been ~6.8 without compensation to 7.10. Compensation is rarely complete in severe metabolic acidosis; this does not make it ineffective."],
"np160":[null,"If the kidneys overcompensated for respiratory acidosis, the pH would not be this high (7.55). Overcompensation is extremely rare physiologically; the body does not typically overcompensate.","In respiratory alkalosis, PCO2 would be low (primary event) with compensatory HCO3- decrease. Here PCO2 is elevated, indicating it is the compensation, not the primary problem.","The values are internally consistent: plugging into Henderson-Hasselbalch gives pH = 6.1 + log(38/1.44) = 7.52, close to the stated 7.55."],
"np161":[null,"Methyl benzoate (an ester) would not show the 11.8 ppm exchangeable signal -- esters lack an O-H proton. The ester C=O would also appear at ~1735 cm-1, not 1710.","4-hydroxybenzaldehyde would show an aldehyde H at ~9.8 ppm (singlet, non-exchangeable) and would lack the 3.9 ppm OCH3 signal. Its formula would be C7H6O2, not C8H8O3.","Acetophenone (C8H8O) has only one oxygen and no methoxy group. Its formula does not match C8H8O3, and it would show a singlet at ~2.6 ppm (COCH3), not 3.9 ppm."],
"np162":[null,"Sigma bond (sigma to sigma-star) transitions require much higher energy and absorb below 200 nm, well outside the range measured here.","An isolated carbonyl absorbs weakly around 270-280 nm (n to pi-star). The 254 nm peak with strong absorption is characteristic of aromatic pi to pi-star, not isolated C=O.","n to sigma-star transitions occur in the far UV (<200 nm) and are not typically observed in standard UV-vis spectroscopy."],
"np163":[null,"Diffusion of responsibility involves spreading responsibility across multiple people. In all conditions, there is only one participant, so group size is not the variable being manipulated.","The bystander effect describes the reduced likelihood of helping when others are present. These conditions do not vary the number of bystanders.","Social facilitation describes enhanced performance of dominant responses in the presence of others. The conditions vary victim proximity, not audience presence."],
"np164":[null,"Deindividuation typically increases antisocial behavior in groups, not prosocial resistance. Also, the participants are still individually identifiable, not anonymous.","Groupthink involves conformity pressure toward consensus, usually in decision-making groups. Here peers model dissent, which is the opposite of groupthink.","The fundamental attribution error involves attributing others' behavior to personality rather than situation. This question is about the effect of peer behavior on the participant's own obedience, not about attributions."],
"np165":["LEAST support: If participants were fully in an agentic state, they would not show distress. Distress indicates retained moral awareness and personal conflict, contradicting pure agentic state theory.",null,null,null],
"np166":[null,"Research shows stereotype-threatened participants are often MORE motivated (trying harder to disprove the stereotype), not less. The problem is that the extra effort goes toward managing anxiety rather than solving problems.","Experiment 1 directly refutes this: when the test is described as non-diagnostic, the performance gap disappears. If lower ability were the cause, the gap would persist regardless of framing.","Deliberately underperforming is a different phenomenon (self-handicapping). The working memory data shows a genuine cognitive deficit, not strategic behavior."],
"np167":[null,"Self-affirmation does not increase cognitive ability or neural plasticity. It reduces the anxiety that was consuming existing cognitive resources.","The stereotype is not eliminated from awareness. Participants are still aware of it. Self-affirmation reduces its psychological impact, not its salience.","Self-affirmation does not provide counter-stereotypical evidence. It works by broadening the basis of self-worth so that one domain cannot define the entire self-concept."],
"np168":[null,"Adrenal fatigue is not a recognized medical diagnosis. The passage shows elevated waking cortisol (14 vs 8), not low cortisol. The adrenals are overactive, not underactive.","Sustained cortisol is immunosuppressive, not enhancing. Table 1 shows decreased NK cells, T-cells, and IgA -- all indicators of immune suppression.","Sleep disruption can affect cortisol timing, but the passage specifically links the flattened curve to perceived stress levels and shows it persists chronically in high-stress students even during non-exam periods."],
"np169":[null,"Cortisol does not directly lyse immune cells through cytotoxicity. It suppresses their activation and proliferation through gene regulation, primarily via NF-kB inhibition.","Cortisol reduces B-cell function but does not destroy bone marrow precursors. Its primary immunosuppressive mechanism is transcriptional regulation of inflammatory mediators.","Cortisol does not compete with antigens for MHC binding. Its mechanism is intracellular (nuclear receptor -> gene regulation), not surface receptor competition."],
"np170":[null,"The intestine actually has a much larger surface area than the stomach (villi and microvilli). The drug is absorbed in the stomach despite smaller surface area because of favorable pH for passive diffusion.","Passive diffusion, not active transport, is the primary absorption mechanism for most small molecule drugs. The passage describes pH-dependent absorption consistent with passive diffusion.","Plasma protein binding occurs in the blood after absorption, not in the stomach lumen. Stomach acid does not affect plasma protein levels."],
"np171":[null,"There are no pH-activated transport proteins described for this drug. The passage specifically describes passive diffusion based on ionization state.","While the pKa indeed doesn't change, the RATIO of ionized to unionized drug does change with pH. It is this ratio that determines absorption, and it changes dramatically between pH 2 and pH 5.","Improved solubility does not help absorption if the dissolved drug is ionized and cannot cross membranes. Solubility and membrane permeability are different properties."],
"np172":[null,"An increase of 180% means the AUC goes UP by 180% (to 280% of normal), not down. CYP3A4 inhibition reduces drug metabolism, increasing exposure.","AUC directly measures total systemic drug exposure (concentration x time). Higher AUC means higher effective concentration over time.","CYP3A4 inhibition by grapefruit juice lasts 24-72 hours because it destroys the enzyme protein. New CYP3A4 must be synthesized. The effect is not limited to one dose."],
"np173":[null,"While the puzzle-solving comparison was notable, the passage does not identify it as controversial. It is presented as a descriptive observation, not a provocation.","Dismissing anomalies is presented as a factual description of scientific practice, not as a controversial philosophical claim.","The cyclical pattern is presented as Kuhn's descriptive framework, not as his most provocative claim. The controversy centers on the rationality of paradigm shifts."],
"np174":[null,"Kuhn explicitly argues against the smooth accumulation model. Paradigm shifts are revolutionary ruptures, not gradual transitions.","While Kuhn acknowledges sociological factors, he does not reduce paradigm shifts to mere personal charisma. The claim is that non-rational factors supplement, not replace, evidence.","Kuhn's central argument opposes the linear/cumulative view. He argues for discontinuous revolutions, not smooth progression."],
"np175":[null,"Kuhn would actually predict this: younger scientists are less committed to the old paradigm and more open to revolution. This supports, not weakens, his theory.","Kuhn explicitly describes anomaly accumulation as part of normal science leading to crisis. This is evidence FOR his model, not against it.","Different methods across fields does not address whether scientists WITHIN a field can share evaluation criteria during paradigm shifts."],
"np176":[null,"The passage does not claim AI overrides patient preferences. The concern is about opacity, not override.","The passage does not discuss physicians losing independence. The focus is on whether patients can understand AI-driven recommendations.","The passage never suggests high accuracy makes consent unnecessary. It raises the opposite concern: accuracy without transparency still violates autonomy."],
"np177":[null,"This scenario involves only beneficence (reduced wait times) with no clear tension with non-maleficence. It does not illustrate the bias-related conflict described in the passage.","This scenario actually resolves the tension by keeping the physician in the decision loop. It does not illustrate a conflict between principles.","Regulatory benchmarks address general safety but do not illustrate the specific tension between aggregate benefit and subgroup harm described in the passage."],
"np178":[null,"The passage specifically argues that placement depends on factors beyond test scores, including teacher recommendations influenced by implicit bias. Tracking is not presented as accurate prediction.","The passage attributes the performance gap to institutional factors (teacher quality, rigor, expectations), not to student beliefs or deliberate underperformance.","This is the position the passage argues AGAINST. The whole point of the self-fulfilling prophecy framing is that tracking creates differences rather than reflecting pre-existing ones."],
"np179":[null,"The passage states the opposite: schools that implement detracking report 'narrowing achievement gaps without measurable harm to high-achieving students.'","The passage does not attribute greater educational expertise to affluent parents. It frames their resistance as protecting perceived competitive advantage, not as pedagogically informed.","Detracking reorganizes classes within the same school, not between schools. It does not involve school reassignment."],
"np180":[null,"The passage explicitly states the opposite: 'Recipients generally maintain or increase employment, contradicting predictions of mass idleness.'","The passage does not raise sample size concerns. The limitation is about systemic vs. individual effects, not statistical power.","The passage cites pilots in Finland, Kenya, and Stockton, California -- diverse populations, not exclusively wealthy ones."],
"np181":[null,"While economists do disagree about costs, the passage's point is deeper: even with perfect cost data, the question of whether to implement UBI is a values question.","The passage does not claim philosophical and economic traditions are incompatible. It argues that the fundamental question is philosophical rather than economic.","The passage presents the work-ethic concern as one view (Schumpeter-adjacent) but does not endorse it as proven. The conclusion frames it as an open philosophical question, not a settled one."],
"np182":[null,"Negative E-cell means non-spontaneous. This contradicts K>1, which indicates products are favored (spontaneous direction).","Positive delta-G means non-spontaneous, which contradicts positive E-cell (spontaneous). These values are thermodynamically inconsistent.","All three values here indicate non-spontaneous. While internally consistent, this describes an electrolytic cell, not a galvanic cell."],
"np183":[null,"A virtual image would have negative di. Here di = +30 cm (positive), so the image is real and on the opposite side from the object.","1/di = 1/10 - 1/15 = 1/30, so di = 30 cm, not 6 cm. Check the arithmetic: 3/30 - 2/30 = 1/30.","Virtual and upright would require the object to be inside the focal length (do < f). Here do = 15 > f = 10, so the object is outside the focal length, producing a real, inverted image."],
"np184":[null,"Half-life removes half of the REMAINING amount, not a fixed amount. After the first half-life: 40 (not 65). After the second: 20 (not 50). The amounts get smaller each time.","24/6 = 4 half-lives exactly, not 2.4. The number of half-lives is the total time divided by the half-life period.","Radioactive decay is exponential and never reaches exactly zero. After 4 half-lives, 1/16 of the original amount remains (5 mg)."],
"np185":[null,"Molecular weight does not determine boiling point elevation. Colligative properties depend on the NUMBER of particles, not their size or mass.","Boiling point elevation is a colligative property that depends on particle count, not on the type of intermolecular forces the solute forms with the solvent.","Thermal conductivity is not related to colligative properties. Boiling point elevation results from solute particles lowering the vapor pressure of the solvent."],
"np186":[null,"Below 400K, this reaction IS spontaneous (delta-G is negative). It becomes non-spontaneous above 400K when the -TdeltaS term (positive because delta-S is negative) exceeds the favorable delta-H.","It is not spontaneous at all temperatures. At temperatures above 400K, the unfavorable entropy term (-TdeltaS) overwhelms the favorable enthalpy, making delta-G positive.","Exothermic reactions are NOT always spontaneous. When delta-S is also negative, high temperatures can make delta-G positive. Spontaneity depends on BOTH enthalpy and entropy."],
"np187":[null,"CD4+ helper T-cells recognize antigens presented on MHC class II, not class I. MHC I deficiency would not directly impair CD4+ responses.","B-cell activation does not require MHC I. B-cells are activated through their B-cell receptor binding antigen and through CD4+ T-cell help via MHC II.","NK cells kill cells that LACK MHC I (missing-self recognition). MHC I deficiency would actually make cells MORE susceptible to NK killing, not less."],
"np188":[null,"TSH is suppressed, not elevated. The high T3/T4 from antibody stimulation activates negative feedback on the pituitary. The antibodies stimulate the thyroid but cannot stimulate the pituitary.","The autoantibodies ACTIVATE the TSH receptor, causing increased hormone production. They do not block it. Blocking antibodies would cause hypothyroidism.","The body cannot compensate -- the autoantibodies continuously stimulate the thyroid regardless of TSH levels, causing sustained hyperthyroidism."],
"np189":[null,"ADH regulates water reabsorption in the collecting duct, not glucose reabsorption in the proximal tubule. Glucose reabsorption depends on SGLT2 transporters, not water balance.","Lower GFR would filter less glucose, not more. This would actually reduce the glucose load on SGLT2 transporters, making glucosuria less likely.","Aldosterone promotes Na+ reabsorption and K+ secretion in the distal tubule and collecting duct. It does not promote glucose secretion."],
"np190":[null,"Fluent/receptive aphasia results from damage to Wernicke's area (posterior superior temporal gyrus), not Broca's area.","Global aphasia involves damage to both Broca's and Wernicke's areas (or the arcuate fasciculus connecting them). Isolated Broca's damage does not produce global aphasia.","Anomic aphasia involves difficulty with word-finding but is associated with diffuse or angular gyrus damage, not specifically Broca's area. Broca's aphasia is non-fluent, not anomic."],
"np191":[null,"Rb does not have ubiquitin ligase activity and does not degrade cyclin-CDK complexes. Rb is a transcriptional repressor that works by sequestering E2F.","Rb and p53 are separate tumor suppressor pathways. Rb does not directly activate p53. They cooperate but through independent mechanisms.","Rb does not phosphorylate anything -- it IS phosphorylated (by CDK4/6) to become inactive. Rb is a substrate, not a kinase."],
"np192":[null,"Correlation never establishes causation regardless of strength. The coefficient measures association strength, not causal certainty.","The sign (positive or negative) indicates direction, not strength. Strength is determined by the absolute value: |0.72| is strong regardless of sign.","R-squared (0.52), not r (0.72), gives the proportion of variance explained. Squaring the correlation gives the coefficient of determination."],
"np193":[null,"Peripheral route uses superficial cues (attractiveness, expertise cues, emotional tone), not careful logical evaluation. Careful argument analysis is the central route.","Cognitive dissonance is a separate theory about attitude change following inconsistency between beliefs and behavior. It is not part of the elaboration likelihood model.","The availability heuristic is about estimating frequency/probability based on ease of recall. It is a cognitive shortcut unrelated to the persuasion model described."],
"np194":[null,"Low SES does not directly cause biological changes. The theory emphasizes that SES operates through access to resources, knowledge, and power -- not through a direct biological mechanism.","Genetic reductionism does not explain the SES-health gradient. SES is primarily socially determined, and the gradient persists across societies with different genetic compositions.","The SES-health gradient exists even in countries with universal healthcare (e.g., UK, Scandinavia). Access to healthcare is one resource, but money, knowledge, and power provide health advantages beyond clinical care."],
"np195":[null,"New-onset schizophrenia in an elderly patient with Parkinson's is extremely unlikely. Parkinson's hallucinations are a well-recognized feature of the disease itself, not a concurrent psychiatric condition.","While temporal lobe epilepsy can cause visual phenomena, these are typically brief, stereotyped auras, not formed visual hallucinations of animals. The Parkinson's context makes Lewy body or medication etiology far more likely.","Conversion disorder produces neurological symptoms without organic cause, but this patient has a known organic disease (Parkinson's) that commonly causes visual hallucinations."],
"np196":[null,"Intimacy vs. isolation is Stage 6, occurring in young adulthood (18-40). The question describes an adolescent, not a young adult forming romantic relationships.","Industry vs. inferiority is Stage 4, occurring in school-age children (6-12). The question describes adolescent identity concerns, not academic competence concerns.","Generativity vs. stagnation is Stage 7, occurring in middle adulthood (40-65). The question describes an adolescent, not a middle-aged adult."],
"np197":[null,"Molecular weight does not determine reactivity in nucleophilic substitution. The key factor is leaving group stability.","Neither acid chlorides nor amides are aromatic. Aromaticity is not relevant to nucleophilic acyl substitution reactivity.","The opposite is true: the carbonyl carbon in amides is LESS electrophilic than in acid chlorides because nitrogen's lone pair donates electron density into the carbonyl via resonance."],
"np198":[null,"This is backward: OH on the right = D, not L. L-sugars have the OH on the LEFT at the highest-numbered chiral center.","R/S (Cahn-Ingold-Prelog) and D/L are completely different naming systems. D/L compares to glyceraldehyde; R/S uses priority rules. A D-sugar can be R or S at different carbons.","D/L does NOT indicate optical rotation direction. Dextrorotatory (+) and levorotatory (-) are measured experimentally. D-glucose happens to be dextrorotatory, but D-fructose is levorotatory."],
"np199":[null,"Front-side (retention) attack does not occur in SN2 because the leaving group blocks that approach. The nucleophile can only attack from the opposite side.","Racemic mixtures result from SN1 reactions via a planar carbocation intermediate. SN2 has no carbocation intermediate -- it is concerted with mandatory backside attack.","SN2 inversion is not random or solvent-dependent. The backside attack mechanism always produces clean inversion at the chiral center."],
"np200":[null,"HCl would protonate the acid further (or have no effect since it's already protonated), keeping it in its neutral, organic-soluble form. You need base, not acid, to extract an organic acid.","Sodium sulfate is a drying agent that removes water from organic layers. It does not selectively remove organic acids.","Heating would evaporate solvent, not selectively remove the acid. Extraction uses differences in solubility between ionized and neutral forms, not volatility."],
"np201":[null,"While oxygen electronegativity contributes to carbonyl reactivity, not all carbonyl reactions are thermodynamically favorable. The specific driving force here is conjugation stabilization.","Le Chatelier's principle is relevant but is a secondary effect. The primary thermodynamic driving force is the stability gained from conjugation in the enone product.","New C-C bonds are not always exothermic. The energetics depend on the specific bonds formed and broken. Here, conjugation stabilization is the key driving force."]});

// === PROMPT 5: EXPANDED CONTENT ===
PASSAGES["p72"]={"text": "A biochemistry lab studies the regulation of pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDC) in rat liver cells. PDC catalyzes the irreversible conversion of pyruvate to acetyl-CoA, linking glycolysis to the citric acid cycle. The researchers measure PDC activity under different metabolic conditions. In Condition A (fed state), PDC activity is high, with low NADH/NAD+ and low acetyl-CoA/CoA ratios. In Condition B (fasted state), PDC activity drops by 80%, with elevated NADH/NAD+ and acetyl-CoA/CoA ratios. They also find that insulin activates PDC phosphatase (which activates PDC by removing phosphate), while PDC kinase (which inactivates PDC by adding phosphate) is activated by elevated ATP, NADH, and acetyl-CoA. When they add dichloroacetate (DCA), a PDC kinase inhibitor, to fasted liver cells, PDC activity increases to near-fed levels."};
PASSAGES["p73"]={"text": "A molecular biology lab investigates the lac operon in E. coli under four growth conditions. In Condition 1 (glucose present, no lactose), beta-galactosidase activity is undetectable. In Condition 2 (glucose absent, lactose present), beta-galactosidase activity is high. In Condition 3 (both glucose and lactose present), activity is low but detectable. In Condition 4 (neither glucose nor lactose), activity is undetectable. The researchers note that cAMP levels are inversely related to glucose concentration: high glucose depletes cAMP, while low glucose allows cAMP accumulation. The cAMP-CAP complex binds upstream of the lac promoter and enhances RNA polymerase binding. A mutant strain with a defective lacI gene shows constitutive beta-galactosidase expression regardless of lactose availability."};
PASSAGES["p74"]={"text": "An organic chemistry student performs a series of reactions starting with (R)-2-bromobutane. In Reaction 1, the substrate is treated with NaCN in DMSO, yielding a product with inverted stereochemistry. In Reaction 2, the same substrate is dissolved in aqueous ethanol and heated, producing a racemic mixture of substitution products along with alkene byproducts. In Reaction 3, the substrate is treated with potassium tert-butoxide in tert-butanol, yielding predominantly 2-butene (Zaitsev product) with no substitution product observed. The student measures the reaction rates and finds that Reaction 1 rate depends on both substrate and nucleophile concentration, Reaction 2 rate depends only on substrate concentration, and Reaction 3 shows second-order kinetics overall."};
PASSAGES["p75"]={"text": "A physics experiment examines the behavior of light passing through different optical systems. In Setup A, a beam of white light passes through a glass prism (n = 1.52), separating into its component colors with violet bending more than red. In Setup B, light travels from water (n = 1.33) into air (n = 1.00) at various angles; at angles above 48.8 degrees from the normal, total internal reflection occurs. In Setup C, a converging lens with focal length 20 cm is used to form images of objects at different distances. When the object is placed 30 cm from the lens, a real, inverted image forms at 60 cm on the other side. When the object is placed 10 cm from the lens (inside the focal point), a virtual, upright, magnified image is observed."};
PASSAGES["p76"]={"text": "A cell biology study examines apoptosis (programmed cell death) versus necrosis in cultured hepatocytes exposed to different stressors. In Group A (UV radiation), cells show chromatin condensation, membrane blebbing, formation of apoptotic bodies, and activation of caspase-3. DNA gel electrophoresis reveals a characteristic ladder pattern of fragments at 180-bp intervals. In Group B (severe hypoxia followed by reoxygenation), cells show swelling, membrane rupture, organelle degradation, and inflammatory infiltration of surrounding tissue. DNA electrophoresis shows random-length smearing. In Group C (moderate oxidative stress with H2O2), cells initially show apoptotic features, but at higher concentrations transition to necrotic morphology, suggesting a dose-dependent switch between death pathways."};
PASSAGES["p77"]={"text": "Researchers investigate the genetics of coat color in mice using crosses between different inbred lines. Gene A controls pigment production (A_ = pigmented, aa = albino). Gene B controls pigment distribution (B_ = agouti/brown, bb = black). When they cross AaBb x AaBb mice, the expected 9:3:3:1 ratio is observed in offspring: 9 agouti, 3 black, 3 brown (a modified category), and 1 albino. However, when they introduce a third gene C (where cc is epistatic to both A and B, producing a white phenotype regardless of other genotypes), a cross of AaBbCc x AaBbCc yields a modified ratio of 27:9:9:3:16. The researchers confirm that the 16 white mice carry at least one cc allele, masking the phenotypic effects of genes A and B."};
PASSAGES["p78"]={"text": "A developmental psychology study follows 200 children from ages 2 to 18, assessing cognitive development using standardized tests at regular intervals. Consistent with Piaget's theory, children in the preoperational stage (ages 2-7) demonstrate egocentrism and fail conservation tasks. By age 7-11 (concrete operational), most children pass conservation tasks and demonstrate reversibility of thought, but struggle with abstract hypothetical reasoning. By age 12+, formal operational thinking emerges, including hypothetical-deductive reasoning and systematic problem-solving. Notably, 15% of adolescents never fully achieve formal operational thinking by age 18. The researchers also find that children raised in environments with rich problem-solving opportunities reach each stage approximately 1.5 years earlier than those in less stimulating environments, supporting Vygotsky's emphasis on social learning."};
QS.push({id: "ek16", cat: "ENZYME_KINETICS", tags: ["Metabolic Regulation", "Enzyme Inhibition"], diff: 3, pass: "p72", q: "Based on the passage, PDC activity is reduced in fasted state primarily because:", o: ["PDC kinase phosphorylates and inactivates PDC", "PDC phosphatase removes activating phosphate groups", "Pyruvate concentration drops below Km", "Insulin directly inhibits PDC"], a: 0, ex: "In the fasted state, elevated NADH, acetyl-CoA, and ATP activate PDC kinase. PDC kinase phosphorylates PDC, inactivating it. This prevents pyruvate from entering the TCA cycle, redirecting it toward gluconeogenesis instead.", mn: "Fasting = kinase ON = PDC OFF. Fed = phosphatase ON = PDC ON."});
QS.push({id: "ek17", cat: "ENZYME_KINETICS", tags: ["Metabolic Regulation", "Experimental Design"], diff: 3, pass: "p72", q: "The effect of DCA on fasted liver cells demonstrates that:", o: ["PDC kinase inhibition restores PDC activity even without insulin", "Insulin is required for any PDC activation", "PDC phosphatase is constitutively active", "Acetyl-CoA directly activates PDC"], a: 0, ex: "DCA inhibits PDC kinase, preventing it from phosphorylating (inactivating) PDC. Even without insulin signaling, blocking the kinase allows PDC phosphatase to keep PDC in its active (dephosphorylated) form. This shows the kinase is the primary off-switch.", mn: "DCA blocks the OFF switch, so PDC stays ON."});
QS.push({id: "ek18", cat: "ENZYME_KINETICS", tags: ["Metabolic Regulation", "Enzyme Inhibition"], diff: 2, pass: "p72", fmt: "data", q: "If NADH/NAD+ ratio increases 5-fold while acetyl-CoA/CoA stays constant, PDC activity would most likely:", o: ["Decrease, because NADH activates PDC kinase", "Increase, because NADH activates PDC phosphatase", "Remain unchanged since only acetyl-CoA matters", "Increase, because NADH directly activates PDC"], a: 0, ex: "NADH is one of the signals that activates PDC kinase. Higher NADH/NAD+ means more kinase activity, more phosphorylation, and less active PDC. The passage states PDC kinase is activated by elevated NADH.", mn: "High NADH = 'enough energy' signal = slow down PDC."});
QS.push({id: "ek19", cat: "ENZYME_KINETICS", tags: ["Enzyme Inhibition", "Kinetics Parameters"], diff: 2, q: "An enzyme follows Michaelis-Menten kinetics with Km = 5 mM. At [S] = 5 mM, the reaction rate is:", o: ["Exactly half of Vmax", "Equal to Vmax", "One-quarter of Vmax", "Cannot determine without Vmax"], a: 0, ex: "By definition, Km is the substrate concentration at which the reaction rate equals exactly half of Vmax. When [S] = Km, V = Vmax/2. This is the most fundamental relationship in enzyme kinetics.", mn: "Km = [S] at half-max. When [S] = Km, V = Vmax/2. Always."});
QS.push({id: "ek20", cat: "ENZYME_KINETICS", tags: ["Enzyme Inhibition", "Kinetics Parameters"], diff: 3, fmt: "except", q: "All of the following would increase the rate of an enzymatic reaction EXCEPT:", o: ["Adding a noncompetitive inhibitor", "Increasing substrate concentration (below Vmax)", "Increasing enzyme concentration", "Raising temperature toward the optimum"], a: 0, ex: "A noncompetitive inhibitor lowers Vmax by reducing effective enzyme concentration. It always decreases the maximum rate. The other three options all increase rate: more substrate pushes toward Vmax, more enzyme raises Vmax, and approaching optimal temperature increases catalytic efficiency.", mn: "EXCEPT = find the one that HURTS. Inhibitors hurt."});
QS.push({id: "ek21", cat: "ENZYME_KINETICS", tags: ["Enzyme Inhibition"], diff: 2, q: "Allosteric enzymes differ from Michaelis-Menten enzymes in that they:", o: ["Show sigmoidal rather than hyperbolic kinetics", "Always have lower Km values", "Cannot be regulated by inhibitors", "Follow first-order kinetics at all substrate concentrations"], a: 0, ex: "Allosteric enzymes have multiple subunits with cooperative binding, producing a sigmoidal (S-shaped) V vs [S] curve instead of the hyperbolic curve of simple Michaelis-Menten enzymes. They don't follow classical Michaelis-Menten assumptions.", mn: "Allosteric = S-curve. Michaelis-Menten = hyperbolic."});
QS.push({id: "gen17", cat: "GENETICS", tags: ["Mendelian Genetics", "Experimental Design"], diff: 3, pass: "p77", q: "The 27:9:9:3:16 ratio in the trihybrid cross results from:", o: ["Recessive epistasis by gene C masking A and B phenotypes", "Codominance between genes A and B", "Incomplete penetrance of gene C", "X-linked inheritance of gene C"], a: 0, ex: "When cc is present (probability 1/4), it masks both A and B phenotypes, producing white regardless. The 16/64 white mice are all the cc genotypes (1/4 of 64). The remaining 48/64 (3/4 CC or Cc) show the normal 9:3:3:1 ratio scaled up: 27:9:9:3.", mn: "Recessive epistasis: cc hides everything above it."});
QS.push({id: "gen18", cat: "GENETICS", tags: ["Mendelian Genetics"], diff: 3, pass: "p77", q: "In the trihybrid cross, what fraction of pigmented offspring are expected to be agouti?", o: ["9/16 of non-white offspring (27 out of 48)", "9/16 of all offspring", "27/64 of all offspring", "3/4 of all offspring"], a: 2, ex: "27 out of 64 total offspring are agouti. But if the question asks about non-white offspring specifically, it's 27/48 = 9/16. Read the question carefully: 'of pigmented offspring' vs 'of all offspring' changes the denominator.", mn: "27/64 total, or 9/16 of the 48 non-white."});
QS.push({id: "gen19", cat: "GENETICS", tags: ["Population Genetics"], diff: 2, q: "In Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, which condition is NOT required?", o: ["Equal reproductive success of all genotypes (no selection)", "Large population size", "Random mating", "Equal numbers of males and females"], a: 3, ex: "Hardy-Weinberg requires: no selection, no mutation, no migration, random mating, and large population. Equal sex ratio is not a requirement. The five conditions ensure allele frequencies remain constant across generations.", mn: "HW needs: No SMMR + Large pop. (Selection, Mutation, Migration, Random mating, Large)."});
QS.push({id: "gen20", cat: "GENETICS", tags: ["Mendelian Genetics"], diff: 2, fmt: "twostep", q: "A woman who is a carrier for hemophilia A (X-linked recessive) has children with an unaffected man. What is the probability their first son is affected?", o: ["1/2", "1/4", "1/8", "0"], a: 0, ex: "Step 1: The mother is X^H X^h (carrier). The father is X^H Y. Step 2: For SONS specifically (XY), they get X from mom: 50% chance of X^h (affected) or X^H (unaffected). So P(affected son) = 1/2. Note: P(affected child) = 1/4 since only half of children are sons.", mn: "X-linked: sons get mom's X. Carrier mom = 50% chance for each son."});
QS.push({id: "gen21", cat: "GENETICS", tags: ["Mendelian Genetics", "Experimental Design"], diff: 3, q: "A chi-squared test on a monohybrid cross yields X² = 0.53 with 1 degree of freedom. The critical value at p = 0.05 is 3.84. This means:", o: ["The observed results are consistent with the expected ratio (fail to reject null)", "The observed results significantly deviate from expected (reject null)", "The experiment should be repeated with more organisms", "The inheritance pattern is not Mendelian"], a: 0, ex: "X² (0.53) < critical value (3.84), so we fail to reject the null hypothesis. The observed data is consistent with the expected Mendelian ratio. There is no statistically significant deviation. We'd only reject if X² exceeded 3.84.", mn: "X² < critical value = data fits the model. Don't reject."});
QS.push({id: "gen22", cat: "GENETICS", tags: ["Mendelian Genetics"], diff: 2, q: "Nondisjunction during meiosis I differs from meiosis II in that:", o: ["Meiosis I nondisjunction affects all four resulting gametes", "Meiosis II nondisjunction produces two normal and two abnormal gametes", "Meiosis I nondisjunction only affects sex chromosomes", "Both produce identical outcomes"], a: 1, ex: "In meiosis I nondisjunction, homologs fail to separate, so all 4 gametes are abnormal (2 with an extra chromosome, 2 missing one). In meiosis II, sister chromatids fail to separate, but only 2 of 4 gametes are affected — the other 2 are normal.", mn: "MI = all 4 bad. MII = 2 bad + 2 good."});
QS.push({id: "gen23", cat: "GENETICS", tags: ["Mendelian Genetics"], diff: 2, q: "A couple has had 3 unaffected children. Both parents are carriers for an autosomal recessive condition. The probability their 4th child is affected is:", o: ["1/4", "Less than 1/4 because previous children were unaffected", "3/4", "1/16"], a: 0, ex: "Each pregnancy is an independent event. Previous outcomes don't affect future probabilities (gambler's fallacy). Aa x Aa always gives 1/4 chance of aa regardless of how many unaffected children they've already had.", mn: "Each child = independent coin flip. Past results don't change the odds."});
QS.push({id: "mb15", cat: "MOLECULAR_BIO", tags: ["Gene Expression", "Experimental Design"], diff: 3, pass: "p73", q: "In the passage, Condition 3 shows low but detectable beta-galactosidase because:", o: ["Glucose represses via low cAMP even though lactose removes the repressor", "Lactose inhibits the lac repressor but glucose activates it", "Both glucose and lactose activate the operon partially", "The CAP protein directly blocks transcription"], a: 0, ex: "With both sugars present: lactose (via allolactose) removes the lac repressor, allowing some transcription. But glucose keeps cAMP low, so the cAMP-CAP activator complex cannot form, meaning RNA polymerase binds poorly. Result: low but not zero expression. This is catabolite repression.", mn: "Glucose = boss. Even if lactose says GO, glucose says SLOW DOWN via low cAMP."});
QS.push({id: "mb16", cat: "MOLECULAR_BIO", tags: ["Gene Expression"], diff: 2, pass: "p73", q: "The lacI mutant strain shows constitutive expression because:", o: ["No functional repressor protein is made, so the operator is always open", "cAMP levels are permanently elevated", "RNA polymerase has increased affinity for the promoter", "The inducer is produced endogenously"], a: 0, ex: "The lacI gene encodes the lac repressor. Without it, no repressor binds the operator, so RNA polymerase can always access the structural genes. Expression occurs regardless of lactose presence. This is constitutive (always-on) expression.", mn: "No repressor = door always open = genes always ON."});
QS.push({id: "mb17", cat: "MOLECULAR_BIO", tags: ["Gene Expression", "Experimental Design"], diff: 3, pass: "p73", fmt: "data", q: "If researchers add a non-hydrolyzable cAMP analog to cells in Condition 1 (glucose, no lactose), beta-galactosidase activity would:", o: ["Remain undetectable because the repressor still blocks the operator", "Become high because cAMP-CAP now activates transcription", "Become moderate because only one regulatory element is active", "Decrease further because excess cAMP inhibits translation"], a: 0, ex: "Even with cAMP-CAP bound upstream (activator present), the lac repressor is still bound to the operator (no lactose to remove it). The repressor physically blocks RNA polymerase. Both conditions must be met: repressor OFF and activator ON. Having only the activator isn't enough.", mn: "Lac operon needs BOTH: repressor off AND CAP on. One isn't enough."});
QS.push({id: "mb18", cat: "MOLECULAR_BIO", tags: ["Gene Expression"], diff: 2, q: "Which post-transcriptional modification is NOT found on eukaryotic mRNA?", o: ["Addition of a poly-A tail at the 5' end", "5' capping with 7-methylguanosine", "Splicing to remove introns", "Polyadenylation at the 3' end"], a: 0, ex: "The poly-A tail is added to the 3' end, not the 5' end. The 5' end receives a 7-methylguanosine cap. Both modifications protect mRNA from degradation and facilitate translation. Splicing removes introns from pre-mRNA.", mn: "5' = cap (G hat). 3' = tail (AAAA). Never reversed.", fmt: "except"});
QS.push({id: "mb19", cat: "MOLECULAR_BIO", tags: ["Gene Expression"], diff: 2, q: "During translation, the ribosome moves along mRNA in which direction?", o: ["5' to 3'", "3' to 5'", "Both directions simultaneously", "Direction depends on the codon sequence"], a: 0, ex: "Ribosomes read mRNA codons in the 5' to 3' direction. This means the protein is synthesized from N-terminus to C-terminus. The mRNA was also transcribed 5' to 3' by RNA polymerase, so both processes move in the same direction on the template.", mn: "Everything goes 5'→3': transcription, translation, mRNA reading."});
QS.push({id: "mb20", cat: "MOLECULAR_BIO", tags: ["Gene Expression"], diff: 3, q: "A point mutation changes a codon from UAC to UAG. This is a:", o: ["Nonsense mutation creating a premature stop codon", "Missense mutation changing the amino acid", "Silent mutation with no effect on protein", "Frameshift mutation disrupting the reading frame"], a: 0, ex: "UAC codes for tyrosine. UAG is one of the three stop codons (UAG, UAA, UGA). Changing a sense codon to a stop codon is a nonsense mutation, causing premature termination and usually a nonfunctional truncated protein.", mn: "UAG/UAA/UGA = STOP. Sense→Stop = nonsense mutation."});
QS.push({id: "cb20", cat: "CELL_BIO", tags: ["Cell Cycle", "Experimental Design"], diff: 3, pass: "p76", q: "The DNA ladder pattern in Group A indicates:", o: ["Internucleosomal cleavage by caspase-activated DNase during apoptosis", "Random DNA degradation by lysosomal enzymes", "Replication fork collapse during S phase", "Restriction enzyme digestion at palindromic sites"], a: 0, ex: "During apoptosis, caspase-activated DNase (CAD) cleaves DNA between nucleosomes (every ~180 bp). This creates the characteristic 'ladder' of DNA fragments at multiples of 180 bp on a gel. Necrosis produces random smearing instead.", mn: "Ladder = apoptosis (orderly). Smear = necrosis (chaotic)."});
QS.push({id: "cb21", cat: "CELL_BIO", tags: ["Cell Cycle"], diff: 2, pass: "p76", q: "Group B shows necrosis rather than apoptosis. Which feature distinguishes necrosis?", o: ["Membrane rupture causing inflammatory response", "Formation of apoptotic bodies", "Caspase-3 activation", "Chromatin condensation"], a: 0, ex: "Necrosis is characterized by cell swelling, membrane rupture, and release of cellular contents that trigger inflammation. Apoptosis is orderly: chromatin condenses, caspases activate, membrane blebs but doesn't rupture, and apoptotic bodies are engulfed without inflammation.", mn: "Necrosis = messy explosion (inflammation). Apoptosis = quiet cleanup (no inflammation)."});
QS.push({id: "cb22", cat: "CELL_BIO", tags: ["Cell Cycle", "Experimental Design"], diff: 3, pass: "p76", fmt: "twostep", q: "Group C's dose-dependent switch from apoptosis to necrosis most likely occurs because:", o: ["High ROS levels overwhelm caspase pathways and cause direct membrane damage", "Low concentrations activate p53 while high concentrations do not", "Apoptosis requires more ATP than necrosis, and severe stress depletes ATP", "All oxidative stress triggers necrosis regardless of dose"], a: 2, ex: "Step 1: Apoptosis is an active, energy-requiring process that needs ATP for caspase activation and apoptotic body formation. Step 2: Severe oxidative stress depletes ATP (damages mitochondria), making the cell unable to execute apoptosis. It defaults to necrosis — a passive, uncontrolled death. This ATP-dependent switch is a key MCAT concept.", mn: "Apoptosis needs energy. No ATP = can't do apoptosis = default to necrosis."});
QS.push({id: "cb23", cat: "CELL_BIO", tags: ["Membrane Transport"], diff: 2, q: "Facilitated diffusion differs from active transport in that it:", o: ["Does not require ATP and moves solutes down their concentration gradient", "Requires a membrane protein", "Is slower than simple diffusion", "Can only transport ions"], a: 0, ex: "Facilitated diffusion uses carrier proteins or channels but moves solutes DOWN their concentration gradient without ATP. Active transport moves solutes AGAINST their gradient and requires energy. Both use membrane proteins, so that's not a distinguishing feature.", mn: "Facilitated = downhill + protein + no ATP. Active = uphill + protein + ATP."});
QS.push({id: "cb24", cat: "CELL_BIO", tags: ["Organelles"], diff: 2, fmt: "except", q: "All of the following are functions of the smooth endoplasmic reticulum EXCEPT:", o: ["Protein synthesis and folding", "Lipid synthesis", "Steroid hormone production", "Drug detoxification"], a: 0, ex: "Protein synthesis occurs on the ROUGH ER (ribosomes attached). The smooth ER lacks ribosomes and handles: lipid/phospholipid synthesis, steroid hormone production, drug/toxin detoxification (especially in liver), and calcium storage in muscle cells.", mn: "Rough = Ribosomes = pRotein. Smooth = Steroids, lipids, detox."});
QS.push({id: "org22", cat: "ORGO", tags: ["Substitution Reactions", "Stereochemistry"], diff: 3, pass: "p74", q: "Reaction 1 produces inverted stereochemistry because:", o: ["SN2 proceeds via backside attack on the electrophilic carbon", "SN1 forms a planar carbocation intermediate", "E2 requires anti-periplanar geometry", "The CN⁻ nucleophile attacks from the front side"], a: 0, ex: "Reaction 1 is SN2: strong nucleophile (CN⁻) + polar aprotic solvent (DMSO) + rate depends on both [substrate] and [nucleophile]. SN2 is concerted with mandatory backside attack, producing complete inversion of configuration (Walden inversion).", mn: "SN2 = backside attack = inversion. Always."});
QS.push({id: "org23", cat: "ORGO", tags: ["Substitution Reactions"], diff: 2, pass: "p74", q: "Reaction 2 produces a racemic mixture because:", o: ["The SN1 carbocation intermediate is planar and attacked from both faces", "SN2 has equal probability of front and back attack", "The solvent randomizes stereochemistry", "E1 elimination destroys the stereocenter"], a: 0, ex: "Reaction 2 is SN1: polar protic solvent (aqueous ethanol), rate depends only on [substrate], and racemic products. The carbocation intermediate is sp2 (planar), so the nucleophile can attack from either face with roughly equal probability, yielding a racemic mixture.", mn: "SN1 = carbocation = flat = both sides = racemization."});
QS.push({id: "org24", cat: "ORGO", tags: ["Substitution Reactions"], diff: 3, pass: "p74", fmt: "twostep", q: "Reaction 3 gives exclusively elimination product because:", o: ["tert-Butoxide is too bulky for SN2 and a strong enough base for E2", "The substrate is primary, favoring elimination", "Polar protic solvent always favors elimination", "Heat is not required for E2 to occur"], a: 0, ex: "Step 1: tert-Butoxide is a strong base but extremely bulky — too large to perform the backside attack needed for SN2. Step 2: As a strong base, it abstracts a beta-proton in a concerted E2 mechanism. The 2° substrate can form a stable alkene product (Zaitsev). No SN1/E1 because no polar protic solvent.", mn: "Big base + strong = E2. Can't fit for SN2."});
QS.push({id: "org25", cat: "ORGO", tags: ["Functional Groups"], diff: 2, q: "Rank the following in order of decreasing acidity: carboxylic acid, alcohol, phenol, alkane", o: ["Carboxylic acid > phenol > alcohol > alkane", "Phenol > carboxylic acid > alcohol > alkane", "Alcohol > phenol > carboxylic acid > alkane", "Alkane > alcohol > phenol > carboxylic acid"], a: 0, ex: "Acidity follows conjugate base stability: carboxylate (resonance-stabilized, 2 equivalent oxygens) > phenoxide (resonance into aromatic ring) > alkoxide (no resonance) > carbanion (extremely unstable). pKa values: ~5, ~10, ~16, ~50 respectively.", mn: "COOH > PhOH > ROH > RH. More stable conjugate base = more acidic."});
QS.push({id: "org26", cat: "ORGO", tags: ["Functional Groups", "Stereochemistry"], diff: 2, q: "A molecule with 2 stereocenters can have a maximum of how many stereoisomers?", o: ["4 (2^n where n = number of stereocenters)", "2", "3", "8"], a: 0, ex: "The maximum number of stereoisomers = 2^n where n is the number of stereocenters. With 2 stereocenters: 2^2 = 4. These include 2 pairs of enantiomers, or possibly a meso compound (reducing the total). But the MAXIMUM is always 2^n.", mn: "Max stereoisomers = 2^n. 2 centers = 4 max."});
QS.push({id: "org27", cat: "ORGO", tags: ["Functional Groups"], diff: 2, q: "Which carbonyl compound is most susceptible to nucleophilic addition?", o: ["Formaldehyde (H2C=O)", "Acetone (CH3COCH3)", "Acetaldehyde (CH3CHO)", "Methyl acetate (CH3COOCH3)"], a: 0, ex: "Nucleophilic addition requires electrophilic carbonyl carbon. Formaldehyde has no electron-donating alkyl groups, making its carbonyl carbon the most electrophilic. Alkyl groups (acetaldehyde, acetone) donate electron density. Esters have resonance donation from the OR group, reducing electrophilicity most.", mn: "Fewer/smaller substituents = more electrophilic carbonyl = more reactive to nucleophiles."});
QS.push({id: "ph26", cat: "PHYSICS", tags: ["Optics"], diff: 2, pass: "p75", q: "Violet light bends more than red light in the prism because:", o: ["Violet has a shorter wavelength and higher refractive index in glass", "Violet has higher energy so it travels faster in glass", "Red light is absorbed more by the prism", "All colors bend equally but separate due to speed differences"], a: 0, ex: "Dispersion occurs because refractive index depends on wavelength. Shorter wavelengths (violet) have higher n in glass, so they refract more according to Snell's law. This is why prisms separate white light into a spectrum with violet bending most and red least.", mn: "Short wavelength = high n = more bending. Violet bends most."});
QS.push({id: "ph27", cat: "PHYSICS", tags: ["Optics"], diff: 3, pass: "p75", fmt: "data", q: "In Setup C, when the object is at 30 cm from a 20 cm focal length lens, the magnification is:", o: ["-2 (inverted and twice the size)", "2 (upright and twice the size)", "-0.5 (inverted and half the size)", "0.5 (upright and half the size)"], a: 0, ex: "Using thin lens equation: 1/f = 1/do + 1/di → 1/20 = 1/30 + 1/di → di = 60 cm. Magnification m = -di/do = -60/30 = -2. Negative means inverted; magnitude 2 means the image is twice the object size.", mn: "m = -di/do. Negative = inverted. |m| > 1 = magnified."});
QS.push({id: "ph28", cat: "PHYSICS", tags: ["Optics"], diff: 2, pass: "p75", q: "Total internal reflection in Setup B occurs because:", o: ["Light travels from a denser medium to a less dense medium above the critical angle", "Light travels from a less dense to denser medium", "The angle of incidence equals exactly 90 degrees", "Water absorbs all the light energy"], a: 0, ex: "Total internal reflection occurs when: (1) light goes from higher n to lower n (water to air), AND (2) the angle of incidence exceeds the critical angle. At the critical angle, the refracted ray travels along the surface. Beyond it, all light reflects back.", mn: "TIR needs: high n → low n + angle > critical angle."});
QS.push({id: "ph29", cat: "PHYSICS", tags: ["Thermodynamics", "Equilibrium"], diff: 2, q: "An ideal gas is compressed isothermally. Which statement is true?", o: ["Work is done ON the gas and heat flows OUT of the gas", "Work is done BY the gas and heat flows INTO the gas", "Internal energy increases significantly", "Both temperature and pressure decrease"], a: 0, ex: "Isothermal = constant temperature. For an ideal gas, internal energy depends only on T, so ΔU = 0. By the first law: ΔU = Q - W → 0 = Q - W → Q = W. Compression means work is done ON the gas (W < 0 by gas convention), so Q < 0: heat flows out.", mn: "Isothermal compression: work IN, heat OUT, ΔU = 0."});
QS.push({id: "ph30", cat: "PHYSICS", tags: ["Work and Energy"], diff: 2, q: "A 2 kg ball is dropped from 10 m. Its speed just before hitting the ground is approximately (g = 10 m/s²):", o: ["14 m/s", "10 m/s", "20 m/s", "7 m/s"], a: 0, ex: "Using energy conservation: mgh = ½mv² → v = √(2gh) = √(2 × 10 × 10) = √200 ≈ 14.1 m/s. The mass cancels out. Alternatively, using kinematics: v² = 2gh gives the same result.", mn: "v = √(2gh). Mass doesn't matter for free fall speed."});
QS.push({id: "ps42", cat: "PSYCH_SOC", tags: ["Developmental Psychology", "Experimental Design"], diff: 2, pass: "p78", q: "According to the passage, which finding supports Vygotsky's theory over a strict Piagetian view?", o: ["Children in stimulating environments reach stages earlier", "15% of adolescents never reach formal operations", "Conservation tasks are passed by age 7", "Egocentrism is observed in preoperational children"], a: 0, ex: "Piaget proposed relatively fixed developmental stages. Vygotsky emphasized that social interaction and environmental stimulation accelerate cognitive development. The finding that enriched environments advance stage progression by 1.5 years directly supports Vygotsky's view that development is socially mediated.", mn: "Piaget = fixed stages. Vygotsky = environment and scaffolding matter."});
QS.push({id: "ps43", cat: "PSYCH_SOC", tags: ["Developmental Psychology"], diff: 2, pass: "p78", q: "A child who understands that flattening a ball of clay does not change its amount demonstrates:", o: ["Conservation (concrete operational stage)", "Object permanence (sensorimotor stage)", "Egocentrism (preoperational stage)", "Hypothetical reasoning (formal operational stage)"], a: 0, ex: "Conservation is the understanding that changing shape doesn't change quantity. Children in the preoperational stage fail conservation tasks (they think the flat clay is 'more'). Passing conservation is a hallmark of entering the concrete operational stage (ages 7-11).", mn: "Conservation = 'same amount, different shape.' Concrete operational achievement."});
QS.push({id: "ps44", cat: "PSYCH_SOC", tags: ["Social Psychology"], diff: 2, q: "Cognitive dissonance theory predicts that a person who is paid $1 to lie about enjoying a boring task will:", o: ["Change their attitude to believe the task was enjoyable", "Maintain that the task was boring", "Experience no psychological discomfort", "Refuse to lie regardless of payment"], a: 0, ex: "Festinger's cognitive dissonance: $1 is insufficient justification for lying, creating dissonance between 'I lied' and 'I'm honest.' To resolve it, the person changes their attitude to match their behavior ('maybe it was fun'). $20 provides sufficient external justification, so no attitude change occurs.", mn: "Small reward + lie = change attitude. Big reward = 'I did it for the money' (no change)."});
QS.push({id: "ps45", cat: "PSYCH_SOC", tags: ["Learning and Conditioning"], diff: 2, q: "In operant conditioning, a child stops throwing tantrums when parents consistently ignore the behavior. This is an example of:", o: ["Extinction", "Negative punishment", "Positive punishment", "Negative reinforcement"], a: 0, ex: "Extinction occurs when a previously reinforced behavior is no longer reinforced, causing the behavior to decrease over time. The tantrums were previously reinforced by parental attention. Removing the reinforcer (attention) extinguishes the behavior.", mn: "Remove the reinforcer = behavior fades = extinction."});
QS.push({id: "pek4", cat: "ENZYME_KINETICS", tags: ["Enzyme Inhibition", "Lineweaver-Burk"], diff: 3, pass: "p1", q: "If the researcher doubles the inhibitor concentration, the Lineweaver-Burk plot would show:", o: ["Lines shift further but remain parallel to each other", "Lines converge to a single point on the y-axis", "The slope changes but intercepts stay the same", "Lines become perpendicular"], a: 0, ex: "Uncompetitive inhibition always produces parallel lines on a Lineweaver-Burk plot regardless of inhibitor concentration. More inhibitor shifts both intercepts further (higher 1/Vmax, more negative -1/Km) but the slope Km/Vmax remains constant because both change proportionally.", mn: "Uncompetitive = ALWAYS parallel. More inhibitor = lines shift up, still parallel."});
QS.push({id: "pek5", cat: "ENZYME_KINETICS", tags: ["Enzyme Inhibition", "Kinetics Parameters"], diff: 3, pass: "p1", fmt: "data", q: "From the passage data, the ratio of Vmax(inhibited)/Vmax(uninhibited) equals:", o: ["0.5 (50/100)", "2.0 (100/50)", "0.25 (Km ratio)", "1.0 (unchanged)"], a: 0, ex: "Vmax drops from 100 to 50 umol/min, so the ratio is 50/100 = 0.5. In uncompetitive inhibition, this same factor (called alpha-prime) also affects Km: Km drops from 8 to 4 (also factor of 0.5), confirming proportional decrease. This is why LB lines are parallel.", mn: "Both Km and Vmax decrease by the same factor in uncompetitive inhibition."});
QS.push({id: "pbs6", cat: "BIO_SYSTEMS", tags: ["Cardiovascular System"], diff: 2, pass: "p2", q: "The positive direct Coombs test in this patient indicates:", o: ["Antibodies are bound to the patient's red blood cells (autoimmune hemolysis)", "The patient has a bacterial infection causing hemolysis", "Complement proteins are deficient", "The patient is iron deficient"], a: 0, ex: "The direct Coombs test detects antibodies or complement bound to the surface of red blood cells. A positive result confirms autoimmune hemolytic anemia — the patient's immune system is destroying their own RBCs. This explains the spherocytes, elevated LDH, low haptoglobin, and reticulocytosis.", mn: "Direct Coombs + = antibodies ON the RBCs = autoimmune hemolysis."});
QS.push({id: "pbs7", cat: "BIO_SYSTEMS", tags: ["Cardiovascular System"], diff: 3, pass: "p2", q: "Low haptoglobin in this patient is explained by:", o: ["Haptoglobin binds free hemoglobin from lysed RBCs and is consumed", "Haptoglobin production is suppressed by bilirubin", "The liver is failing to produce haptoglobin", "Haptoglobin is being filtered by the kidneys"], a: 0, ex: "When RBCs lyse (intravascular hemolysis), they release free hemoglobin into the blood. Haptoglobin binds this free hemoglobin to prevent kidney damage. The haptoglobin-hemoglobin complex is cleared by the liver, consuming haptoglobin. Low haptoglobin = lots of hemolysis.", mn: "Low haptoglobin = it's being used up binding free Hb from broken RBCs."});
QS.push({id: "gc29", cat: "GEN_CHEM", tags: ["Acid-Base", "Equilibrium"], diff: 2, q: "A buffer solution with pH 4.75 contains acetic acid (pKa = 4.75) and sodium acetate. The ratio of [CH3COO⁻]/[CH3COOH] is:", o: ["1:1", "10:1", "1:10", "100:1"], a: 0, ex: "Henderson-Hasselbalch: pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]). When pH = pKa: 4.75 = 4.75 + log(ratio), so log(ratio) = 0, meaning ratio = 1. Equal concentrations of acid and conjugate base. This is the point of maximum buffering capacity.", mn: "pH = pKa means [A-] = [HA] = 1:1. Maximum buffer capacity."});
QS.push({id: "gc30", cat: "GEN_CHEM", tags: ["Thermodynamics"], diff: 2, q: "For an exothermic reaction at equilibrium, increasing temperature will:", o: ["Shift equilibrium toward reactants (decrease Keq)", "Shift equilibrium toward products (increase Keq)", "Have no effect on equilibrium position", "Increase the rate but not change Keq"], a: 0, ex: "Le Chatelier's principle: heat is a 'product' of exothermic reactions. Adding heat (raising T) shifts equilibrium LEFT (toward reactants), decreasing Keq. For endothermic reactions, increasing T shifts RIGHT and increases Keq.", mn: "Exothermic + heat = shift LEFT. Heat is on the product side."});
QS.push({id: "bs32", cat: "BIO_SYSTEMS", tags: ["Immune System"], diff: 2, q: "MHC class I molecules present peptides to:", o: ["CD8+ cytotoxic T cells", "CD4+ helper T cells", "B cells", "Natural killer cells only"], a: 0, ex: "MHC I is expressed on ALL nucleated cells and presents intracellular peptides (from viral proteins, self-proteins) to CD8+ cytotoxic T cells. MHC II is on antigen-presenting cells (dendritic cells, macrophages, B cells) and presents to CD4+ helper T cells.", mn: "MHC I → CD8 (I × 8 = 8). MHC II → CD4 (II × 4 = 8). Both multiply to 8."});
QS.push({id: "bs33", cat: "BIO_SYSTEMS", tags: ["Immune System"], diff: 2, fmt: "except", q: "All of the following are components of the innate immune system EXCEPT:", o: ["Memory B cells", "Neutrophils", "Natural killer cells", "Complement proteins"], a: 0, ex: "Memory B cells are part of the adaptive (acquired) immune system — they provide long-lasting immunity after antigen exposure. Neutrophils (phagocytes), NK cells (kill virus-infected and tumor cells), and complement (protein cascade) are all innate immune components that respond immediately without prior exposure.", mn: "Memory = adaptive. No memory = innate. B/T cells = adaptive. Everything else = innate."});
