var MODULES={"Enzyme Inhibition": {"title": "Enzyme Inhibition", "icon": "🧬", "steps": [{"title": "The big picture", "content": "Enzymes speed up reactions. Inhibitors slow them down. There are 3 main types, and the MCAT loves asking you to distinguish them by their effects on Km and Vmax.\n\nKm = how tightly the enzyme grabs substrate (LOW Km = HIGH affinity)\nVmax = the fastest the enzyme can work when saturated with substrate", "visual": {"type": "table", "headers": ["Parameter", "Meaning", "Analogy"], "rows": [["Km", "[S] needed for half-Vmax", "How hungry the enzyme is"], ["Vmax", "Max rate at saturation", "Top speed of the factory"], ["kcat", "Turnover number per site", "Speed per machine"], ["kcat/Km", "Catalytic efficiency", "Overall productivity"]]}, "check": {"q": "If an enzyme has a LOW Km, what does that mean?", "o": ["High affinity for substrate", "Low affinity for substrate", "High Vmax", "Low Vmax"], "a": 0, "ex": "Low Km means the enzyme reaches half its max speed at a LOW substrate concentration — it grabs substrate very efficiently."}}, {"title": "Competitive inhibition", "content": "The inhibitor looks like the substrate and competes for the ACTIVE SITE. It's a direct rival.\n\nKey insight: if you flood the system with substrate, you can outcompete the inhibitor completely. That means Vmax is UNCHANGED — you just need more substrate to get there.", "visual": {"type": "diagram", "label": "Competitive inhibition", "items": [{"text": "Inhibitor blocks active site", "color": "#e63946"}, {"text": "Km INCREASES (harder to bind)", "color": "#f4a261"}, {"text": "Vmax UNCHANGED (can be overcome)", "color": "#2a9d8f"}, {"text": "LB plot: lines cross on Y-axis", "color": "#457b9d"}]}, "check": {"q": "A competitive inhibitor is added. What happens to apparent Km?", "o": ["Increases", "Decreases", "No change", "Depends on [I]"], "a": 0, "ex": "The inhibitor competes for the active site, so the enzyme needs MORE substrate to reach half-Vmax. Apparent Km increases."}}, {"title": "Noncompetitive inhibition", "content": "The inhibitor binds an ALLOSTERIC SITE (not the active site). It binds the enzyme whether or not substrate is already bound. It doesn't block substrate from binding — it just makes the enzyme less effective.\n\nThink of it as breaking some machines in the factory. The remaining machines work at the same speed (same Km), but total output drops (lower Vmax).", "visual": {"type": "diagram", "label": "Noncompetitive inhibition", "items": [{"text": "Binds allosteric site (E or ES)", "color": "#e63946"}, {"text": "Km UNCHANGED (binding unaffected)", "color": "#2a9d8f"}, {"text": "Vmax DECREASES (fewer working enzymes)", "color": "#f4a261"}, {"text": "LB plot: lines cross on X-axis", "color": "#457b9d"}]}, "check": {"q": "Why is Km unchanged in noncompetitive inhibition?", "o": ["Inhibitor doesn't affect substrate binding", "Inhibitor binds the active site", "Substrate outcompetes the inhibitor", "The enzyme denatures"], "a": 0, "ex": "The inhibitor binds at a different site, so it doesn't interfere with the substrate's ability to bind. The enzyme's affinity for substrate (Km) stays the same."}}, {"title": "Uncompetitive inhibition", "content": "The inhibitor ONLY binds the ES complex (enzyme-substrate together). It can't touch the free enzyme.\n\nThis traps ES in a dead-end ESI complex. By Le Chatelier's principle, the equilibrium E + S ↔ ES shifts RIGHT to replace the trapped ES. This makes the enzyme appear to grab substrate better (lower Km), but the trapped complexes reduce Vmax too.\n\nBoth Km and Vmax decrease PROPORTIONALLY.", "visual": {"type": "diagram", "label": "Uncompetitive inhibition", "items": [{"text": "Binds ONLY the ES complex", "color": "#e63946"}, {"text": "Km DECREASES (apparent ↑ affinity)", "color": "#2a9d8f"}, {"text": "Vmax DECREASES (ESI is dead-end)", "color": "#f4a261"}, {"text": "LB plot: PARALLEL lines (unique!)", "color": "#457b9d"}]}, "check": {"q": "What is the Lineweaver-Burk signature of uncompetitive inhibition?", "o": ["Parallel lines", "Lines crossing on y-axis", "Lines crossing on x-axis", "Identical lines"], "a": 0, "ex": "Both Km and Vmax decrease by the same factor, so slope (Km/Vmax) is unchanged. Same slope = parallel lines. This is the ONLY inhibition type with this pattern."}}, {"title": "The comparison table", "content": "This is what you need burned into memory. The MCAT will give you a scenario and expect you to identify the inhibitor type from the kinetic data.", "visual": {"type": "table", "headers": ["Type", "Binds", "Km", "Vmax", "LB Plot"], "rows": [["Competitive", "Active site (E only)", "↑ Increases", "Unchanged", "Cross Y-axis"], ["Noncompetitive", "Allosteric (E and ES)", "Unchanged", "↓ Decreases", "Cross X-axis"], ["Uncompetitive", "ES complex only", "↓ Decreases", "↓ Decreases", "Parallel lines"]]}, "check": {"q": "An inhibitor lowers both Km and Vmax. The Lineweaver-Burk plot shows parallel lines. This is:", "o": ["Uncompetitive", "Competitive", "Noncompetitive", "Mixed"], "a": 0, "ex": "Parallel LB lines + both Km and Vmax decrease = uncompetitive. This is the only type where both parameters drop proportionally."}}, {"title": "Memory tricks", "content": "Use these mnemonics to lock it in:\n\n• COMPETITIVE: Competes at the active site. Think 'C' for 'Competes' and 'Changes Km.'\n\n• NON-competitive: 'NON' = 'NO Km change.' Only Vmax drops.\n\n• UN-competitive: Everything goes UN-der. Both Km and Vmax decrease. UN-ique parallel lines.\n\n• Lineweaver-Burk tip: the parameter that DOESN'T change is where the lines intersect. Competitive = same Vmax = same y-intercept. Noncompetitive = same Km = same x-intercept.", "check": {"q": "Which mnemonic helps remember noncompetitive effects?", "o": ["NON = NO Km change", "NON = NO Vmax change", "NON = both decrease", "NON = parallel lines"], "a": 0, "ex": "NON-competitive = NO change in Km. The 'NON' reminds you Km is unaffected. Only Vmax decreases."}}]}, "Amino Acid Properties": {"title": "Amino Acid Properties", "icon": "🧪", "steps": [{"title": "The 4 categories", "content": "All 20 amino acids have the same backbone: amino group (NH3+), carboxyl group (COO-), alpha-carbon, and a unique R-group (side chain). The R-group determines everything.\n\nThe MCAT groups them by side chain polarity at pH 7.4:", "visual": {"type": "table", "headers": ["Category", "Charge at pH 7.4", "Amino Acids"], "rows": [["Nonpolar (hydrophobic)", "Neutral", "G, A, V, L, I, P, F, W, M"], ["Polar uncharged", "Neutral", "S, T, N, Q, C, Y"], ["Positively charged (+)", "Positive", "K, R, H"], ["Negatively charged (-)", "Negative", "D, E"]]}, "check": {"q": "At physiological pH, which amino acids carry a negative charge?", "o": ["Aspartate (D) and Glutamate (E)", "Lysine (K) and Arginine (R)", "Serine (S) and Threonine (T)", "Histidine (H) and Cysteine (C)"], "a": 0, "ex": "D (Asp) and E (Glu) have carboxylate side chains with pKa ~4. At pH 7.4, they're deprotonated and carry a negative charge."}}, {"title": "The special ones", "content": "Several amino acids have unique properties the MCAT loves to test:\n\n• CYSTEINE: Forms disulfide bonds (S-S) between two Cys residues. Critical for stabilizing tertiary/quaternary structure.\n\n• PROLINE: Has a cyclic side chain bonded to the backbone N. Acts as a 'helix breaker' — introduces kinks. Essential in collagen (every 3rd position: Gly-X-Pro).\n\n• GLYCINE: Smallest AA (R = H). Maximum flexibility. Fits in tight spaces. Also every 3rd residue in collagen.\n\n• HISTIDINE: pKa ≈ 6.0 — near physiological pH, so it can act as both proton donor AND acceptor. Makes it perfect for enzyme active sites (acid-base catalysis).\n\n• TRYPTOPHAN: Largest AA. Absorbs UV light at 280nm (along with Tyr, Phe).", "check": {"q": "Why is histidine commonly found in enzyme active sites?", "o": ["Its pKa (~6) allows it to donate and accept protons at physiological pH", "It forms disulfide bonds", "It is the largest amino acid", "It breaks alpha helices"], "a": 0, "ex": "His has a pKa of ~6, close to physiological pH 7.4. This means it exists in both protonated and deprotonated forms, making it an excellent acid-base catalyst."}}, {"title": "Amino acids at different pH values", "content": "Every amino acid is a zwitterion at physiological pH: the amino group is protonated (NH3+) and the carboxyl is deprotonated (COO-).\n\nThe isoelectric point (pI) is the pH where the net charge = 0.\n\nFor neutral AAs: pI = average of pKa1 (COOH, ~2) and pKa2 (NH3+, ~9)\nFor acidic AAs (D, E): pI = average of pKa1 and pKa(side chain)\nFor basic AAs (K, R, H): pI = average of pKa2 and pKa(side chain)", "visual": {"type": "table", "headers": ["AA", "Side chain pKa", "pI", "Charge at pH 7.4"], "rows": [["Asp (D)", "3.65", "2.77", "−1"], ["Glu (E)", "4.25", "3.22", "−1"], ["His (H)", "6.00", "7.59", "+0.1 (mostly neutral)"], ["Cys (C)", "8.18", "5.07", "neutral"], ["Lys (K)", "10.53", "9.74", "+1"], ["Arg (R)", "12.48", "10.76", "+1"]]}, "check": {"q": "What is the pI of aspartate (pKa1=1.88, pKa2=9.60, pKa(R)=3.65)?", "o": ["2.77 (average of 1.88 and 3.65)", "5.74 (average of 1.88 and 9.60)", "6.63 (average of 3.65 and 9.60)", "4.77 (average of all three)"], "a": 0, "ex": "For acidic amino acids, pI = average of the two LOWEST pKas. These are pKa1 (1.88) and pKa(R) (3.65). pI = (1.88 + 3.65)/2 = 2.77."}}, {"title": "Protein structure levels", "content": "• PRIMARY: The amino acid sequence itself. Held by peptide bonds (covalent). Survives denaturation.\n\n• SECONDARY: Local folding patterns. Alpha-helices (H-bonds between i and i+4 residues) and beta-sheets (H-bonds between strands). Proline breaks helices.\n\n• TERTIARY: The overall 3D shape of ONE polypeptide. Held by: hydrophobic interactions (strongest driving force), disulfide bonds (Cys-Cys), H-bonds, ionic/salt bridges, van der Waals.\n\n• QUATERNARY: Multiple polypeptide subunits assembled together (like hemoglobin's 4 subunits). Same forces as tertiary.", "check": {"q": "Which level of protein structure is maintained after denaturation by urea?", "o": ["Primary (amino acid sequence)", "Secondary (alpha-helices)", "Tertiary (3D shape)", "Quaternary (subunit assembly)"], "a": 0, "ex": "Denaturation by urea disrupts non-covalent interactions (H-bonds, hydrophobic, ionic), destroying secondary through quaternary structure. But peptide bonds are covalent and survive — primary structure is intact."}}]}, "Metabolic Regulation": {"title": "Metabolic Regulation", "icon": "🔥", "steps": [{"title": "Fed vs. fasted state", "content": "The body constantly switches between building up (anabolism) and breaking down (catabolism). Two hormones control the switch:\n\n• INSULIN (fed state): 'Store everything.' Promotes glycolysis, glycogen synthesis, fatty acid synthesis, protein synthesis. Released by beta cells when blood glucose is HIGH.\n\n• GLUCAGON (fasted state): 'Release fuel.' Promotes glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis, fatty acid oxidation, ketogenesis. Released by alpha cells when blood glucose is LOW.", "visual": {"type": "table", "headers": ["", "Fed (Insulin)", "Fasted (Glucagon)"], "rows": [["Glycolysis", "↑ Active", "↓ Suppressed"], ["Gluconeogenesis", "↓ Suppressed", "↑ Active"], ["Glycogen synthesis", "↑ Active", "↓ Suppressed"], ["Glycogenolysis", "↓ Suppressed", "↑ Active"], ["Fatty acid synthesis", "↑ Active", "↓ Suppressed"], ["Beta-oxidation", "↓ Suppressed", "↑ Active"]]}, "check": {"q": "After a 24-hour fast, which pathway is most active in the liver?", "o": ["Gluconeogenesis", "Glycolysis", "Fatty acid synthesis", "Glycogen synthesis"], "a": 0, "ex": "During fasting, glucagon signals the liver to make glucose (gluconeogenesis) to maintain blood glucose for the brain. Glycolysis and anabolic pathways are suppressed."}}, {"title": "Glycolysis — the committed step", "content": "Glycolysis converts glucose → 2 pyruvate (in the cytoplasm).\n\nThe rate-limiting (committed) step is catalyzed by PFK-1 (phosphofructokinase-1). This is the most important regulatory enzyme in glycolysis.\n\nPFK-1 activators: AMP, fructose-2,6-bisphosphate (F2,6BP), insulin (via F2,6BP)\nPFK-1 inhibitors: ATP, citrate, glucagon (via lowering F2,6BP)\n\nF2,6BP is the most potent activator. It's made by PFK-2 (a bifunctional enzyme). Insulin activates PFK-2; glucagon inhibits it.", "check": {"q": "Which molecule is the MOST potent activator of PFK-1?", "o": ["Fructose-2,6-bisphosphate", "ATP", "AMP", "Citrate"], "a": 0, "ex": "F2,6BP is the strongest activator of PFK-1. It's produced by PFK-2, which is activated by insulin. This links hormonal signals directly to glycolytic rate."}}, {"title": "Gluconeogenesis — the bypass enzymes", "content": "Gluconeogenesis is essentially glycolysis in reverse, BUT 3 irreversible glycolytic steps must be bypassed with different enzymes:\n\n1. Pyruvate → Oxaloacetate → PEP (bypasses pyruvate kinase)\n   Enzymes: Pyruvate carboxylase + PEP carboxykinase (PEPCK)\n\n2. F1,6BP → F6P (bypasses PFK-1)\n   Enzyme: Fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (FBPase-1)\n\n3. G6P → Glucose (bypasses hexokinase/glucokinase)\n   Enzyme: Glucose-6-phosphatase (liver and kidney ONLY — this is why muscle cannot export glucose)", "check": {"q": "Why can't muscle perform gluconeogenesis and release glucose into the blood?", "o": ["Muscle lacks glucose-6-phosphatase", "Muscle lacks PFK-1", "Muscle lacks hexokinase", "Muscle lacks pyruvate kinase"], "a": 0, "ex": "The final step of gluconeogenesis (G6P → glucose) requires glucose-6-phosphatase, which is only in liver and kidney. Without it, muscle cannot dephosphorylate G6P to free glucose."}}, {"title": "The reciprocal regulation principle", "content": "Glycolysis and gluconeogenesis are reciprocally regulated — when one is ON, the other is OFF. This prevents a 'futile cycle' that would waste ATP.\n\nThe key regulatory point: PFK-1 vs. FBPase-1\n• F2,6BP activates PFK-1 (glycolysis ON) and inhibits FBPase-1 (gluconeogenesis OFF)\n• Citrate and ATP inhibit PFK-1 (glycolysis OFF) and activate FBPase-1 (gluconeogenesis ON)\n\nThis is why F2,6BP is the master switch — it simultaneously controls both pathways in opposite directions.", "check": {"q": "What prevents glycolysis and gluconeogenesis from running simultaneously (futile cycle)?", "o": ["F2,6BP activates one and inhibits the other simultaneously", "They occur in different organs", "ATP is required for both", "They use the same enzymes"], "a": 0, "ex": "F2,6BP activates PFK-1 (glycolysis) while inhibiting FBPase-1 (gluconeogenesis). This reciprocal regulation ensures only one pathway runs at a time."}}]}, "Electron Transport Chain": {"title": "Electron Transport Chain", "icon": "⚡", "steps": [{"title": "The big picture", "content": "The ETC is in the inner mitochondrial membrane. It takes electrons from NADH and FADH2, passes them through 4 protein complexes, and uses the energy released to pump H+ ions into the intermembrane space. This creates a proton gradient that drives ATP synthase (Complex V).\n\nThe final electron acceptor is O2, which combines with H+ to form H2O. This is why you need oxygen to live — without it, the ETC backs up and stops.", "visual": {"type": "table", "headers": ["Complex", "Name", "Accepts e- from", "Inhibitor"], "rows": [["I", "NADH dehydrogenase", "NADH", "Rotenone, barbiturates"], ["II", "Succinate dehydrogenase", "FADH2", "Malonate"], ["III", "Cytochrome bc1", "CoQ (ubiquinol)", "Antimycin A"], ["IV", "Cytochrome c oxidase", "Cytochrome c", "CN⁻, CO, H2S"], ["V", "ATP synthase", "H+ gradient", "Oligomycin"]]}, "check": {"q": "Cyanide poisoning blocks which ETC complex?", "o": ["Complex IV (cytochrome c oxidase)", "Complex I (NADH dehydrogenase)", "Complex III (cytochrome bc1)", "Complex V (ATP synthase)"], "a": 0, "ex": "Cyanide binds to the iron in Complex IV, preventing it from transferring electrons to O2. This halts the entire chain, stopping ATP production."}}, {"title": "The proton gradient and ATP yield", "content": "Complexes I, III, and IV pump H+ from the matrix into the intermembrane space. Complex II does NOT pump protons.\n\nThis is why NADH produces MORE ATP than FADH2:\n• NADH donates to Complex I → gets pumping from I, III, and IV → ~2.5 ATP\n• FADH2 donates to Complex II → only gets pumping from III and IV → ~1.5 ATP\n\nTotal ATP per glucose (oxidative phosphorylation): 10 NADH (×2.5) + 2 FADH2 (×1.5) = 25 + 3 = 28 ATP from the ETC. Plus 2 ATP (glycolysis) + 2 ATP (Krebs) = ~30-32 total.", "check": {"q": "Why does FADH2 produce fewer ATP than NADH?", "o": ["FADH2 enters at Complex II, bypassing Complex I's proton pumping", "FADH2 has fewer electrons", "FADH2 is less stable", "FADH2 cannot reach the ETC"], "a": 0, "ex": "FADH2 donates electrons to Complex II, which does NOT pump protons. So FADH2 skips one proton-pumping step compared to NADH (which enters at Complex I). Fewer protons pumped = less ATP."}}, {"title": "Uncouplers vs. inhibitors", "content": "This distinction is an MCAT favorite:\n\n• ETC INHIBITORS (rotenone, CN⁻, antimycin A, oligomycin): Block electron flow or ATP synthase directly. O2 consumption STOPS. Proton gradient builds up (for channel blockers) or collapses (for ETC blockers).\n\n• UNCOUPLERS (2,4-DNP, thermogenin/UCP1): Create holes in the inner membrane, letting H+ leak back without going through ATP synthase. O2 consumption INCREASES (ETC runs full speed trying to maintain gradient). ATP production DECREASES. Energy released as HEAT.\n\nThermogenin in brown fat uses this for thermoregulation in newborns.", "check": {"q": "Adding 2,4-DNP (an uncoupler) to mitochondria will:", "o": ["Increase O2 consumption, decrease ATP production", "Decrease O2 consumption, decrease ATP production", "Increase O2 consumption, increase ATP production", "Decrease O2 consumption, increase ATP production"], "a": 0, "ex": "Uncouplers dissipate the proton gradient, so the ETC runs faster (more O2 consumed) trying to rebuild it. But H+ bypasses ATP synthase, so ATP production drops. Energy becomes heat."}}]}, "SN1/SN2/E1/E2 Decision Framework": {"title": "SN1/SN2/E1/E2 Reactions", "icon": "⬡", "steps": [{"title": "Substitution vs. elimination", "content": "When a nucleophile/base encounters a substrate with a leaving group, TWO things can happen:\n\n• SUBSTITUTION (SN1, SN2): The nucleophile REPLACES the leaving group. A new bond forms to the carbon.\n\n• ELIMINATION (E1, E2): The base REMOVES a proton from the beta-carbon. A double bond forms (alkene product).\n\nThe '1' and '2' refer to molecularity — how many molecules are involved in the rate-determining step:\n• 1 = unimolecular (only the substrate). Two-step mechanism via carbocation.\n• 2 = bimolecular (substrate + nucleophile/base). One-step, concerted mechanism.", "check": {"q": "What does the '2' in SN2 mean?", "o": ["Two molecules involved in the rate-determining step", "Two products formed", "Two bonds broken", "Two equivalents of nucleophile needed"], "a": 0, "ex": "The '2' means bimolecular — both the substrate and nucleophile are involved in the single, concerted rate-determining step. Rate = k[substrate][nucleophile]."}}, {"title": "Start with the substrate", "content": "The substrate's carbon type is your FIRST decision point:\n\n• METHYL / PRIMARY (CH3-X, RCH2-X): Favor SN2. Too unstable to form a carbocation (no SN1/E1). Strong base → E2 is possible.\n\n• SECONDARY (R2CH-X): The crossroads. All 4 reactions compete. Conditions determine the winner.\n\n• TERTIARY (R3C-X): SN2 is impossible (too sterically hindered). Favor SN1/E1 (stable carbocation). Strong base → E2.", "visual": {"type": "table", "headers": ["Substrate", "SN2", "SN1", "E2", "E1"], "rows": [["Methyl (CH₃X)", "Best", "Never", "Possible", "Never"], ["Primary (1°)", "Great", "Rare", "Strong base", "Rare"], ["Secondary (2°)", "OK", "OK", "OK", "OK"], ["Tertiary (3°)", "Never", "Great", "Great", "OK"]]}, "check": {"q": "A tertiary substrate is treated with a weak nucleophile in a polar protic solvent. The major pathway is:", "o": ["SN1", "SN2", "E2", "Neither substitution nor elimination"], "a": 0, "ex": "Tertiary = too hindered for SN2. Weak nucleophile = not a strong base, so no E2. Polar protic solvent stabilizes the carbocation intermediate. This is textbook SN1."}}, {"title": "Strong nucleophile/base vs. weak", "content": "SECOND decision: what's attacking?\n\n• STRONG nucleophile (not bulky): Favors SN2 on primary/secondary substrates. Examples: CH3O⁻, CN⁻, RS⁻, I⁻\n\n• STRONG, BULKY base: Favors E2 (too bulky for SN2 backside attack). Examples: t-BuO⁻ (tert-butoxide), LDA, DBU\n\n• WEAK nucleophile/base: Favors SN1/E1 (must wait for carbocation to form). Examples: H2O, ROH, CH3OH\n\nRule of thumb: Strong + small → SN2. Strong + bulky → E2. Weak → SN1/E1 (need good substrate).", "check": {"q": "tert-Butoxide (a strong, bulky base) reacts with 2-bromobutane. The major product forms via:", "o": ["E2 elimination", "SN2 substitution", "SN1 substitution", "E1 elimination"], "a": 0, "ex": "tert-Butoxide is strong (favoring bimolecular) but too bulky for SN2 backside attack. It acts as a base, abstracting a beta-proton in a concerted E2 mechanism."}}, {"title": "Solvent effects", "content": "THIRD decision: what's the solvent?\n\n• POLAR PROTIC (water, alcohols, acetic acid): Stabilize carbocations and anions through H-bonding. Favor SN1/E1. Slow down SN2 by solvating the nucleophile.\n\n• POLAR APROTIC (DMSO, DMF, acetone, acetonitrile): Don't H-bond to nucleophiles, leaving them 'naked' and reactive. Favor SN2. Cannot stabilize carbocations well.", "check": {"q": "Switching from DMSO to ethanol would favor:", "o": ["SN1 over SN2", "SN2 over SN1", "E2 over E1", "No change"], "a": 0, "ex": "Ethanol is polar protic (H-bonds to and solvates the nucleophile, slowing SN2). It also stabilizes carbocations. This shifts the balance from SN2 toward SN1."}}, {"title": "The decision flowchart", "content": "Here's the algorithm:\n\n1. Is the substrate tertiary? → SN1/E1 (weak nuc) or E2 (strong base). Never SN2.\n2. Is the substrate methyl/primary? → SN2 (strong nuc) or E2 (strong bulky base). Never SN1.\n3. Is the substrate secondary? → Check the nucleophile/base and solvent:\n   - Strong, small nuc + polar aprotic → SN2\n   - Strong, bulky base → E2\n   - Weak nuc + polar protic → SN1/E1\n4. Heat favors elimination (E) over substitution (S) in borderline cases.", "check": {"q": "1-bromobutane + NaCN in DMSO. Predict the major pathway:", "o": ["SN2", "SN1", "E2", "E1"], "a": 0, "ex": "Primary substrate (1°) + strong nucleophile (CN⁻) + polar aprotic solvent (DMSO) = textbook SN2. Primary substrates can't form stable carbocations (no SN1), and CN⁻ is a better nucleophile than base."}}]}, "Acid-Base Chemistry": {"title": "Acid-Base Chemistry", "icon": "⚗️", "steps": [{"title": "pH, pKa, and Henderson-Hasselbalch", "content": "pH = -log[H+]. Lower pH = more acidic.\n\nThe Henderson-Hasselbalch equation: pH = pKa + log([A⁻]/[HA])\n\nKey implications:\n• When pH = pKa: [A⁻] = [HA], the ratio is 1:1. This is the midpoint of a titration and where buffering capacity is maximum.\n• When pH > pKa: The conjugate base (A⁻) dominates. The acid is mostly deprotonated.\n• When pH < pKa: The acid (HA) dominates. The acid is mostly protonated.", "check": {"q": "At pH 7.4, an amino acid side chain with pKa 4.0 is mostly:", "o": ["Deprotonated (COO⁻)", "Protonated (COOH)", "50% protonated", "Cannot determine"], "a": 0, "ex": "pH (7.4) > pKa (4.0), so the equilibrium favors the deprotonated form (A⁻). The side chain is overwhelmingly in the COO⁻ form. Using H-H: log([A⁻]/[HA]) = 3.4, meaning >99.9% deprotonated."}}, {"title": "Buffers", "content": "A buffer resists pH change. It works best when pH is within 1 unit of pKa.\n\nBuffers contain a weak acid and its conjugate base in similar concentrations.\n\n• Add acid → the A⁻ absorbs H+, converting to HA. pH barely changes.\n• Add base → the HA donates H+, converting to A⁻. pH barely changes.\n\nBiological buffers: bicarbonate (H2CO3/HCO3⁻, pKa 6.1), phosphate (H2PO4⁻/HPO4²⁻, pKa 6.8), proteins (histidine residues, pKa ~6).", "check": {"q": "Which buffer system is most important for blood pH regulation?", "o": ["Bicarbonate (H2CO3/HCO3⁻)", "Phosphate", "Acetate", "Ammonia"], "a": 0, "ex": "The bicarbonate system is the primary blood buffer. CO2 + H2O ↔ H2CO3 ↔ HCO3⁻ + H+. The lungs control CO2, the kidneys control HCO3⁻, giving the body two ways to adjust pH."}}, {"title": "Titration curves", "content": "When you titrate a weak acid with strong base:\n\n1. Initial pH: Determined by the weak acid alone. pH < 7.\n2. Buffer region: pH changes slowly. Centered around the pKa.\n3. Half-equivalence point: Exactly half the acid is neutralized. pH = pKa. [HA] = [A⁻].\n4. Equivalence point: All acid is converted to conjugate base. pH > 7 (basic, because A⁻ is a weak base).\n5. Past equivalence: Excess strong base dominates. pH rises steeply.\n\nFor polyprotic acids (H2SO4, amino acids), there are multiple buffer regions and equivalence points.", "check": {"q": "At the equivalence point of a weak acid/strong base titration, the pH is:", "o": ["Greater than 7 (basic)", "Exactly 7 (neutral)", "Less than 7 (acidic)", "Equal to pKa"], "a": 0, "ex": "At the equivalence point, all HA has been converted to A⁻ (conjugate base). This weak base hydrolyzes water slightly: A⁻ + H2O → HA + OH⁻, making the solution basic (pH > 7)."}}]}, "Thermodynamics": {"title": "Thermodynamics", "icon": "🔬", "steps": [{"title": "Gibbs free energy", "content": "ΔG = ΔH - TΔS\n\nThis single equation predicts whether a reaction occurs spontaneously:\n• ΔG < 0: Spontaneous (exergonic). Reaction proceeds forward.\n• ΔG > 0: Non-spontaneous (endergonic). Requires energy input.\n• ΔG = 0: At equilibrium.\n\nΔH = enthalpy change (bond energy). Negative = exothermic (releases heat).\nΔS = entropy change (disorder). Positive = more disorder.\nT = temperature in Kelvin.", "visual": {"type": "table", "headers": ["ΔH", "ΔS", "Spontaneous?"], "rows": [["-", "+", "Always (ΔG always < 0)"], ["+", "-", "Never (ΔG always > 0)"], ["-", "-", "Spontaneous at LOW T"], ["+", "+", "Spontaneous at HIGH T"]]}, "check": {"q": "A reaction has ΔH = +30 kJ/mol and ΔS = +100 J/(mol·K). At what condition is it spontaneous?", "o": ["High temperature (T > 300K)", "Low temperature", "All temperatures", "Never spontaneous"], "a": 0, "ex": "ΔG = ΔH - TΔS. Both ΔH and ΔS are positive. At high T, the TΔS term exceeds ΔH, making ΔG negative (spontaneous). Specifically: T > ΔH/ΔS = 30000/100 = 300K."}}, {"title": "ΔG vs. ΔG° and the relationship to Keq", "content": "ΔG° = standard free energy change (at standard conditions: 1M, 1atm, 25°C)\nΔG = actual free energy change (depends on current concentrations)\n\nΔG = ΔG° + RT·ln(Q) where Q = reaction quotient\n\nAt equilibrium: ΔG = 0, Q = Keq, so: ΔG° = -RT·ln(Keq)\n\nImplications:\n• ΔG° < 0 → Keq > 1 → products favored at equilibrium\n• ΔG° > 0 → Keq < 1 → reactants favored at equilibrium\n• ΔG° tells you WHERE equilibrium lies. ΔG tells you which DIRECTION you're going RIGHT NOW.", "check": {"q": "A reaction has ΔG° > 0. This means:", "o": ["Keq < 1 (reactants favored at equilibrium)", "The reaction can never occur", "Keq > 1 (products favored)", "The reaction is at equilibrium"], "a": 0, "ex": "ΔG° = -RT·ln(Keq). If ΔG° > 0, then ln(Keq) < 0, meaning Keq < 1. Reactants are favored at equilibrium. But the reaction CAN still proceed if coupled to a favorable reaction."}}, {"title": "Coupling reactions", "content": "How does the body drive endergonic reactions? By COUPLING them to exergonic ones.\n\nATP hydrolysis: ATP → ADP + Pi, ΔG° = -30.5 kJ/mol\n\nIf your reaction needs +15 kJ/mol, coupling it to ATP hydrolysis gives:\nΔG°(total) = +15 + (-30.5) = -15.5 kJ/mol → spontaneous!\n\nThis is how enzymes drive unfavorable reactions. The enzyme doesn't change ΔG — it couples the reaction to ATP (or another energy source) and lowers the activation energy (Ea).", "check": {"q": "An enzyme speeds up a reaction. What does it change?", "o": ["Activation energy (Ea) — it decreases", "ΔG of the reaction", "Keq of the reaction", "Both ΔG and Ea"], "a": 0, "ex": "Enzymes lower the activation energy (Ea), making the reaction faster. They do NOT change ΔG or Keq — the thermodynamics are the same. The reaction reaches equilibrium faster, but the equilibrium position doesn't change."}}]}, "Cell Cycle": {"title": "Cell Cycle & Checkpoints", "icon": "🔬", "steps": [{"title": "The phases", "content": "G1 → S → G2 → M (mitosis)\n\n• G1: Cell grows, makes proteins. Decision point: commit to division or enter G0 (quiescence).\n• S: DNA replication. Each chromosome becomes two sister chromatids.\n• G2: Cell prepares for division. Checks for replication errors.\n• M: Mitosis (nuclear division) + cytokinesis (cytoplasm splits).\n\nCyclin-CDK complexes drive progression through each phase. Cyclins rise and fall; CDKs are always present but only active when bound to their cyclin partner.", "check": {"q": "During which phase does DNA replication occur?", "o": ["S phase", "G1 phase", "G2 phase", "M phase"], "a": 0, "ex": "S = Synthesis. This is when the cell copies all its DNA. After S phase, each chromosome consists of two identical sister chromatids joined at the centromere."}}, {"title": "Checkpoints and tumor suppressors", "content": "Three major checkpoints prevent damaged cells from dividing:\n\n• G1/S checkpoint (Restriction point): Is DNA intact? Is the cell big enough? Controlled by p53 and Rb.\n  - p53: 'Guardian of the genome.' Detects DNA damage → activates p21 → p21 inhibits cyclin-CDK → ARREST. If damage is irreparable → triggers apoptosis.\n  - Rb: When hypophosphorylated, Rb binds E2F transcription factor, blocking S-phase genes. Cyclin D/CDK4 phosphorylates Rb → releases E2F → S-phase proceeds.\n\n• G2/M checkpoint: Is all DNA replicated? Any damage? Prevents mitosis with errors.\n\n• Spindle checkpoint (during M): Are all chromosomes attached to spindle? Prevents aneuploidy.", "check": {"q": "Loss of BOTH copies of p53 (two-hit hypothesis) leads to:", "o": ["Uncontrolled cell division — damaged cells bypass G1/S checkpoint", "Immediate cell death", "Increased DNA repair", "Cell cycle arrest in G0"], "a": 0, "ex": "p53 normally stops cells with DNA damage from dividing. Without p53, damaged cells pass the G1/S checkpoint unchecked, accumulate mutations, and proliferate — this is how many cancers develop."}}]}, "Signal Transduction": {"title": "Signal Transduction", "icon": "📡", "steps": [{"title": "GPCRs and second messengers", "content": "G-protein coupled receptors (GPCRs) are the LARGEST family of membrane receptors.\n\nMechanism: Ligand binds GPCR → activates G-protein (swaps GDP for GTP) → G-protein activates an effector enzyme → second messenger is produced → cellular response.\n\nTwo main pathways:\n• Gs → activates adenylyl cyclase → ↑ cAMP → activates PKA\n• Gq → activates phospholipase C → PIP2 → IP3 + DAG\n  - IP3 → Ca²+ release from ER\n  - DAG → activates PKC", "check": {"q": "Cholera toxin locks a Gs protein in its active (GTP-bound) state. What happens?", "o": ["cAMP levels stay permanently high", "cAMP levels drop to zero", "Ca²+ floods the cell", "The receptor is destroyed"], "a": 0, "ex": "Gs activates adenylyl cyclase, which makes cAMP. If Gs is permanently ON (can't hydrolyze GTP → GDP), adenylyl cyclase runs non-stop, and cAMP accumulates to very high levels. This causes massive water secretion in the gut (diarrhea)."}}, {"title": "Receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs)", "content": "RTKs are single-pass transmembrane receptors. Unlike GPCRs, they have intrinsic kinase activity.\n\nMechanism: Ligand binds → two RTK monomers dimerize → they phosphorylate EACH OTHER (autophosphorylation) on tyrosine residues → phosphotyrosines recruit signaling proteins (via SH2 domains) → activate downstream pathways.\n\nKey pathway: Ras → Raf → MEK → ERK (MAPK cascade)\n\nRas is a GTPase. Mutations that prevent Ras from hydrolyzing GTP (keeping it permanently ON) are found in ~30% of all cancers. Ras is an ONCOGENE when mutated.", "check": {"q": "Ras is considered an oncogene when mutated because:", "o": ["It stays permanently active, driving constant cell proliferation", "It destroys the cell membrane", "It blocks all protein synthesis", "It prevents DNA replication"], "a": 0, "ex": "Normal Ras cycles between active (GTP) and inactive (GDP). Oncogenic mutations prevent GTP hydrolysis, so Ras stays ON permanently, continuously signaling cell growth through the MAPK cascade."}}]}, "Nervous System": {"title": "Action Potentials & Neurotransmission", "icon": "🧠", "steps": [{"title": "Resting potential and the action potential", "content": "Resting membrane potential: approximately -70mV. Maintained by the Na+/K+ ATPase (pumps 3 Na+ out, 2 K+ in) and K+ leak channels.\n\nAction potential steps:\n1. DEPOLARIZATION: Stimulus reaches threshold (-55mV) → voltage-gated Na+ channels open → Na+ rushes IN → membrane goes positive (+30mV)\n2. REPOLARIZATION: Na+ channels inactivate. K+ channels open → K+ rushes OUT → membrane returns toward negative\n3. HYPERPOLARIZATION: K+ channels slow to close → briefly overshoots below -70mV\n4. REFRACTORY PERIOD: Na+ channels reset. Absolute refractory = no new AP possible. Relative refractory = needs stronger stimulus.", "check": {"q": "During depolarization, which ion is primarily responsible?", "o": ["Na+ rushing into the cell", "K+ leaving the cell", "Ca²+ entering the cell", "Cl⁻ entering the cell"], "a": 0, "ex": "Voltage-gated Na+ channels open at threshold, allowing Na+ to flood in down its electrochemical gradient. This rapid Na+ influx causes the membrane potential to shoot up from -55mV toward +30mV."}}, {"title": "Synaptic transmission and neurotransmitters", "content": "When the action potential reaches the axon terminal:\n1. Voltage-gated Ca²+ channels open → Ca²+ enters\n2. Ca²+ triggers vesicle fusion with presynaptic membrane (exocytosis)\n3. Neurotransmitter released into synaptic cleft\n4. Binds receptors on postsynaptic cell\n5. Creates EPSP (excitatory) or IPSP (inhibitory)\n\nKey neurotransmitters:\n• Acetylcholine (ACh): NMJ, parasympathetic NS\n• Norepinephrine: sympathetic NS\n• Dopamine: reward, motor control. Low → Parkinson's\n• Serotonin: mood, sleep. Low → depression\n• GABA: main inhibitory NT in brain\n• Glutamate: main excitatory NT in brain", "check": {"q": "Ca²+ entry into the presynaptic terminal is necessary for:", "o": ["Neurotransmitter vesicle fusion and release", "Action potential propagation", "Maintaining resting potential", "Synthesizing neurotransmitters"], "a": 0, "ex": "Ca²+ influx triggers the SNARE protein machinery that causes synaptic vesicles to fuse with the presynaptic membrane and release neurotransmitter into the cleft. Without Ca²+, no release occurs."}}]}, "Mendelian Genetics": {"title": "Mendelian Genetics", "icon": "🧬", "steps": [{"title": "Mendel's laws and basic crosses", "content": "Law of Segregation: Each parent passes ONE allele (of two) to each offspring. Alleles separate during meiosis.\n\nLaw of Independent Assortment: Genes on different chromosomes sort independently (unless linked).\n\nKey crosses:\n• Aa × Aa → 1 AA : 2 Aa : 1 aa (3:1 phenotypic ratio with complete dominance)\n• Aa × aa → 1 Aa : 1 aa (1:1 ratio — this is a TESTCROSS)\n• AaBb × AaBb → 9:3:3:1 (dihybrid cross, independent assortment)", "check": {"q": "Two carriers (Aa × Aa) for an autosomal recessive disease have a child. What is the probability the child is affected?", "o": ["1/4 (25%)", "1/2 (50%)", "3/4 (75%)", "1/3 (33%)"], "a": 0, "ex": "Aa × Aa gives 1 AA : 2 Aa : 1 aa. Only 'aa' is affected = 1 out of 4 = 25%. The classic Mendelian monohybrid ratio."}}, {"title": "Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium", "content": "For a population in genetic equilibrium: p² + 2pq + q² = 1 and p + q = 1\n\nWhere: p = frequency of dominant allele, q = frequency of recessive allele\np² = frequency of homozygous dominant\n2pq = frequency of heterozygous carriers\nq² = frequency of homozygous recessive (often the given/known value)\n\nThe MCAT almost always gives you q² (the disease frequency) and asks you to find carrier frequency (2pq).\n\nStep 1: q = √(q²)\nStep 2: p = 1 - q\nStep 3: 2pq = carrier frequency", "check": {"q": "A disease affects 1 in 10,000 people (autosomal recessive). The carrier frequency is approximately:", "o": ["1 in 50 (2%)", "1 in 100 (1%)", "1 in 10,000", "1 in 5,000"], "a": 0, "ex": "q² = 1/10000, so q = 1/100. p = 1 - 1/100 ≈ 99/100. Carrier frequency = 2pq = 2 × (99/100) × (1/100) ≈ 2/100 = 1 in 50. Carriers are MUCH more common than affected individuals."}}]}, "Protein Structure": {"title": "Protein Structure & Folding", "icon": "🧪", "steps": [{"title": "The four levels", "content": "Each level builds on the one below it:\n\n• PRIMARY: The linear sequence of amino acids. Determined by DNA. Held together by PEPTIDE BONDS (covalent, planar, partial double-bond character). Survives denaturation.\n\n• SECONDARY: Local repeating patterns. Alpha-helix: coiled, H-bonds every 4 residues along backbone. Beta-sheet: zigzag strands, H-bonds between strands (parallel or antiparallel).\n\n• TERTIARY: Overall 3D shape of a single polypeptide. Driven primarily by the HYDROPHOBIC EFFECT (nonpolar residues pack into the core, away from water). Also: disulfide bonds (Cys-Cys), H-bonds, ionic bonds, van der Waals.\n\n• QUATERNARY: Assembly of multiple polypeptide subunits. Same forces as tertiary. Example: hemoglobin (α2β2).", "check": {"q": "What is the PRIMARY driving force for protein folding into its tertiary structure?", "o": ["Hydrophobic effect (nonpolar residues burying in core)", "Disulfide bonds", "Peptide bonds", "Hydrogen bonds between backbone atoms"], "a": 0, "ex": "The hydrophobic effect is the dominant force: nonpolar side chains are driven out of water into the protein interior. This isn't a 'bond' — it's the thermodynamic drive to minimize hydrophobic surface area exposed to water."}}, {"title": "Denaturation and Anfinsen's experiment", "content": "Denaturation = loss of 3D structure (secondary through quaternary) while keeping primary structure intact.\n\nDenaturing agents: heat, extreme pH, urea, guanidinium chloride, detergents (SDS), organic solvents, heavy metals.\n\nAnfinsen's dogma: The amino acid sequence (primary structure) contains all the information needed for a protein to fold into its correct 3D shape.\n\nProof: Anfinsen denatured ribonuclease A with urea + beta-mercaptoethanol (broke disulfide bonds). When he removed both agents, the enzyme REFOLDED and regained full activity. The sequence alone dictated the correct fold.", "check": {"q": "In Anfinsen's experiment, what happened when urea and reducing agent were both removed?", "o": ["The protein refolded into its native, active conformation", "The protein remained denatured permanently", "The protein formed a different structure", "The protein was degraded"], "a": 0, "ex": "Removing both denaturing agents allowed ribonuclease to spontaneously refold into its native structure with full enzymatic activity. This proved that primary structure determines tertiary structure."}}]}, "Hormones": {"title": "Hormones & Endocrine System", "icon": "🫀", "steps": [{"title": "Hormone types and signaling", "content": "Two main types based on solubility:\n\n• PEPTIDE/PROTEIN HORMONES (insulin, glucagon, GH, ADH): Water-soluble. Cannot cross membrane. Bind SURFACE receptors (GPCRs, RTKs). Act via second messengers. Fast onset, short duration. Stored in vesicles (preformed).\n\n• STEROID HORMONES (cortisol, aldosterone, estrogen, testosterone) + THYROID HORMONES: Lipid-soluble. Cross membrane freely. Bind INTRACELLULAR/NUCLEAR receptors. Act as transcription factors. Slow onset (hours), long duration. Made on demand (not stored).\n\nException: Thyroid hormones are amino acid-derived but behave like steroids (bind nuclear receptors).", "check": {"q": "Why do steroid hormones have a slower onset than peptide hormones?", "o": ["They act by changing gene transcription, which takes time", "They travel more slowly in blood", "They are less potent", "They require more hormone molecules"], "a": 0, "ex": "Steroids enter the cell, bind nuclear receptors, and alter gene expression. New mRNA must be transcribed and translated into protein — this takes hours. Peptide hormones activate pre-existing signaling cascades (seconds to minutes)."}}, {"title": "Hypothalamic-Pituitary axis and feedback", "content": "The hypothalamus controls the pituitary, which controls peripheral glands:\n\nHypothalamus → Anterior Pituitary → Target Gland → Hormone → NEGATIVE FEEDBACK to hypothalamus/pituitary\n\nExamples:\n• TRH → TSH → T3/T4 (thyroid). T3/T4 inhibit TRH and TSH release.\n• CRH → ACTH → Cortisol (adrenal cortex). Cortisol inhibits CRH and ACTH.\n• GnRH → FSH/LH → Estrogen/Testosterone (gonads).\n\nAnterior pituitary hormones to memorize: GH, TSH, ACTH, FSH, LH, Prolactin (mnemonic: FLAT PiG)\nPosterior pituitary: ADH and Oxytocin (made in hypothalamus, stored in posterior pit)", "check": {"q": "A patient has HIGH cortisol and LOW ACTH. The problem is most likely in the:", "o": ["Adrenal gland (autonomous cortisol production)", "Anterior pituitary (ACTH excess)", "Hypothalamus (CRH excess)", "Kidney"], "a": 0, "ex": "High cortisol should suppress ACTH via negative feedback. If cortisol is high AND ACTH is low, the feedback loop is working — but cortisol is being produced independently by the adrenal gland (e.g., adrenal tumor)."}}]}, "Renal Physiology": {"title": "Renal Physiology", "icon": "🫘", "steps": [{"title": "Nephron anatomy and function", "content": "Each kidney has ~1 million nephrons. Blood flow: Renal artery → afferent arteriole → GLOMERULUS (filtration) → efferent arteriole → peritubular capillaries → renal vein.\n\nThe nephron has 4 main segments:\n1. PROXIMAL CONVOLUTED TUBULE (PCT): Reabsorbs ~65% of all filtrate. Na+, glucose, amino acids, HCO3⁻, water. Constitutive (always on). Site of most drug secretion.\n2. LOOP OF HENLE: Creates the medullary concentration gradient. Descending = permeable to water. Ascending = impermeable to water, actively pumps NaCl out.\n3. DISTAL CONVOLUTED TUBULE (DCT): Fine-tuning. Aldosterone acts here (Na+ reabsorption, K+ secretion).\n4. COLLECTING DUCT: ADH acts here. ADH → aquaporin-2 insertion → water reabsorption → concentrated urine.", "check": {"q": "ADH primarily acts on which part of the nephron?", "o": ["Collecting duct", "Proximal convoluted tubule", "Loop of Henle descending limb", "Glomerulus"], "a": 0, "ex": "ADH (vasopressin) binds V2 receptors on the collecting duct, triggering insertion of aquaporin-2 water channels. This allows water to be reabsorbed, concentrating the urine. Without ADH, dilute urine is produced (diabetes insipidus)."}}]}, "Cardiovascular System": {"title": "Cardiovascular System", "icon": "❤️", "steps": [{"title": "Cardiac cycle and blood flow", "content": "Blood flow path: Vena cava → RA → RV → Pulmonary artery → LUNGS → Pulmonary vein → LA → LV → Aorta → Body\n\nThe cardiac cycle:\n• SYSTOLE: Ventricles contract. Blood ejected into aorta (LV) and pulmonary artery (RV). AV valves close (S1 'lub').\n• DIASTOLE: Ventricles relax and fill. Semilunar valves close (S2 'dub'). Blood flows from atria to ventricles.\n\nThe SA node is the natural pacemaker (~60-100 bpm). Signal path: SA node → AV node (slight delay) → Bundle of His → Purkinje fibers → ventricular contraction.", "check": {"q": "Deoxygenated blood returns to the heart via the:", "o": ["Vena cava → right atrium", "Pulmonary vein → left atrium", "Aorta → left ventricle", "Pulmonary artery → right ventricle"], "a": 0, "ex": "Deoxygenated blood from the body returns via the superior and inferior vena cava into the RIGHT atrium. Pulmonary veins carry OXYGENATED blood from the lungs back to the LEFT atrium."}}, {"title": "Starling forces and edema", "content": "Fluid exchange at capillaries is governed by Starling forces:\n\nNet filtration = (Pc - Pi) - (πc - πi)\n\nPc = capillary hydrostatic pressure (pushes fluid OUT)\nPi = interstitial hydrostatic pressure (pushes fluid IN)\nπc = capillary oncotic pressure (pulls fluid IN — due to albumin)\nπi = interstitial oncotic pressure (pulls fluid OUT)\n\nAt the ARTERIAL end: Pc > πc → net filtration (fluid exits)\nAt the VENOUS end: πc > Pc → net absorption (fluid returns)\n\nEdema occurs when: ↑Pc (heart failure), ↓πc (liver failure → low albumin), ↑capillary permeability (inflammation), or blocked lymph drainage.", "check": {"q": "A patient with liver failure develops edema. The most likely cause is:", "o": ["Decreased plasma oncotic pressure (low albumin production)", "Increased capillary hydrostatic pressure", "Blocked lymphatic drainage", "Increased interstitial oncotic pressure"], "a": 0, "ex": "The liver makes albumin, the main plasma protein that creates oncotic pressure (πc). Liver failure → low albumin → low πc → fluid not pulled back into capillaries → edema."}}]}};
